<SLUG> BC-BIGBRO-ATTACK-LADN </SLUG>
 
PRANKSTERS PENETRATE `BIG BROTHER'S' DEFENSES &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   STUDIO CITY, Calif. _ Bored to action by CBS' ``Big Brother,''
two budding screenwriters took matters into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Allen and Caleb Wilson pierced the hermetically sealed
environment of CBS' reality show by simply walking up to the Studio
City soundstage and lobbing tennis balls filled with bogus
newspaper stories into the courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   While the show's producers on Friday dismissed the prank as a
desperate publicity stunt, the 28-year-olds said they did it for a
laugh, to test security on the show and, well, because they were
bored with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it needed a little spice,'' said Allen, adding that
they don't need publicity since one of their scripts is already
under development at New Line Cinema.
</P>
<P>
   The stunt caused an immediate splash on the compound, where one
condition of the $500,000 contest is that participants have no
contact with the outside world - no papers, TV, radio, phones or
mail.
</P>
<P>
   The rule held until Thursday afternoon, when two of the seven
tennis balls hit their mark. Friends of the pranksters monitoring
the ``Big Brother'' Web site said one of the contestants said, ``I
think they're trying to help us,'' as the tennis balls landed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, you hear through a big loudspeaker, `This is
Big Brother. There's been a security breach. Put down the articles.
Tear them up immediately,''' Wilson said Friday, describing how the
scene unfurled on the show's live Internet feed that his friends
were watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we felt we could get in trouble was if we hit
someone on the head with a tennis ball,'' said Wilson of Santa
Monica. ``So our friend relayed on the cell phone that they were
out of the way, so go ahead and chuck them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' publicist Diane Ekeblad said the show's
producers were considering what sort of action they could take
against Wilson and Allen. She declined to discuss what security
measures would be taken to prevent a repeat attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two yahoos mocked up what looked like (legitimate news)
articles,'' Ekeblad said, adding that the contestants saw the
articles but did not have much time to read them. ``Big Brother''
producers ``brought the contestants into the Red Room and told them
it was a hoax and took (the tennis balls) away.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mock front page article, President Clinton is said to
have ``spoken out against'' the show and its contestants,
chastising them for abandoning their families to chase fame and
fortune on television.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's purported remarks were wholly made up, Wilson and
Allen admitted, as was an article that said banished ``Big
Brother'' contestant William ``Mega'' Collins had cut a rap record
with lyrics lashing out at each of the other contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Allen of Bel Air said the duo were unsure up to the last minute
whether they would toss the tennis balls and articles, which a
graphic artist friend designed to look stunningly real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we saw the articles, we knew we had to try this,'' Allen
said. ``We just thought it would be really funny if we could pull
it off.''
</P>
<P>
   With connections in the industry, Allen said he and Wilson
entered the CBS lot legitimately, using their own names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were wondering, how do they keep these people totally
isolated from information?'' Wilson said. ``If you somehow got a
fake newspaper in there, wouldn't they have to believe anything you
gave them because they have no information?''
</P>
<P>
   With a rough idea of where the yard was, they let loose with the
tennis balls from about 75 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Just for good measure, the pranksters videotaped themselves in
the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that if it didn't succeed, none of our friends
would believe we did it,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The show sealed 10 strangers in a prefabricated house, where
they are monitored around the clock by 28 cameras and 60
microphones, with the feeds carried live on the Internet and edited
down to primetime shows most nights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Every other week, two of the contestants are nominated by their
peers to be removed from the house; viewers calling a 900-telephone
number select the person who must leave.
</P>
<P>
   The last housemate remaining wins a $500,000 prize.
</P>
<P>
   Since its big July 5 premiere, the show has struggled in the
ratings, especially compared to CBS' other reality show,
``Survivor,'' a summer hit that reached its all-time ratings high
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said `'Big Brother'' is boring, although its show
Wednesday, which directly followed ``Survivor,'' saw the best
ratings since its premiere.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
