<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS SET FOR BIG TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The prelude to a possible Western Conference
Finals matchup between the Sparks and the Houston Comets takes
place today at 1 p.m. at the Compaq Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The nationally televised game pits the top two teams in the WNBA
- the Sparks (23-3) and the three-time defending WNBA champion
Comets (22-4). So far, they are the only teams in the league to
clinch a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in four years, the Sparks have the edge over
the most dominant team since the league's inception. They defeated
the Comets 90-84 and 63-58, both in Los Angeles. In the latter
game, though, Houston was without guard Cynthia Cooper, who had a
severe sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks have yet to win in the Compaq Center, where they are
0-8, including two playoff games last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will show us where we are at,'' Sparks coach Michael
Cooper said. ``I think we need to compete. I don't care if we win
or lose as long as we compete on that court. We've done that so
far, so I don't know why wouldn't do that (today). We just have to
come and compete and then our play we'll take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston has enjoyed a three-day rest this week, while the Sparks
are playing their fourth game this week.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the league's best offensive and defensive teams meet in
this matchup. The Comets are explosive behind Sheryl Swoopes, who
leads the league in points (21.2), Cooper (fifth, 18.2) and Tina
Thompson (11th, 16.5, 7.1 rebounds). Lisa Leslie (17.5 points, 9.8
rebounds), Mwadi Mabika (12.9 points, 5.8 rebounds), DeLisha Milton
(11.7 points, 5.8 rebounds) and Tamecka Dixon (10.5) are the
Sparks' leaders.
</P>
<P>
   This is the beginning of a six-road game trip for the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a good test for us,'' Sparks forward DeLisha
Milton said. ``They are definitely going to get us ready for
everyone else we have to play. Playing a team like Houston makes
you get energized right away from the sound of their name. Once you
walk into their arena and you hear everybody say, 'Beat L.A.' that
should energize you right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough if you let it get to you. If you're focused and
focused on what your game plan is, sometimes you can be so focused
you won't hear it. But if you're out there and letting little snide
comments that people make get into your head affect you, then the
outcome of the game is in the air then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
