<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 07/28/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) PHILADELPHIA -- July 28, 2000 --
REPUBS-CONVENTION-PREPARE -- A visitor to the Philadelphia
Convention Center walks across a carpet welcoming all to Political
Fest, a 'world's fair' of politics on Friday in Philadelphia.
Political Fest runs alongside the Republican National Convention
which begins on Monday. (Jim Wilson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SPRINGDALE, Ark. -- July 28, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY-2 --
Gov. George W. Bush, with his wife, Laura, and running mate, Dick
Cheney, and his wife Lynne were greeted by a roaring crowd packed
into Springdale High School in Springdale, Ark., during a campaign
rally on Friday. With his stop in the rolling green farm country in
the Northwest corner of Arkansas, Bush began a five-day march to
the Republican National Convention that will take him through the
battleground states of Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio, West Virginia and
Pennsylvania. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SPRINGDALE, Ark. -- July 28, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY-1 --
Gov. George W. Bush and his running mate Dick Cheney during a rally
at Springdale High School in Springdale, Ark. Brimming with
confidence, Bush flew into President Clinton's home territory
proclaiming that he intended to contest areas that the Democrats
won solidly in the last two presidential elections. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PHILADELPHIA -- July 28, 2000 -- PHILA-MAYOR-PROFILE --
Mayor John F. Street of Philadelphia, the powerful incumbent of the
nation's fifth largest city, faces a critical test next week as the
Republican convention begins. As the arriving Republicans pack into
Philadelphia, so will assorted protest groups, vowing to rally by
the tens of thousands. ``There are some people who believe their
rights are the only rights. We can't allow people to destroy
Philadelphia,'' says Street. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- July 28, 2000 -- INVEST-SARAH-2 -- Sarah
Jessica Parker, the actress, may be adventurous in ``Sex and the
City,'' but when it comes to investing she remembers being one of
eight eight children in a family receiving welfare and living in
subsidized housing. Today 30 percent to 40 percent of her
investment portfolio is in tax-free bonds. The remainder is in
stocks and mutual funds primarily handled by McDonald &AMP; Co. and
other investment firms. Parker in a promotional photo for HBO's
``Sex and the City.'' (HBO/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SARASOTA, Fla. -- July 28, 2000 -- SPRINGER-SLAYINGS-2
-- Eleanor Panitz, appears in a Sarasota, Fla. courtroom Friday
after turing herself in to Sarasota Sheriffs along with husband
Ralf Panitiz. Panitz is the man suspected of murdering his ex-wife,
Nancy Campbell-Panitz, after their twisted love story aired on
``The Jerry Springer Show.'' Ralf Panitz is being held without bail
on a murder charge, while Eleanor Panitz is being held as a
material witness. (Rod Millington/The Sarasota Herald-Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SARASOTA, Fla. -- July 28, 2000 -- SPRINGER-SLAYINGS-1
-- Ralf Panitz, the ex-husband of a woman found dead after their
twisted love story aired on ``The Jerry Springer Show'' is escorted
by Sarasota County Sheriff's deputies into the Sarasota County
Jail, Friday. Panitz who had disappeared after Nancy
Campbell-Panitz was beaten to death Monday, made a brief court
appearance and was ordered held without bail on a murder charge.
Panitz's wife, Eleanor Panitz, is also being held as a material
witness. (Barry McCarthy/The Sarasota Herald-Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PHILADELPHIA -- July 28, 2000 -- REPUBS-CONVENTION --
Shirley Lightcap, sitting behind the desk, tries out a replica of
the president's desk in a mock Oval Office set up during Political
Fest, an event running in conjunction with the Republican National
Convention, Friday. Joining her are friends Susan Morris, right and
Doris Loscig. The festival contained various interactive exhibits
relating to the office of the president. The GOP's convention
begins Monday. (Jim Wilson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa -- July 28, 2000 -- CARS-RACING --
Pat and Mary Brooks of Marshalltown, Iowa, with their 1949 Buick
Super wood-paneled station wagon, were one of 10 American teams
participating in the Around the World in 80 Days Motor Challenge
sponsored by the Classic Rally Association. The Brookses, who
received $10,000 in sponsorship money from Buick, finished 21st out
of 29 entries in the division that covered cars from 1941 to the
1960s. (The New York Times) Story moved 07-27-00.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- July 28, 2000 -- NY-KENNEDY-HOSTAGES-2 --
Aaron Commey is led by police in Brooklyn federal court where he
was charged with attempted aircraft piracy, Friday. Police said
Comely burst into the cockpit of a plane at John F. Kennedy Airport
late Thursday and held a gun to the pilot's head. (William C.
Lopez/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 28, 2000 -- NY-KENNEDY-HOSTAGES --
Federal agents stand guard at the tail section of National Airlines
flight 19 where an unidentified man carrying a gun entered the
cabin and took the pilot and co-pilot hostage late Thurdsday at
John F. Kennedy Airport. The mentally disturbed man charged with
bursting into the cockpit of a plane at John F. Kennedy Airport and
holding a gun to the pilot's head had plotted his brazen crime for
months, prosecutors said Friday. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) DALLAS -- July 28, 2000 -- BUSH-BIO-VI-2 -- As he
approached his 40th birthday, an age when Al Gore was already a
senator running for president, George W. Bush was just a
heavy-drinking, fun-loving oilman struggling to control his temper,
salvage his business and hold on to his marriage. Then Bush grew
up. George W. Bush holds his twins, Barbara and Jenna, born in the
fall of 1981. (Bush Presidential Library/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MIDLAND, Texas -- July 28, 2000 -- BUSH-BIO-VI-1 -- As
he approached his 40th birthday, an age when Al Gore was already a
senator running for president, George W. Bush was just a
heavy-drinking, fun-loving oilman struggling to control his temper,
salvage his business and hold on to his marriage. Then Bush grew
up. George W. Bush and his wife Laura on their wedding day, Nov. 5,
1977, flanked by the elder Bush and his wife Barbara. (Bush
Presidential Library/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- July 28, 2000 -- SWASTIKAS-REDEEM-2-B&AMP;W --
Before the Nazi party adopted the swastika and turned it into the
most potent icon of racial hatred, it traveled the world for
centuries as a good luck symbol. A label for a matchbox, circa
1950's, right. At left, the cover of the November 1915 issue of The
Swastika magazine published by the Girls's Club. (From ``The
Swastika'' by Steven Heller,Allworth Press/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) JERSEY CITY, N.J. -- July 28, 2000 -- NY-MOTOR-HOMES --
What do RV vacationers do when they want to see the Big Apple? Why,
they just drive to the RV park at Liberty State Park, where the
Winnebagos have views of the World Trade Center and the Statue of
Liberty. The scene at the park earlier this week. (Edward
Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. -- July 28, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.
AUG. 30 -- GOLF-FASHION-2 -- At the Poxabogue Golf Center in
Bridgehampton, N.Y., Claudia Romana, left, wears trouser shorts and
a top from her golf fashion collection. Romana, 36, is one of a new
breed of golfwear designers who realize that the women who wear
Armani in the boardroom have no intention of taking to the course
dressed like Emmett Kelly. (Maxine Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. -- July 28, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.
AUG. 30 -- GOLF-FASHION-1 -- Designer Claudia Romana, 36, left, is
one of a new breed of golfwear designers who realize that the women
who wear Armani in the boardroom have no intention of taking to the
course dressed like Emmett Kelly. At the Poxabogue Golf Center in
Bridgehampton, N.Y., Claudia Romana, left, wears white trouser
shorts and a black top from her golf fashion collection. (Maxine
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 28, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JULY 30 --
JUNGER-BAR -- Sebastian Junger, right, the best-selling author of
``The Perfect Storm,'' is one of the owners of The Half King bar in
Manhattan. The bar was dreamed up as a saloon for writers, in a
time when watering holes for those in the literary life have
virtually dried up. At the Half King, from left, Jerome O'Connor,
Scott Anderson, Nanette Burstein and Junger. (David Corio/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- July 28, 2000 -- SWASTIKAS-REDEEM -- Before
the Nazi party adopted the swastika and turned it into the most
potent icon of racial hatred, it traveled the world for centuries
as a good luck symbol. A good luck card from the early 20th
century. (Manwoman.net/The New York Times) NO SALES
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK-- July 28, 2000 --
TRILLING-LITERARY-CRITICISM-B&AMP;W --How quaint the literary criticism
of Lionel Trilling can seem, now that successive waves of
structuralism, deconstruction, cultural studies, post-colonialism
and other literary technologies have transformed university
departments of literature. But what makes his pieces of continuing
importance is not Trilling's judgment that the Kinsey Report
fetishizes science or that Kipling gave nationalism a bad name. The
essays' subjects really were occasions for Trilling to brood on
much larger themes that, far from being dated or quaint, have lost
none of their urgency. Trilling during a news conference as
students rallied on the embattled campus of Columbia University on
May 3, 1968. (Neal Boenzi/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- July 28, 2000 -- INVEST-SARAH -- Sarah Jessica
Parker, the actress, may be adventurous in ``Sex and the City,''
but when it comes to investing she remembers being one of eight
eight children in a family receiving welfare and living in
subsidized housing. Today 30 percent to 40 percent of her
investment portfolio is in tax-free bonds. The remainder is in
stocks and mutual funds primarily handled by McDonald &AMP; Co. and
other investment firms. Parker in a promotional photo for HBO's
``Sex and the City.'' (HBO/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- July 28, 2000 --DRESSDOWN-INSECURITTY-BOS --
Gray-haired traditionalists aren't the only ones balking as
corporate America leaps onto the Casual-Day bandwagon. Ed Colbert,
an attorney with Looney &AMP; Grossman, prefers to dress more formally
than his colleague, Robert Barber. (Bill Greene/The Boston Globe)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) McLEAN, Va. -- July 28, 2000 -- LLBEAN-RETAIL-BOS -- It
can be a tricky business, trying to export a New England retail
icon south. So, in opening its first full-price store outside of
Maine this week, L. L. Bean Inc., is taking no chances. Leon
Gorman, president and grandson of the founder of L.L. Bean, tries
on some wares at the new company's store. (Jonathan Wiggs/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 28, 2000 -- IVILLAGE-CEO -- IVillage,
the online women's network, says Candice Carpenter, the company's
co-founder, is stepping down as chief executive. Carpenter during a
meeting in April. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JAMAICA PLAIN, Mass. -- July 28, 2000 -- MA-WESTNILE -- A
second dead crow infected with the West Nile virus triggered a
round of emergency meetings in the Boston area on Friday where
officials contemplated a spraying campaign to eradicate mosquitoes.
Officials on Wednesday said a dead crow in the neighborhood of
Jamaica Plain also carried the virus. A crow flies over Willos Pond
on Wednesday where authorities found the dead crow. (John
Tlumacki/The Boston Globe)
</P>
