u a BC-OBIT-GUILES-NYT &LR;      07-29 0172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GUILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRED LAWRENCE GUILES, 79, MOVIE STAR BIOGRAPHER AND PLAYWRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fred Lawrence Guiles, a biographer of Hollywood movie stars, was
found dead on June 24 at his home in Gainesville, Fla. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Among Guiles' best-selling books was his 1969 ``Norma Jean: The
Life of Marilyn Monroe,'' which was translated into 14 languages.
The book became the center of a dispute in 1973 when its publisher
accused Norman Mailer of having plagiarized portions of it and of
another Monroe biography in writing ``Marilyn,'' his own book about
the actress. Mailer and Guiles jointly refuted the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Guiles' play, ``Song for a Certain Midnight,'' was produced off
Broadway in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the author of ``Marion Davies'' and ``Tyrone Power,
the Last Idol'' and published another version of his Monroe
biography, ``Legend: The Life and Death of Marilyn Monroe,'' in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   Guiles is survived by a sister, Nadine G. Jackson of
Quarryville, Pa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
