<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-TWINS-NYT     07-29 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD START, BAD FINISH FOR YANKEES IN 5-4 LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Denny Neagle pitched Friday night in a style with
which the Yankees have grown accustomed. Mariano Rivera did not.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle walked off the field with the Yankees leading, 4-2, in
the eighth, but Rivera allowed back-to-back singles to score the
tying and go-ahead runs with two out, and Minnesota prevailed, 5-4.
David Ortiz tied the game with a two-run single, and Jay Canizaro
drove in the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle allowed just three hits in seven-plus innings. Jorge
Posada and Tino Martinez, both fighting slumps, fueled the offense
before the lead was blown: Posada had two doubles and his 17th
homer, and Martinez had three hits, scored one run and drove in
another.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led, 4-2, when Midre Cummings pinch-hit to begin the
bottom of the eighth; interestingly, Cummings was traded with
Neagle from Minnesota to Pittsburgh in 1992. Neagle walked Cummings
and walked Denny Hocking, on close pitches. After Neagle was
relieved by the Yankees manager Joe Torre, Neagle stalked off the
mound screaming out of the side of his mouth at the home plate
umpire Chuck Merwether, his head aimed straight ahead at the
dugout, until he shot one withering glance at the ump.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton took over, and Cristian Guzman pushed a ball down
the first base line, where Martinez had a decision: he could either
tag Guzman to get the first out of the inning and concede the
advancement of the runners, or he could let it roll in the hope it
went foul. Martinez opted for the latter, the ball rolled foul, and
Stanton whiffed Guzman and then Matt Lawton.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson relieved Stanton and walked Coomer, after Coomer
fouled three pitches with a full count. Rivera took over, and Ortiz
rolled a two-run single through the middle, two runners scoring to
tie the game, before Canizaro pulled a single to right, driving
home Coomer with the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle began his career in the Minnesota organization, making a
handful of major league appearances before he was traded to
Pittsburgh in 1992. But his changeup, his most effective pitch, has
deeper ties to the Twins than he does. While watching the 1987
World Series as a teenager, Neagle saw how Frank Viola gripped his
changeup, with the ball buried deep in his palm and the tips of his
thumb and forefinger touching: A circle change, it is called, and
Neagle was fascinated.
</P>
<P>
   He adapting the pitch for his own use, and a few years later
Neagle was pitching in Double-A when a couple approached him, the
parents of Frank Viola, and Viola's father complimented Neagle and
commented how closely his style resembled that of his son; Neagle
was overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   He overwhelmed the Twins early Friday night, using his typical
pattern, throwing fastballs and changeups, the Minnesota batters
seemingly caught guessing somewhere in between, hitting popups and
easy fly balls. Neagle retired the first nine batters in order, and
Jorge Posada's solo homer in the second gave the Yankees a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Hocking topped a ground single to lead off the fourth
inning. Guzman, who spent part of his afternoon batting practice
trying to direct line drives at a bucket moved around the infield,
reached out and served a line drive into the right-center field
gap, to score Hocking.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle walked Lawton, snapping his glove at the return throw
from Posada after delivering ball four. Two ground balls sent
Guzman home, pushing Minnesota ahead, 2-1. When Canizaro attempted
to bunt with two outs, fouling off the ball, Neagle's temper
appeared to flair. He fired a fastball high and inside, pushing
Canizaro back from the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez opened the sixth inning by smashing a single, and when
Jorge Posada ripped a double, Martinez was waved around third, in
an attempt to score with nobody out. The throw actually beat
Martinez to the plate, but the catcher Chad Moeller fumbled the
ball, and Martinez slid across home safely with the tying run;
Posada took third. Radke retired the next two hitters, holding
Posada at the bag.
</P>
<P>
   But Chuck Knoblauch, who will be booed here forever because he
forced his trade from the Twins after the 1997 season, smacked a
single, and the Yankees moved ahead, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added a run in the top of the seventh, when Martinez
pulled a double into right-center field, pushing across David
Justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
