<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY HAD ANSWERS FOR SIMILAR HEALTH QUESTIONS IN PAST
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLA MARINUCCI and JOHN WILDERMUTHc.2000 San Francisco &LR; 
 &UR; Chronicle &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney's first congressional campaign in Wyoming, in 1977,
had just about all the drama anybody could want _ the candidate had
the first of three heart attacks in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Francisco ad man who handled all of Cheney's
congressional races said Bush's choice for vice president decided
to deal with it head-on. Cheney, who was taken off the campaign
trail for a month after the experience _ a lifetime in politics _
agreed to an ad in which he talked face-to-face with voters about
his health problems.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second spot, which shows Cheney sitting cross-legged in a
park with followers, gives more than a clue as to how he will deal
with the attacks on his poor health and his politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having had a mild heart attack really led me to pause and
reflect,'' Cheney said in the ad. But he added that the feeling of
``wanting to do something beyond your own self interest'' drove him
to continue the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Then he delivered a history lesson: He was not the first
politician to have a heart attack, he said. And despite theirs,
Eisenhower and LBJ showed their stuff afterward as proven leaders.
``I expect to become one of those,'' he promised.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gardner, who heads the San Francisco ad agency of Gardner,
Geary and Coll, and a friend of the former defense secretary for
more than 20 years, called that evidence of the tough campaigner
Cheney will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is extremely smart, almost intellectual, an avid reader and
thinker _ not a motor mouth,'' said Gardner, whose agency has also
done work for Diamond Walnuts, Delta Dental and The Chronicle.
``Probably the most solid person I've ever met. He inspires
confidence and judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gardner, who also shaped ad campaigns for President Gerald
Ford, says experience assures him that Cheney knows how to weather
the current attacks on his politics and persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very calm, logical guy. People will see that he's not a
hysterical right-winger or a bomb thrower,'' Gardner said. ``Of any
of the politicians I've met, he's the most comfortable in his own
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those qualities are the very ones Cheney sold to voters
in his early races when, fresh from his stint as Ford's chief of
staff, he was tabbed as nothing more than a carpetbagger by some
political opponents. They charged that the young whippersnapper
from inside the Beltway was trying to pretend he was a Wyomingite.
</P>
<P>
   Those first ads in 1978 attempted to answer those criticisms and
sell an earnest (and yes, thinner) Cheney with a heavy dose of
hometown appeal. There was the high school teacher recalling how
Cheney was a first-string football player, and his wife, Lynn, was
homecoming queen. He was depicted proudly as a native son, a man
who achieved much at an early age.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after Cheney was elected a few times, the themes changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't much like Washington telling us how to run our
affairs,'' the voice-over intones, as panoramic photographs of the
Grand Tetons hit the screen. Cheney was described as ``a leader who
gets things done _ Wyoming's best.''
</P>
<P>
   But, proving that there is nothing in politics that hasn't been
tried before, a spot called ``Rope Trick'' takes an interesting
tack _ particularly given that the top of the 2000 Republican
ticket, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, has been accused of having a
thin resume in areas like foreign policy and military affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to get the job done, you've got to know the
ropes,'' the announcer intones, as Cheney is seen sitting with his
daughters, entertaining them with rope tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Voters need a political leader, the voice says, ``who's had
experience _ not an amateur getting tied up in on-the-job
training.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nip-and-tuck contest to win Silicon Valley's
congressional seat that Republican Tom Campbell is surrendering.
Democrat Mike Honda and Republican Jim Cunneen have already raised
a combined $1.5 million, which is a good chunk of money to capture
a job that pays $141,300 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But that number is chump change compared with the cash that has
being tossed around in three Southern California races.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, incumbent Republican Rep. Jim Rogan has raised $4.6
million, while his Democratic opponent, Adam Schiff, has collected
$2.9 million. That combined $7.5 million is just short of the
all-time record for most-expensive race for a House seat, the
nearly $8 million that then-GOP Speaker Newt Gingrich and Michael
Coles spent in Georgia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rogan-Schiff figures are only through June 30, which
leaves plenty of time to take political spending to breathtaking
new heights.
</P>
<P>
   There is also plenty of money being spent a little farther
south, where GOP incumbent Rep. Steve Kuykendall and Democrat Jane
Harman are dueling in the Torrance area. Kuykendall has raised $1.1
million, while Harman, who surrendered the seat to make an
unsuccessful run for governor in 1998, has gathered $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego County features another million-dollar race, where
Republican Rep. Brian Bilbray and Democratic Assemblywoman Susan
Davis have collected about $1.2 million each.
</P>
<P>
   With control of the House up for grabs, Democrats are looking to
pick up most of the seven seats they need right in California,
while Republicans want to hang on to what they have. That means the
campaign money tap is not going to be turned off anytime soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
