<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT JUDGE FAVORED AS QUACKENBUSH SUCCESSOR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ Gov. Gray Davis will name a successor to former
Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush on Monday, and speculation
is focused on a retired San Francisco Court of Appeals judge.
<P>
   Retired Court of Appeal Justice Harry Low heads San Francisco's
Human Rights Commission, is a close politically ally of Mayor
Willie Brown, and would put an Asian American into a prominent
statewide office.
</P>
<P>
   Davis will make up his mind over the weekend and a press
conference is planned for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Low, who has strong ties to San Francisco, received praise
Friday as someone who could return respectability to the tarnished
insurance commissioner post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think he is absolutely what the governor would be
looking for in an interim appointment,'' said Senate President Pro
Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, who said he has known Low for a
long time. ``His reputation is beyond reproach, he is probably not
interested in running for political office, he is highly respected,
and he has tremendous recognition in the Asian community.''
</P>
<P>
   Low did not return phone calls Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush resigned under pressure June 28 and since then Clark
Kelso, a law professor at Sacramento's McGeorge School of Law has
been acting commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' pick will have to be confirmed by both houses of the
Legislature when it returns to Sacramento on August 7. If
confirmed, the successor will serve out the remainder of
Quackenbush's term, which ends in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said he does not want to appoint someone political to
the office, saying he would prefer to name a person who does not
raise money from the industry.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Michael Yaki, who was a clerk for Low
in 1986-87 after graduating from law school, said Low understands
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very politically connected, but at the same time is not
seen as beholden to any one interest group,'' Yaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Yaki also said it would be ``extremely important'' to have an
Asian American in one of the constitutional officer posts.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocate Harvey Rosenfield said he is worried Low's
legal background will make him less aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want someone who is going to be an aggressive advocate for
consumers, not neutral,'' said Rosenfield, who is president of the
Foundation for Taxpayer and Consumer Rights. ``When someone is
neutral, the insurance companies win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield also expressed concern about Low's current work as an
arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where big litigants so to settle out of court,'' he said.
``We need to know if he's handled any arbitration involving big
insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Low's biography on Judicial Arbitration &AMP; Mediation Services,
Inc. web site says he has handled a wide variety of cases,
including ``mediated insurance coverage cases involving
construction costs, business ventures and tort coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to serving on the Human Rights Commission, Low is
the former president of San Francisco Police Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Low's involvement in state government dates to the 1950s when he
was a deputy attorney general under Attorney General Edmund ``Pat''
Brown Sr. As governor Brown, a Democrat, named Low to the Municipal
Court in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Ronald Reagan, a Republican, named Low to the Superior
Court, and Gov. Jerry Brown elevated him to the state Court of
Appeal in San Francisco in 1982. He retired in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
