<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-RULING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT GRANTS NAPSTER A REPRIEVE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ The music will play on for Napster and its
millions of fans following a surprising reprieve by a federal
appeals court in San Francisco Friday.
<P>
   Two U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals judges granted a temporary
stay of a lower court's preliminary injunction that would have
silenced the San Mateo startup at midnight last night.
</P>
<P>
   And because court proceedings do not move as fast as the
Internet, the stay gives Napster users until at least mid-September
to download as many free MP3 songs as they want. That's the
earliest a hearing on the appeal can be scheduled, ``We're happy
and we're grateful that the Court of Appeals is going to allow the
company to keep operating,'' said an upbeat Hank Barry, Napster's
interim CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Record industry executives, who earlier this week thought they
had all but vanquished a company they considered a mortal threat to
their businesses, were chagrined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, of course, that the tens of millions of
daily infringements occurring on Napster will be able to continue,
at least temporarily,'' said Hilary Rosen, president of the
Recording Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, since the district court issued its order, the
illegal downloading of copyrighted music openly encouraged by
Napster has probably exceeded all previous records,'' Rosen said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The stay, capped a wild week in the landmark battle pitting the
established entertainment industries, which are trying to protect
their copyrights and profits, and a rapidly growing grassroots
Internet community that claimed Napster and similar technology put
the power of music in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on relaxing to the sweet sounds of my downloaded MP3's
knowing that I, not the government, own what's on my hard drive,''
said Hagop Kaneboughazian.cocq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The 20-year-old Berkeley resident, who goes by the name
``Kane,'' launched a Web site,
 &UR; www.flyingmiko.comsupportnapster.htm,  &LR; to promote a two-week
boycott of record stores. He also posted fliers calling for a
demonstration Saturday outside a Tower Records store, but said the
stay gives him more time to organize the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Napster, meanwhile, called on its supporters to honor a
``buy-cott weekend'' by purchasing CDs made by a list of
Napster-supporting bands and musicians like Chuck D, Limp Bizkit
and The Offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site that posted an electronic petition to save
Napster registered more than 50,000 signatures, twice as many as a
previous petition to send 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is a computer program originally written by a
19-year-old college student who wanted an easy way to share
MP3-formated songs on his computer with his friends. The program
can search for songs on other Napster members' computer hard
drives, and then link those computers via the Internet so that the
music can be copied.
</P>
<P>
   The company says more than 20 million copies of Napster have
been downloaded since its release in August 1999 as a beta, or
unfinished version. The final version of the program is still in
the works.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the RIAA, which include the biggest U.S. record
labels like Sony Music and Warner Music Group, sued Napster last
December, claiming the program allows rampant piracy of
copyright-protected songs. The record companies say Napster has
already cost them $300 million in lost sales and will undermine the
industry if left unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.S. District Court Judge Marilyn Hall Patel said
there was a strong likelihood the record industry would prove its
case against Napster in a trial. She issued a preliminary
injunction scheduled to take effect at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   She ordered Napster to stop infringing on songs owned by RIAA
members. Napster appealed Patel's order on grounds the injunction
was tantamount to a death sentence because the Napster program
cannot distinguish between legally and illegally copied songs.
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA, meanwhile, protested the Napster's appeal, claiming
the company was overstating the injunction's effect because it
could still maintain its online operations.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-page decision, Circuit Court Judges Alex Kozinski and
Barry G. Silverman agreed that Napster ``raised substantial
questions ... going to both the merits and the form of the
injunction.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there was no further explanation, the order indicates
the judges believe there are both precedent-setting legal issues to
be resolved as well as questions about whether Patel made her
injunction too broad, said Jim Burger, an intellectual rights
attorney with the Washington, D.C. firm Dow, Lohnes &AMP; Albertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real setback for the music industry,'' Burger said.
``They were jubilant over Judge Patel's order, but this will set
them back on their heels a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court gave Napster attorneys an Aug. 18 deadline to
file an opening brief to fight Patel's preliminary injunction. The
recording industry's response is due on Sept. 8. Napster would have
until Sept. 12 to file an optional reply.
</P>
<P>
   That means Napster will remain operating until at least Sept. 8,
and more likely until after Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the court is moving faster than normal because such
appeals usually take at least one year to be heard, said Napster
attorney Daniel Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over til the fat lady sings and she hasn't sung
yet,'' wrote a fan with the screen name Merlin 420 on an online
bulletin board at Napstermaina.com. ``The people may be small, but
together we HAVE the power ... Three cheers for Napster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
