<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HARRIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM HARRIS, DANCE AND FINANCIAL WRITER, 49 
</HEADLINE>
   2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Harris, a dance writer and advocate for new dance
artists, died on Thursday in Manhattan. He was 49 and lived in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said his brother, John, of
Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Harris wrote about dance for SoHo Weekly News, Dance Ink and The
Village Voice and was a managing editor for Theater Crafts
Magazine. He was also a frequent contributor to The New York Times
on dance and theater. As a financial writer, he contributed to
Forbes Magazine, Institutional Investor and The Daily Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was an informal adviser to dance producers and helped to
establish the careers of experimental dance artists and groups
including David Dorfman, Tere O'Connor and the Belgian performance
art company Plan K.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his brother, Harris is survived by his mother,
Vivienne, of Pittsburgh, and a sister, Ellen, of Denver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
