A6721 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-EXAMINER-TRANSFER-SFC     07-29 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-TRANSFER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HEARST COMPLETES TRANSFER OF FLAGSHIP NEWSPAPER TO S.F. FAMILY  &HT;     By WILLIAM CARLSEN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp. announced Friday that it has completed the
transfer of the San Francisco Examiner to the Fang family,
publishers of the thrice-weekly Independent, concluding the final
transaction in the company's nerve-racking yearlong attempt to
purchase The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement means that Hearst will continue to operate the
Examiner for a 120-day transition period before turning the
venerable flagship of the once far-flung Hearst newspaper empire
over to the Fangs at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the staffs of both papers _ the Examiner's 217
reporters and editors and the Chronicle's 378 editorial employees _
are expected to merge newsrooms under The Chronicle masthead.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker ruled on Thursday that
Hearst's $660 million purchase of The Chronicle did not violate
antitrust laws, and the Chronicle acquisition was completed with
several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst chief executive Frank Bennack Jr. met with the editors of
The Chronicle and Examiner for 45 minutes Friday to tell them that
the two transactions had been effectively completed.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack said the Hearst Corp. had a ``binding contract'' to give
the Examiner to the Fangs and said the company intended to honor
that agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He told the assembled news executives that he expected the new
Chronicle, with the combined staffs, to compare favorably to great
U.S. newspapers like the New York Times, the Washington Post, Los
Angeles Times and Chicago Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   He promised that there would be ``a quantum leap in resources''
to make The Chronicle such a paper.
</P>
<P>
   A publisher of the new Hearst-owned Chronicle would be appointed
shortly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack also indicated that Hearst had reached an agreement with
former political consultant Clint Reilly, the millionaire real
estate investor who had sued to block the sale of The Chronicle.
The agreement included paying Reilly $2.5 million for attorney's
fees and costs and in return Reilly agreed that he would not appeal
Walker's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's attorney, Joseph M. Alioto, explained Friday why Reilly
was willing to end his legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not give Clint any certainty as to how much time an
appeal would take and what the Ninth Circuit (court of appeals)
would do,'' Alioto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in light of that and what Hearst was willing to pay to
cover attorneys' fees and costs,'' he said, ``Clint decided he
would not pursue the case any further.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Examiner transaction could still be sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned with some of the comments in Walker's ruling, Hearst
attorney's and executives pored over the decision Friday and
discussed their options with Fang's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Walker virtually invited a lawsuit by newspaper
competitors or advertisers challenging the Fang transaction on
antitrust grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Although Walker approved the Hearst purchase of The Chronicle,
he had harsh words for the Fang deal, calling it ``malodorous''
because of the political pressure exerted on the U.S. Justice
Department and Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's $66 million subsidy to the Fangs to operate the
Examiner for three years, the judge said, ``would appear to create
a barrier to entry by nonsubsidized competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker also said ``an artificially strong Examiner ... would
impair the ability of established participants to compete in that
localized market.''
</P>
<P>
   One potential competitor, the SF Weekly, said Friday that the
paper's lawyers and business staff would have to look at the issue
closely over the next few weeks before any decision about a lawsuit
is made.
</P>
<P>
   Editor John Mecklin said that the Fang deal was clearly
anti-competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more, it's insane,'' Mecklin said.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the Bay Guardian, another potential Examiner
competitor, said he has no intention of suing. Publisher Bruce
Brugmann said: ``I don't give a damn about the Fang deal. I can
take competition. The crime here is that the judge is allowing
Hearst to kill an afternoon newspaper and impose a monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker had savaged the Justice Department in his ruling,
accusing the government lawyers of engaging in ``political
favoritism masquerading as law enforcement '' for caving in to
political pressure in their decision to investigate the Hearst
takeover of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the department called the judge's allegations
``completely unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An experienced team of Department of Justice career attorneys
and economists conducted a thorough investigation of this case,''
said department spokeswomen Gina Talamona. ``The department's
actions were based solely on the facts and the law. Politics played
absolutely no role in this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, who will be the new publisher of the Examiner, said
Friday that his family is ``proud to be the first Asian American
family ever to own a daily newspaper in a major metropolitan
city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department has spoken,'' he said. ``The courts
have ruled. Let the competition begin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
