<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-PLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY ARGUES FOR RESTARTING NUCLEAR PLANT WITH OLD GENERATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Ore.)  By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHANAN, N.Y. _ Despite mounting criticism of its inspection
procedures, Con Ed on Friday renewed its assertions that the Indian
Point 2 power plant could be safely restarted with its existing
steam generators and ran heat and pressure tests in preparation for
the restart.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed engineers elaborately defended their inspection
procedures with charts and numbers during a five-hour public
meeting with the Nuclear Regulatory Commission at the plant site,
35 miles north of New York City. Last week, the commission sent a
letter to plant managers requiring further extensive analysis of
the steam generators before it could be reopened.
</P>
<P>
   The commission delivered another blow Friday in a second letter
that cited Con Ed's lax inspection of the steam generators in 1997
as a contributing factor in the Feb. 15 leak of radioactive steam
that shut down the plant. In that leak, a tiny amount of
radioactive steam escaped after a tube carrying superheated
radioactive water cracked from corrosion. No injuries were
reported, but the accident was the worst in the 26-year history of
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Local government officials, advocacy groups and others have
petitioned the nuclear commission to demand that Indian Point 2
remain closed until the new generators are installed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Con Ed officials have promised to replace the plant's
aging steam generators by the end of the year, they want to restart
the existing generators to increase the company's power reserves in
the hot summer months, when energy use rises.
</P>
<P>
   James Baumstark, vice president of nuclear engineering for Con
Ed, said he disagreed with the nuclear commission's findings on the
1997 inspection. He also emphasized that the company had improved
its methods since then to include an electronic probe that is
better able to spot minute cracks in the tubes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made significant improvements in both equipment and
processes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nuclear Regulatory Commission officials said Friday that
they would needed more time for study and to review the company's
responses before making a final decision. Still, Jack Strosnider,
director of the division of engineering at the commission, said the
plant could reopen in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, workers raised the temperature of the nuclear reactor
in a routine test to check for leaks or other problems. A few weeks
ago, they performed a similar test after receiving permission from
the nuclear commission, said Michael Clendenin, a spokesman for Con
Ed.
</P>
<P>
   Baumstark said it could take nine months to a year before the
new generators are fully operational because of the detailed
preparations involved. During that period of transition, he said,
the existing generators could supply power that is currently being
bought from other power companies. Since the shutdown, the company
has passed on the cost of that arrangement _ about $600,000 a day _
to its utility customers.
</P>
<P>
   Still others on Friday raised the possibility that the most
economical decision for Con Edison may be to keep the Indian Point
2 plant closed permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Edward A. Smeloff, executive director of the Pace University
Energy Project, said that replacing the plant's four existing steam
generators would cost $150 million to $250 million. He said Con
Edison should undertake a comparative cost analysis to determine
whether it would be cheaper in the long run to keep buying energy
from other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Smeloff said two power plants, one in Oregon and one in Maine,
were closed by their owners in the mid-1990s because it was cheaper
than replacing the costly steam generators. ``So the question
becomes Can that investment be recovered in future operations of
the plant through the market?'' he said. ``If it can't, then the
plant wouldn't be economical and should be shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison officials Friday dismissed the idea of shutting down
the plant to save money. The company is in the process of selling
the power plant, which has been licensed by the nuclear commission
to operate until 2013. ``We believe it's less costly to have the
plant running than to have to go purchase power from other
sources,'' Clendenin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
