u a BC-NY-COL-JUSTICE-NYT &LR;      07-29 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-JUSTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN JUSTICE LEAVES A BITTER TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The criminal justice system doesn't work. Just ask
the family of Amadou Diallo and others who were distraught when a
jury acquitted four New York City police officers in the infamous
case of the 41 bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal justice system doesn't work. Just ask ardent
defenders of Charles Schwarz, the former police officer doing
prison time for his role in the brutal assault on Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal justice system doesn't work. Just ask the millions
who cannot believe that O.J. Simpson was found not guilty at his
murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal justice system doesn't work. Just ask the many who
are still shaking their heads because Bernard Goetz, the subway
shooter, was absolved of the most serious felony charges against
him.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal justice system doesn't work. Just ask the family
and friends of Patrick Dorismond, shot to death by an undercover
narcotics detective during a curbside brawl in March. They are the
latest who will tell you that justice is an illusion now that a
Manhattan grand jury has decided against indicting the detective,
Anthony Vasquez.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be a popular pastime: trashing the system when it
does not produce the results you want. Even City Hall cannot resist
playing this game. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has cited the Diallo
and Dorismond outcomes as proof that the wheels of justice turn
smoothly, has been more than willing to denounce the New York
judiciary as jerky, ideological and (gasp!) Democratic when it does
not rule to his liking.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the attackers are unencumbered by certain details,
like evidence. In the Dorismond case, some critics talked
immediately about the system's having failed even though they,
unlike the grand jurors, had no access to the witnesses and
exhibits, no way to evaluate the credibility of the police face to
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who want indictments simply want indictments,'' said
Michael Meyers, executive director of the New York Civil Rights
Coalition. ``They don't care about the evidence. They say, `We want
indictments because we're angry.' That's not the way the criminal
justice system works.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, while they may accept the grand jury's conclusion that
Vasquez committed no crime, many New Yorkers will find it hard to
shake the feeling that this case has not turned out right.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the unarmed Dorismond contributed to his own death, as
the jurors suggested, by letting his short fuse blow when
undercover officers approached him looking to buy crack cocaine.
But he is still the one who is dead _ dead, as his mother said on
Thursday, for saying no to drugs. No way will that sit right with
many people.
</P>
<P>
   The public has a built-in alarm system that enables it _ most of
the time, anyway _ to separate good from bad when police behavior
comes under fire.
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain why there was no outcry a few weeks ago when
two off-duty police officers killed an unarmed man who bizarrely
began punching them on the Grand Central Parkway in Queens. And it
is why, by contrast, the Diallo case continues to cast long shadows
even though the officers who killed the unarmed Diallo were cleared
of murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond's death seems likely to keep on reverberating, too.
</P>
<P>
   Fairly or not, problem cases like this one have caused many New
Yorkers to sour on their machinery of criminal justice, Meyers
said. With all respect to District Attorney Robert Morgenthau of
Manhattan, he said, some will wonder how aggressive any district
attorney can be in police-misconduct cases, given how he has to
work closely with the police every day.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers' solution is not the reflexive call for federal
intervention now being heard, but rather the appointment of a
special state prosecutor to handle such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Others have their own issues. Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough
president and candidate for mayor, was among those who said that
the performance of Vasquez and company showed the need for better
police training and supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer and others are also not about to let the mayor off the
hook for disregarding his own advice on Day 1 of the Dorismond
affair, which was to urge ``everyone not to jump to conclusions.''
In nothing flat, Giuliani then embarked on a campaign of
mercilessly tearing the dead man down, even releasing (possibly
unlawfully) Dorismond's sealed record as a juvenile offender.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor would have done well, many say, to bite his tongue and
let the system prove on its own that it can work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
