<SLUG> BC-BBA-BORCHARD-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORCHARD SIGNS WITH WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW KREDELL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After a little encouragement from his friends and
teammates at Stanford, former Camarillo High two-sport star Joe
Borchard signed with the Chicago White Sox on Friday for the
largest signing bonus offered to a first-round pick this year.
</P>
<P>
   Borchard, the projected starting quarterback on the Cardinal
football team, gives up football as part of the deal, which
includes a team-record $5.3 million bonus to be paid over 2 years.
Borchard, the 12th overall pick in last month's draft, was
struggling between playing football for Stanford or baseball for
the White Sox while agent Jim McDowell and Chicago worked on a
contract. But when McDowell called Thursday with the latest offer,
Borchard was forced to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Borchard went to the birthday party of
Stanford tight end Darin Naatjess and told his friends and
teammates of the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my call at that point,'' Borchard said during a
conference call Friday. ``So I dropped it on my buddies at the
party and their reaction really helped. They said I would be crazy
to turn that down and they were absolutely right.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox made the big offer with the condition that the
6-foot-4, 225-pound switch-hitting outfielder not play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want those big guys chasing him around on the
field,'' Chicago general manager Ron Schueler said. ``I wanted the
commitment (to give up football), and that's what we were after. If
he did both of them, it could be a distraction. I would rather him
put his effort completely into baseball right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox are in town playing the Angels over the weekend.
Schueler said he plans to have Borchard at the game Sunday,
possibly to take part in batting practice with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Schueler said he wants Borchard to report to Tucson for rookie
ball in the Arizona League on Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball summoned clubs to a pre-draft meeting,
where the league discussed curbing escalating bonus payments. No. 1
pick Adrian Gonzalez received a $3 million signing bonus from
Florida, formerly the largest given out this season.
</P>
<P>
   Borchard batted .333 with 21 home runs for Stanford this spring,
as the Cardinal advanced to the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   He sat behind current Washington Redskins rookie Todd Husak at
quarterback last season but was expected to be the starter this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to get this done; it had been dragged on long
enough,'' Borchard said. ''It is good to get it done now rather
than two days before (the college football season).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
