A6733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NAPSTER-NYT &LR;      07-29 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NAPSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COPYRIGHT IN THE AGE OF NAPSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   The record industry, struggling against rampant unauthorized
downloading of copyrighted music on the Internet, cheered when it
got a preliminary injunction this week against Napster Inc., the
Internet music directory service.
</P>
<P>
   But the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals swiftly stayed the
injunction issued by U.S. District Judge Marilyn Patel. The appeals
court, noting that substantial new legal questions had been raised
in this case, has scheduled oral argument for September. In the
meantime, Napster will continue operating.
</P>
<P>
   This case represents only the beginning of the legal and
technological challenge to maintain the legitimate right of
artists, writers, scholars and corporations to reap economic
benefits from the intellectual property that they create, whether
in real space or cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The protection of copyrights is vital to the health of a free
and creative society. It is not simply an economic issue, though
many enterprises, this newspaper included, rely on copyright
protection. The society at large benefits when the law assures that
the creation of new art, writing or other intellectual property is
rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   To defend that principle in cyberspace, the courts, Congress and
information industries must find ways to sustain and adapt
copyright law without stifling the development of new technologies.
This will be no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 million people have downloaded Napster's software
program, which allows users to find and exchange music files
directly with the computers of other users. Napster does not keep
or control the music files, but provides a directory of files that
tells users what is available to be shared by other users who are
online at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of music being downloaded this way is
copyrighted. But the record companies could not in any practical
way sue the millions of Napster users who they say are illegally
copying the music.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs instead sued Napster for contributory copyright
infringement, on the grounds that the service makes it possible for
the wholesale infringement to occur. On Wednesday, Patel agreed and
issued an immediate injunction prohibiting Napster from enabling
its users to download copyrighted music.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction left Napster free to offer its services for
noncopyrighted works, but Napster's lawyers said that the service
could not distinguish between copyrighted music files and
noncopyrighted files. The appeals court granted it an emergency
stay of that injunction.
</P>
<P>
   Patel's interpretation of copyright protection under existing
law seems reasonable, but she acknowledged in her oral ruling that
it was hard to make a ``neat fit'' in applying copyright law to
cases involving new technology.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1984 Sony Betamax case, the Supreme Court ruled that Sony
could not be prohibited from making and selling VCRs because the
machines were ``capable of substantial noninfringing uses'' even
though they could be illegally used. That decision opened the way
to a booming video business that has benefited the movie industry
plaintiffs in the Sony case. Ultimately the courts will have to
determine whether Napster technology has legitimate uses.
</P>
<P>
   Even a legal victory against Napster will not shield the
recording industry from Internet infringement. Newer technology
such as Gnutella and Freenet allow Napster-like
computer-to-computer file sharing without a central list manager.
These programs also enable users to engage in widespread copyright
infringement, but since there is no central server, there is no
company to sue. Yet they offer potential benefits _ such as more
efficient content searches _ that could be extremely important for
the Internet's development.
</P>
<P>
   In the digital era, enforcement of copyrights may depend as much
on new technological answers as on court sanctions. In the next few
years, the recording industry and other content creators may find
that adding anti-copying features to digital material and
developing whole new ways to sell their products and services to
users will become primary to protecting intellectual property
online.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
