<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PARK AT BROOKLYN BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 29:
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn's ragged waterfront has long taunted civic leaders,
developers and ordinary dreamers with the possibility of a
shoreline park with stunning views of Manhattan and the New York
harbor. Now, for the first time in decades, a reasonable plan has
managed to win the support of various neighborhood and political
groups. The proposal for a 70-acre strip of parkland and commercial
space called Brooklyn Bridge Park has also won approval and a big
piece of the funding from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The next important step is for Gov. George Pataki, who likes the
general idea of a shoreline park, to come stand on a lonely quay,
imagine green walkways instead of Port Authority eyesores and give
the project his weighty stamp of approval.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn park enthusiasts have seen more than a few
disappointments over the years, with one plan dying of political
intrigue and another expiring under the weight of public outcry
about an overbearing waterfront hotel. The development of this
latest plan, financed with seed money from the state, included so
much public participation that the vast majority of community
groups support it enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few opponents with rather narrow concerns, like
residents of one street who want to erect an iron gate barring any
pedestrians trying to walk to the park through their neighborhood.
But there are also more legitimate worries that this park, which
includes a hotel and other commercial ventures, creates a
burdensome new requirement that future urban parks must be
sustained by private or commercial support.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Brooklyn's developers still need to work with the
city and state to create a reasonable administrative structure to
manage this shoreline park with both public and commercial areas.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an impossible task, given the successful creation of
a management structure for the bigger and more ambitious Hudson
River Park. But at this stage the governor needs to publicly commit
the staff, energy and funds necessary to convert 1.3 miles of
rusted shoreline into an open waterfront promenade that he and
Giuliani can claim as a durable part of their legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
