<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-CHARGES-LADN </SLUG>
 
RAMPART OFFICER FACES 6 CHARGES &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the most serious case yet filed in the LAPD's
Rampart Division scandal, the partner of rogue cop Rafael Perez was
arrested Friday near his home early Friday and charged with
attempted murder, robbery and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Nino Durden, who has been on administrative leave from the Los
Angeles Police Department, is the LAPD officer his partner fingered
to be charged since a plea agreement reached last fall allowed
Perez, the anti-gang officer turned informant, to get a five-year
sentence for stealing cocaine from the department.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious charge against Durden, who faces up to 46 years
in prison if convicted on all counts, stems from the shooting of an
unarmed man who was left crippled from his injuries and sent to
prison on planted evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he's one big fish,'' District Attorney Gil Garcetti
said in an interview. ``Is he the biggest fish? Maybe. Clearly,
he's a main target, if not the main target.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti said prosecutors have corroborating evidence or
testimony to back up Perez's allegations against Durden. Perez's
credibility has been strained by his admissions of perjury and
failures to pass lie detector tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have corroboration - we believe we have it,''
Garcetti said, adding the case still poses challenges. ``No case
against a police officer is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Oaks attorney Darryl Mounger said Durden intends to
plead not guilty to the six-count charge at an arraignment
scheduled for Monday. Durden was taken to Los Angeles County Jail,
where bail was set at $680,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mounger said he hasn't seen the prosecutors' case, but that he
can show Perez to be a liar in other matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's told so many stories in his life, he doesn't know what's
true,'' Mounger said.
</P>
<P>
   Mounger accused the LAPD of double-crossing his client after it
originally was agreed Durden could turn himself in as other Rampart
officers did. Instead, police arrested Durden as he and three
passengers were driving near his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They broke their word. I think they showed how this case is a
circus,'' Mounger said.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish said Durden was arrested only
after police determined he had been tipped off and officers became
afraid he'd flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some actions by him caused concern and required the department
to serve the arrest warrant,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious charge is the attempted murder of Javier
Francisco Ovando on Oct. 12, 1996. Perez told investigators as part
of his plea deal that he and Durden both fired at the unarmed man,
and that they later planted a semiautomatic, assault-type rifle on
him.
</P>
<P>
   Ovando was sentenced to 23 years and four months in prison but
was released last year. He is suing the city.
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript of Perez's testimony, he heard Durden
cursing at someone during a stakeout in an abandoned apartment
building. When he turned around, he saw Durden raise his gun and
fire a shot. Perez then fired three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Durden walks out the door for a few minutes, and then he
returns with a gun wrapped in a red, very dirty shirt. Very few
words are said,'' Perez told investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, takes the weapon - holding the rag and the weapon, and
drops it from chest level down to the ground and lets it fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said the .22-caliber rifle had been secured by the
officers a couple of weeks before. They had run the gun on a
computer, and then Durden had filed off the identification numbers
to cover their tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Ovando told authorities that Perez grabbed him by the shirt, and
put a gun to his head. While Ovando screamed, ``I don't want to
die,'' Perez pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Perez has denied that.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he and Durden turned dirty in the spring of 1987. He
said he never liked or trusted his partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was cheating me on top of cheating everybody else,'' Perez
told investigators.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed Durden led their criminal enterprises, stealing
thousands of dollars in cocaine and other drugs, giving drugs to
informants, selling drugs on the street, taking guns and then
planting them on victims.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those allegations are not contained in the complaint
which charges Durden with second-degree robbery, filing false
reports and perjury under oath.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
