<HEADLINE>
FOR CHANG, L.A. IS STILL THE PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At 28, Michael Chang is in the September of his
tennis career. He's won 33 ATP titles, amassed almost $20 million
in prize money and been as high as No. 2 in the world, but that
Michael Chang is a lot different from the one we know now.
</P>
<P>
   His slump over the past 2 years has been so severe - he hasn't
won since October 1998 and he's since humbled himself by playing
Challenger matches - that he's openly considered calling it a day.
</P>
<P>
   But performing in Los Angeles always has invigorated Chang, who
won here in 1996 and appeared in three finals from 1989-93.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after beating Wayne Ferreira 6-3, 7-6 (9-7) in Friday's
Mercedes-Benz Cup quarterfinal, Chang suddenly has the inside track
for a long overdue triumph at UCLA's L.A. Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days I've felt like I reached the point of brokeness,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Chang's first two victories this week, he showed flashes of
that same tenacity and consistency that originally brought him to
the forefront. Against Ferreira, Chang left a lot of us believing
he's all the way back: the crisp ground strokes, the timely
volleys, the extra oomph during key moments.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer has a choice but to look at his career as one match
at a time; he took that same mindset into the Ferreira match,
worrying about one !ital!swing!off! at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely was just trying to hang in there,'' he said.
``The only thing I was concentrating on was the next point. I never
looked at the whole. It was tight and every point was crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Such concentration worked in the tiebreaker. Chang was down 5-3,
two points away from going to a third set against a hungry
adversary who had never beaten Chang in six previous matchups.
Chang won three of the next four points and eventually surged to an
8-7 lead on an ace and a service point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never let me do anything,'' Ferreira said. ``He just kept
getting a lot of balls back. He was solid and consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Any success Chang had over Ferreira in the past had nothing to
do with Friday's approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every match is different,'' Chang said. ``If I think it's
gonna be a piece of cake, I'll get steamrolled. We've had some
tough matches and today was no exception. He's a dangerous player
and a shot maker. I think he just got out of his groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in Chang's way today is upstart Justin Gimbelstob, the
unseeded former UCLA star who came through with the tournament's
biggest upset, a three-set victory over top-seeded Mark
Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's never played Philippoussis, but considering it's Chang's
chance to return to the limelight, he's not choosy about who he
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played Justin but I've practiced against him often,
and I know it's not going to be easy,'' Chang said. ``He's got a
big serve and he covers the net well. We'll just have to wait and
find out what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang is sniffing a victory, even if he won't admit it. Today
marks the third time he's made it to the semifinals in what is
turning out to be a mini-comeback even without a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would feel great to win. It's been a while,'' he said.
``But there's still a ways to go and they're all tough players. I
can't take anyone lightly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
