<HEADLINE>
MAKESHIFT RANGERS HAVEN'T GIVEN UP ON PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Every indication screams that the Texas
Rangers' season is over.
</P>
<P>
   Their best player, 1999 American League MVP Ivan Rodriguez,
watches the games from a luxury suite with a cast on his broken
thumb. General manager Doug Melvin has begun unloading the team's
high-priced talent, trading designated hitter David Segui and his
.336 batting average to Cleveland before Friday night's game. The
pitching staff is dotted with young arms barely out of the minors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers keep breathing anyway. With the replacements for
Rodriguez and Segui powering an offense that cranked out 14 hits,
the Rangers slammed the Detroit Tigers, 11-5, Friday night at The
Ballpark in Arlington for their fourth consecutive victory since
Rodriguez was injured Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Rangers stayed 81/2 games behind AL
West-leading Seattle and moved within 41/2 games of Oakland,
currently the leader in the wild-card race. And while nobody is
ready to declare them contenders just yet, the Rangers have made it
clear they are not ready to concede anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of games left,'' said Rick Helling
(12-7), who pitched six innings to earn the victory. ``We're
professional baseball players for a reason. We all have the will to
win and the competitiveness to get the job done. Regardless of the
situation, regardless of who gets traded or who gets hurt, it's
still our job to go out there and win games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good enough team right now to go out and win games
and make things interesting at least. There's still 61 games left.
That's a lot of season. It's not impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if the Rangers continue hitting the way they did Friday
night, when they buried Tigers starter Brian Moehler (6-7) with an
eight-run third inning that put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   The big blow of the inning was a bases-loaded double off the bat
of Bill Haselman, the veteran backup catcher who has filled in
brilliantly in Rodriguez's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have insurance policies, and that's what he is for
us,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``A family is not excited
about cashing their policy, but they're glad they have it. We're
not happy about losing Pudge, but we're very glad we have Haselman.
This is exactly what we expected from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates also got a lift from Frank Catalanotto, who replaced Segui
at DH at the last minute and bashed a solo home run in the second,
and Gabe Kapler, who added two hits, a run and a run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive night, the Rangers were victimized
early by their former teammates. This time, Juan Gonzalez was
joined by designated hitter Dean Palmer, who gave the Tigers a 3-0
lead by following Gonzalez's first-inning double with a homer to
center. But the Rangers closed the gap to 3-2 with a run-scoring
double by Rafael Palmeiro and Catalanotto's home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers sent 12 batters to the plate in the third, pounding
out eight hits to tie the season high for an inning. The eight runs
were the most the Rangers had scored in an inning since Sept. 25,
when they scored eight in the second against Oakland. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
