<HEADLINE>
NEW GUARDS CAN BOOST THEIR STOCK ON COWBOYS' THIN OFFENSIVE LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ For Jorge Diaz and Kelvin Garmon, the
starters at right and left guard, respectively, against the
Pittsburgh Steelers tomorrow, the Cowboys' preseason opener is all
about perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz is a veteran who was signed as a free agent in the
off-season to be a backup before being thrust into the spotlight by
tackle Erik Williams' holdout/retirement. Diaz, who fills in as
Solomon Page moves to Williams' spot, is looking to prove he can
handle the job after some shaky workouts early in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to come here and be a starter anyway,'' Diaz said.
``Whether I was backing up or starting, my approach was going to be
same. The only thing that changes now is the sense of urgency to
get things down pat. We are in game situations now. I can't let no
one touch \Rquarterback Troy Aikman\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Garmon, the former Haltom High School standout who is starting
in place of the injured Larry Allen, is just happy to be on the
field again. He sat out last season with a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good,'' Garmon said. ``It's taken a long time for me
to realize my dream of being able to suit up and play in Texas
Stadium in front of my family. It's what I've been working for.''
</P>
<P>
   Garmon's and Diaz's stories alone are worthy of attention
heading into the Steelers game. But add in the Cowboys' jumbled
guard situation, which has been in flux since the first day of
training camp, and coach Dave Campo said both players and anybody
else who suits up at guard will be under an intense microscope
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural to look at guys who are playing in place of other
people,'' Campo said. ``And that's a position we would look at
anyway. That is an area we are concerned with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' plans of starting Page at right guard have been put
on hold by Williams' absence. Page's move to right tackle left Diaz
battling veteran backup Tony Hutson at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   That battle, however, has been limited by Hutson's recovery from
off-season knee surgery. He participates in only one practice a day
at training camp and will not play against the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   And though the team is confident about Diaz because of his
starting experience in Tampa Bay the past four years, his daily
struggles against Cowboys defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman haven't
helped the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The guard position took another hit this week when rookie free
agent James Tenner (broken hand) and second-year guard/center Chris
Brymer (sprained knee) joined Allen on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the Cowboys will try to sign a player or two for
depth purposes in the next week. However, he said they will go with
whom they have against Steelers, which means that Diaz, Garmon and
rookie free agents Al Jackson and George Hudson will log a lot of
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   The extra duty is fine with the 6-foot-4, 315-pound Diaz, who
acknowledges being frustrated with his practice performances. While
he partly blames his struggles on Spellman's sheer dominance, he
said differing techniques coached in Dallas compared with Tampa Bay
also is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything here is different, the way we pass-block people and
the timing with the way we run the ball,'' Diaz said. ``It's just
like readjusting yourself and starting over again.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Cowboys are being supportive, pointing to Diaz's
experience and lauding his perseverance. However, considering their
high expectations for the season, the Cowboys are bound to lose
patience if Diaz struggles in games as he does in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz agrees, saying: ``The games are what's important. That's
how you find out if someone can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Just being able to practice, let alone play in game, is a
triumph in itself for Garmon, who was injured as a senior at Baylor
in 1998. The Cowboys selected him in the seventh round of the 1999
draft, though they knew he would not be healthy until this season.
</P>
<P>
   Garmon, still rusty after the layoff, has been one of the
biggest surprises in camp. He has been singled out for praise by
Campo and offensive line coach Hudson Houck.
</P>
<P>
   Garmon said his teammates are also taking notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year everybody just looked at me rehabbing,'' said
Garmon, who knows he has no chance of supplanting the All-Pro Allen
and is just trying to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know I could play. Now they are talking to me.
They respect me now. It feels good.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
