<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DEAL SEGUI FOR LEDEE, MAY KEEP WETTELAND AFTER ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Earlier this week, David Segui said he was
certain that he would be traded. His prediction came true Friday
when the Rangers traded the designated hitter/first baseman to the
Cleveland Indians for one-time top prospect Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, who is expected to join the club Sunday, will replace the
platoon of Dave Martinez and Chad Curtis in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an opportunity to get a young player who can be with us
next year,'' general manager Doug Melvin said. ``With him and Rusty
(Greer) and Gabe (Kapler), we've got a chance to have a good, young
outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal does not necessarily signal the start of the
dismantling of the team. It might be the Rangers' only major trade
before the nonwaivers deadline on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is listening to offers for closer John Wetteland, who
like Segui can become a free agent at the end of the season, but
it's no longer certain he'll also be leaving town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I'm a little less motivated at this time to move
John,'' Melvin said. ``He's a big part of this ballclub. He does
bring veteran leadership to this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland still could be traded for the right deal, but although
several clubs have called and expressed interest in the reliever,
that deal isn't currently on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just going to give John Wetteland away,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The GM also said that although next year's outfield appears
overly crowded if Ruben Mateo comes back from his broken leg, he
isn't trying to deal Ledee or any of the incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to turn him around, and I'm not going to trade
Rusty Greer or Gabe Kapler,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible Martinez or Curtis, the two veterans who now
become extra players, could be traded, but Melvin said he doesn't
have anything working with either one.
</P>
<P>
   There were two other offers for Segui, but Ledee fit the
description of the type of player Melvin was looking for. He wanted
players on the verge of making it to the majors, or young players
already in the majors, rather than prospects in the low minors.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee fits that description. He's 26 years old, and in his third
season in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee once was considered one of the best outfield prospects in
the game, but has yet to fulfill that promise. He's hitting .254
with 19 homers and 91 RBI in 209 games in his brief career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not established in the big leagues, it's going to
happen,'' Ledee said of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   He had the opportunity to win the Yankees' left-field job in the
spring, but failed to seize it. He batted .241 with seven homers
and 31 RBI in 62 games as a part-timer, and was traded to the
Indians on June 29 in a package for David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   He batted .222 with two homers and eight RBI in 16 games with
the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, still like his potential. When Melvin
presented the deal to Oates, the manager urged him to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside of Ricky is very exciting,'' Oates said. ``This is
a guy who has a chance to be an outstanding major-league player for
a lot of years.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee is signed for the remainder of this season, after which he
will be eligible for arbitration. But as a player with less than
six years of major-league service, Ledee's contract is under club
control for the next three years. Segui's contract this year was
for $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto is expected to get most of Segui's at-bats at
DH, perhaps platooning with Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get more at-bats because of it,'' Oates said. ``The
trade opens more opportunities to get Cat into the lineup.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
