<HEADLINE>
JUAN GONZALEZ WON'T DECIDE FUTURE UNTIL SEASON ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers general manager Doug Melvin slammed
the door in outfielder Juan Gonzalez's face Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will not pursue the two-time American League MVP as
a free agent this winter, according to Tigers general manager Randy
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't bother me,'' said Gonzalez, who yesterday spoke
to selected members of the Fort Worth/Dallas media for the first
time since his return to The Ballpark in Arlington. ``I'm here to
play baseball. I'm not here for Doug. I'm not here for other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Gonzalez would not eliminate the possibility of returning
to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All doors are open,'' said Gonzalez, who captured those two
MVP awards with the Rangers before being traded to the Tigers
nearly nine months ago. ``If the Rangers have an interest in me,
I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith spoke with Melvin on Thursday and said the Rangers ``have
no interest in bringing \RGonzalez\S back on a multiyear contract,
and \RMelvin\S said I could say that publicly.'' Melvin
acknowledged his conversation with Smith, but he declined to
divulge its nature.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Gonzalez glowed while describing Thursday's
emotion-filled return to The Ballpark. Gonzalez received a mixed
reaction from the crowd before stepping to the plate for his first
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably one of the best, exciting moments of my career
to this point,'' Gonzalez said. ``It was great. I'll never forget
that moment. I know the fans like me here. The fans understand that
Juan didn't trade himself. The team traded Juan.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade stung Gonzalez, and several players _ including first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro and catcher Ivan Rodriguez _ have suggested
the Rangers attempt to re-sign the outfielder this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt my pride a little bit because when I played for the
Rangers, I did the best I could inside the lines for the great
fans, the organization and for myself,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Gonzalez acknowledged that the trade was a business
decision and praised the Rangers for his 14 years with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for the great opportunity to play professional
baseball,'' he said. ``Thank you for the opportunity to play in the
big leagues. Thank you for the opportunity to make a lot of money.
Thank you for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   So, where will Gonzalez report next spring?
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez rejected a seven-year contract worth $123 million with
an option for an eighth season from the Tigers earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Tigers offered the great contract, I'd never been
there in Detroit,'' said Gonzalez, who likely will not draw that
type of offer this winter. ``I didn't know about the city. You need
to see it before you make the big decision. Money is good, but
money is not everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez called a return to the Tigers his ``No. 1 option,'' but
mainly because the organization is the only one eligible to
negotiate with him until two weeks after the conclusion of the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made the big decision already,'' Gonzalez said.
``I'll make the big decision after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also defended his friend and confidant, Luis Mayoral,
who has been portrayed by some in the media as his puppet master.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a man,'' Gonzalez said. ``I'm 30 years old, and I have
initiative and my own mind. I don't need a baby sitter. I make my
own decisions, but I have a great relationship with Luis, like
father and son or a brother. Luis never makes my decisions. I make
my decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Smith, the Rangers already have made one for
Gonzalez.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
