<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-BRUSHBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRABTREE SAYS BRUSH WITH GONZALEZ `NOT PERSONAL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right fielder Juan Gonzalez's emotional
return to The Ballpark in Arlington nearly escalated into a brawl
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd wait for him anywhere,'' Gonzalez said of Rangers
right-hander Tim Crabtree, whose first pitch of the seventh inning
nearly hit the two-time American League MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Rangers traded me, he made comments in the paper,''
Gonzalez added. ``I don't talk behind anybody. I talk face to face.
A real man talks face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree told reporters this winter that Gonzalez ``was (the
Tigers') problem now,'' but the reliever said he was referring to
the outfielder's contract status.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might think it's personal,'' Crabtree said. ``It's not
personal for me. I'm not trying to hit anyone. I feel if I hit
anyone, I can seriously hurt someone. ... I wasn't trying to hit
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree's first-pitch sinker bore in on Gonzalez, but did not
hit him. Gonzalez approached the mound before being restrained by
Rangers catcher Bill Haselman. Both benches emptied, but no punches
were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez yelled at Crabtree, and ``and all hell broke loose,''
Crabtree said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I became a man,'' Crabtree said. ``I was in
front of 40,000 people, and he started jawing at me. I guess my ego
took over. Juan is a great player. He's done a lot of great things.
He's also with the Detroit Tigers now, and I need to get him out.
That's all.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
