<HEADLINE>
BIG 12 NORTH'S LITTLE THREE HOPE FOR BREAKTHROUGH SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Being upwardly mobile typically requires
talent, hard work and luck. Unless, of course, you're a team in the
lower half of the Big 12 Conference North Division. Then all that
striving turns into surviving.
</P>
<P>
   If preseason predictions are accurate, Nebraska, Kansas State
and Colorado are the North's Big Three. Kansas, Iowa State and
Missouri are the Little Three. With seven bowl slots guaranteed to
Big 12 teams, the race is basically to finish fourth in the North.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conference has done a great job in securing postseason
play for seven teams, so the incentive is here,'' Iowa State coach
Dan McCarney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're good enough to be in the top three,'' Kansas
running back Moran Norris said at this week's Big 12 media
meetings. ``We came close last year and this year we can smell it.
We're trying to do it all this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's what the Cyclones and the Tigers believe. Three into
one won't go. Players and coaches for Kansas, Iowa State and
Missouri should be watching ``Survivor'' to gain some tips on how
to stay on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could very well have a better team and our record would not
reflect that,'' Jayhawks coach Terry Allen said. ``We're being
optimistic, but we also have to be realistic. There are no foregone
conclusions and we think we can sneak in to one of those top three
spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be a darn good football team and finish fourth and
feel pretty good about what you've accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   But before the first pads pop in August, optimism beats realism
like rock beats scissors.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas was 5-7 last season, Iowa State and Missouri were 4-7.
All three figure record reversals are possible. Assuming none of
the Big Three fall, two teams are going to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expects to lose right now,'' Missouri junior defensive
end Justin Smith said. ``Somebody's going to be right and
somebody's going to be wrong. We want to wind up being right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of guys on the roster who have been on winning
teams and know it's an attainable goal.''
</P>
<P>
   In four previous Big 12 seasons, only Missouri has broken
through the glass ceiling, finishing third in 1997 and 1998. That
recent success shows that for the North's ``other'' teams, moving
up is possible. However, in the 1990s, Kansas, Iowa State and
Missouri combined for six winning seasons, a 113-182-8 record and
five bowl trips.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Smith is entering his seventh season as Missouri's coach.
McCarney is entering his sixth season at Iowa State. Allen is in
his fourth season. The Tigers' rebuilding was rewarded with bowl
trips in '97 and '98. The Cyclones and the Jayhawks have yet to
have breakthrough seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Little Three, Iowa State gets a break with Missouri and
Kansas coming to Ames, Iowa. Kansas plays both Missouri and Iowa
State on the road. Missouri is at home against Kansas and plays at
Iowa State. The Cyclones' non-conference schedule is the tamest of
the three.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas had a 9-0 halftime lead against Nebraska. Iowa State had
a 28-7 halftime lead on Kansas State before losing. And, while the
Cyclones lost their last five games, three came by a total of 10
points. Close losses to top teams give losing programs hope, even
if it might be false hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can play with \RNebraska\S and we think we can play
with anyone,'' Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so close last year,'' Iowa State senior quarterback
Sage Rosenfels said. ``We were right there in some games and should
have won some of those games. We just need to make a few more
plays, get a few bounces go our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches despise relying on fate. But for either Missouri, Kansas
or Iowa State to have a winning season and reach a bowl game, good
luck is a prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has injuries,'' said McCarney, whose team's goal is
the school's first bowl game since 1978. ``But for teams like us,
we can't afford to lose certain players. You need to have some
luck. That can make a difference between a winning and losing
season.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
