<HEADLINE>
PITCHING SAVES METS FROM THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The left side of the New York Mets infield will be
overhauled Saturday, when Mike Bordick arrives from Baltimore to
play shortstop and Robin Ventura returns from the disabled list to
reclaim his third-base job.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is a Gold Glover, and Bordick may be the best fielder
who has not won one. Asked what he brings to a team, Bordick said:
``In the field, hopefully just consistency. That's what I've
strived for my whole career _ make the plays when the ball's hit to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will welcome that, because they know they cannot win
many more games the way they have the last two days. The Mets made
seven errors on Thursday but swept a doubleheader against the
Expos, and they beat the St. Louis Cardinals at Shea Stadium Friday
night, 3-2, despite two more errors in the late innings, one by
third baseman Lenny Harris and the other by shortstop Kurt Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets prevailed because of the pitching of Al Leiter and
three relievers, and one pickoff move. Leiter (11-4) worked seven
innings, striking out eight and allowing a run on three hits. The
bullpen _ which will also get a boost Saturday when the newly
acquired setup man Rick White arrives from Tampa Bay _ secured the
victory, with Armando Benitez earning his 24th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals trailed, 3-1, in the seventh when Eduardo Perez
hit a hard grounder in the hole between third and short. Abbott
ranged to his right and could not come up with the ball; it was
unjustly scored an error, manager Bobby Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The bases were loaded, and Leiter thought back two starts, to a
loss at Toronto. Frustrated with the umpire's ball-strike calls,
Leiter had grooved a pitch with the bases loaded and given up a
grand slam. This time, he stayed tough, striking out Mike Matheney
and inducing the pinch-hitter Craig Paquette to pop out, ending the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that thought in my mind _ I'm not laying anything in
there,'' Leiter said. ``If I walk him, I walk him, but I'm not
giving in.''
</P>
<P>
   John Franco, who had not allowed a run in his last 13
appearances, relieved Leiter to start the eighth. But Franco was
not sharp, giving up two singles and retiring one hitter. Turk
Wendell came on to face the Cardinals' clean-up hitter, Fernando
Tatis, with runners at the corners. It was the perfect occasion for
Wendell's signature pickoff move, faking to third and then throwing
to first.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell perfected it three springs ago when the former pitching
coach Bob Apodaca told him his third-to-first move was horrible.
Taking the challenge, Wendell spent 20 minutes in the bullpen that
day, working solely on that move. Now, he picks off several runners
a year that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I do it, I chuckle _ there you go, 'Dac,'' Wendell
said. ``I might want to send him a videotape.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell had picked off a Montreal runner doing that on Thursday,
and he did it again Friday night, faking to third and spinning to
first to freeze Jim Edmonds, who crawled right into Todd Zeile's
tag for the second out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis grounded to third, where Harris bobbled the ball, allowing
Fernando Vina to score to cut the Mets' lead to 3-2. But Wendell
blew a fastball by Eric Davis to end the inning, escaping further
harm.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets got all their runs in the second inning. Mike Piazza
hit a leadoff single, and Zeile followed with a walk. Benny
Agbayani then drove a pitch off the wall in right-center field,
scoring Piazza. A Jay Payton groundout brought in Zeile, and Abbott
flied to shallow center field.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds caught it and fired to home plate, where the bulky
Agbayani was bearing down on the catcher, Matheney. Edmonds' throw
took one hop and bounced off Matheney's body; a moment later,
Agbayani barreled into home.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds was credited with an assist, Matheney was charged with
an error and Agbayani's run gave the Mets a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for Leiter, who snapped a personal three-start
losing streak and said he has overcome a ``dead-arm'' phase and had
probably his best stuff of the year Friday night. Valentine agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he threw as well as he's thrown all year,''
Valentine said. ``He was determined, free, he threw all his pitches
for strikes. It was a terrific effort by him, as well as by Turk
and Armando.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
