<HEADLINE>
LESS WORK COULD MEAN MORE FOR TEXAS RUNNING BACK HODGES MITCHELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In order for Texas tailback Hodges Mitchell
to play a more prominent role during the stretch run this season,
coaches plan to see less of him on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's carries will be curtailed, coach Mack Brown said
yesterday, to enable the 5-foot-7, 185-pound senior to return punts
and be at his best in November and December. Last season, Mitchell
led the Longhorns in rushing with 1,343 yards on 256 attempts. He
averaged 5.2 yards per carry and scored nine touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But his two least-productive outings came in the Longhorns'
biggest games: a 22-6 loss to Nebraska in the Big 12 title game and
a 27-6 loss to Arkansas in the Southwestern Bell Cotton Bowl. In
those games, Mitchell combined to rush for 50 yards on 21 carries
(2.4 average). He had no run longer than 8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find someone to give Hodges some rest. He had to
play too many plays last season,'' Brown said. ``He's a great back,
but he gave out by the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Brown plans to create more playing time for
reserve tailbacks Ivan Williams, Kenny Hayter and Victor Ike.
Mitchell said he's on board with the decision, especially because
it means a return to the punt-return team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing too much when I was tired last year,'' said
Mitchell, who has a career average of 7.3 yards as a punt returner
but relinquished that role last season after cracking the starting
lineup. ``I need to be more of a game-breaking back, and you can't
do that when you're not fresh. I know I've got guys behind me who
can get the job done. I learned how to trust my fellow running
backs this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his small stature, Mitchell said his best opportunity
to turn the heads of NFL scouts rests with his skills as a punt
returner. Also, he conceded that Williams (6-1, 236 pounds) and
Hayter (5-11, 215) are better suited for running between the
tackles. Mitchell, meanwhile, operates best on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to enhance his elusiveness, the Dallas native has
lost 5 pounds since last season and hopes to trim to 181 by the
team's Sept. 9 opener against Louisiana-Lafayette. Mitchell said he
does not mind the reduced workload because he knows he's entrenched
as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My carries will go down a little bit. That's not a problem,''
said Mitchell, who also caught 32 passes for 342 yards last season.
``I'll get more touches on special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he had ``no idea'' about an optimum number of
snaps he'll play each game. His marching orders, he said, are
simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I get tired, I'll come out. If the coaches feel they
need a change of pace, they'll take me out. That's OK,'' Mitchell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who watched his special teams struggle last season, likes
the arrangement as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best teams in the country return kicks and punts,'' Brown
said. ``Last year, I had to tell our punt-return team it wasn't
against the rules to return one farther than six yards. There
seemed to be some confusion about that. I think that's an area
where Hodges can really help us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
