<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' PLAN FOR PRESEASON OPENER: GO VERY BASIC, AVOID INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ As with any first preseason game, the
Cowboys have their share of mixed feelings about playing the
Pittsburgh Steelers tomorrow night at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In these early preseason games, NFL veteran players are just
trying to come away injury-free while coaches are trying to avoid
tipping their hand too much for when the games really count,
beginning Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is just going in there ``not'' to show anything,
proving once again that preseason is too long,'' quarterback Troy
Aikman said yesterday on the final full practice day of training
camp at Midwestern State University until Aug. 8, because of the
upcoming Tokyo trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to move the football against Pittsburgh _ I mean,
that's the objective _ yet we're doing it with a pretty scaled-back
version,'' Aikman said. ``I'm sure that \Rthe Steelers\S
defensively will scale back some of the things they will be doing
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones is aware that there is always a risk of
injury] in early preseason games because both rosters have an
optimum disparity of 1) highly paid veteran players and 2)
overzealous, young long shots.
</P>
<P>
   With Aikman slated to take 10 snaps, Jones said, ``We should be
thinking about protection ... leaving some \Rblockers\S in, if
there's any question at all. I want to protect Randall Cunningham
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is the Cowboys' highest-paid player at a little more than
$6 million a year. Cunningham will make $1 million this season as
Aikman's backup.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' starting guards are Jorge Diaz and Kelvin Garmon.
Solomon Page gets his first NFL start at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have to play some guys a little longer than they'd
normally play because we're banged up there,'' coach Dave Campo
said. ``We're going to be very generic.'' \Nsubheds:Ekuban goes
left Ebenezer Ekuban will make his first NFL start at left
defensive end. He finished last season at right end for the injured
Greg Ellis (broken leg, Dec. 12).
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, everything is backward,'' said Ekuban, who was a
tight end and primarily a right defensive end at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ekuban has added 90 pounds of strength in the weight
room this off-season, his forte is his speed rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``A right offensive tackle is more of a run blocker, so you
learn to get better angles on him because you know he's going to
sit back more,'' Ekuban said. ``He probably doesn't have the
footwork of a left tackle, or else he would be playing there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban calls his practice partner, Solomon Page, the exception.
The Cowboys' starting right offensive tackle has good footwork for
a 321-pound man. \Nsubheds:Injury update Barron Wortham, who is
competing for the starting middle linebacker job with Dat Nguyen
and Chris Bordano, went down with a knee injury in morning
practice. Wortham was taken to Dallas where he had arthroscopic
surgery on his left knee to repair cartilage damage. He is expected
to be out three to four weeks. Wortham started in 15 games for the
Tennessee Titans last year, including Super Bowl XXXIV. Running
back Emmitt Smith (big-toe sprain) doesn't have a serious injury,
but Dave Campo emphasized yesterday, ``We're going to be really
cautious on that.'' Smith is a game-time decision for tomorrow
night.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
