<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' WETTLELAND PLAYING WAITING GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ AND ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers closer John Wetteland has begun
clearing out his locker in anticipation of a trade before the
nonwaivers deadline Monday.
</P>
<P>
   His guitar, roller blades and most of his personal items are
gone. The only things remaining are his clothes and his Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always bring your stuff back if it doesn't happen,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland might want to bring it back. Rangers GM Doug Melvin
said last night that it's less likely that the closer will be
traded. Although several clubs have called and expressed interest
in acquiring the reliever, Melvin said that deal isn't currently on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clubs that have interest, but for a rent-a-player,
clubs aren't as interested in giving up the kind of players I'm
looking for,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland has made no secret of the fact that he'd like to stay
in Texas but is stoic about a possible deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared, but I'm not resigned to it happening,''
Wetteland said. ``I'm not an emotional guy. You prepare for it one
way or another.'' OFF THE BENCH ... FOR GOOD?
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto made his 22nd start of the season and his
first as a designated hitter for the Rangers on Friday, replacing
David Segui, who was traded before game time. With Segui traded to
Cleveland, Catalanotto is likely to get a chance to play every day,
something he hasn't had all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play him at second (every day) when you've got one
of the best second basemen in the league this year (Luis Alicea),''
manager Johnny Oates said before the trade was announced. ``And
I've got a pretty good DH who's hitting about .350. So if you've
got any suggestions, I'm up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Segui deal allows Oates to get an extended look at
Catalanotto, who was hitting .380 in 49 appearances before last
night's game. But it also takes Catalanotto out of his role as the
American League's premier pinch hitter; his .450 pinch-hit average
leads the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty valuable coming off the bench,'' Oates said.
``It's nice to have that one at-bat whenever you want it every
night. It's like playing poker with a joker on the bottom of the
deck and you can pull it out whenever you want it. He's the best
player I've ever had coming off the bench, by far.'' MR.
VERSATILITY
</P>
<P>
   Shane Halter's .255 batting average, like the rest of his
statistics, is unremarkable. But the Tigers' utility man is the
major-league leader in versatility. The former University of Texas
player has played all nine positions in his three-year major-league
career _ eight of them this year. In fact, he has appeared this
season as a defensive replacement at six different positions
(first, second, third, shortstop, right field and catcher).
</P>
<P>
   The only spot Halter hasn't filled in 2000 is pitcher, and he's
already dropped hints to manager Phil Garner that he'd be available
to work an inning in a blowout. The Detroit newspapers have begun
lobbying to let him play all nine spots in a single game, a feat
accomplished only once in big-league history, by Bert Campaneris of
the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' said Halter, who pitched a scoreless
inning for Kansas City in 1998. ``It would be kind of a dream to
play all nine positions in a game, to get my name in the record
books. I just like it that when the manager comes up and asks, `Can
you play there?' I can say, `Yes, I can.' '' PERFECT MEMORY
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the sixth anniversary of the only perfect game
thrown at The Ballpark in Arlington. On July 28, 1994, Kenny
Rogers, in his first stint with the Rangers, retired all 27 Anaheim
Angels in a 4-0 victory. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
