<HEADLINE>
AYALA-TAPIA REMATCH BEING NEGOTIATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ World Boxing Association bantamweight
champion Paulie Ayala of Fort Worth and his management team are
negotiating a rematch with former champion Johnny Tapia scheduled
for October, Boxing Management Inc. president Lester Bedford said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   An Ayala bout scheduled for Aug. 25 at TCU's Daniel-Meyer
Coliseum was canceled because of problems securing the venue,
Bedford said, but BMI is still targeting a fight for Ayala before
the possible rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tapia rematch is a real possibility,'' Bedford said. BMI
chairman Scott Sherman ``is negotiating with Tapia's manager,
Theresa Tapia, and with Top Rank.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, 30, defeated Tapia with a unanimous decision on June 26,
1999, for the WBA title. The match was voted ``Fight of the Year''
and Ayala earned ``Fighter of the Year'' honors from ``The Ring
Magazine''. Ayala defended his title with a unanimous decision
against former WBA No. 1 contender Saohin Condo on Oct. 23, in Fort
Worth and won by majority decision against Johnny Bredahl on March
4 in his most recent bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being discussed, but it has not gone past the preliminary
stages,'' Top Rank spokesman Lee Samuels said. ``There is no
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala (30-1, 12 knockouts) said he chose not to risk his title
on an ABC fight card in June because no opponent was named two
weeks before the fight. After being turned down by featherweight
champion Naseem Hamed for a July bout, Ayala said he is eager to
get back in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't holding out,'' Ayala said. ``Things happen and fights
fall through. I'm the world champion, but things still happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the fans want to see me fight Johnny. I'm sure he wants
to fight me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala made about $120,000 for each of his first two title
defenses. Bedford said a rematch with Tapia will surpass that
amount.
</P>
<P>
   ```This is an opportunity to make more money in a lot more
significant fight,'' Bedford said. ``Paulie could have fought on
August 25th if he wanted to, but we're looking for a major fight.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
