<HEADLINE>
CRUISING ROAD TO GOLD NOT WITHOUT POTHOLES FOR TEAM USA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are roving ambassadors. They are on the road from Central
Park to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, they also bring baggage.
</P>
<P>
   But if the lawyers, arbitrators and bitter former players will
kindly cease and desist, the U.S. Olympic softball team has a
mission to conclude.
</P>
<P>
   The women will stop at Gateway Park in Fort Worth, Texas, on
Saturday night on their way from ``Central Park to Sydney'' _ the
golden brick road, or so they dream.
</P>
<P>
   Despite two months of planes, trains and automobiles, Team USA
continues its scorched-earth march to the Games at Sydney. Four
summers ago, on a similar coast-to-coast pre-Olympic campaign, Team
USA outscored its opposition by a combined 449 runs to 3.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Saturday night's doubleheader, the tour's run
differential is a more humane 252-2.
</P>
<P>
   Gosh, ladies. Anything wrong?
</P>
<P>
   I'm only being partly facetious. For some of us, their 1996
performance _ played out on a field of dreams, of sorts, in
Columbus, Ga. _ was one of the feel-good moments of the Atlanta
Olympics. The home team defeated China, 2-1, to win the gold medal
in front of a sweating, standing-room-only crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The victory inspired uncommon spoils, like the night on David
Letterman's show when the host invited shortstop Dot Richardson out
onto the side street to hit a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could think about was not breaking a window or putting a
dent in a Mercedes or somebody's limo,'' Richardson recalls.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't. But the four years since Atlanta haven't all been
soft stuff from Dave.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Richardson is a full-fledged surgeon now, but no longer
a shortstop. For 2 1/2 years, in fact, the most familiar face from
the 1996 team was told by Team USA that her services were no longer
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very difficult, feeling unwanted,'' Richardson
remembered. ``I was hurt. But I think everything happens for a
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   There are theories about why Richardson was left off the team.
The most likely is that Dot had been a part of the national team
for so long _ she played in the Pan Am Games as a 17-year-old in
1979 _ it was time to push her from the nest and see if both could
function without the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a sign, too, that maybe I should focus on
medicine more,'' said Dr. Richardson, now a practicing orthopedic
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, a funny thing happened while Dr. Dot was off examining
rotator cuffs and kneecaps. Team USA found its veneer of
invincibility shattered, losing to Australia three times.
</P>
<P>
   Something wasn't working. Later, Richardson's teammates would
tell her how much her presence was missed.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson tells a tale from late-1998 about working a 24-hour
shift in the surgical intensive care unit and then having to drive
three hours to San Diego, without sleep, for what could have been
her one last Team USA tryout. If she got sleepy and had to pull
over to the side of the road, Dot decided, it was a sign that it
was time to give up softball.
</P>
<P>
   She made it, wide awake. She's been a part of the team ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been anything but a smooth homecoming. A former
longtime national team player, Julie Smith, was passed over for the
Olympic team and appealed the process that was used to select the
team. Smith reportedly has claimed that she was left off because
coach Ralph Raymond doesn't like her.
</P>
<P>
   When an arbitrator ordered the team re-selected, an alternate
who was dropped from the squad appealed, forcing yet another
arbitrator's ruling that the roster needed to be redrawn again.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, Smith still wasn't on the team. On Thursday
night, in fact, she went 0-for-3 for the professional Ohio Pride in
a 2-0 exhibition loss to the Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Richardson plays in Smith's old position at second
base. Team USA's shortstop is now the power-hitting prodigy Crystyl
Bustos.
</P>
<P>
   The team might not be rapping out the timely singles and doubles
that Raymond would like. But the pitching staff has thrown 35
shutouts in 37 games.
</P>
<P>
   Their so-called ``Central Park to Sydney'' tour has had its
other moments, like the night in Worcester, Mass., when Richardson
was called out of the dugout to assist a fan who had collapsed. The
man, a 70-year-old former softball umpire, had stopped breathing
and showed no pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson gave him CPR and then stayed with the man until the
ambulance drove away. Later, Dot and the team learned that the man
died.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that kind of tour.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, it will be a stern test for the U.S. women to repeat
against the hometown Aussies. But as Richardson said, they like
their chances, and those who go to see them Saturday at Gateway
Park should be similarly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Now playing shortstop, Crystl Bustos. Park your limos at your
own risk. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
