<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGERS GET VICTORY BY DESIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This is what the Los Angeles Dodgers thought they
had last season, and what they hoped would eventually shine through
this one. Not just a dynamic one-two combo in starting pitching,
but a third wheel as well.
</P>
<P>
   It's also what the Dodgers need after the Arizona Diamondbacks
got Curt Schilling. They need the development of Chan Ho Park and
Darren Dreifort to turn into results if postseason aspirations are
to remain.
</P>
<P>
   And the seven innings of two-hit ball Dreifort (7-7) threw in
Friday's 2-0 Dodgers win against the Philadelphia Phillies is a
continuation of what's been sweet post All-Star success.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was unhittable for five innings, and then battled
through his last two innings before the bullpen worked to design,
with Mike Fetters pitching the eighth and re-crowned Jeff Shaw
closing the ninth for his 16th save.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the second straight outing in which Dreifort allowed
two hits in seven shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we like it Dreif pitching seven, (Fetters)
pitching the eighth and me pitching the ninth,'' Shaw said. ``You
can't write it any better than that, and Dreif, good God! I'll tell
you what. The last two games, he's been unhittable. When he throws
his true slider it just seems to get to the plate and disappear. It
goes straight down.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, Brown and Park are 7-0 in their past seven starts, and
that could improve with Brown and Park set to pitch the final two
games of this series.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (55-47) have won five of six and 10 of 13 and
matched a season-high by being eight games over .500, which they
were May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen (Dreifort) good in spurts before, but his ball was
down all night,'' said Phillies manager Terry Francona. ``We've
seen him good, but tonight, 'Wow.' `'
</P>
<P>
   When Dreifort has problems, as he did during the 10-start
stretch before the All-Star break in which he went 1-6 with a 7.51
ERA, everyone gets so frustrated because of his high ceiling. His
arm is awesome, and overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Davey Johnson said sometimes Dreifort's mentality
works against him. Yet, there are nights like this one against the
Phillies in which Dreifort pitches wonderfully, rather than
throwing uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about overthrowing,'' Johnson said. ``You've got guys
with good arms, and when they come out there and overthrow, it
takes away from their stuff because they can't locate as well. He
likes dominate people and he likes to strike people out.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning his third straight start, Dreifort extended his
scoreless innings streak to 18, dating back to Pittsburgh's Brian
Giles' third-inning home run on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, who walked two and struck out six, didn't allow a hit
until Mickey Morandini's two-out double in the sixth inning, and
his only jam was the seventh. Scott Rolen led off with a single and
Pat Burrell walked, but pinch-hitter Rico Brogna grounded into a
double play and Brian Jordan grounded out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Catcher) Chad Kreuter did a great job behind the plate again,
calling a game and blocking balls, and we had some real nice
defensive plays out there,'' said Dreifort, who is 3-0 with a 1.29
ERA in his past three starts. ``We had two big ones in the seventh
with (Kevin) Elster and (Mark) Grudzielanek. (Adrian) Beltre made
some nice plays at third. (Eric) Karros made a nice play in the
hole, Shawn Green made a nice catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillies starter Omar Daal, a former Dodger who was acquired by
the Phillies in the Schilling deal, wasn't too shabby, but his own
defensive blunder cost him.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded in the third, Karros popped up in front of
the mound. Daal said he called first baseman Pat Burrell off, but
then didn't catch the ball and Mark Grudzielanek scored. Adrian
Beltre added an RBI-single to right field to give the Dodgers a 2-0
lead, but there was also an alarming moment.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star left fielder Gary Sheffield got his left leg
momentarily pinned while catcher Tom Prince allegedly tagged him
out. Sheffield, who leads the Dodgers with a .340 average, 34
homers and 87 RBI, fell and grabbed his left knee. The pain went
away there, but his left ankle was also injured. Sheffield remained
in the game, and afterward said his left ankle was sore, but not
enough to keep him out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be as good as our starting pitching,'' Karros
said. ``Any team (is like that). It's why the Giants have had such
a great run, why went out and got a pitcher. You see all the teams
that are making moves, they're going out and getting a pitcher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
