<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS WERE READY TO DUMP VALDES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA -- The Los Angeles Dodgers are counting on
right-hander Ismael Valdes to bolster the pitching staff with about
10 quality starts, and the risk is minimal because of how little
the Dodgers gave up to get him.
</P>
<P>
   However, his price tag could've been even smaller. Valdes'
relationship - and his pitching - with the Chicago Cubs was so bad
that several baseball sources said the Cubs would have released the
26-year-old right-hander if he wasn't traded by Monday's 9 p.m.
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the same pitcher he was last season with the
Dodgers,'' one scout said. ``If he was, it would be a steal.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, acquired Wednesday for Triple-A pitcher Jamie Arnold and
Single-A outfielder Jorge Piedra, finally met up with the Dodgers
on Friday in Philadelphia and was told he would start Monday in
Pittsburgh against right-hander Jose Silva.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes rejected a multi-year deal by the Dodgers before the 1999
season. Then, and after he and Eric Young were traded to the Cubs
after the 1999 season, he signed a one-year deal worth $5.8 million
and was poised to become one of the marquee free agents of the 2000
class if he had a big year in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Valdes fizzled. Injuries have limited him to 12 starts
this season. He's 2-4 with a 5.37 ERA with the Cubs, missing starts
because of a shoulder ailment, a sore hamstring and his
ever-present blister problem. It was so bad the Cubs paid $500,000
of the remaining $2 million on Valdes' contract to move him.
(Valdes said he's conquered his blister problem by exercising it in
a bucket of rice every day.)
</P>
<P>
   That comes on top of the Dodgers' public comments that Valdes
didn't have the toughness and heart to grow into the No.1 or No.2
starter they believed he could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control whether they say you're one thing or
another,'' said Valdes, who was 61-54 with a 3.38 ERA in 176 games
for the Dodgers. ``The only thing you can control is to do your
best on the mound. That's all you can do. Even though it didn't
work out the way I wanted it to, I'm healthy and ready to go. I
believe what happened in the past is already buried in the past.
This is a new life, a new year, a new day. I don't waste my time
thinking in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes' agent, Jim Bronner, wouldn't discuss whether the pitcher
was seeking a contract extension from the Dodgers, but it also
doesn't matter. General manager Kevin Malone said contracts won't
be discussed during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't discussed that and we didn't plan on it,'' Malone
said. ``We'll see how he pitches during these final two months.
We'll discuss a contract when the time is proper.''
</P>
<P>
   But since the trade, Valdes has told people close to him he
would consider re-signing with the Dodgers, something unheard of a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my mind is set to finish strong,'' Valdes said. ``I'm
not worried about anything else. If I take care of step one, I
think everything else will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillies sign UCLA star: Chase Utley, a standout at UCLA and the
15th overall pick by the Phillies in last month's amateur draft,
agreed to a contract that includes a $1.78 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Utley, who will report to short-season Single-A Batavia of the
New York-Penn League on Monday, batted .342 with 53 homers and 174
RBI in 179 games for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to fail,'' Utley said. ``I'm confident in myself.
I wanted to play from day one. We just finally reached a point
where I could get to come out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Catcher Todd Hundley felt the effects of
returning after a 15-game absence Thursday at Colorado, so Chad
Kreuter caught right-hander Darren Dreifort. Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said Hundley would catch Kevin Brown today.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't catch for a month and you get back there in Colorado
for three hours ... you feel like you've been run over by a
truck,'' Johnson said. ... Right fielder Shawn Green's problems at
the plate continued. He went 0 for 3 and his average has dropped to
.279.
</P>
</TEXT>
