<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE TALKS ARE UNSETTLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia doesn't
anticipate the club making a major deal before the Monday trading
deadline, but acknowledges the rumors of who might be traded can
sometimes be unsettling in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys have a sense of uneasiness,'' Scioscia said before
Friday night's game against the Chicago White Sox at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, the reality is, it's out of their control, and most
realize it and don't fret about it. They know that this is a
business and, that no matter who you are, you can be traded.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia didn't dismiss the possibility the Angels may make a
lesser deal, just not a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is primarily our group anyway,'' he said. ``This is our
core unit. This team isn't going to be blown up July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to make one deal that will totally redesign
this club. After the (trading) deadline the mental state of this
club won't change one way or another. I don't expect any major
trades.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Hatcher in a halo: The Angels did make one minor-league
deal Friday, swapping right-hander Brett Hinchliffe and infielder
Keith Luuloa to the Chicago Cubs in exchange for outfielder-first
baseman Chris Hatcher, right-hander Mike Heathcott and infielder
Brett King.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the deal as far as the Angels were concerned is the
31- year-old Hatcher, who was hitting .278 with 24 home runs and 71
runs batted in for Triple-A Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good outfielder with a big right-handed bat,'' Scioscia
said of Hatcher, who played briefly in the big leagues in 1998 with
Kansas City and, earlier that year, hit 46 home runs at Triple-A
Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Scioscia added, ``before I agreed to the deal I made
sure he didn't have the same genealogy as Mickey Hatcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The irrepressible Mickey Hatcher is Scioscia's longtime buddy,
not to mention the Angels' hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   One of those nights: Catcher Bengie Molina had one of those ...
well, just call it a rough game Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate Molina was 0 for 3. But it was behind the plate
where he had his darkest moments.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, when Chicago's leadoff hitter, Ray Durham,
stole second Molina's throw was a little off the mark. It hit the
pitcher, Brian Cooper. And in the fourth inning Molina was charged
with a passed ball, which was especially ill-timed: there was a
runner on third base at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, a catcher himself for 13 years in the big leagues,
quickly came to Molina's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a few throws like that,'' Scioscia said. ``But, yeah,
Bengie was a little awkward on that throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, Bengie's been very consistent, so consistent
that when something like happens you stop and say, `Gosh, what
happened?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so consistent that he spoils you. He's fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
