<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-SUMMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR AN OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE MINARD  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ As the Southern California Summer Pro
League playoffs kicked off at the Pyramid on Friday afternoon, more
than one interested observer watched from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   As former Long Beach State players Marcus Johnson and Tommy
Davis led Team West Coast to a win over Nutriola, there was a look
of happiness and agony on the face of Everett Ratleff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's kind of hard to watch. That's why I haven't been
here around too much,'' said Ratleff, who played at Long Beach
Jordan and Long Beach State.
</P>
<P>
   Ratleff was a guard for coach Ron Massey as Jordan won two CIF
Southern Section I-AA titles.
</P>
<P>
   He then decided to attend Long Beach State, where his father,
Ed, was a standout in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ratleff, a 6-foot-2 shooting guard, found himself
caught in a numbers' game, stuck behind All-Big West Conference
pick James Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 49ers coach Seth Greenberg preferred using taller
wing players in his offense and tried to move Ratleff to the point
guard position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a numbers thing. I didn't feel like my game was
developing because I had to switch positions and then I didn't play
a lot. It was really frustrating,'' said Ratleff, who also endured
criticism for having a bad attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it seemed that way to people, and it's true, I wasn't
happy, but I always worked hard and did what the coaching staff
asked me to do. It just wasn't working out. Then, when it looked
like Schea (Cotton) might transfer here, I decided to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he would have to sit out a year if he transferred to
another Division I school, Ratleff took his remaining eligibility
and ended up at Caldwell College in Idaho, a Division II school
near Boise, far away from the Southern California lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caldwell is really nice,'' said Ratleff. ``The area is more
integrated than you might think and the people are really nice. It
was a fun place to play because we ran an uptempo offense and
everyone got a lot of touches. My game really grew there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the fact he had a young daughter back in Southern
California, Ratleff knew his dreams of a professional basketball
career would probably die out in Idaho. So after receiving his
degree in physical education, he returned to the southland, eager
to jumpstart his career.
</P>
<P>
   He signed up with the sports management group founded by Magic
Johnson and former NFL defensive end Sean Jones. While at Johnson's
camp last year, Ratleff suffered a partial tear of the medial
collateral ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   For Ratleff, who had never endured a serious injury, it was a
humbling experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was, trying to come back and then I got hurt. I wasn't
sure what to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ratleff sits and watches his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am playing, but my knees are not 100 percent. I didn't want
to come here (to the summer league) and not be at my best, so I am
still working on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of his father, friends and a new agent, Ratleff
hopes to land a contract, though most likely it will be overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my buddies - Marcus (Johnson), Eric Brown, Akili (Jackson)
- went overseas and seemed to do well. I know I can play. I'll be
back, and even better than I was before,'' he said. &QL; 
Playoff results
</P>
<P>
   Despite a game-high 39 points from Kendrick Johnson, Nutriola
was upset by Team West Coast in the first quarterfinal game.
</P>
<P>
   Former Long Beach State player Marcus Johnson had 10 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
