</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL TURNS A CLOSE SHAVE IN THE NINTH INTO A VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
  (This story replaces original story, which was sent in error) 
By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Glenallen Hill came to the Yankees with his hair
styled in short braids, and it was not long before he felt out of
place. The vast majority of the Yankees wear conservative haircuts,
very simple and short _ a reflection, Hill thought, of the team's
serious approach.
</P>
<P>
   So he shaved his head, wanting to make sure he would not draw
attention to himself. In his first game with his new look, he
became the center of attention, blasting a game-winning pinch-hit
grand slam off Minnesota's Bob Wells Friday night as the Yankees
overcame a blown save by Mariano Rivera to beat the Twins, 9-5.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada had four hits, including his 17th home run, and
first baseman Tino Martinez had three hits. Rivera improved his
record to 4-3 with the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hill is the latest in a series of additions the Yankees have
made, along with: Denny Neagle, who pitched effectively into the
eighth inning; David Justice, who spurred the ninth-inning rally
with a double; and Jose Vizcaino, who started at second base.
``Their payroll is $150 million,'' said Brad Radke, a Twins pitcher
who was furious. ``What do you expect? They should win every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez said: ``Hopefully, this will propel us on a big
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   They won this game, unexpectedly, after giving away a two-run
lead in the bottom of the eighth. The Yankees led, 4-2, when Midre
Cummings pinch-hit to begin the bottom of the inning;
interestingly, Cummings was traded with Neagle from Minnesota to
Pittsburgh in 1992. Neagle walked Cummings and Denny Hocking on
close pitches. After Neagle was relieved by Yankees manager Joe
Torre, Neagle stalked off the mound screaming out of the side of
his mouth at the home plate umpire Chuck Meriwether, his head aimed
straight ahead at the dugout, until he shot a withering glance at
the umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton took over and struck out Cristian Guzman and Matt
Lawton. Jeff Nelson relieved Stanton and walked Ron Coomer, after
Coomer fouled off three pitches with a full count. Rivera took
over, and David Ortiz rolled a two-run single through the middle to
tie the game. Jay Canizaro then pulled a single to right, driving
home Coomer with the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill led off the ninth with a single off the left-hander
Travis Miller, setting off a series of changes by the managers, and
changes to counter the changes. LaTroy Hawkins relieved Miller and
retired Bernie Williams on a fly to center field, and Eddie
Guardado replaced Hawkins to face back-to-back left-handed hitters,
Justice and Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Justice foiled the strategy by ripping a line drive into the gap
and the ball bounced over the fence _ unluckily for the Yankees,
because O'Neill would have probably scored if the ball had stayed
in play.
</P>
<P>
   Guardado fell behind Martinez three balls and no strikes before
he completed the walk intentionally, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Delgado was inserted as a pinch-runner for Martinez at
first, and when Delgado took some time to warm up, Twins manager
Tom Kelly emerged from the dugout to call for Bob Wells to face
Posada. Posada ripped a single through the middle and O'Neill
scored, tying the game. Justice was held at third.
</P>
<P>
   Hill came in as a pinch-hitter for Clay Bellinger and fell
behind no balls and two strikes. Wells threw perhaps the only pitch
Hill would have bashed in that situation, a fastball down the
middle _ and Hill launched a high drive to straightaway center.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, Nelson and Stanton began yelling happily in the Yankees'
clubhouse, watching on television as Hill dropped his bat and
stared at the ball, knowing it would clear the fence, and swaggered
around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   His new teammates shouted and clapped and rushed to the front of
the visitors' dugout. This was the sort of attention Hill wants to
draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
