<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN WITH BIG SIXTH INNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Another rocky start, another wild comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Angels baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The difference this time, the Anaheim Angels actually won one,
storming from behind to slow the runaway Chicago White Sox, 10-7,
Friday night before a roaring Edison Field crowd of 40,711.
</P>
<P>
   The win, the result of a rousing seven-run sixth inning - which
was launched with Tim Salmon's leadoff homer and was capped by Mo
Vaughn's thunderous three-run homer on a 3-0 pitch - enabled the
Angels to avert their fourth loss in a row, which would have been
the season's longest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do whatever we have to do to get the win,'' Vaughn said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' 25th come-from-behind win did not, however, ease
concern over their starting pitching, which has been slapped around
freely for more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill was the latest. He had something less than what you'd
call a quality start - seven runs on 11 hits, one of them a home
run, in just 5 innings - but he's hardly been alone.
</P>
<P>
   In the past seven games, Angels starters have given up 39 runs
in 33 innings, a much too high earned-run average of 10.43, and
they've been whacked for 66 hits, including 31 the last two nights.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was banged around for five runs in the second inning and
two more in the sixth when the White Sox opened a 7-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' manager Mike Scioscia was quick to point out, ``give
some credit to Hill. He put up some 0's (after the White Sox'
five-run second) and gave us a chance to get close.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Vaughn noted, ``You don't want to keep getting into
those situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 5-0, the Angels got two runs in the bottom of the
second, and Garrett Anderson, who had three of the Angels' 10 hits,
hit his 30th homer to lead off the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels were still trailing, 7-3, entering the bottom of
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon's leadoff homer got the Angels started. Singles by
Anderson, Bengie Molina and Adam Kennedy followed, and the Angels
were within two, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's single knocked out Chicago starter Mike Sirotka, but
reliever Kevin Beirne hit pinch hitter Scott Spiezio with his first
pitch to load the bases for Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad got one run home with a sacrifice fly to center, then
Kevin Stocker singled home Kennedy with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn quickly untied it, unloading homer No. 26 into the
center-field seats for a 10-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys have the green light on 3-0,'' Scioscia said,
``but Mo's at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' bullpen - Mike Fyhrie, Mike Holtz, Shigetoshi
Hasegawa and Troy Percival - restricted the free-swinging White Sox
to just two hits the final 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz (1-2) benefited from the Angels' seven-run explosion in
the bottom half for his first win. Percival pitched a 1-2-3 ninth
for his 24th save.
</P>
<P>
   For the second successive night everybody in the Chicago lineup
had at least one hit.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels, it turned out, got the bigger hits, handing the
White Sox their fifth loss in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's homer gave the Angels two players with 30 or more
homers for only the third time in club history (Troy Glaus also has
30). Don Baylor (36) and Bobby Grich (30) hit 30 or more in 1979,
and Salmon (34) and Jim Edmonds (33) had 30 or more in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have never had three 30-plus homer sluggers the same
season, though after Friday night Vaughn has 26 and Salmon 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
