<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA BAGS BLUE JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As the July trade deadline approaches and rumors fill
local coffee houses, dot.com offices _ and yes, the Mariners
clubhouse _ consider Seattle's 7-4 victory over the Blue Jays
Friday night a helpful reminder of the good and the bad that can
result from such deals.
</P>
<P>
   There was Jose Cruz Jr., the former first-rounder sent to
Toronto at the trade deadline in 1997 for Mike Timlin and Paul
Spoljaric. He crushed a three-run homer in the third inning, giving
the Blue Jays an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   More pleasantly for Mariners fans, there was Freddy Garcia, who
came to Seattle with Carlos Garcia and John Halama for Randy
Johnson at the deadline in 1998. He pitched his fifth consecutive
solid game to earn his first victory since returning from the
disabled list. And there was Robert Ramsay, who came to the
Mariners for Butch Huskey near last year's deadline, striking out
three of the four batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cameron, who came to the Mariners in February's Ken Griffey
Jr. trade, scored two runs and drove in two.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended a mini-crisis _ a whopping three-game losing
streak _ and extended Seattle's lead back to four games. It also
left the clubhouse a little livelier than after previous games.
</P>
<P>
   There is enough anxiety about possible trades in the normally
calm Seattle clubhouse that manager Lou Piniella said after the
Thursday night loss that he might have a talk with his players.
After the victory last night, he said there was no need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked through you guys,'' he said to the reporters
surrounding his desk. ``They read the newspapers. Listen to the
radio. Watch TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit trying time, but at the same time, it's part
of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And always cause for speculation among fans and media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one I remember is the Mark Langston trade for Randy
Johnson,'' said Ramsay, who grew up in Vancouver, Wash. ``Langston
was their top gun, and everyone was disappointed they got rid of
their ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did, too, but the fans don't understand when there's a trade
like that. They just think, `Oh, you're not getting a guy with much
major league experience.' But these guys know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners certainly did when they traded Johnson, when
effectively forced to deal the lefty two years ago. Garcia won 17
games last year and seems back in form since returning from the
disabled list just before the break.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia allowed four runs _ all in the third inning _ and struck
out a season-high eight batters for his first victory since April
16, the start before he left the game with a hairline fracture in
his right leg. He has a 2.50 earned-run average since returning
from his long stay on the DL, and said he feels better now than
before the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia shut down the Blue Jays with little trouble in every
inning but the third, when Toronto scored all four of its runs,
three coming on Cruz's 22nd home run, to right field. He recovered
after that, holding Toronto scoreless the next three innings, and
left with two out, two on and Cruz up in the seventh inning. ``I
made adjustments and came back after that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay took over and struck out Cruz to end the inning, then
struck out two more in a 1-2-3 eighth, setting up Kazu Sasaki for
his single-season, club-record 15th consecutive save. Sasaki hasn't
blown a save opportunity since June 20.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, which scored only three runs in its previous two games,
didn't exactly put on a hitting display. Trailing 4-3, the Mariners
took a 6-4 lead in the fourth inning with a rally that was more
effective than dramatic, scoring three runs on two singles, an
error, two walks, a hit batter and a fielder's choice grounder.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' final five runs scored on a sacrifice fly, a walk,
a hit batter, and two groundouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works. Sometimes,'' Piniella said. ``But there's nothing
wrong with a bases-loaded clearing double, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade deadline is Monday afternoon, which can't come soon
enough for the Mariners. Said Edgar Martinez: ``It's always a
relief when the deadline passes.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
