<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6776 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-KICK-SCOOTERS-REVIEW-     07-29 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KICK-SCOOTERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW UP! BUY WINKY DINKS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(Eds: Boldface words should be set in italics.) 
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TO: Marketing Committee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FROM: Your Rapidly Aging Boss &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RE: Selling the '50s and '60s &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the office after lunch today, I was nearly run down
by a middle-aged guy braying into a cell phone while he rolled down
Lexington Avenue on a kick scooter.
</P>
<P>
   My first thought was that they were filming one of those Comedy
Central commercials that ridicule baby boomers. But I was
astonished to learn that these scooters have become all the rage,
as we used to say back in those odd and ancient days when J. Edgar
Hoover was considered a tough guy.
</P>
<P>
   Seems this latest trendlet started in Japan and spread to the
San Francisco Bay area, where the Internet hyped it eastward. Kick
scooters evidently sell to a bifurcated market: college kids and
adults born roughly between 1946 and 1964 (OK, and small children,
too). The fad is said to be driven by baby boomer nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Well, excuuuuse me, boys and girls. Please allow a charter baby
boomer (b. 1946) to provide some historical context here. I was
maybe 10 when kick scooters started showing up. I forget whether
this was around the time baseball gloves stopped resembling quilted
oven mitts and developed useful webbing. Incidentally, how did Pee
Wee Reese ever  &UR; catch  &LR;  a grounder with one of those muffins?
Anyway, what was I saying? Oh, right:  &UR; Kick scooters were
considered ridiculous and without practical value even in the
1950s! &LR;  You know what we yelled when some kid scooted by? ``Hey,
pal! Get a bike!''
</P>
<P>
   And do you know what I was really thinking today when I saw that
50-year-old scuffing past on a $200 designer kick scooter?
Geriatric skateboard! I swear, I mulled over the idea of calling
the Hemlock Society for a consultation.
</P>
<P>
   We aging baby boomers are constantly hearing advertisers and
marketers babble about our growing irrelevance. At the same time,
we've watched the popular culture that we created, as we bulged our
demographic mass through the '50s, '60s and '0s, devour itself.
Music, television, movies, attitudes, fashion, fads and philosophy
_ marketers have strip-mined the whole baby boom landscape. We're
scraping bottom now, folks. Last month it was capri pants _
remember pedal pushers? And now it's  &UR; kick scooters? &LR;  Give me a
break! This is a culture running on fumes!
</P>
<P>
   But who am I to argue with the pop market? Where there is a
trend, there is a fee. So let's free-associate here and tweak some
other candidates for profitable exhumation from the baby boom
graveyard:
</P>
<P>
   Think ``Betsy Wetsy Meets Depends.''
</P>
<P>
   Or ``The Revenge of Winky Dink.'' Remember the 1950's cartoon
program that sold plastic sheets that stuck on the television
screen so you could use crayon on it during the show? Imagine the
fun that a Winky Dink 2000 can offer cranky boomers watching
programs like ``The Capital Gang''!
</P>
<P>
   Try Cinerama computer monitors (three screens, thus tripling
sales).
</P>
<P>
   Flagg Flyers 2000. Remember those 50's men's dress shoes with
the leather-covered metal snap that replaced laces and were popular
for about three weeks? Reposition them as safety shoes: No More
Dangerous Bending Over to Tie Laces.
</P>
<P>
   Or appeal to the active lifestyle market and bring back beverage
cans that have to be pierced with a pointy opener called a church
key? Think aerobic exercise!
</P>
<P>
   Consider ``Mitch Miller Rapz.''
</P>
<P>
   Or cowboy outfits (``Draw your Palm Pilot and cell phone from
them holsters, pardner!'').
</P>
<P>
   How about a Mental Hygiene Classroom Films Festival? Hold it in
Telluride, maybe get the Hollywood Foreign Press Association to
have an awards dinner honoring classics like ``Is This Love?''
(1957); ``Girls Beware'' (1961); ``Highways of Agony'' (1969); and
the ``Citizen Kane'' of the classroom genre, ``Duck and Cover''
(1951).
</P>
<P>
   ``Duck and Cover'' featured Bert, the wise cartoon turtle who
warned, ``Always remember, the flash from the atomic bomb can come
at any time!'' Sporting a tin-pot civil defense helmet, Bert was
serenaded in the film by a jingle that suggested he was going to be
OK in the event of a thermonuclear blast. Bert ``never got hurt,''
the jingle went, because ``he knew just what to do. He'd duck! And
cover!''
</P>
<P>
   I've decided to skip this afternoon's marketing meeting. Just
brainstorm on your own, folks. Afterward, anybody who wants to do
some strategizing, I'll be home, sipping a can of Pabst Blue Ribbon
in my fallout shelter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
