<HEADER>
A6777 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-DR-LAURA-TEXT-REVIEW-     07-29 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DR-LAURA-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKING BACK TO TALK RADIO: DR. LAURA ATTRACTS ONLINE CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since Anita Bryant has a morality-minded woman been the
target of as much vitriol as Dr. Laura Schlessinger, the
conservative radio talk-show therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Laura,'' whose audience is estimated at 18 million, is
best known just now for having stated her belief that homosexuality
is wrong, to which gay rights groups have responded by lobbying
corporations to pull their advertisements from her radio show and
upcoming television series.
</P>
<P>
   She is a woman of many opinions, however, and has managed to
offend everybody from librarians and psychologists to witches and
vegetarians. In the process, she has spawned a virtual industry of
Web sites devoted to mocking, reviling or simply haranguing her _
often with the same blunt mean-spiritedness they complain of
regarding the good doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Herewith a sampling of online commentary.
</P>
<P>
   _ By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Recently, after nude photos of Dr. Laura
circulated on the Internet, one viewer wrote: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so much interested in what she looks like. I just want
to see that she just might be a human being after all.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In ``How Could You Do That?! The Abdication
of Character, Courage, and Conscience'' (HarperCollins, 1996), Dr.
Laura writes: ``Acknowledging that you are basically the
perpetrator of your mess of a life is admittedly very upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   Her therapeutic method, however, consists largely of browbeating
hapless callers into making that admission, or listening to Dr.
Laura make it for them, a phenomenon that seems to hold some
fascination for many Laura haters, or at least those who correspond
with Dr. Laura Watch
(either.or.com/(tilde)chansen/least-fav/dr-laura-watch.html). (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing thing about this woman is how I find myself
masochistically tuning her in sometimes, wanting to be enraged by
her. Perhaps this is some MORAL FLAW in my liberal personality?
</P>
<P>
   Driving home this afternoon, I heard our local Laura affiliate
(760 AM KFMB) run a promo spot for the Doc's show. It was one of
those spots that takes a small sound bite from the program. Went
something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura: . . . and you actually let him do that?!?!
</P>
<P>
   Male Caller: Well, we try to encourage him . . .
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura: (Abruptly cutting him off in her inimitable style)
ENCOURAGE HIM?!?!? What do you mean encourage him?! There's NO
ENCOURAGEMENT at my house! There are only rules!!
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In the September 1997 issue of Current
Biography, Dr. Laura says: ``I do not see it as my mission to make
anybody feel better, I want them to get better.'' Janice Leber, the
creator of a Web site called The Moral Irresponsibility of ``Dr.''
Laura (www.sonomacountyfreepress.org/liver/dr-laura .html),
describes Dr. Laura's preferred treatment: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   1. What is your moral dilemma? (Your answer is unimportant.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Why are you so stupid as to have created this problem? (Your
response will be disjointed.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Yes, you DID create this problem. Examine your behavior to
this point. (Any sound you utter will be mocked. You will fall
silent.)
</P>
<P>
   4. This behavior marks you as an irresponsible, immoral jerk.
(You will object.)
</P>
<P>
   5. I can't take your whining any more. Next call. (You will be
cut off.)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) ``Killjoy,'' who wrote this spoof which can
be found on the Dr. Laura Parody Pages
(www.geocities.com/Soho/Studios/7141/laura.htm), took a similar
tack: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Caller: Uh, OK . . . Well, my wife and I have been married for
fourtee_
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura: You're having marital problems, aren't you, Phil? You
and your wife have been together quite some time, and you're having
problems, aren't you? This is not a healthy relationship right now.
You can't go on like this with your wife.
</P>
<P>
   Caller: Um, yeah. You see, we've been having trouble
communicating. When I go to tell her how _
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura: Phil, what we don't need is a whole bunch of examples
of your problems. What all this boils down to is that you're having
trouble communicating with your wife, aren't you? You want to find
a solution to this, but you don't know how, do you? You're feeling
guilty about talking to other women, and you're afraid that she
thinks that you're coming on to them. You can't let her go on
feeling this way, Phil.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
