<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0217 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-YOUNGADULT-BOOKS-REVI     07-29 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNGADULT-BOOKS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF RAW MISERY FOR AGES 12 AND UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(Eds: Optional sidebar at end of 2nd take.) 
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's most honored young-adult novel, ``Monster,'' grabs
the 12-and-up crowd from the very first sentence: ``The best time
to cry is at night, when the lights are out and someone is being
beaten up and screaming for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Dean Myers' story of a boy in jail, charged with taking
part in a convenience-store killing, was a finalist for the
National Book Award, and the first winner of the American Library
Association's new prize for the burgeoning category of young-adult
fiction, an honor created as a sort of big brother to the group's
prestigious Newbery and Caldecott Medals.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from ``Anne of Green Gables,'' or, for that
matter, Harry Potter _ but, in its grimness, not too far removed
from many of the new young-adult books.
</P>
<P>
   Another National Book Award finalist last year, ``Speak,'' by
Laurie Halse Anderson, concerns a ninth-grade girl who has been an
outcast, and almost mute, since an end-of-summer party where she
got drunk, was raped, and called the police.
</P>
<P>
   This is by no means a brand new genre. Ever since the 1970s,
