territory. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Facts Speak for Themselves,'' Brock Cole's book about a
13-year-old girl whose adult lover is shot, in front of her, by her
mother's boyfriend, who then shoots himself.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Smack,'' Melvin Burgess' story of two British teen-age
runaways who move into a ``squat'' and take up heroin.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Edge,'' Michael Cadnum's tale of a high-school dropout whose
divorced, upper-middle-class father is shot in the neck while
stopped at a traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   All fiction needs drama, and many beloved children's classics _
from ``Heidi'' to ``The Secret Garden'' _ feature protagonists who
overcome loneliness and grief.
</P>
<P>
   But in much of today's young-adult fiction, the miseries of life
are not just the backdrop, but the whole point. And while the
situations vary, the books sound pretty much the same, offering
first-person, affectless accounts of a troubled time, with little
description or artfulness. ``The envelope has been pushed and
pushed and pushed,'' said Michael di Capua, a publisher of
children's books at Hyperion. ``You need a bigger and bigger jolt
to keep people's attention. There's a big, fat, wide streak of
sensationalism in there. It's depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt such stories sell. But why they appeal to
adolescents, what their effect is and what they mean about society
are more complicated questions. ``Teen-agers and preteens have
particular curiosity,'' said Dr. Alvin Poussaint, a professor of
psychiatry at Harvard Medical Center. ``They want to know about the
world, what's really going on. They're sticklers for honesty and
they don't want to be shielded from reality. These kids are
watching `Jerry Springer' on television, and all kinds of violent
movies, and if they see these kinds of books around, they'll want
to read them.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he wonders along with many parents, to what effect? ``Does
it contribute to the increased depression we're seeing among young
people? We don't know, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Rovenger, a youth services consultant at Westchester
Library Systems in Ardsley, N.Y., sees the gritty reality books as
a healthy, no-consequences way for adolescents to explore intense
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these books are about people surviving at the
extremes, and that's very interesting to adolescents,'' she said.
``Kids who haven't been through any of these horrors still know the
intense feeling of being misunderstood. It's part of adolescence
that every child feels abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rovenger has her caveats. ``There's no book that's good
for every kid,'' she said. ``But assuming they're choosing to read
these books, I worry more that, if they're badly written, it will
numb them to good literature. And if gritty books were the only
thing a child was reading, I'd say lighten up a little.''
</P>
<P>
   For some children, books that reflect tough realities may be
helpful. Myers, the author of ``Monster,'' said he saw his books as
a validation for young people who do not find their situations
reflected in literary classics. ``My experience, growing up poor,
in Harlem, was that none of the books I saw had anything to do with
my life at all, so I came to the conclusion that my life was not
valuable,'' he said. ``I think young people have to have some books
that they can pick up and say, this is about me.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But a too literal reflection of problems may not be useful, said
Robert Coles, a child psychiatrist who teaches at Harvard.
``Children in difficult situations ask the larger questions, the
kind of questions the Bible asks,'' he said. ``Why does this
happen? Why am I the one? I remember a girl I was treating who had
leukemia. She knew what was happening to her blood. What she was
worried about was what would happen to her mother. A book about a
kid with leukemia wouldn't help her. What would help her was
Tolstoy. A great novelist puts the reader in subjectivity, not
objectivity. This obsession with factuality has its limits and may
actually deprive children of an imaginative response.''
</P>
<P>
   And fact-based books are not the only way to tackle tough
issues. Certainly, fantasies like the Harry Potter books _ like
C.S. Lewis' Narnia series or Madeleine L'Engle's ``A Wrinkle in
Time'' before them _ deal with good and evil, suffering, love and
betrayal, albeit within a magical setting.
</P>
<P>
   L'Engle recalled an Authors Guild program on children's
literature in which New York City teen-agers were asked to bring
their favorite books _ and three out of four were fantasy. ``The
kids,'' she said, ``picked up on the unspoken assumption that they
were interested in reading about problems like neglect and abuse,
and they said, `No, we're living that, why would we want to read
about it?'''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   COMPELLINGLY GRIM FICTION, THEN AND NOW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A taste of grim reading for young adults from 1898, from ``Paul
and Virginia,'' by Bernardin de Saint-Pierre: ``The body was half
covered with sand, and preserved the attitude in which we had seen
her perish. Her features were not sensibly changed, her eyes were
closed, and her countenance was still serene; but the pale purple
hues of death were blended on her cheek with the blush of virgin
modesty.''
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of more modern fare:
</P>
<P>
   From ``Speak,'' by Laurie Halse Anderson (Farrar Straus &AMP;
Giroux, 1999), about a ninth-grader who has been raped: ``It is
getting harder to talk. My throat is always sore, my lips raw. When
I wake up in the morning, my jaws are clenched so tight I have a
headache. Sometimes my mouth relaxes around Heather, if we're
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Facts Speak for Themselves,'' by Brock Cole (Puffin,
2000): ``The woman policeman says why don't you come in here, and
so I went. It was a little room with a table and some chairs. That
was all. Instead of a window, there was a big mirror. I wouldn't
look at that. I didn't want to see myself. I sat down and folded my
hands. There was still blood under my nails, so after a minute I
put them under the table.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Smack,'' by Melvin Burgess (Avon, 1999): ``I got to
admit, heroin's the best. I mean, THE BEST. The others, well . . .
acid, your thoughts come alive and they start to live a life of
their own. Hash, your senses sort of wake up. But with heroin,
ahhh. You can just sit in a sewer all day and be sooo happy and
feel sooo good.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Monster,'' by Walter Dean Myers (HarperCollins Juvenile
Books, 2000): ``They take away your shoes and your belt so you
can't kill yourself no matter how bad it is. I guess making you
live is part of the punishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
