<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6781 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-ATOMIC-PARTICLES-REVI     07-29 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATOMIC-PARTICLES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIRD SCIENCE: THE WONDER OF WEIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If asked what makes a bowling ball heavy, anyone who remembers a
little high school physics might point to the tightly packed atoms
in the ball's resin or the massive protons and neutrons inside the
atoms. Resourceful as it is, that answer would not satisfy a real
physicist, because it does not explain why the particles have mass
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   For most physicists, there is only one answer to the question of
why matter weighs anything at all. It is called the Higgs boson, a
peculiar particle that laboratories in Europe and the United States
are racing to detect. It would be one of the most sublime
discoveries in the long history of physics.
</P>
<P>
   After scientists at the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory,
near Chicago, announced on July 21 that they had seen a ghostly
particle called the tau neutrino, there remained only one
undetected particle whose existence was predicted by the standard
model of particle physics. Without that final, confirming piece of
the puzzle, however the standard model could still be a castle
built on clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining particle is, of course, the Higgs.
</P>
<P>
   The Higgs should manifest itself both as a particle and as a
sort of thick molasses of pure energy permeating space. The
molasses, called the Higgs field, is normally undetectable except
as the source of mass for all ordinary particles drifting through
space, from the quarks that make up protons, neutrons, planets and
bowling balls, to electrons and neutrinos.
</P>
<P>
   According to theory, violent collisions produced in particle
accelerators should jostle the molasses enough to shake loose a
detectable particle _ the Higgs boson. Capturing one would
demonstrate that the molasses indeed filled space.
</P>
<P>
   A Higgs detection on American soil would also involve a certain
amount of scientific crow-eating since, a decade ago, American
scientists told Congress that the nation absolutely had to build a
superconducting supercollider at a cost of about $10 billion, or
forgo being at the cutting edge of particle physics. But since
Congress canceled the project in 1993 amid cost overruns and
charges of mismanagement, scientists' estimates of the Higgs' mass
have fallen so much that far less powerful accelerators might be
adequate to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   One of those accelerators is Fermilab's Tevatron, originally
built in the early 1980s and recently upgraded at a cost of $260
million. In the bitter competition to build the superconducting
supercollider, Fermilab lost out to Waxahachie, Texas, where the
canceled project has left behind only a vast, oddly shaped tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be big revenge,'' said Dr. Franco Bedeschi,
co-spokesman for an experimental team called the collider detector
at Fermilab and a physicist at the National Institute for Nuclear
Physics in Italy. Although Bedeschi spoke jokingly, the scars of
the supercollider fiasco are still painful for particle physicists
_ call it Higgs guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Higgs, a British theorist, and others worked out the
mathematics of the particle in the early 1960s. But it was Sheldon
L. Glashow and Steven Weinberg, two physicists who had been
classmates at the Bronx High School of Science, and Abdus Salam, a
Pakistani theorist, who showed how the Higgs field could produce
mass in a particle theory that described the complexities of matter
in the real world. Glashow, Weinberg and Salaam received the Nobel
Prize for their work in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is based on postulated symmetries of nature.
Physicists use the word symmetry whenever they find that physical
laws remain indifferent to some change. Physical laws are the same
for particles moving to the left or to the right, for example. But
some of the deepest symmetries occur in an abstract space where the
properties of distinct particles _ say, an electron and a neutrino
_ can be interchanged. The most symmetrical and natural state of
this space, however, is one in which all particles have no mass,
meaning weightlessness, meaning no bowling balls.
</P>
<P>
   The Higgs field allows particles to have various masses because
it fills space like molasses, said Dr. Tiziano Camporesi, a
physicist at the CERN particle physics laboratory in Geneva and the
spokesman for a large experimental team there.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance it offers against particles moving through it
amounts to inertia, ``and after all, inertia is the manifestation
of mass,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The molasses is thought to have congealed in space as the
universe cooled in the Big Bang, the giant explosion in which most
scientists believe the universe was born, said Dr. Michael E.
Peskin, a theorist at the Stanford Linear Accelerator Center.
</P>
<P>
   Peskin, who warned that advanced theories that made all this
less dependent on the caprice of one particle would predict the
existence of even more particles, said the Higgs field could not be
detected directly. But by producing ordinary massive particles in
accelerators, he said, the molasses could be jostled enough so that
it spawned a Higgs boson, which would decay in a tiny fraction of a
second, making decay products that could be detected.
</P>
<P>
   So now the race is on between physicists at Fermilab and at CERN
to be the first to find the Higgs boson. The two institutions make
little attempt to conceal the stakes involved in the competition,
which could lead to a Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be like an adrenaline shot,'' Camporesi said. ``It
would be the achievement of my life, clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   The first chance belongs to CERN's Large Electron-Positron
collider, or LEP, which is approaching the end of its planned
lifetime this fall. Scientists there have not seen the Higgs yet,
but they are trying to decide whether to extend their run just a
bit longer to keep hunting.
</P>
<P>
   With a higher energy than the LEP, Fermilab's upgraded Tevatron
will have the next shot at the Higgs when it starts producing data
next spring. After that, the much more powerful Large Hadron
Collider should begin operation at CERN by 2005 or 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists say all the signs point to a great discovery within
the next few years. ``Having hunted for this weird beast for so
long,'' Camporesi said, ``the day it is discovered I would really
be very, very happy. And probably get drunk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
