<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6782 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-BOSNIA-MASSACRES-REVI     07-29 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-MASSACRES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A PICTURE BOOK, CLUES TO A MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The women, many of them with their heads covered, peer
tentatively at the massive bound volume, studying photographs of
jewelry, shoes, socks, trousers and other bits of clothing. There
is no art here, merely suffering.
</P>
<P>
   They are searching for some evidence of their loved ones,
missing and believed dead in the massacre of Srebrenica, the 1995
murder by the Bosnian Serbs of up to 7,000 men, separated from
their families, who thought they were under the protection of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Since this book was printed on June 12, more than 1,000 families
have seen it in the company of local workers from the Bosnian Red
Cross. The book contains 1,756 photos with short descriptions,
showing the belongings of 354 bodies found near Srebrenica that
forensic experts have been unable to identify.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 92 families have recognized belongings of their loved
ones, said Balthasar Staehelin, head of the International Committee
for the Red Cross in Bosnia-Herzegovina, giving forensic scientists
a very good chance of making positive identifications. More
important, some families are closer to knowing what happened to
their missing men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some families even have difficulty opening the book,''
Staehelin said. ``But for most, not knowing is worse than knowing
the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for this book came from Rifat Kesetovic, the director
of the Podrinje Identification Project, which was established 18
months ago to work exclusively on identifying the missing from
Srebrenica. The Red Cross financed its preparation and publication,
and is providing local teams to take copies to the families of the
missing, and to stand by to provide information and psychological
care.
</P>
<P>
   Srebrenica has become a metaphor for many big topics: the worst
atrocity of the Bosnian war; the empty promises of a West in love
with its own moralizing; the bureaucratic, murderous failure of a
United Nations trying to make peace without fighting; the cowardice
of Dutch troops serving with the United Nations who let Bosnian
Serbs overrun Srebrenica and watched them march the men away.
</P>
<P>
   For these women, Srebrenica is an unfilled hole exploded in
their lives. Of the 20,000 people reported missing in
Bosnia-Herzegovina, the Red Cross has only been able to resolve the
fate of 3,000, even five years after the Dayton agreement that
ended the Bosnian war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
