<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-PRISON-REVIE     07-29 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-PRISON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER FINDS ITS WAY OUT OF ONE MAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Though the Maze prison takes its name from the suburban
village outside Belfast where it is located, it is an apt word for
a place that is so representative of the perverse paths Ulster has
followed in its struggle to find its way from war to peace.
</P>
<P>
   The brutalist fortresslike building ringed by rusted barbed wire
and studded with searchlights and watchtowers has drawn the world's
eye for its hunger strikes, riots, killings, mass escapes,
posturing paramilitary fighters and alumni like Gerry Adams,
president of Sinn Fein, the political party of the Irish Republican
Army. It held more guerrillas than any other prison in the world,
and the ruthlessness and political commitment of its inhabitants
made it a place where guards were often more endangered than
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   It has at once embodied Ulster's most evil instincts and shaped
many of the men now trying to guide its political future. Five
members of the new Northern Ireland Assembly were Maze inmates; in
a society of 1.6 million, nearly 30,000 were prisoners. Behind the
1998 accord that has brought stability to Northern Ireland is a
conviction that these people, once perpetrators of mayhem, can be a
significant constituency for calm.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-seven guerrillas walked free last week in the last stage
of the pact's early release program, under which more than 400
prisoners have been let out. The Maze prison, which has held as
many as 1,800 inmates, now houses 15 and is to close at year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the bombers and killers come out the Maze's turnstile
exit is dreadfully hard for many residents of Northern Ireland,
since most of the crimes were recent, and for victims' families,
the memories are fresh. The released do not express regret or
remorse. Instead, they say they were participating in a war and
trying to protect their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question most longingly asked these days by the
citizens of Northern Ireland is whether the war that has cost 3,600
lives is finally over, and they may find some reassurance in the
shuttering of the Maze and the freeing of inmates who always
insisted on being considered prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   The Maze began as a prisoner-of-war camp on the site of Long
Kesh Royal Air Force Base to handle the hundreds of people arrested
and interned without trial in the early 1970s. Its Nissen huts and
tents made way several years later for eight stolid H-blocks,
so-called because of their shape, housing 100 cells each and
suitable for keeping members of murderously opposing paramilitary
groups segregated from one another.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, a decision by the British government to treat inmates
not as prisoners of war but as criminals led to riots and a period
when the distinctive aerial photo of the jail became a norm on
television news. Inmates went ``on the blanket,'' wearing
bedclothes instead of prison uniforms, and started their ``dirty
protest'': refusing to bathe, littering their cells and corridors
with broken furniture and smearing walls with their feces.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Bobby Sands, a convicted IRA bomber, started a hunger
strike that cost him his life after 66 days. Nine other inmates
starved themselves to death before the protest was dropped, but
Sands became a republican hero and brought international scrutiny
of ``the troubles,'' as the Catholic-Protestant sectarian violence
is commonly called.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of the Sands case pointed to the future. A month
before his death, Sands was elected a member of the British
parliament from Northern Ireland _ the first indication that Sinn
Fein might be able to attract widespread political support.
</P>
<P>
   While the Maze _ or Long Kesh, as inmates often still insist on
calling it to emphasize its prisoner-of-war origins _ remained a
chaotic and violent place through the 1980s and 1990s, it also
provided many guerrillas with their first education since grade
school. The men largely studied political and social issues and
emerged from prison with so-called Free University degrees. The
Shankill Road, the principal avenue of Protestant Belfast, and the
Falls Road, the main street through the largest Catholic
neighborhoods, are now home to scores of storefront community
action organizations run by former prisoners who are trying to keep
youths from perpetuating sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   Through these years, the Maze developed into prisons within a
prison, with entire H-blocks in the control of the paramilitary
inmates. Prisoners elected their own leaders who negotiated
conditions directly with the prison governor. Prisoners won the
right not to be locked in their cells, and guards were forbidden to
search their quarters without gaining the commanders' approval and
a day's notice. In an unsuccessful prison break three years ago,
IRA men managed to keep undetected the 13 tons of earth they had
dug up while making a tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates showed their growing power in ways ranging from the
cooperative to the menacing. During the last two decades, 22 guards
and a deputy governor of the Maze were killed outside the prison by
guerrillas acting on information from inside. In recent years,
leaders inside the Maze gave the political parties representing
paramilitary groups the necessary go-ahead to participate in the
talks that produced the 1998 settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Talk has already begun about what to do with the Maze.
Suggestions range from destroying every gray brick of it to
preserving it as a museum, as was done in South Africa with the
Robben Island jail, where Nelson Mandela was held.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the closing is a powerful symbol and may
provide a hopeful answer to a question posed at the end of a
popular republican song of the 1970s. ``And will the last
obscenity,'' it concluded, ``be the grim H-block cell?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
