<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-POLITICS-INTERNET-REV     07-29 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-INTERNET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONVENTION FOR EVERYONE, ONE AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this summer's political party gatherings, where the outcomes
are preordained, the hottest activity may be interactivity. For the
Republican National Convention this week, for example, Chris Long
wants to put you in the director's seat. On C-SPAN's Web site, run
by Long, users will be able to click on one of several distinct
video feeds from the convention hall, or even choose to watch the
action from the vantage point of the C-SPAN control booth.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN is one of several operations using similar technology at
the conventions. In each case, their U-pick-em-style camera angles
takes the editor out of the equation and put the accent in media on
the ``me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They allow users to have different experiences of the same
event,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the nation's armchair politicos can now begin to
create their own show.
</P>
<P>
   Customized political conventions are just one example of the
nation's growing, technologically abetted obsession with getting
what you want when you want. From sites that download music onto
personalized players, to digital television services that rearrange
prime-time offerings to fit viewers' schedules, electronic wizardry
is constantly expanding the possibilities for satisfying consumer
demand for individualization.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing, though, to go online to order a pair of jeans
tailored to specifications for ankle width and button color, and
quite another to design one's own idea of a political convention.
The quadrennial events, with their idiosyncratic procedures and
highly scripted programs, are at heart communal exercises for both
the participants and the audience. So what happens to the shared
national experience when no two members of the audience share the
same convention, or, by logical extension, the same election-day
coverage?
</P>
<P>
   Some media observers, like Russell Newman, a researcher on
Internet issues at the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the
University of Pennsylvania, are not convinced customized camera
angles are anything but Webfoolery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My estimate of the audience for a bird's eye view of the top
of the convention dome,'' Newman said, ``is seven people.''
</P>
<P>
   But if this initial stab at a Web-enabled convention doesn't
work, that will hardly spell its death. In fact, the Internet, a
technology that is inherently individualistic and interactive, is
rapidly growing in prominence in the political process. Candidate
Web sites are getting better, Internet fund-raising and voter
communications are growing more sophisticated and effective, and
many people think the advent of voting via the Web is only a matter
of time.
</P>
<P>
   The water cooler has long played a significant role in the
nation's political conversation. Indeed, part of the enjoyment of
watching conventions is the post-mortem critiquing of the
politicians and the anchors and the conventioneers in the silly
hats. But who is going to shoot the breeze with friends if one
spent the night before in a chat room, exploring tobacco policy
with lobbyists from Kentucky, another was transfixed by a camera
trained on the Hawaii delegation, a third was consumed with
e-mailing questions to a Webcast on MSNBC _ and none paid attention
to a word of the vice presidential nominee's address?
</P>
<P>
   With more options, your water-cooler conversations are going to
be many times smaller,'' said Sam Hollander, executive producer of
Pseudopolitics.com, a Web site that will, among other things,
provide a 360-degree view through a series of cameras inside the
First Union Center in Philadelphia and the Staples Center in Los
Angeles, where the Democrats convene in August. ``There will be a
lot of two-person conversations, rather than 20-person
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   This relentless subdividing of common ground, Hollander said, is
akin to the fragmenting of television viewership, thanks to the
multiplicity of choices on cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to do is look at what ratings share a network has
to get today to have a success,'' he said. ``There was a time when
if you didn't get a 30 share, it wasn't that big. Now, if you get a
20, you're a huge hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Where once the country was knit together by the collective
experience of watching the same sitcom on one of the networks, or
having the meaning of a national tragedy interpreted by Walter
Cronkite, the I-can-do-it-myself ethos engendered by technology is
on the verge of assuring that there will be no collective
electronic experience.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo, for example, is a year-old digital service based in
California that allows subscribers to program their televisions to
play only what they want to see at a time of their choosing. Its
recent television commercial depicting network programmers being
tossed out of windows asked , ``When you've got TiVo, who needs
them?'' Some networks refused to run it, say TiVo executives.
</P>
<P>
   No one as yet is confidently predicting just how all this
electronic democracy will affect the democratic process. Paul
Sagan, president of Akamai Technologies, an Internet company
selected by the Democrats to deliver all of their streaming media
convention coverage, says the interactive age is probably too new
in this election cycle to profoundly affect voters' view of events.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cat is out of the bag, and the savviest politicians,
Sagan said, will quickly begin to look for ways to satisfy the
demands for individualized attention from users of the Internet,
who now number more than 115 million in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In interactivity, people expect to control the query and get
back the answer,'' Sagan said, adding his own customized parable:
``I have an odd Swiss watch that requires an authorized dealer to
change the battery. I went to the company's Web site and sent them
a query: how can I get the battery replaced? I got a response from
someone in Switzerland saying thank you for your inquiring and that
the query had been forwarded to their U.S. offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagan never heard from the American branch. ``My watch is now
dead in a drawer and they have a disgruntled customer,'' he said.
``They did something that's worse than not trying at all. They
raised expectations and they failed to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about scary scenarios: a political world in which every
voter gets a personalized Internet checklist of promises from the
candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0240 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-POLITICS-INTERNET-REV     07-29 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-INTERNET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONVENTION FOR EVERYONE, ONE AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this summer's political party gatherings, where the outcomes
are preordained, the hottest activity may be interactivity. For the
Republican National Convention this week, for example, Chris Long
wants to put you in the director's seat. On C-SPAN's Web site, run
by Long, users will be able to click on one of several distinct
video feeds from the convention hall, or even choose to watch the
action from the vantage point of the C-SPAN control booth.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN is one of several operations using similar technology at
the conventions. In each case, their U-pick-em-style camera angles
takes the editor out of the equation and put the accent in media on
the ``me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They allow users to have different experiences of the same
event,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the nation's armchair politicos can now begin to
create their own show.
</P>
<P>
   Customized political conventions are just one example of the
nation's growing, technologically abetted obsession with getting
what you want when you want. From sites that download music onto
personalized players, to digital television services that rearrange
prime-time offerings to fit viewers' schedules, electronic wizardry
is constantly expanding the possibilities for satisfying consumer
demand for individualization.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing, though, to go online to order a pair of jeans
tailored to specifications for ankle width and button color, and
quite another to design one's own idea of a political convention.
The quadrennial events, with their idiosyncratic procedures and
highly scripted programs, are at heart communal exercises for both
the participants and the audience. So what happens to the shared
national experience when no two members of the audience share the
same convention, or, by logical extension, the same election-day
coverage?
</P>
<P>
   Some media observers, like Russell Newman, a researcher on
Internet issues at the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the
University of Pennsylvania, are not convinced customized camera
angles are anything but Webfoolery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My estimate of the audience for a bird's eye view of the top
of the convention dome,'' Newman said, ``is seven people.''
</P>
<P>
   But if this initial stab at a Web-enabled convention doesn't
work, that will hardly spell its death. In fact, the Internet, a
technology that is inherently individualistic and interactive, is
rapidly growing in prominence in the political process. Candidate
Web sites are getting better, Internet fund-raising and voter
communications are growing more sophisticated and effective, and
many people think the advent of voting via the Web is only a matter
of time.
</P>
<P>
   The water cooler has long played a significant role in the
nation's political conversation. Indeed, part of the enjoyment of
watching conventions is the post-mortem critiquing of the
politicians and the anchors and the conventioneers in the silly
hats. But who is going to shoot the breeze with friends if one
spent the night before in a chat room, exploring tobacco policy
with lobbyists from Kentucky, another was transfixed by a camera
trained on the Hawaii delegation, a third was consumed with
e-mailing questions to a Webcast on MSNBC _ and none paid attention
to a word of the vice presidential nominee's address?
</P>
<P>
   With more options, your water-cooler conversations are going to
be many times smaller,'' said Sam Hollander, executive producer of
Pseudopolitics.com, a Web site that will, among other things,
provide a 360-degree view through a series of cameras inside the
First Union Center in Philadelphia and the Staples Center in Los
Angeles, where the Democrats convene in August. ``There will be a
lot of two-person conversations, rather than 20-person
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   This relentless subdividing of common ground, Hollander said, is
akin to the fragmenting of television viewership, thanks to the
multiplicity of choices on cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to do is look at what ratings share a network has
to get today to have a success,'' he said. ``There was a time when
if you didn't get a 30 share, it wasn't that big. Now, if you get a
20, you're a huge hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Where once the country was knit together by the collective
experience of watching the same sitcom on one of the networks, or
having the meaning of a national tragedy interpreted by Walter
Cronkite, the I-can-do-it-myself ethos engendered by technology is
on the verge of assuring that there will be no collective
electronic experience.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo, for example, is a year-old digital service based in
California that allows subscribers to program their televisions to
play only what they want to see at a time of their choosing. Its
recent television commercial depicting network programmers being
tossed out of windows asked , ``When you've got TiVo, who needs
them?'' Some networks refused to run it, say TiVo executives.
</P>
<P>
   No one as yet is confidently predicting just how all this
electronic democracy will affect the democratic process. Paul
Sagan, president of Akamai Technologies, an Internet company
selected by the Democrats to deliver all of their streaming media
convention coverage, says the interactive age is probably too new
in this election cycle to profoundly affect voters' view of events.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cat is out of the bag, and the savviest politicians,
Sagan said, will quickly begin to look for ways to satisfy the
demands for individualized attention from users of the Internet,
who now number more than 115 million in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In interactivity, people expect to control the query and get
back the answer,'' Sagan said, adding his own customized parable:
``I have an odd Swiss watch that requires an authorized dealer to
change the battery. I went to the company's Web site and sent them
a query: how can I get the battery replaced? I got a response from
someone in Switzerland saying thank you for your inquiring and that
the query had been forwarded to their U.S. offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagan never heard from the American branch. ``My watch is now
dead in a drawer and they have a disgruntled customer,'' he said.
``They did something that's worse than not trying at all. They
raised expectations and they failed to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about scary scenarios: a political world in which every
voter gets a personalized Internet checklist of promises from the
candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
