adjust and minimize the points of friction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dromi points to the increasing interaction between people on
the two sides as evidence that the process of mutual adjustment is
advancing. He says that his brother, a senior police officer, is in
frequent contact with Palestinian officers and that even when
official relations have been tense, personal ones have been warm.
He notes further that every Saturday there are huge traffic jams as
thousands of Israelis drive to the West Bank cities of Nablus and
Tulkarm to shop. Thousands of others drive to Jericho to gamble.
``These are the same cities where their sons had to chase stone
throwers into the alleys of the casbah,'' he mused.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The reality is indeed new. For two generations, the political
divide in Israel was between those on the left who called for ``two
states for two peoples'' and those on the right who swore there
would never be a Palestinian state. Now the whole discussion is
what the contours and powers of that state would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a major realignment going on,'' said Yoram Hazony, a
conservative who was an aide to Benjamin Netanyahu when he was
prime minister. ``There is, in effect, a condition of political
independence for the Palestinians. Today, there is no such thing as
a `not-one-inch' position. Now you hear people on the far right
saying that if we are going to trade territory, let's give the
Palestinians as many Arab villages in Israel as possible to
maximize the Jewish majority in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is another useful myth that animated the Camp
David peace process: that only the governments of Barak and Arafat
in their current configurations can make this peace and so a
historic opportunity is at stake. The same was said of Yitzhak
Rabin and Arafat. After Rabin's assassination in 1995 by a Jewish
extremist, the hawkish Netanyahu was elected and the doomsayers
seemed correct. But the peace process did not die, and it is
unlikely to if Barak and Arafat fail to decide how to share
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   All acknowledge that Jerusalem is the most difficult issue
because while land can be divided, it is far less clear how to
divide a symbol that is, in Hazony's words, ``at the heart of what
we think we are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a myth that only at Camp David did the issue of
Jerusalem first get an airing. It was certainly the first time it
was broached directly at the very top, but Jerusalem has been under
discussion for quite a while. Yossi Beilin, a senior minister in
Barak's government, negotiated Jerusalem's future with Abu Mazen, a
senior Palestinian official, in 1995. The Rabin assassination in
November of that year ended those discussions.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for pessimism over the Israeli-Arab
conflict. There is a huge disparity in culture and income and
numerous bases of resentment. Meron Benvenisti, a leftist former
deputy mayor of Jerusalem and an Israeli expert on the West Bank,
is dismissive of the negotiations over Jerusalem neighborhoods and
sovereignty sharing because he believes the Israelis still do not
take the Palestinians seriously as human beings. That failure, he
believes, will bring the process to a very unhappy end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit back and feel self-righteous and convert the whole
question into whether there will be violence,'' he said. ``The
Arabs are interesting to us only as a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many others, the peace process is best seen like the
stock market. It may have its frightening ups and downs, but its
positive direction in the long term is clear. The key is to avoid
irrational exuberance or utter gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Salameh Nematt, a Jordanian journalist for the Arab newspaper Al
Hayat, says he marvels at how much has happened in a decade. ``In
the beginning, they spoke of Gaza first,'' he recalled of Israeli
proposals in the early 1990s. ``Then it was Gaza and Jericho first
and Gaza and Jericho last. Then came Nablus and Tulkarm and then 9
percent of the land and then 13 percent and then talk of maybe 50
percent and now we are hearing about more than 90 percent. Any
Israeli government that moves too fast will be burned but so will
any government that moves too slowly. The final settlement may take
another 10 or 15 years, but it will come. Remember how Israelis who
met with Arafat used to go to jail? Now he's their best friend.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
