<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, a dull overcast helped to hold temperatures in the 70s
across much of the Northeastern States. The summer chill is
symptomatic of the region's weather this July with little change
expected Sunday. The day will dawn with patchy fog near the
Northeast Seaboard while showers and thunderstorms accompany a
front crossing New York and parts of New England. By afternoon,
additional thunderstorms will erupt in the Northeast as peeks of
the sun warm and destabilize the muggy air.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will also form ahead of a front crossing the Ohio
Valley Sunday while the Southeast stays partly sunny with spotty
storms expected mainly in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptionally hot weather will occupy the interior West.
Brilliant sunshine will boost readings to near 100 degrees in many
places.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HAWAIIAN HURRICANES
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Hawaiians were keeping a wary eye on Hurricane
Daniel about 600 miles east of the island chain. But, as is typical
for tropical storms approaching Hawaii from the east, the once
powerful tempest was steadily weakening. Strong hurricanes are
infrequent visitors to Hawaii, although Hurricane Iniki slammed
into Kauai from the south in 1992. The ocean near the islands is
several degrees cooler than the 80-degree water needed to sustain
hurricanes. Deprived of energy from the warmth of the eastern
Pacific, hurricanes usually dissipate as they approach Hawaii.
</P>
</TEXT>
