 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NEW-DESERT (Lagan, China) _ A new desert is forming here
on the eastern edge of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, a legendary
stretch once known for grasses reaching as high as a horse's belly
and home for centuries to ethnic Tibetan herders. The spread of
wastelands on these 9,000-foot-high steppes, and across the
pastures and farmed hillsides of a broad swath of northern China,
is threatening to rend patterns of life that depend intimately on
the land and to strand millions of herders and farmers who have no
other place to go. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-DRUGS (Leogane, Haiti) _ The drug planes that circle over
the cornfields have become as common as flies. They swoop down, and
men with machine guns stash their cargo _ cocaine _ into cars.
Impoverished villagers gather in hope of snatching a few bags of
cocaine they can then sell. Recently gunmen kept a mob at bay while
unloading the drugs, then abandoned the plane. The angry crowd tore
it apart in a vain search for drugs. Unwittingly, these mobs have
become perhaps Haiti's only front-line deterrent to the Colombian
cocaine traffickers, who have flocked to impoverished Haiti
bringing cash, crime and corruption. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-ELECTION (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Two months after a
first attempt collapsed in ineptitude and scandal, Venezuela will
try again Sunday to hold the biggest vote in its history, a
``mega-election'' in which thousands of candidates, from President
Hugo Chavez down to state legislators, are competing. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   EVANGELICAL-CONVENTION (Amsterdam, Netherlands) _ The Billy
Graham Evangelistic Association has gathered 10,000 evangelists
from 190 countries in Amsterdam this weekend for a nine-day
conference billed as the largest such event ever held. Amsterdam
2000, as the gathering is called, has turned a rambling convention
center on the city's southern edge into an extraordinary crossroads
of global evangelical Christianity. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-HOMECOMINGS (Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina) _ Five years
after the bloodshed and ethnic cleansing that tore apart Bosnia's
communities of Serbs, Muslims and Croats, the first Muslims are now
heading home to areas of eastern Bosnia that were the scene of some
of the war's worst atrocities. Serbs, too, are returning to
Muslim-dominated Sarajevo, a capital once known for its
multiethnicity but subjected to three and a half years of Serbian
siege and shelling in the 1992-95 war. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Dateline TK) _ Developments after the collapse of
the Camp David peace talks between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SLAVES-DATABASE (New Orleans) _ Gwendolyn Midlo Hall spent 15
years in the courthouses of Louisiana, as well as in archives in
Spain, France and Texas, seeking all records of slave transactions
and entering them into laptop computers. She eventually amassed
computerized records on more than 100,000 slaves _ the largest
collection of individual slave information ever assembled. For
historians who thought such information could never be collected
and analyzed, the database is a once-unimaginable prize. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   DOCS-RENEGE (Undated) _ At least 700 doctors, dentists,
psychologists and other health professionals who have signed up for
two-year stints in poor urban and rural areas to pay back their
student loans are now being told that the money they expected will
not materialize, federal officials say. The National Loan Repayment
Program, a $30 million pool of money to attract health workers to
remote towns and inner-city neighborhoods, has exhausted its funds
after making only a few dozen grants to new applicants this year,
threatening the government's ability to get medical professionals
where they are needed most. By Greg Winter.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-BUYBACKS (Cleveland) _ Defying congressional Republicans,
the Clinton administration said Saturday that it will continue
paying local governments to buy back guns from private owners
despite orders from House budget appropriators to end the program.
By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CRAB-SANCTUARY (Newport News, Va.) _ In the face of economic and
environmental warning signs, state fishery authorities have taken
the drastic step of declaring a vast 665-square-mile fishermen-free
sanctuary through the heart of the lower Chesapeake Bay to provide
safe passage for the millions of female blue crabs now on the
southward trek to their high-salinity spawning grounds. By Francis
X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-EMPORIUMS (Middlesboro, Ky.) _ The use of tobacco, much
of it in smokeless forms like snuff, plugs and chewing tobacco,
remains firmly entrenched in Appalachia and in parts of the South
and the Rocky Mountain states. Along the main drags of the pillowy,
kudzu-sculptured Cumberland hills of Appalachian Kentucky,
Tennessee and Virginia and in West Virginia are rural siblings of
the wood-paneled pipe and cigar emporiums that survive in many
cities. These stores cater to older farmers and coal miners with
plugs, twists and chewing tobacco; to younger customers with moist
snuff _ the one growing segment of the national tobacco market _
and to both with discount cigarettes. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DONORS (Philadelphia) _ The Republican convention opening
here on Monday is really two conventions, one for the delegates in
the hall and another for the party's biggest contributors, who will
be treated to a panoply of perks, from yacht rides to skyboxes high
above the convention floor. By John M. Broder and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-GOP-CONVENTION (Washington) _ Republicans in Congress
have long chided their Democratic colleagues for ignoring
shortfalls in the defense budgets, but the Pentagon's decision to
send a display of some of the military's latest hardware to the
Republican National Convention gave the Democrats a golden
opportunity to turn the tables. Two Democratic congressmen sharply
criticized the Pentagon's decision to send an array of weapons and
other equipment to the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard for a
three-day exhibition that begins Saturday, saying the money would
be better spent on repairs or benefits for service members and
their families. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ANTITERRORISM-BUDGET (Washington) _ When border police arrested
a man last December for smuggling bomb parts from Canada, the
authorities suspected a plot to turn the millennial New Year's
celebration into a terrorist fiasco and the Customs Bureau
immediately reinforced security along the border. Amid intense
publicity, President Clinton asked Congress to increase spending
for efforts to counter international and domestic terrorism by $300
million. But this summer, as spending bills wind their way through
Congress, the anti-terrorism accounts at Customs and other federal
agencies are coming up short. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   NERVEGAS-LEAKS (Washington) _ A group of workers who were
overcome last year by fumes at a chemical weapons plant in Oregon
is accusing the Army of covering up leaks of highly toxic nerve
agents and mustard gas on the day of the incident. By Christopher
Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Not our class, darling. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Facing the music. By Paul Krugman.
</P>
