<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0297 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTA     07-29 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: DENISE GRADY  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Music Industry and Napster
</P>
<P>
   First, it was a victory for the recording industry. Then it was
a defeat, when an appeals court granted a stay of the preliminary
injunction issued a day earlier by a U.S. District Court judge that
would have shut down Napster, the Internet music-swapping service
that the major record labels have charged with contributing to
widespread music piracy. Either way, as millions of Internet users
stampeded to Napster and alternatives, the legal wrangling raised
the question of whether enforcing copyright law in a digital age
might take more than winning in court.
</P>
<P>
   _ By AMY HARMON
</P>
<P>
   A Delicate Senate Balance
</P>
<P>
   There can be opportunity even in tragedy, and Georgia's
Democratic governor, Roy Barnes, seized it by appointing his
immensely popular predecessor, Zell Miller, to fill the Senate seat
vacated by the recent death of Paul Coverdell, a Republican. Miller
will run in a special election in November to fill the remaining
four years of Coverdell's term. The appointment brought the
Democrats one seat closer to regaining control of the Senate, where
the Republicans now hold 54 of 100 seats.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   Prosecuting Suharto
</P>
<P>
   Pushing ahead in the face of threats, bombs, demonstrations and
political obstacles, Indonesia's attorney general, Marzuki
Darusman, has completed a corruption investigation of former
President Suharto and forwarded the case to a prosecutor. A formal
indictment was expected in the coming days. But Suharto's lawyers
say he is too ill to face the rigors of a courtroom or to answer
questions coherently.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH MYDANS
</P>
<P>
   Germany Pays for a Call
</P>
<P>
   Germany's largest telephone company, Deutsche Telekom, entered
the U.S. cellular telephone market by buying the VoiceStream
Wireless Corp., for $50.7 billion. The deal caught the attention of
more than two dozen legislators in Washington, who have written to
the chairman of the Federal Communications Commission seeking to
block the acquisition because Deutsche Telekom's majority
shareholder is the German government.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN
</P>
<P>
   Charges of IRS Corruption
</P>
<P>
   At least five of eight suspended IRS tax collectors, auditors
and other employees in Chicago are expected to be indicted soon by
a federal grand jury for fixing tax cases. It would be the first
major corruption case since Congress ordered the agency overhauled
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Schooling Details
</P>
<P>
   Educators and policy-makers with funds would do better buying
curricular materials or PCs for teachers than raising salaries,
according to a new analysis linking test scores to state policy
initiatives and education spending patterns. The study, by the Rand
Corp., suggested that reforms over the past 15 years are showing
success with smaller classes in the early grades and access to
preschool.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JODI WILGOREN
</P>
<P>
   A Strain of Mad Cow
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, mad cow disease is scarier than ever. Fourteen
people have died of it already this year and five more are dying,
compared to 14 in all of last year. Experts say the rising death
toll might presage an even higher death rate.
</P>
<P>
   So the U.S. Department of Agriculture is acting zealously to
combat any chance of mad cow disease entering the country. It has
condemned two flocks of imported Belgian dairy sheep because four
sheep related to the 355 animals tested positive for an
undetermined disease in the mad cow family. Fighting back in
federal court, the owners of the sheep have challenged the science
behind the tests.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   Not Quite Certifiable
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers who spent $2.65 extra for certified mail when they
sent their money to the IRS and other tax agencies may have noticed
that their checks went uncashed for weeks. The reason? The U.S.
Postal Service delayed using new technology and lacked workers,
causing tens of thousands of certified letters, with hundreds of
millions of dollars of checks, to languish. To add insult to
injury, New York City tax officials dunned hundreds of property
owners on the assumption that they had failed to pay.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
