<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BOSNIA-HOMECOMING-965     07-29 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-HOMECOMING-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILES RETURN TO BOSNIA, SHARING A SCARRED LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Five years after the bloodshed
and ethnic cleansing that tore apart Bosnia's communities of Serbs,
Muslims and Croats, the first Muslims are now heading home to areas
of eastern Bosnia that were the scene of some of the war's worst
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs, too, are returning to Muslim-dominated Sarajevo, a
capital once known for its multiethnicity but subjected to 3 and a
half years of Serbian siege and shelling in the war, from 1992 to
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The homecomings _ largely spontaneous but helped by
international officials who run Bosnia, enforcing laws on returning
property to original owners _ are beginning to remedy a cardinal
failure of the uneasy peace: the inability of those officials to
overcome local hatreds and fears, or to return refugees to areas
dominated by ethnic foes.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of Bosnians remain refugees, and foreign
officials have not dented the vivid hatreds that continue to feed
murder and expulsion not far away in Kosovo. But each refugee who
comes home to Bosnia without major mishap _ particularly to the
strongholds of hard-core Serbian nationalists in eastern Bosnia _
can help persuade others to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Visnja Trkulja, a Serbian schoolteacher, has been back in
Sarajevo for nearly a year, living quietly in her apartment house
in the suburb called Ilidza. As she greets visitors, she explains
that her wing is almost back to its prewar makeup: six Serbian
families, two Muslim families and two more Serbian families
expected back soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one likes refugees,'' she said. ``I knew I wanted to go
home when I realized no one wanted me.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was where my friends were, my first loves, my parents'
graves,'' she went on. ``This is my Mount Igman, my sky,'' she said
in a gesture to the Sarajevo landscape.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Ilidza was under Serbian control and Muslims had
to flee. Then, when the 1995 Dayton peace accords ended the
fighting, it was the Serbs' turn to run.
</P>
<P>
   In an exodus that was partly orchestrated by the Serbian
leadership and partly panic, 100,000 Serbs abandoned their homes in
the suburbs of Sarajevo. The peace deal gave the Muslim-Croat
Federation jurisdiction over the whole city, including the Serbian
suburbs, and all but a few thousand Serbs moved out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are filtering back, reclaiming their houses from
Muslims who have occupied them and returning to the capital some of
its former multiethnic atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 Serbs have returned to the Sarajevo area in the
last 18 months, nudging displaced people to return to other regions
around the country. In the first five months of this year, 15,665
people registered after returning home across Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The change is largely due to property laws introduced in 1998,
which international officials at the Office of the High
Representative _ the all-powerful civilian authority in Bosnia _
are using to bulldoze local obstructions. Using law alone, they
want to reverse the ethnic polarization that makes Bosnia barely
workable as a country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is ruthless implementation so that all property is
returned to its owner. We are using the law to subvert ethnic
territorialism,'' said David Stewart-Howitt, a former British Army
officer who coordinates the property returns at the Office of the
High Representative. ``What we have to ensure is a blending that
can allow this country to knit together.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are evicting people from homes so owners can
reclaim their property. There are 25 to 45 evictions every week in
Sarajevo, Stewart-Howitt said. ``Muslims are being evicted here,
the local police are dragging people out, war veterans get
involved, then we have street protests,'' he said. ``It's happening
all over the country. It's a very difficult process but it's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the multiethnic presidency of Bosnia, Alija
Izetbegovic, originally opposed the idea and his adviser, Mirza
Hajric, blames the evictions for the recent fall in the popularity
of Izetbegovic's Muslim party, the Party of Democratic Action. The
paucity of returns of Muslims to Serbian areas, while Sarajevo has
welcomed so many Serbs, is one reason that Izetbegovic, 75, says he
will resign from office in October, Hajric said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the Serbian half of Bosnia have long blocked returns
but have grown more compliant since Wolfgang Petritsch, the high
representative, began firing local officials, 22 on one occasion
last fall, for obstructing the Dayton peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Fear and intimidation also hamper movement. Trkulja said she was
the only Serb in a refugee center in the eastern town of Foca brave
enough to return. ``Many said they did not want to be the first,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of 750,000 people displaced in Bosnia, about 220,000 have made
claims for the return of their homes under the property laws. To
date, 17 percent of those claims in the Muslim-Croat federation
have been settled and 7 percent so far in the Serbian entity, known
as Republika Srpska.
</P>
<P>
   Although few Muslims are returning to Serb-dominated areas,
officials say that even there the trend is upward and the flow will
increase rapidly over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian officials in Pale, the former ski resort outside
Sarajevo that Serbian leaders proclaimed their capital during the
war, and in Foca and Rogatica in eastern Bosnia, where Muslims were
ruthlessly murdered and expelled, have freed up dozens of
apartments belonging to Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   At a joint news conference this month with his Muslim
counterpart from Sarajevo, the Serb who is mayor of Pale guaranteed
security for all returning Muslims. Fifty families are being taken
back to Pale, Foca and Rogatica in coming weeks, said
Stewart-Howitt. ``I find that pretty revolutionary. It would have
been unthinkable even last year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Croat-run areas of Bosnia are showing the least movement,
and seven of the 10 municipalities with the worst record on returns
are Croat, he said. Despite the new mood of cooperation in Croatia
itself since President Franjo Tudjman died and was replaced by more
moderate leaders, foreigners have yet to observe much change among
Bosnian Croat nationalists on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   House burnings and intimidation still occur every week in every
region across Bosnia, although officials insist that violence is
declining.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, refugees are on the move. Villagers all over are
traveling back to their homes to test the atmosphere and negotiate
for their houses.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, 400 families have gone back to villages around Foca
and over 100 Serbs have returned to their nearby village of
Ustikolina in the Muslim-Croat Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian police have freed up 36 apartments in Foca, handing over
the keys to returnees, and other families are back in the Muslim
quarter rebuilding destroyed homes.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Sarajevo, always renowned for its tolerance and
diversity _ its ancient mosques jostle with Orthodox and Catholic
churches in the old part of the city _ that has led the way. The
scars of war are still evident. Smashed buildings and bullet-pocked
walls still mark the old front line. ``Sarajevo roses,'' the shell
craters etched in the sidewalks and now filled with red rubber, are
reminders of the years under siege and fire from Serbian artillery.
Today Serbs walk freely downtown and eat in Muslim-run restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In exile, Trkulja said, she realized she was a Sarajevan first
and had little in common with the Serbian nationalists who
dominated Foca. ``We here have the same sense of humor,'' she said.
``We do the same things. I do not have to explain to someone who I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   It is mostly older people and those without children who are
returning, and the women come back first to test the water, says
Bozidar Stanojevic of the Democratic Initiative for Sarajevo's
Serbs, an organization that helps Serbs return.
</P>
<P>
   There are few jobs for Serbs and continuing discrimination, and
some just reclaim a house in order to sell it, he said. Young
Serbs, especially those who served in the army, remain scared to
return, he added. ``But it is not an objective fear,'' he said.
``We have received threats but nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven Serbs have been killed in the last 18 months, but appear
to have been victims of personal score settling, rather than
attacks aimed at deterring Serb returns.
</P>
<P>
   Sretko Tambur, 60, is a Serbian laborer who returned with his
wife, Joka, in January to Blazuj, on the edge of Sarajevo. Pausing
from chopping wood with a young Muslim worker in his front yard,
Tambur said: ``I've never had any trouble since I came back. It's
the best thing, living at home.''
</P>
<P>
   His village was once all Serbian, but now Muslims, refugees from
other parts of Bosnia, live in his neighbors' homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first days the women next door, refugees, provoked me,
saying they would blow my house up. But nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbs had tried to deter him from going home too. ``I did not
listen to anyone,'' he said. ``People from both sides are scared.''
</P>
<P>
   The local police checked on them regularly, his wife said. And
the local Muslim shopkeeper offered credit for months until their
pensions came through, Tambur said. He praised Petritsch for
pushing the returns. ``We had Yugoslavia before and it was great,''
he said. Banging his fist on the table, he went on: ``Someone has
to say, `You all have to live together.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
