<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-ELECTION-NY     07-29 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA TRIES ELECTIONS AGAIN SUNDAY: NO VOTE-FIXING, CARTER
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Two months after a first attempt collapsed
in ineptitude and scandal, Venezuela will try again Sunday to hold
the biggest vote in its history, a ``mega-election'' in which
thousands of candidates are vying for office, from President Hugo
Chavez down to state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez himself is the only real issue in the vote, which he
called in hopes of winning a new, six-year term in office. Despite
an economy that shrank by more than 7 percent last year, record
unemployment and a big jump in crime, public opinion polls are
unanimous in predicting a Chavez romp by a margin of 15 percentage
points or more.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for 23 governorships and 165 seats in a new one-house
National Assembly is expected to be somewhat closer, with most
opinion surveys predicting Chavez will fall short of the two-thirds
majority he will need in the new chamber to gain quick approval of
his radical social and economic reform program. Such a result could
force him to pursue a more moderate course and negotiate with the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Those races are expected to be particularly close in areas where
the multiparty coalition supporting Chavez was unable to unite
behind a common candidate, possibly splitting the pro-Chavez vote
and allowing his opponents to squeak through to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was first elected in December 1998, Chavez has blamed a
``rancid oligarchy'' of political and business interests for the
country's troubles. In a typically fiery speech Wednesday ending
his campaign, he asked his followers for a landslide victory Sunday
to ``liquidate our adversaries from the field of battle'' once and
for all and allow him finally to carry out the ``peaceful social
revolution'' he has long promised.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's main challenger is Francisco Arias, who, like Chavez,
is a former army colonel who took part in a coup attempt in 1992.
The men then spent two years in jail together and were friends and
political allies until early this year, when Arias angrily accused
the president of concentrating all power in his own hands,
alienating the United States and falling under the spell of Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela has become ``a de facto dictatorship,'' Arias charged
at a news conference here on Friday. ``Corruption, poverty and
unemployment are accelerating,'' he said, because the Chavez
administration has ``violated all the norms and protocols'' of good
government and pursued economic policies that were hostile to free
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a third candidate, the former Caracas mayor,
Claudio Fermin. He has no chance of winning, and has come under
pressure from the Arias camp to withdraw, but chose to remain in
the race because, he said, he did not think the choices available
to voters should be limited to two military officers who have tried
to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Venezuela's sixth vote in less than two years,
including three to draft and ratify a new constitution expanding
presidential powers, and voters are showing signs of boredom and
impatience. At a breakfast with reporters on Friday, Foreign
Minister Jose Vicente Rangel predicted that half of the 11.8
million eligible voters would stay home due to ``voter fatigue''
and a lack of suspense about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I'm getting tired of having to cast a ballot every
few months or so,'' said Zoila Chacon, a sales clerk in a
department store here. ``Democracy is great, but what we really
need is for somebody to do something about the economy, and the
quicker the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's vote was originally scheduled for May 28. But when the
National Electoral Council, dominated by inexperienced Chavez
loyalists, proved unable to provide the ballot information needed
for new computerized voting machines, Chavez reluctantly urged a
postponement rather than running the risk of seeing the legitimacy
of his anticipated landslide victory tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   Council members at first sought to blame an American company
hired to supply the technology for the vote, but that explanation
convinced no one here, and a public furor forced the entire
commission to resign.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the country's chief prosecutor filed corruption
charges against five former members of the council.
</P>
<P>
   Arias and other opposition figures have complained of
irregularities in the new council's organization, saying that
oversight measures that ``would have generated confidence have been
eliminated.'' But international observers maintain that, though
some technical flaws remain, they can find no evidence of a
government effort to steal votes or alter results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no concern that the integrity of the election has been
endangered at all,'' former President Carter, leading a 48-member
observer delegation, said at a news conference here Friday. Ruben
Perina, head of an Organization of American States observer team,
added: ``We see this vote very differently from the May process.''
He attributed the accusations to a growing ``polarization and
mistrust in the political culture here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
