<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REGAINING MIDEAST MOMENTUM  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, July 30:
</P>
<P>
   Israelis and Palestinians are trying to pick up where they left
off at the unsuccessful Camp David summit meeting and continue
moving toward a final peace agreement. It is now critically
important to sustain some of the positive momentum established
there.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, senior negotiators from both sides are to resume
discussions on a range of unsettled issues. The negotiators were
close to the Camp David discussions and are aware of the
path-breaking compromises discussed there on security and border
issues, Palestinian refugees and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   America stands ready to remain involved, with Washington's
Mideast mediator, Dennis Ross, and perhaps Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, prepared to re-enter the discussions if
sufficient progress can be made.
</P>
<P>
   But progress is far from assured, especially with Yasser Arafat
talking about proclaiming a Palestinian state if no agreement is
reached by Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   With that possibility in mind, President Clinton suggested last
week that he might consider relocating America's Embassy in Israel
from Tel Aviv to West Jerusalem. Like most other countries, the
United States resists treating Jerusalem as Israel's capital. Such
a move would be particularly sensitive now, with East Jerusalem the
central issue of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, Israel was prepared to consider an American
compromise plan that would have given Arafat a presidential office
in the Old City of Jerusalem. It would also have joined some Arab
areas of East Jerusalem to Arab suburbs now outside the city to
form, in effect, a new, Palestinian-ruled city of Arab Jerusalem. A
bridge would have linked these Palestinian-ruled areas to Muslim
holy sites in the Old City, guaranteeing unimpeded access to these
shrines.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, regrettably, showed no interest in this proposal,
holding out for full control of all areas of the city formerly
under Jordanian rule. Talks on Jerusalem cannot usefully resume
until Arafat shows a greater willingness to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat seems to feel he cannot do so. His rigidity reflects his
failure to prepare Palestinian opinion for anything less than full
sovereignty over East Jerusalem. But it also reflects the vocal
opposition of Arab countries like Saudi Arabia to recognizing any
Israeli sovereignty there. This Arab opposition must be defused in
the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Barak faces fresh challenges to his government. But
polls taken since Camp David show strong support for continued
peace efforts. Longstanding taboos in Israeli politics were broken
at Camp David. The possible compromises discussed there by Barak
are now being digested by the Israeli public. Equally bold moves
are needed from the Palestinians, especially on Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
