<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6903 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-DONORS-ART-2TA     07-29 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DONORS-ART-2TAKES-865(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS AS USUAL ON CAMERA, PERKS FOR DONORS AND SOLICITATIONS
OFF-STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republican convention opening here on Monday
is really two conventions, one for the delegates in the hall and
another for the party's biggest contributors, who will be treated
to a panoply of perks, from yacht rides to skyboxes high above the
convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   With a record $137.4 million in large contributions already
collected, the Republican Party is flush with soft money, the
unrestricted party checks. But one of the central purposes of the
gathering is to motivate the party's most generous supporters to
raise and give still more.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party is poised to collect a post-convention
windfall from corporate interests. A core group of business donors
_ oil, tobacco, guns, real estate and software _ now form the
financial backbone of the modern Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket of George W. Bush and Dick Cheney is generating even
greater enthusiasm in the business world, and corporate donors have
helped put the Republican Party in the best financial shape it has
ever enjoyed going into a general election.
</P>
<P>
   To capitalize on the popularity of Bush, the second-term Texas
governor, the party has created a new level of top givers _ the
Regents, individuals and companies who have given the party at
least $250,000 since January 1999. As of July 1, the Republican
Party had more than 100 such donors, who will be rewarded at the
convention with skybox seats, private dinners with party leaders,
champagne receptions and deluxe hotel accommodations (most of the
Regents are staying at the Four Seasons). A few will be going on a
fishing trip with House Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, political conventions have revolved around the
drama of delegates selecting a presidential and vice-presidential
nominee or fights over platform issues. With these issues largely
decided before the convention, entertaining donors and pushing them
to contribute more for the general election have become central
parts of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   During the four-day convention, television cameras will focus on
the stage where Bush will accept his party's presidential
nomination and other party figures will speak. But much of the
convention's real business will take place off-camera in hotel
suites, hospitality tents, restaurants and country clubs where
donors will be rewarded for past generosity and asked to give
again.
</P>
<P>
   For the party's top underwriters, there will be an array of
gold-plated events in Philadelphia, including cocktails with Gen.
Colin Powell and an evening cruise on the Delaware River aboard the
``Enterprise,'' the yacht owned by Richard M. DeVos, the Amway
founder, who is a Bush supporter.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of two distinctly different conventions, one a
televised coronation of the Republican ticket, the other a
behind-the-scenes parade of big donor events, is a striking
development, said historian Richard F. Fenno Jr. of the University
of Rochester. ``I'm not sure those two conventions even meet,''
Fenno said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has excited the corporate world more than any recent
Republican presidential nominee, party leaders say. His running
mate, Cheney _ a former congressman and defense secretary who until
his selection was the chief executive of Halliburton Co., the
world's largest oil field services company _ also generates
enthusiasm in corporate boardrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It excites the business community when they see people on the
ticket who know what it takes to meet a payroll, fill out
regulatory forms and pay taxes,'' said Thomas J. Donohue, president
of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Bush's campaign has collected a record $90 million in
federally restricted, individual donations of $1,000 or less;
nearly one-quarter of that amount was raised by a national network
of 212 business executives and wealthy individuals who call
themselves the Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with many of the top 25 soft-money donors to the
Republican National Committee reveal that they are united by their
opposition to what they describe as intrusive government
regulation, their desire for much lower taxes and their loathing of
lawmaking by litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal for a deep tax cut and his record of passing
legislation to limit civil lawsuits in Texas are extremely
appealing to the Republican Party's major underwriters. Meanwhile,
Vice President Al Gore's environmental views, among other issues,
make some donors in the business community nervous.
</P>
<P>
   According to David B. Magleby, director of the Center for the
Study of Elections and Democracy at Brigham Young University, many
of those who write six-figure checks to a political party do so for
calculated business reasons. ``This is money coming from interested
companies and interested individuals who have agendas,'' Magleby
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes for these donors are large: government appointments,
from the Supreme Court to the Environmental Protection Agency;
antitrust enforcement; tax policy; land use decisions; oil drilling
permits; regulatory decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the stakes they have, the investment they have made in
this convention in Philadelphia is very modest, given the potential
rate of return,'' Magleby added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Democrats, of course, will be giving royal treatment to
their largest donors at their convention in Los Angeles, too, with
labor unions, trial lawyers and Hollywood executives among the
biggest underwriters of the Democratic ticket. But the Democratic
Party is struggling to compete with Bush and the Republican Party
in America's corporate suites.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pascoe, the Republican Party press secretary, emphasized
that the party gets the bulk of its financial support from 570,000
small donors, including 140,000 people who contributed to the party
for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fund-raising success is a measure of the broad and deep
support that our party, its principles and our nominee _ Gov.
George W. Bush _ have across this great land,'' Pascoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Republican National Committee's 10 largest donors,
Philip Morris, the National Rifle Association and Microsoft, have
contributed record sums to the Republican Party this year at a time
when they face legal and legislative assaults led by the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Enron Corp., the Republican National Committee's second-largest
donor, strongly favors the party's economic policies, particularly
its preference for free trade and a hands-off approach to the
regulation of business, including enterprises as different as
derivatives trading and Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The companies and the individuals who make up the list of top
contributors to the Republican National Committee say they are
delighted by Bush's rhetoric and his record.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Bush supports limits on damages in
product liability lawsuits and on fees for trial lawyers and
opposes federal anti-tobacco litigation. In Texas, he was also
responsible for a $1.7 billion property tax break and environmental
waivers for the oil and energy industries and has opposed most gun
control legislation and government lawsuits against gun
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sympathetic to lawsuits,'' Bush said at a campaign
stop in Washington state in February. ``Write that down. I worry
about lawsuits on job creation. If you are looking for the kind of
president I will be, I will be slow to litigate.''
</P>
<P>
   This is music to the ears of most business executives.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Philip Morris, the Republican committee's
largest single donor at $619,000 as of June 30, said that the
company supports Republicans because they are ``people who share
similar views on issues that are important,'' including the
regulation of tobacco. Another industry official said he expected
that Bush would treat cigarette companies fairly, while President
Clinton has used the industry as a whipping boy.
</P>
<P>
   Few companies have as much at stake in November's election as
Enron, the giant Houston energy and trading concern that, over the
years, has been Bush's largest corporate sponsor as well as a
generous soft-money donor to the Republican Party. Enron and its
chairman and chief executive, Kenneth L. Lay, have been the top
patrons of Bush's political career since his first campaign for
Congress in 1978. Since January 1999, Enron and its executives have
donated $615,550 to the Republican National Committee, the
second-highest amount of any individual or corporation in that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tenure in Texas has been beneficial to Enron: He backed
several of the company's most important legislative initiatives,
including electric utility deregulation and limits on civil
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Enron is even more explicit about why it wants to see Bush and
other Republicans elected in November. A June 15 internal
memorandum to executives soliciting contributions to the company's
political action committee lays out the reasons: Enron faces
numerous legal and regulatory challenges, the memorandum says,
including taxation of electronic commerce, restructuring of the
electric industry, international trade legislation, regulation of
power plants and oil pipelines and a variety of environmental and
tax issues.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum, which cites a $1 million fund-raising goal,
details suggested ``voluntary'' contributions for Enron executives,
from $500 a year for a low-level manager to $5,000 a year for a
member of the executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic Enron employee who received the letter said some
employees found the solicitation objectionable. The employee also
said that some employees have begun to complain that too many
corporate resources are being spent to support Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wholehearted endorsement of Governor Bush, and the brazen
use of the corporate machinery to ensure his election, seems
distasteful,'' said the employee, who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. Palmer, a vice president at Enron, said the political
action committee is intended to improve Enron's name recognition.
``We are one of the few companies in this industry that has
advocated 100 percent for open markets and for taking away the
monopoly protection that this industry has enjoyed for so long,''
Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association is the fifth-largest donor to the
Republican committee, with contributions totaling $508,000 since
the beginning of 1999. The group has given other Republican
committees an additional $250,000, while donating nothing to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposed state and federal lawsuits against gun makers and
supported the NRA's version of a bill to require background checks
at gun shows. In the House, Cheney was a staunch ally of gun
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Wyly and his brother, Charles J. Wyly Jr., longtime friends
of Bush, are among the most generous individual underwriters of the
Republican Party. They have supported Bush not only with $500,000
in donations to the party but also with a $2.5 million television
advertising campaign against his rival in the Republican primaries,
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Wyly's businesses have fared well during Bush's tenure as
Texas governor. Two years ago, one of the Wyly firms, Maverick
Capital, won a state contract to manage $96 million of the
University of Texas endowment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly said that he supported Republican economic policies, but
that he hoped to make the party more broad-minded on social policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a long history working for minorities,'' Wyly said,
``and I think our efforts make it easier for people of similar
persuasions to feel more comfortable with the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Fox, the chairman and chief executive officer of Harbour
Group, a manufacturing company in Missouri, is the individual who
has contributed the most to the Republican National Committee _
$575,000. But in an interview last week, he insisted that he gives
a lot to the party because it shares his goal of ``good government
and no debts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we part with $250,000 of after-tax money that is not
deductible, we have to believe in the cause,'' Fox said, adding
that he is motivated by a desire ``to see honor and dignity
restored to the White House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
