<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OLDER-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EMPLOYMENT'S NEW AGE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, July 30:
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, American businesses have begun to discover the
value of hiring or retraining older workers. In some cases, those
placements have been for specialized, high-income jobs _ as in the
financial services sector, where companies like New York Life and
Salomon Brothers Asset Management have begun hiring more
salespeople over 50, in part because their age may give them an
edge in a world where two-thirds of the money in the stock market
is controlled by managers over 50.
</P>
<P>
   Other placements have been for specialized, low-income jobs,
like the 100 women, average age 71, hired by Bonnie Bell to package
lip gloss. They replaced a group of younger, less reliable
temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   It is so far a tiny trend. But the reasons for it are big and
growing, and the nation's employers need to learn from them. The
unemployment rate has been hovering around 4 percent in recent
months. The tight labor market, which has created intense
competition for qualified employees at every level, may not be a
fluke but a new reality. That is because it stems not just from a
growing economy, and an older work force that has been retiring at
progressively younger ages, but from a shrinking number of young
workers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to lower birth rates, there are simply fewer young people
available to fill new jobs. Within four years, for the first time
in American history, there will be fewer people aged 20 to 29 in
the population than people 55 to 69. The gap will grow. By 2020,
the younger group may be 40 percent smaller than the older one.
</P>
<P>
   By then, about half the boomer generation _ those 76 million
people born between 1946 and 1964 _ will have passed the age of 65.
They are healthier than their parents. They will live longer, and
two surveys in the last two years, by Fortune magazine and AARP,
found that 74 percent to 80 percent of them expect to still be
working in retirement. A recent Harris poll estimated that there
are 4 million people over 65 who would like to be working
</P>
<P>
   In the past, traditional biases against older workers _ that
they are slow, less motivated than younger people and
technologically inept _ have closed that door. But the changing
demographics led William Zinke, head of a private human resources
company, to commission a survey by Harris last fall of the human
resource directors at almost 800 American companies.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of them agreed that there was less turnover among
older workers than younger ones, 74 percent said they were more
reliable, and 71 percent said they had as much ability to acquire
new skills. Sixty-two percent agreed that younger workers were
actually less creative and innovative than older workers, and 80
percent said they had more absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   It seems a striking vote of confidence by the nation's corporate
gatekeepers in the qualities of older workers. But their actions
have not been the equal of their words. Those gatekeepers have been
doing their best to push older workers out for years, because they
are paid more than younger ones. As the boomer generation begins
turning 55 next year, corporate America should be finding ways to
retain, retrain or rehire old workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
