<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SPOKE OF EMBASSY TO HELP BARAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In raising the prospect of moving the U.S. Embassy
in Israel to Jerusalem, President Clinton was responding to an
unusual request from Prime Minister Ehud Barak as he left the
failed Camp David peace talks to help shore up his political
position back home, administration officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
Saturday that Clinton had decided to use an interview on Israeli
television Friday as a platform to support Barak, who had explained
to Clinton the difficulties he was in during a parting conversation
at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president said that the United States would stand by those
who took risks for peace,'' Berger said. He acknowledged that
Clinton's statement on Jerusalem was more ``forward leaning'' than
in the past and closer to a readiness to make the move.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly spontaneous remark from the president, who said
unprompted that he had ``always wanted'' to move the embassy to
Jerusalem, was actually carefully vetted before hand by U.S.
negotiators who had accompanied Clinton to Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official acknowledged Saturday that Clinton had
raised the issue as a way of trying to help Barak survive a
no-confidence vote scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of preparing for Monday's vote in Parliament,
Barak also called a number of congressmen on Thursday asking them
to introduce a resolution on moving the embassy to Jerusalem,
according to officials familiar with the calls.
</P>
<P>
   Among those Barak telephoned was the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott, and Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, who is chairman of the
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who returned home to raucous criticism in Parliament, for
the concessions he was prepared to make to the Palestinians _
including on the status of Jerusalem _ is considered an absolutely
vital ingredient by the administration for any chance of continuing
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been monitoring on an almost hourly basis
political developments in Israel as Barak faces the no-confidence
vote. By some calculations, if he loses the votes of only two
legislators who supported him on the last no-confidence vote, he
will be forced to call new elections. Barak lost his parliamentary
majority on the eve of coming to the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Clinton's public proclamation on the embassy and
Jerusalem was considered extraordinary because in the past, this
administration has been careful to tamp down any enthusiasm in
Congress for moving the embassy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some Israeli prime ministers, including Yitzhak Rabin, have also
been careful not to encourage too much eagerness for the embassy
move, on the grounds that it would unnecessarily inflame the
Palestinians and set back peace prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Saturday whether Clinton's statement would also serve to
help his wife, Hillary, who is running for the U.S. Senate in New
York, a senior administration official said: ``It had nothing to do
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official said, however, that it was known that as
Clinton prepared for the interview that the relocation of the
embassy to Jerusalem would come up and that a positive answer would
not ``hurt'' Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Clinton himself said that he had refrained
from pushing for the embassy to be relocated before because he was
concerned that such a move would interfere with peace talks between
Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he would ``review'' the idea and make a
decision between now and the end of the year. The president said
that it would be done in ``the light of what has happened'' at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   By making such a pledge, Clinton was also warning the
Palestinians that if they did not come to an agreement, the United
States would consider recognizing Jerusalem as the capital of the
Jewish state. The United States and most other nations have kept
their embassies in Tel Aviv, arguing that the status of the Holy
City remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing the parameters of what Clinton would say in the
interview, U.S. negotiators weighed his position on the embassy as
a six on a scale of 10.
</P>
<P>
   On the lowest end of the scale, Clinton could have said _ as the
White House has in the past _ that it did not want to jeopardize
the peace efforts by advocating a move. Or Clinton could have gone
all-out and said he wanted to move the embassy, a position that the
Whited House ultimately decided was too forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
