u i BC-MIDEAST-ARAFAT-380(2T     07-29 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ARAFAT-380(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISGRUNTLED ARAFAT SEEKS SUPPORT ON TOUR, ACCUSING ISRAEL OF
LYING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A deeply disgruntled Yasser Arafat left his base in
the Gaza Strip on Saturday on a diplomatic tour aimed at
solidifying Palestinian support in the wake of the Camp David
talks.
</P>
<P>
   As the Palestinian leader departed for Paris, where he was to
meet President Jacques Chirac before visits to Russia and several
key Arab nations, he gave vent to some of the frustration and anger
that has built up among Palestinians since the Camp David talks
broke up on Tuesday over the issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks since the talks, President Clinton and Ehud Barak,
the Israeli prime minister, have represented Arafat as the spoiler
who wrecked the possibility of a wide-ranging peace agreement by
rejecting U.S. proposals for the future of the Holy City.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian anger was compounded on Friday when Clinton, seeking
to bolster Barak's political standing in Israel ahead of a crucial
parliamentary no-confidence vote on Monday, gave an interview to
Israeli television saying that Israel's flexible stance at Camp
David had pushed him toward a decision to move the U.S. Embassy in
Israel to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   By raising the possibility of a presidential order for the
embassy to be moved from Tel Aviv, and saying he would make the
decision before the end of the year, Clinton delighted the Jews,
and enraged the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Although largely symbolic when measured against the financial
and diplomatic support the United States has given Israel since
1948, the fact that the U.S. Embassy, along with those of most
other nations, has remained in Tel Aviv has always been taken as a
signal that Washington has not prejudged the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gaza airport, Arafat avoided direct criticism of Clinton,
and of the president's remarks about the embassy issue, masking the
deep dismay that aides said he had expressed privately about
Clinton's remarks since the Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Arafat focused on the Israelis, saying that his
diplomatic tour would seek to counter ``the big lies'' that had
characterized Israeli accounts of Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will put our friends and our brothers, the Arabs and the
Europeans, far away from the Israeli propaganda and big lies that
they are trying to put out about what happened at Camp David,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because Clinton's remarks about Jerusalem were broadcast just as
the Sabbath began on Friday evening, there was little formal
reaction from Israeli politicians. Privately, many were delighted,
although some right-wingers were critical of Clinton for speaking
at a juncture that seemed directly linked to the series of
no-confidence votes that Barak's shaky government faces in Israel's
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli news reports on Friday said that Clinton made the
remarks as a direct result of a telephone call from Barak asking
for a gesture that would bolster his support with the Israeli
public, and in particular with right-wing and religious groups that
will determine whether the government survives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the interview to reiterate his praise of Barak
after the Camp David talks, describing him as ``more creative and
more courageous'' than Arafat in his readiness to accept painful
compromises over Jerusalem. He said Barak had ``done everything he
could to reach agreement while backing the vital interests of
Israel,'' and chided Arafat for saying that the Palestinians would
go ahead with a formal declaration of Palestinian statehood after
Sept. 13. Clinton said that the proclamation of statehood could
have ``consequences,'' including a review of American relations
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of any direct response from Arafat, the
Palestinians made their views known through Hanan Ashrawi, who
frequently acts as a spokesman for the Palestinian cause. In
remarks to Agence France-Presse, Ashwrawi said that Clinton's
remarks exposed the ``underlying American bias'' in the peace
process, and added, ``It sounds like blatant political blackmail,
all in the interest of Barak.'' At another point, she said that the
television interview amounted to ``pandering to Barak and Clinton's
domestic needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The mention of Clinton's political needs at home appeared to be
a veiled reference to an allegation that has frequently been made
in the Palestinian media in recent months, that Clinton has tilted
increasingly toward the Israelis in the peace talks in an attempt
to help Hillary Rodham Clinton in her Senate election campaign in
New York. The suggestion is one that the White House has ridiculed,
saying Clinton is acting in what he regards as the best interests
of peace, not in support of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   What was still more strident was the reaction of Hamas, the
militant Islamic movement that has vigorously opposed Arafat's
engagement in the peace effort. Commenting on Clinton's remarks
about moving the embassy, Mahmoud al-Zahhar, a senior Hamas aide,
hinted that the group could attack U.S. installations in the Middle
East if the move went ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamas will be the first to fight against this issue, and it's
not only Hamas,'' he said in an interview with Reuters. ``The
entire interests of the United States will be in danger in all
Islamic states. Moving the embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem would
be regarded as American recognition of Israel's occupation of
Jerusalem, which is a flagrant challenge to Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   On his tour of Europe and Arab nations, which his aides said
would include Jordan, Saudi Arabia and Tunisia, and possibly other,
non-Arab Muslim states, Arafat will in effect be countering a U.S.
diplomatic offensive in support of Clinton's peace proposals, and
in particular the U.S. plan for Jerusalem. That proposal would give
the Palestinians limited authority in parts of east Jerusalem in
return for giving up their claim to all the eastern half of the
city, which was seized by Israel in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's first stop on his way home on Wednesday was in Egypt,
where he met with President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat will be trying to blunt the impact of a tour beginning
this week by Edward Walker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state
for Near Eastern affairs, who is a former ambassador to Israel and
Egypt. The State Department announced on Friday that Walker would
visit 14 countries over the next several weeks, including Egypt,
Jordan, Lebanon, Syria and Saudi Arabia, apparently in a bid to
change Arab thinking on Jerusalem. Most of the Arab reaction since
Camp David, from governments and in the media, has been strongly
supportive of Arafat's demand that ``all of Jerusalem'' be returned
to the Palestinians in a final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Arafat were at pains not to depict the Palestinian
leader as opening a political battle with Clinton. At Gaza airport,
reporters were told that Arafat had received a private letter of
``encouragement and praise'' from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Palestinian officials urged Clinton to remain impartial.
``We hope he will remain fair in all issues relating to us,'' said
Nabil Shaath, who was an adviser to Arafat at Camp David. Speaking
in the West Bank town of Ramallah, he added, ``We hope that
President Clinton remains as the knight of peace, who continues
what he started at Camp David until we reach a just peace that goes
in line with international legitimacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
