<P>
   CVN-BUSH (Louisville, Ky.) _ George W. Bush challenges Al Gore
to ``pick up the phone'' and urge President Clinton to sign
GOP-backed legislation that would end the penalty paid by many
married couples on their income tax. Clinton has vowed to veto the
bill because, he said, it would drain too much money from the U.S.
treasury. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-EDUCATION (Philadelphia) _ George W. Bush's campaign
aides force the R epublican Platform Committee to withdraw its
efforts to undercut much of Bush's plan to aid and improve
education. The Bush aides also turn back a committee effort to
retain the party's 1996 plank calling for the abolition of the
Department of Education. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-GAYS (Philadelphia) _ Despite strong anti-gay language
in the party platform expected to be approved Monday, Republican
National Chairman Jim Nicholson says the GOP is ``steadfastly
against discrimination of any kind _ against anybody regardless of
their race, sex, creed and any other preferences that they choose
to follow.'' By SUSANNA McBEE.
</P>
