<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FAT-SOUTHERNERS0730-C     07-29 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAT-SOUTHERNERS0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diet? Exercise? We set our own rules
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a nation that just seems to keep getting fatter,
the South is claiming an ever-larger piece of the pie. And the
reasons may be rooted as much in the attitudes Southerners have
about being overweight as in their diets and exercise patterns.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll conducted for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution found
that, while Southerners are significantly more likely than other
Americans to acknowledge that they themselves are overweight, they
are less likely to agree with national guidelines defining what
being overweight means _ and they certainly don't listen to most
government recommendations on eating healthfully and staying fit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll:
</P>
<P>
   Southerners are unlikely to exercise on most days.
</P>
<P>
   They do not eat enough of the right kinds of foods to meet
federal dietary standards.
</P>
<P>
   They believe overweight people face discrimination in daily
life.
</P>
<P>
   They are significantly more likely than other Americans to blame
their own bad habits for being overweight, rather than genetics or
other factors they can't control.
</P>
<P>
   The poll responses help explain why, when it comes to weight and
diet, the South is on the leading edge of a negative trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found that there are regional patterns in the
prevalence of obesity,'' said Deborah Galuska, an epidemiologist in
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's division of
nutrition and physical activity. ``And there is higher prevalence,
in general, in the South and Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Overweight is a national problem. In a special issue of the
Journal of the American Medical Association published last October,
the CDC reported that more than half of all Americans over 18 _ 63
percent of men and 55 percent of women _ could be considered
overweight and, therefore, at risk for heart disease, high blood
pressure, diabetes, gall bladder disease and arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   The prevalence of obesity also was rising: In 1998, 18 percent
of the population qualified as obese. In Georgia, the obesity rate
doubled between 1991 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners are noticing our weight problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have really seen a difference since I moved here,'' said
Rashida Coleman, who is originally from California. ``In fact,
people tell me I should put on weight.'' The 23-year-old, who
participated in the survey, considers herself slightly underweight
and works out only occasionally ``for fun,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, 46 percent of Southerners who were
interviewed felt they were ``slightly overweight'' or ``moderately
to seriously overweight''; in other regions, only 39 percent of
respondents felt the same. And those numbers may be under-reporting
the problem because Southerners, in contrast to the rest of the
country, have a looser definition of what overweight means.
</P>
<P>
   The poll asked how much extra weight an average person would
have to carry to be considered unhealthfully fat. Those outside the
South put the upper limit at 33 pounds for women and 36 pounds for
men; Southerners allowed 36 pounds for women and 40 pounds for men.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the extra weight coming from?
</P>
<P>
   Southerners who participated in the poll agree that eating well
is a challenge. Jodi Lynn Cash, 33, of Dallas, Ga., owner of
Dallas/Millennium Metal Inc., a construction company, watches his
diet carefully to keep trim enough for work. On the road, that can
be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cover probably half the U.S., and when you go into some
towns, you find they've rolled up the sidewalks at 8:30 p.m.,'' he
said. ``Then you're stuck with a Waffle House, or some late night
fast food chain. When you have a chance to get a home-cooked meal,
or some type of vegetable meal, on the road, you have to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra King, a 38-year-old mother of two who works full time,
fights her schedule to be sure she eats well. Recently divorced,
she has recruited her 17-year-old daughter to help cook wholesome
meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do try to think about eating in a healthy way, because there
are health issues in my family,'' she said. ``But I eat out at
lunch, I get home at 6 or 7 p.m., so I'm eating late in the
evening, and then I don't have time to exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Southerners may be heftier than other Americans, but they're
clear about why their weight is rising: Fifty-six percent of poll
respondents in the South agreed that overweight comes from ``bad
diet and exercise habits,'' compared with 49 percent of those
elsewhere. And 80 percent of Southerners felt that fat people
``should take responsibility for their own health and lose
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to see someone who's overweight. It seems like a
shame that they are shortening their life,'' said Jim Stricklin,
54, of Marietta, Ga. His family hails from rural Alabama; he was
raised in New York, but returned south 25 years ago. Summers spent
on his grandparents' farm kept him acquainted with the Southern way
of eating _ ``There wasn't a meal I can think of that didn't have
something deep-fried,'' he said _ but he and his wife, Laura, have
evolved a healthier style instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical breakfast for me is two fruits and a bagel, and
lunch is soup and a salad,'' he said. ``I work out five days a week
in a health club. I am in better shape now than I was in the Air
Force 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Among respondents to the Southern Poll, the Stricklins _ who
work out together on the weekends, often riding their bikes on a
trail near their house _ are extraordinary. According to the
findings, Southerners do not exercise often, and compared with
residents of other regions, Southerners are less likely to eat
dairy products or significant amounts of fruits and vegetables.
Despite those differences, Southerners are as likely as most
Americans to consider themselves to be in excellent or very good
health.
</P>
<P>
   But three out of every 10 Southerners polled said they never
exercise; another two out of 10 exercise one to two days a week.
All told, half the Southern poll respondents do not meet the
minimum goal established by health authorities of 30 minutes of
exercise at least three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners who were asked to estimate what they eat in an
average day came up similarly short of national recommendations.
Almost half the Southerners _ 46 percent _ said they eat no dairy
products or had one serving at most. In the rest of the country,
the proportion of those eating very little dairy-based food was 29
percent. The federal dietary recommendation is two to three
servings of low-fat dairy products a day.
</P>
<P>
   And although the vegetable plate is a Southern icon, almost
one-third of Southerners said they ate no fruit or vegetables on an
average day or consumed one serving at best. In the rest of the
country, only one of every five people eat one or fewer servings
per day. At the other end of the spectrum, one of every four
Southerners said they ate four or more vegetable servings on
average, compared with one-third of other Americans. The national
recommendation is five servings of fruit or vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners and non-Southerners scored roughly the same in the
amount of meat, fish or eggs they eat: Nine of 10 eat up to three
servings of animal protein a day, one more than is called for in
national dietary goals.
</P>
<P>
   In one area, Southern health practices outshine the rest of the
country: Southerners are much less likely to drink unhealthy
amounts of alcohol. According to the poll, 63 percent of those in
the South never drink at all, compared with 51 percent of those
outside the South. Only 15 percent of Southerners drink on more
than two days of an average week; outside the South, it's 21
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners think overweight people carry a social stigma _ but
still want them to take responsibility for their health. More than
three-fourths agreed that obese people face discrimination, and 68
percent thought that wider seats in airplanes and theaters would be
a helpful gesture.
</P>
<P>
   But Southerners aren't willing to be too helpful: Asked whether
obese people should be allowed to park in handicapped spaces or be
given other ``special accommodations,'' 73 percent said no.
</P>
<P>
   With overweight so prevalent, Southerners are likely to have
friends or family members who have struggled with extra poundage.
Combine that with compassion for personal failings, and with
Southern rituals of hospitality, and the reasons for our weight
problem become clearer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us have family members who are larger, and so when you
have people close to you who are like that, you will tend to be
more accepting of other people that you see,'' King said. ``It goes
back to that sense that, if you were overweight, it meant you ate
well, and that meant you had enough money to provide for your
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we like to eat,'' she added, chuckling. ``That may be one
of the main reasons why we have this problem: We just enjoy food.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
