<HEADER>
A6936 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CONVENTION-2TAKE     07-29 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONVENTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO APPEAL TO DEMOCRATS AND INDEPENDENTS IN CONVENTION
SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Gov. George W. Bush said Saturday that in his
speech to the Republican National Convention he would go out of his
way to break through party lines and make a direct appeal to
Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bush said he was determined for the country to
see that he is inclusive. Mindful, perhaps, that this pitch beyond
his party could be unsettling to conservatives, Bush said his
remarks would be subtle _ but unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a sentence in the speech that looks in the camera
and says, `I want you!''' said Bush, speaking from Joplin, Mo.,
where he was wending his way through key states that voted for
President Clinton four years ago. ``But the speech itself should do
that. The speech, if it's done right, and I think it will be, will
send a broadened message.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he said, he would tell the nation about the late Bob
Bullock, a Democrat who was his former lieutenant governor in Texas
with whom he had forged such a close working relationship that
Bullock endorsed him for re-election. He also said he had no
intention of criticizing Hillary Rodham Clinton, a favorite target
at Republican gatherings, saying that the convention was not the
proper forum for attacks.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans gathered here Saturday for the convention's
opening on Monday, Bush said he realized that the usual suspense
may be gone because he has already announced that Dick Cheney is
his running mate. He also said that he had instilled an ``iron-fist
rule'' to make sure there is a harmonious show for the American
public.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that effort, Bush defended his decision to keep some
hard-edged conservatives off stage, saying there were ``no slights
intended.'' He explained that he was determined to avoid a
repetition of the scene at the Houston convention in 1992, which is
remembered not for his father's re-election drive but for the
divisive speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said the '92 convention set a negative tone
and that it set a divisive message for the country,'' Bush said.
``I didn't see it that way at the time. People felt it was part of
a dismal political year. This is a different time, a different
approach, in the sense that we are trying to limit the amount of
time that elected officials are speaking relative to the amount of
time that we spell out policy.'' He added: ``This is not a divisive
moment. This is a uniting moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush acknowledged that all the happy talk could limit the
drama _ and the public's interest in the convention. Asked about
the possible lack of excitement, he laughed and said: ``That's a
pretty legitimate question. I hope, I think, if there is any
suspense it will be in the rollout of ideas. Hopefully, people will
be interested in what I have to say. I hope we can get enough
people to pay attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican presidential candidates have sought to reach
beyond their own party; in fact, they have needed to win over
independents to capture the White House. Bob Dole four years ago
declared in his acceptance speech, ``The Republican Party is broad
and inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush advisers made clear that the governor intends to go
much further than Republicans have in the past, especially in
appealing to Democrats. To drive that message home, Bush will be
introduced at the convention by Bullock's widow, Jan.
</P>
<P>
   And all week long, the stage will be filled with women and
minorities, faces that are not usually highlighted at Republican
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's effort is reminiscent of what Bill Clinton did in his
acceptance speech in 1992. ``The choice we offer is not
conservative or liberal,'' Clinton said. ``In many ways it's not
even Republican or Democratic. It is different. It is new. And it
will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in the interview that he would emphasize how he had
worked with Democrats. ``One of the things that people don't really
know about me is that I've been good about bringing people together
to get things accomplished in Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would not speak directly about how important it was in his
speech on Thursday night to convey to the American people that he
is ready to be president. ``It's hard for me to answer because I
literally don't pay attention to a lot of these polls and focus
groups,'' he said. ``But to the extent that people wonder whether I
can speak before a national audience and speak from my heart _
hopefully the speech will answer that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said his ability to impose an ``iron-fist
rule'' on who can speak and who cannot and limit dissension was
``an indication of the Republican Party's desire to win.'' Taking
issue with conservatives and many members of Congress who were not
invited to speak, he said: ``Not everybody's going to be given a
speaking role because of the limitation in time. There's room for
many voices in our party.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
