<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN0730-COX     07-29 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: It's a dog, dog, dog, dog world
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ This past week, I broke my long-standing rule.
To wit:
</P>
<P>
   You have to take all the dogs God sends you.
</P>
<P>
   I still believe, as I have for some years, that dogs are our
guardian angels. Of course, dogs go to heaven. That's where they
come from, sent down to Earth to watch over us.
</P>
<P>
   As best as I can figure, God must think I need a whole lot of
watching.
</P>
<P>
   We have eight dogs, all of which came from either the side of
the road or the pound. They are:
</P>
<P>
   _ John the Dog, named for John the Baptist, due to his
propensity early on to go wandering in the wilderness, boy dogs
being boy dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Patty, a cocker-sheltie mix, who joined our family after
retiring as the Humane Society's pet-therapy pooch that visited in
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buster Black, a Jack Russell terrier that looks more like a
Jack Rabbit terrier, what with the Chihuahua ancestry of his ears.
I found Buster under the overpass. I whistled and he came right to
me.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maggie Baxter, a shaggy dog right out of a Disney movie. My
wife found her on Thanksgiving night during a sleet storm, sitting
forlornly beside a for-sale sign in the front yard of an empty
house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jag Wire, a small Schnauzer that's our only dog with a
recorded pedigree, complete with official papers when we adopted
her from the animal shelter _ deeply grieved at the time because
her owners had given her up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beauty, a Catahoula cow dog that came to us as a tiny puppy
from a poor family that couldn't afford to care for her. It's not
for nothing she's called a cow dog. That's about the size she's
grown to.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lily, a red-bone hound that's even bigger than Beauty. My wife
found her on the steps of the church house _ thus her name, Lily of
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last and least in size, Lamp Chop, my laptop miniature poodle,
that was little more than a giant-size hair ball matted with grass
burrs when we spotted her lost and alone on a downtown street.
</P>
<P>
   And then, briefly, there was Roscoe, who turned up last week,
crying in the night like a baby.
</P>
<P>
   So much like a baby, in fact, that one of my daughters and her
husband, visiting here with their six-month-old son, went out
before dawn to investigate, thinking someone had abandoned a child.
</P>
<P>
   They found, instead, a tiny beagle-terrier mix about 12 weeks
old, hollering its heart out for someone to help him.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter decided to call him Roscoe, a name that she picked
for no particular reason, but it seemed to fit him just fine, thank
you.
</P>
<P>
   She shampooed him clean of fleas, fed him puppy chow and warm
milk and took him to the vet for a check-up.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no way she could keep him. She already responsible
for a baby, a dog, a cat and a husband, pretty much in that order.
That's enough, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I have no ambition to field a baseball team of dogs.
Eight is enough.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Roscoe has gone to live with my friend Ricky. He
was an easy sell.
</P>
<P>
   Roscoe looked at Ricky. Ricky looked at Roscoe. Roscoe's eyes
brightened up. Ricky's misted over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of the little dog I had as a boy,'' Ricky
sniffed. Roscoe sniffed, too, at Ricky's leg.
</P>
<P>
   They went home together, the two of them meant for each other.
</P>
<P>
   As best as I can figure, maybe God got the address wrong. It
could happen to Anybody.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
TX, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
