<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CONVENTION-2NDTA     07-29 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONVENTION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PHILADELPHIA: our party.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush brushed aside criticism from some moderates that his choice
of Cheney underscores that he is more concerned with burnishing his
credentials on the right. ``To the extent that there's people out
there carping,'' he said, ``that's just normal.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was not worried that in picking a running mate
with far more government service he would draw a contrast to his
own lack of national experience. ``I'm a secure enough fellow to
understand that picking a very strong candidate like Dick Cheney is
the right thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to say how serious he had been about turning to a
running mate who backed abortion rights, like Gov. Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania or Gov. George Pataki of New York. ``I considered a
lot of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was not worried about advisers who have warned that
the campaign is missing a prime opportunity by not sharply
attacking Democrats on stage. ``I will needle my opponent but we
don't have a let's-tear-down night or a slash-and-burn night, or a
night that subjects the other side to public ridicule,'' he said.
``And I'm not going to talk about Mrs. Clinton. She is running for
the United States Senate and has her hands full in the great state
of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also sounded defiant about the criticisms that he has
relied on his father, the former president, for guidance in picking
Cheney and in making other decisions. Bush is clearly taking the
offensive on that count, and said that in his acceptance speech he
planned ``to say how much I love my family _ how much I respect my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush can afford to be so upbeat because many Republicans said
they had not seen such a united party since President Ronald
Reagan's re-election campaign in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen since '84 this degree of unity and enthusiasm
through the ranks left and right of our party,'' said Sen. Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky. ``We're hungry for victory like the
Democrats were in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock, executive director of the Missouri Republican
Party, said the tone of this convention was strikingly different
from ones of the past. ``The goal for the past ones was to come out
unified,'' he said. ``And now we already have that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign and the convention planners took great care to
make sure that when viewers tune in they will see only harmony on
stage _ and a message of moderation and inclusion. People familiar
with the discussions said that while there was no choice but to let
Sen. John McCain speak, given that he emerged from his losing
primary fight with a considerable following, the Bush campaign did
not want its message delivered by more conservative, and perhaps,
outspoken party members, like Alan Keyes and Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, in an interview, insisted that he was not offended. ``In
terms of speaking, realistically, how many people are going to
listen unless you're William Jennings Bryan?'' He said Bush's
acceptance speech ``towers over everything else'' and any other
speech delivered this week. Moreover, Forbes said he was reassured
by Bush's decision to pick a conservative as his running mate.
``His choosing Cheney speaks volumes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans inside and outside the campaign said that since
there is no longer any suspense about a running mate, but far the
most attention will be on Bush's speech. It will be the first time
for millions of Americans to get a close look at Bush _ and for him
to appeal beyond the party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Michael K. Deaver, who was President Ronald Reagan's image
consultant, said Bush has much the same challenge that his boss had
in 1980 at the convention in Detroit, when he used his speech to
reassure the public that he had the breadth and command to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan was a likable guy, people genuinely had a positive
impression of him through Hollywood and through his governor's
days,'' Deaver said. ``But they really weren't sure this guy had
any depth or any original thoughts. That impression began to change
with the speech he gave. Bush is in a similar position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his advisers have sought to play down how much of a
political lift they will get from the convention. They note that
polls show that Republican voters are already much more
enthusiastic about their candidate than Democrats are about Gore _
so they have less room to gain.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, said of
Gore: ``I think he'll get a bigger bounce out of the convention
than we will. There's very little more we can gain by consolidating
our base.'' Asked how much Bush might gain in the polls, he said:
``You can pick up 4 or 5 points. Our view is that he's going to
essentially get twice the bounce out of the convention than we're
going to. We're going to find ourselves in a very tight race after
Labor Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove said he did not see any one particular issue defining the
contest. ``We're in an environment where several issues matter,''
he said. ``Reducing Social Security, national defense _ we're not
in an election where the race is dominated by one overriding
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not worried about Pat Buchanan, the conservative
who is expected to run as the Reform Party nominee, drawing votes
from Bush. ``He's something always to watch, but he is
diminished,'' Rove said. ``He's not grown in stature or grown in
impact as the years have gone on. Why? Because he's Pat Buchanan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign and Bush's supporters do not seem worried that
McCain will try to upstage the nominee when he speaks at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he looks like he's a spoiler in some fashion against George
Bush,'' said Pat Robertson, the founder of the Christian Coalition
and a foe of McCain's, ``it will destroy him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is clearly delighting in this opportunity to be glorified
all week by his party. Asked what will be the convention's best
moment, he referred to his speech, saying, ``It's when, from my
selfish perspective, it's walking out on that stage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
