<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TRADES ARE SYMPTOM OF BASEBALL'S INEQUITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a little general manager in every sports fan. If you
don't think so, check out the ravers and the ranters, the schemers
and the dreamers, on talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   While weaving through traffic, these people call up and propose
the most outrageous trades. Someday soon I fully expect to hear a
collision live on WFAN radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawg, what about Clay Bellinger and Wilson Delgado for Edgar
Martinez? That seems fair to me. I mean, the Yankees need a better
DH. (sounds of shearing metal and shattering glass). Oops, Dawg,
gotta go. I just rear-ended a Beamer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with both hands on the wheel and both eyes on the road,
fans love trades, except when their own favorite player is exiled.
Then it gets personal.
</P>
<P>
   I will never forget the morose sound of our third child,
muttering, ``It stinks, it just stinks'' when the Mets traded his
scuzzy idol, Lenny Dykstra, for a mope named Juan Samuel. It turned
out to be the third-worst trade in Mets history (right behind the
ones that ditched Nolan Ryan and Amos Otis), and it is a safe bet
the Mets are not promoting that blatant miscalculation among the 10
greatest moments in history on Old-Timers Day on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, when old-timers lumber back for their reunions,
most of them feel withdrawal pangs from the way they left in the
first place _ some sheepish clubbie sidling over to them and
whispering, ``Hey, could you see the GM out in the hallway?''
</P>
<P>
   There have always been trades, so try as I might I cannot work
up severe bombast about the assorted comings and goings the past
few days.
</P>
<P>
   When players like Curt Schilling and Mike Bordick start flying
around in the closing hours of the baseball trading period, it just
seems like business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The rich get richer; what else is new? The Arizona Diamondbacks
now go into the postseason throwing Randy Johnson and Schilling in
every series. Schilling won his first start Friday night and
chortled more about his double than his pitching.
</P>
<P>
   It seems downright unfair for a first-place team to be able to
afford a horse like Schilling. However, the real inequity in
baseball stems from the division of local television revenue,
according to a recent so-called blue-ribbon panel. (Just what is a
blue-ribbon panel? Is that like the first prize in the breeder pig
category at the county fair?)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, these blue-ribbon experts determined that baseball was
operating with a tilted table because the Yankees realized $175.94
million in so-called local revenues while the Expos were pulling in
only $11.97 million in local revenue.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the Yankees were twirling their gold chain like a
latter-day Sportin' Life in ``Porgy and Bess,'' crooning, ``There's
a jet that's leaving soon for New York,'' trying to lure Rondell
White from the destitute denizens of La Belle Provence.
</P>
<P>
   Weak teams cough up expensive players this time of year. Get
used to it. Then there is the sad drama of useful players caught in
the crossfire. No doubt Mets fans are mourning the exile of Melvin
Mora, the soulful utility man who was shuttled off to barren
Baltimore in the rent-a-shortstop move for Bordick.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Mora. He loves New York, loves Bobby Valentine, loves the
Mets, and now he has been dealt to the latter-day 25-man, 25-cabs
ice age of the Orioles, the most sour and solipsistic rich team on
the face of the earth, in the last decade or two of the Cal Ripken
era.
</P>
<P>
   But as the man said in the movie, there's no crying in baseball
_ and no loyalty in sports. Certainly not at those prices.
Disloyalty runs both ways. Players bolt teams. Teams discard
players. And the fans would trade anybody, too. Just listen to
them.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like a sharp elbow in the nose of Phillies fans to
unload Schilling with more than two months left in a season, but
where were the Phillies going, anyway? Besides, teams have come
back from the bitterness of these late-July discount sales.
</P>
<P>
   It was only three years ago that the Chicago White Sox divested
themselves of just about their entire pitching staff. Words like
``travesty'' and ``contempt'' were bandied about, some of them in
this very space. The White Sox management was spitting in the face
of its fans, cutting the payroll, cheating the ticket-holders. All
of the above. Yet these are the very same White Sox who are so far
ahead of Cleveland that the Indians themselves were making deals
just to prove they exist.
</P>
<P>
   Or, what about the Seattle Mariners? They have survived twin
disasters. This is the second anniversary of the vanishing of Randy
Johnson, a spectral presence in the Mariners' dugout one inning, on
a jet to the National League the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Ken Griffey Jr. left the Mariners in midseason,
although his uniform remained active until the final day of the
season. This year Junior is presiding over the downfall of the
Reds. Meanwhile, the Mariners are once again in first place, using
good young players obtained in the Johnson deal, and hoarding money
from Junior's departure that they will try to use to retain Alex
Rodriguez, probably in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the moment, Seattle is competitive. This year is all
that matters. In the long run, local revenue separates winners from
losers (except for the Orioles, of course). Lack of money does
indeed guarantee failure. We already knew that, long before the
blue-ribbon panel told us.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
