<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CALIF-SURFER-ART-NYT &LR;      07-29 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SURFER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFER CHASES THE MOON IN A RIPKEN-LIKE EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Hawaii)  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``a.'')  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 3, 4 and 9 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a typically foggy morning recently in Bodega Bay, a
fishing village along Highway 1 on the Northern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   The water was 52 degrees, and you could see your breath. A sign
at the Bodega Dunes Campground beach warned of dangerous undertow,
rocks and sharks. ``Surfing Unsafe,'' it read. ``No Lifeguard On
Duty.''
</P>
<P>
   The only ones in the water were the seals and the sea lions _
and, of course, Dale Webster. Wearing a wetsuit with hood, boots
and gloves, he had been riding waves for a good two hours and now
sat straddling his board, surveying the swells rolling steadily
toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was his wave. He leaned back and deftly pivoted his
board around. He gave a couple of quick paddles and sprang to his
feet. Sliding down the face of the glassy 4-foot wave, he began
dancing on it with the grace of Fred Astaire and rode it smack onto
the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Some beachcombers in jeans and windbreakers stared, but it was
just another day of surfing for Webster _ actually, his 9,067th
consecutive day of surfing, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   Webster, 51, has surfed every day since Sept. 2, 1975. It all
started, he said, when Bodega Bay was pounded with 15-foot waves
for a week straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surfed all seven days,'' he said, ``and then I thought, `Let
me see if I can keep this going.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And 25 years later, he's still going. As of Saturday, the streak
had reached 9,097. Webster intends to continue the streak until he
completes a 28-year lunar cycle, surfing the tides caused by the
moon in all its calendar phases. He will not be happy, he said,
until he can reuse his original 1976 tide chart book in February
2004, when the days of the week will fall on the same calendar
dates as they did in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Other quirky personal goals and theories help fuel his streak.
For example, 1976 was a leap year in which February had five
Sundays. He surfed each of them and hung five _ draped five toes
over the front of the board's nose _ on the final Sunday, Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on hanging five again on Feb. 29, 2004,'' he said.
``That's called hanging 10 the hard way. Then I'll be the hyperbole
Sunday surfer.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as daily surfing streaks go, Webster is in a class of his
own, said Drew Kampion, a former editor at both Surfer and Surfing
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale Webster _ actually, we call him Daily Wavester _ has a
whole different concept of longevity,'' said Kampion, the author of
``Stoked: A History of Surf Culture'' (General Publishing Group,
1997). ``I mean, surfing for a lunar cycle, no one's ever even come
close to that. It's just so far out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Local surfers here wear wet suits 5 millimeters thick
year-round. At the beginning of his streak, Webster bought an
O'Neill wet suit with a one-year warranty. Thereafter, every Sept.
2, he traded in his suit, worn out from daily use, for a new one.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years of this, the company decided to give Webster wet
suits free, because he was such an advertisement for their
durability.
</P>
<P>
   And Webster caused the company to add a ``10,000-wave clause''
to its warranty, a maximum-use caveat prohibiting exchanges for all
suits subjected to unusually intense use. Dozens of shredded wet
suits hang in Webster's shed at home, a testament in tattered
neoprene to his streak.
</P>
<P>
   Webster himself, however, is anything but worn out. He has a
broad back, long stringy blond hair and piercing blue eyes that
focus on the horizon when he speaks.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up surfing in San Diego, and in 1973 he moved to Bodega
Bay, which is 75 minutes north of San Francisco (Alfred Hitchcock
filmed most of ``The Birds'' there). He now lives in Valley Ford
(population, 126), a dairy community near Bodega Bay. He works as a
custodian at Bodega Bay Elementary School, with a clear view of the
ocean from the parking lot where he parks his 1981 Toyota Corolla.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 10 years of his streak, Webster would ask
witnesses _ surfers, beachgoers, park rangers _ to sign his log
book to verify that they saw him surfing. His wife, Kaye, his
frequent surfing partner until she injured her knee in 1995, also
kept a diary. But often elements like storms or fog made witnesses
scarce. Sometimes people refused to sign, bewildered by the
request.
</P>
<P>
   His requirement for a daily surf session means riding at least
three waves regardless of height. His norm is about 20 waves in
roughly two hours. But some days, the weather can be brutal or the
waves almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Deterrents include the water temperature, which ranges from 48
to 58 degrees. Surfers have been killed by waves and sharks in the
area, and Webster said he once crossed paths with a 20-foot great
white.
</P>
<P>
   He has paddled out in hurricane force winds and surfed with
illnesses of all kinds, including the flu, sprains, cuts and
earaches. Once a kidney stone attack left him barely able to walk.
His wife carried his board, he surfed three waves and was then
taken to the hospital directly afterward. ``I had to crawl on the
beach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The surfing part was difficult enough, said Webster, who for
years had little money and no car. He relied on his wife, friends,
or else his thumb, to get to the beach. He supported his surfing
addiction with dozens of different menial jobs, quitting them when
they interfered with his surf sessions.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing interferes with his surf sessions. Not family. Not
geography. Not travel or vacations or dark of night.
</P>
<P>
   Since he cannot take vacations inland, he has never visited the
in-laws in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   When flying, he insists upon surfing beforehand. Once, on a trip
to Hawaii, he arrived on the Big Island of Hawaii in late afternoon
and found the water completely flat on the Kona coast. So he raced
back to the east coast and found some waves just before dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of all the things I'll have missed in life because of
this,'' he said. ``The only thing I'll have is the memory of riding
all those waves. When I'm out there watching the seals and sea
lions, and 30-inch salmon jumping, and I have all those waves to
myself, it's like my own personal Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   For surfers, Bodega Bay is Disneyland. The coastline there gets
consistent surf because it is exposed to ocean swells from all
directions, said Kampion, the editor and author who speaks of
Webster like a zen figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's this passionate, inspired guy who was looking for an aim
and a goal in his life and struck upon this,'' Kampion said. Then,
quoting the poet William Blake, he added: ``If a fool persists in
his folly, he can become wise. And this is making him a wise man.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, his consistency inspires others around him. Margo, his
daughter, 13, is entering the ninth grade and has never missed a
day of school.
</P>
<P>
   She has been surfing since she was 3, she said, standing next to
her dad recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not every day,'' she added looking down sheepishly at her
sneakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-WESTERN-ISSUES0730-CO     07-29 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-ISSUES0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What plays well in Peoria might not play well here
 &HT;    By Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Never underestimate the importance of
the West to presidential candidates on the stump, especially when
reaching out to voters outside the West.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting wilderness, for instance, ``plays well in
California,'' said Michael Gizzi, a professor of political science
at Mesa State College, even if it might not win Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of directional drilling for electoral votes _ sink a
drill in the red-rock side of flyover country and hope to strike
gold in California or New York _ is a staple of national
campaigning. In some cases this year, though, the direction gets
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates often broach regional issues as
spin-offs of major national issues. Republican candidate George W.
Bush, for instance, says on his website that he favors elimination
of the estate tax ``to make it easier for private landowners to
pass their land, intact, from one generation to the next'' _ an
approach tailor-made for ranchers and farmers in the West and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has a horde of proposals aimed at
improving rural transportation and economies, all available on his
website, algore2000.com. Gore even pitches a program to put a kiosk
at every rest stop along interstate highways directing motorists to
interesting places off the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   As they hone their pitches, particularly on the Internet, the
major presidential candidates appeal to narrow constituencies while
trying to preserve their broad demographic attraction.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore administration would move to increase the number of parks
and boost protections for threatened land while balancing the
environment and the economy, said Jano Cabrera from Gore
headquarters in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under a Gore administration,'' said Cabrera, ``American
families would have easy access to parks and open spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's site, georgewbush.com, is less detailed than Gore's,
which might reflect differences over activist government.
</P>
<P>
   On urban sprawl, Bush says the challenges of land management are
best handled by state and local governments. Still, he advocates
putting $900 million into the Land and Water Conservation Fund,
with 50 percent of the money earmarked for state and local
programs. Bush also proposes a $50 million program for the states
to tap into encourage landowner protection of rare species.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Owens, a Republican, couldn't be reached on what
Bush's campaign would promise to western Colorado and the West in
general.
</P>
<P>
   Gore tip-toes around the West's unique perspective of being a
major potential supplier of energy resources with his energy
policy, which calls for tax breaks for natural-gas production. The
proposal is weighed heavily toward other measures, such as tax
credits for the purchase of energy-efficient vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says nothing on the subject of a national energy policy on
his site, but does attack Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   On immigration, U.S. Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Colo., said a Bush
administration would pursue a different course than those of his
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Bush would come in with the idea that immigration
is not inherently evil,'' McInnis said, predicting that immigration
will be a campaign issue that strikes chords with Grand Valley
farmers, ranchers and fruitgrowers.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis praised Bush's proposal to separate the enforcement and
processing functions of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
Under the current organization, ``People tend to get into a law
enforcement mode and be suspicious of everybody who comes in the
door,'' McInnis said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on the subject of immigration, Gore spokesman Cabrera
referred to Gore's urging that Congress approve the judicial
nomination of Enrique Moreno of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has no position on Western water issues and for that
matter, neither does Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, though, ``is pretty well-known on his approach to these
types of ians support monument establishment and land-preservation
efforts, ``but a lot of people aren't comfortable with the process
that created it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such nuance tends to get lost in the polarizing influence of
presidential campaigns. McInnis, while eager to portray Gore as a
distant federal figure, concedes that the vice president ``has
espoused the right kinds of things some times.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether a candidate can strike the right chords remains to be
seen, Gizzi said.
</P>
<P>
   The election ``is a long way away, three and half months,'' he
said. ``It doesn't take a lot for a candidate to raise an issue at
some point.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
