<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MAY CASH IN ON HEAVY PAYROLL INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-NOTEBOOK)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the days of a $100 million payroll, in other words last
season, seven of the nine teams with the highest payrolls reached
the playoffs. The Baltimore Orioles and the Los Angeles Dodgers
stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the way through this season, it is obvious that
the Orioles will again stay home, where they will languish for the
third successive season despite spending more money on their
payroll ($229 million) in that period than any team except the
Yankees ($246.5 million). For all of their lavish expenditures, the
Orioles have fizzled faster than a July 4 fireworks show in the
rain.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, on the other hand, present the appearance of a
contender and may finally gain some reward for their payroll
proclivities, which have made them No. 3 ($221.4 million) behind
the Yankees and the Orioles in this three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're in position to make a good run,'' General
Manager Kevin Malone said. ``We control our own destiny. We're
right where we need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers began play Saturday 2 1/2 games from first place in
the National League West and 2 1/2 games from the wild-card lead.
Since the end of the interleague portion of the schedule, they had
won 10 of 13 games and all four series they had played.
</P>
<P>
   And in the midst of that stretch, they weathered news media
reports that if the Dodgers did not get to the playoffs this year
they would fire Davey Johnson as manager and try to replace him
with the San Francisco Giants' Dusty Baker, the manager of one of
the two teams ahead of them in the division race.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a big payroll, you need to win,'' Johnson said.
``Anything else doesn't matter. I've dealt with that before.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson recently also had to deal with an incidence of
arrhythmia, which put him in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to make this work,'' he said of the team and
its chances of winning. ``I'm going to try not to let it kill me. I
don't want to be looking up; I want to be looking down.''
</P>
<P>
   He referred to his position in life, but he could just as well
have meant the Dodgers' position in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are not generally viewed as strong a contender as
Arizona and San Francisco, but when given a decent team to work
with, Johnson has produced impressive results. His first team in
Los Angeles did not meet that criterion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's team was basically a right-handed ballclub,'' said
Johnson, who was the Orioles' manager in their last two playoff
appearances. ``The bench was very weak. The bullpen was very weak.
And there was no depth or flexibility in any area. There were a lot
of middle infielders on the 40-man roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone made improvements in those areas during the off-season,
and some of the moves paid off in helping the Dodgers overcome a
raft of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had had the kind of injuries last year that we've had
this year, I'd hate to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley, the power-hitting catcher, returned last week from
his second spell on the disabled list, this one for a fractured
thumb. Center fielder Devon White recently came back after missing
2 1/2 months with a partially torn rotator cuff. Third baseman
Adrian Beltre missed three weeks earlier in the season with a
strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, the No. 1 starter, and Jeff Shaw, the closer,
headed a long list of pitchers who have served time on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   The team's most important hitters, however, Gary Sheffield, Eric
Karros and Shawn Green, have remained healthy. Sheffield's bat, in
fact, has been especially healthy. Possibly headed for the best
season of his 12-year career, Sheffield went into Saturday's
schedule leading the major leagues with 34 home runs and had driven
in 87 runs with a .340 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's comfortable; he's at peace with himself,'' Malone said of
the outfielder who has often been an angry player. ``His wife has
had a positive impact on him, and he's grown spiritually.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he has been impressed with Sheffield's versatility
as a hitter. ``He hits home runs, but when he needs a base hit, he
gets it,'' the general manager said. ``He can hit the ball the
opposite way. For a guy with his power he has tremendous bat
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield and friends have provided sufficient run production,
and the relief corps have given the Dodgers a sterling effort. As
with so many contenders, the team's playoff chances will most
likely fall on their starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has performed as a No. 1 starter should, compiling a 10-3
record with a 2.31 earned run average. Chan Ho Park, with an 11-7
record, seems to have straightened himself out after having gone a
month (June 18 to July 20) without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers need consistently effective work from Darren
Dreifort (3-0, 1.29 ERA last three starts) and Carlos Perez, as
well as Ismael Valdes, whom they reacquired from the Cubs last week
after having traded him to Chicago last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreifort has been brilliant at times and mediocre or bad at
times,'' Johnson said. ``Perez has been OK, kept us in some ball
games. You've got to get three out of five well-pitched games,
sometimes four out of five. That's what the good clubs do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have two months to show they belong in that
category. The Orioles have already proved they do not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
