<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' FIVE-MAN INFIELD; 3 FORMER METS IN TRADES; MAKING DEALS TO
CONTEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-DODGERS)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The box score suggested an image that simply didn't compute: Mo
Vaughn playing center field.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, next to Vaughn's name in the box of Anaheim's game in
Texas last Wednesday night was the position designation
``1b-cf-1b.'' And just two names later, it said ``G. Anderson
cf-1b-cf.'' That combination indicated that sometime during the
game Vaughn and Anderson switched positions.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, as it turned out. Several times this season, Mike
Scioscia, the Angels' manager, has brought in an outfielder to
serve as a fifth infielder in obvious sacrifice situations. In this
instance, Frank Catalanotto lashed a pinch-hit triple with one out
in the ninth inning of a 5-5 game. With Luis Alicea the next
batter, Scioscia called for his five-man infield.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson came in from center and assumed the first baseman's
position. Vaughn moved to his right, stationing himself near where
the second baseman usually plays. Adam Kennedy, the second baseman,
played up the middle. The shift turned out to be unnecessary;
Alicea hit a fly to left. Anderson went back to center, Vaughn to
first, but Rusty Greer singled to left, ending the game.
</P>
<P>
   3 FORMER METS IN TRADES
</P>
<P>
   They are all gone now, Jason Isringhausen, Bill Pulsipher, Paul
Wilson. At one time they were the future nucleus of the New York
Mets' starting pitching rotation. But injuries undermined that
plan, leaving the trio as prime examples why some contending teams
are not reluctant to trade top prospects for established
major-league players when they have a chance to get to the
playoffs. Prospects don't come with guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets sent Isringhausen to Oakland at the trading deadline
last year. They traded Pulsipher, for the second time, to Arizona
two months ago after having reacquired him from Milwaukee last
January. Wilson, who seemingly has been on perpetual rehab, was the
last to go, leaving the organization Friday in a trade to Tampa
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING DEALS TO CONTEND
</P>
<P>
   Teams are no longer considered set. They are works in progress,
contending teams every bit as much as less talented, less
experienced clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians came into this season with a string of
five division titles, but stuck 10{ games from No. 6, they
reconfigured 20 percent of their roster in a matter of hours
Friday. In a series of three trades, they added two starting
pitchers (Jason Bere and Steve Woodard), changed their closer (from
Steve Karsay to Bob Wickman) and acquired a first baseman (David
Segui) and a designated hitter (Wil Cordero).
</P>
<P>
   In a frenzy of trade activity, the Indians and two other playoff
contenders executed six trades involving 25 players Friday, and the
deadline for trades without waivers isn't until 4 p.m. tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Six other contenders had previously made moves to bolster their
chances. Prime among them were the Yankees, who have not been
satisfied to rest on the laurels of their World Series success in
recent seasons. Their acquisitions changed 16 percent of their
roster.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent newcomer, Glenallen Hill, won a game for them
Friday night with a pinch-hit grand slam. Another of their
reinforcements, Denny Neagle, has pitched two victories and would
have had three if the bullpen had held his lead Friday. Andy Ashby
has pitched three victories for Atlanta. Curt Schilling won his
first start for Arizona on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona, the defending champ, went out and got arguably the
best pitcher available,'' Davey Johnson, the Los Angeles manager,
said. ``I like Neagle and I like Ashby, but when healthy, Schilling
is the pick of the litter.''
</P>
<P>
   The most untimely trade of those made so far was the one between
the Indians and Milwaukee on Friday. In going to Cleveland, Wickman
left behind 30,000 posters of himself. They were to be given to
fans at the Brewers game Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mentioned it to Dean _ jokingly,'' Jon Greenberg, the
team's media relations director, said, referring to General Manager
Dean Taylor. ``But naturally baseball takes precedence.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, however, was undaunted. ``We'll give them away
anyway,'' he said. ``He was our All-Star.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
