<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-SALMON-NYT &LR;      07-29 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-SALMON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: ATLANTIC SALMON IN NEW BRUNSWICK 
</HEADLINE>
   By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was early evening when my guide, Gerry Thomas, and I arrived
at Humbug Pool on the Upsalquitch River in New Brunswick. The river
was fairly low, low enough for wading. I eased myself over the side
of the canoe, not motivated by caution but by a desire to savor my
first Atlantic salmon fishing trip in the new century. It was also
hot and muggy, a day that courted languor.
</P>
<P>
   I had already tied on one of my favorite wet flies for salmon,
the venerable Blue Charm. I asked Gerry where he wanted me to
start, a ritualistic query because over the years we have fished
Humbug many times together. Then I waded halfway across the river,
enjoying the pressure of the cool water, 64 degrees, against my
legs. I had worked out about 70 feet of line when Gerry said,
``That's far enough, Nelson.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving downstream three or four feet after every cast, I was
soon rewarded with a solid hit. The take had been invisible, no
flash of a silver side, no burst of spray. The spray came later as
the grilse _ a precocious salmon, usually a male, that returns to
its natal stream after only one year at sea _ hurled itself into
the air three times as it surged up and down the pool.
</P>
<P>
   I am always surprised anew at the strength of a fish that
usually weighs no more than five pounds and startled by its
throbbing energy when I remove the fly from its jaw. We set it
free.
</P>
<P>
   Deep shadows covered most of the pool when I resumed fishing
with the Blue Charm, and I soon caught another grilse, which was
also released. In happier days, I would have kept both grilse, but
the Atlantic salmon is in trouble and one hesitates to diminish its
numbers. New Brunswick's current limits for the species allow an
angler to kill two grilse a day. The larger salmon, those that have
spent more than one year in the Atlantic, must be released.
</P>
<P>
   Back at our base at Two Brook camp, I discovered that my fishing
companion Peter Maas, who had gone downriver with the camp manager
and guide, Lee Marshall, had already returned. He was settled in
his favorite Two Brook armchair, drink in hand and looking
fulfilled, perhaps even gleeful. ``Two hits, two grilse,'' I said.
``How about you?''
</P>
<P>
   He rattled the ice in his glass and responded nonchalantly,
``Four grilse.''
</P>
<P>
   I congratulated him. I was sincere, but also slightly irked. We
both write for a living, but my realm is hunting and fishing, and
his books probe other thickets and other waters. Not discounting
his uncanny knack for being in the right place at the right time, I
should have at least a slight edge when salmon are the quarry. On
our previous visit to Two Brook, he had come behind me, fishing
pools where I had struck out a few hours before, catching salmon
and grilse with disconcerting consistency.
</P>
<P>
   I have never liked angling competitions, but Peter and I have
somehow become engaged in an informal and ongoing salmon fishing
contest.
</P>
<P>
   We were at Two Brook as the guests of Joseph Cullman III of
Manhattan. Cullman and his other guests _ Marian Heiskell and
Murray Bring of Manhattan and Joan Wulff of Lew Beach, N.Y. _ were
at Cullman's Runnymeade Lodge on the Restigouche River, into which
the Upsalquitch flows.
</P>
<P>
   Peter and I were back on the Upsalquitch early the following
morning. On our way upriver, Gerry Thomas and I passed a single hen
merganser with 21 ducklings, about double the normal brood for one
hen. She was at the rear of the frantic flotilla, which was
swimming and half-flying ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   We found a pool with several grilse in it and in less than an
hour I had hooked four of them, losing two and landing two, all
save one on the Blue Charm. That one, which I kept, had made three
passes at the Blue Charm, missing it each time, so I switched to a
dry, a Gray Wulff, and he was mine.
</P>
<P>
   Peter caught one grilse that morning. We made the hour's drive
to Runnymeade at midday to have lunch with the others. There we
learned that everyone had taken fish, whether salmon or grilse,
either on Runnymeade waters or on two stretches _ Main Pool and
Matapedia Run on the Restigouche _ controlled by the Ristigouche
Salmon Club. Marian Heiskell was ecstatic, having hooked and landed
two salmon at the Matapedia Run. As we lingered at our meal, dark
clouds piled up over the broad valley, bringing rain, torrential at
times, that lasted about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Peter and I drove to the Ristigouche Salmon
Club and the others of our party went to Two Brook. An
ever-attentive host, Cullman wanted each of us to have a shot at
all the available water.
</P>
<P>
   When Maas and I reached the highway bridge over the Restigouche
between New Brunswick and Matapedia, Quebec, I saw a long, wide,
brown stain, runoff from the storm, covering most of the area we
were to fish. Fishing for salmon in dirty water is usually a
worthless endeavor, and had I been alone I would have returned to
Runnymeade, and an afternoon's reading.
</P>
<P>
   We flailed the water until dark and the only fish we caught or
saw was a grilse that I took in the last half hour on a huge, ugly,
dirty-water wet fly, a cross between a Mickey Finn and an Edson
Tiger. The water was still somewhat discolored when we returned the
following morning and it was Peter's turn to catch the only fish, a
good-sized grilse.
</P>
<P>
   Cool weather moved in. Peter and I went back to Two Brook that
afternoon, and along with Joan Wulff, who loves the remote and
intimate Upsalquitch, we had some first-rate fishing that night and
the next day, our last. On the final morning I caught two grilse
and returned to camp to find Peter in the chair with an ice pack on
his swollen right knee. It had given way while he was wading
Caribou Pool. He had gone down facing upstream with water pouring
into his waders and was extricated from that position by his guide,
John Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, fishing different pools, Joan Wulff and I had fun
with both grilse and salmon that repeatedly slashed at our dry
flies, but didn't connect. Each of us muffed one good chance;
Joan's opportunity came while fishing a deer-hair mouse. Her
attention was diverted for an instant, the instant in which a
good-sized salmon engulfed the mouse, then rejected it. My
opportunity came when a nice grilse took my Royal Wulff, then spit
it out before I was able to tighten the line. My only excuse is
that having floated that fly over the same grilse more than 20
times, my attention had flagged.
</P>
<P>
   Peter had gamely limped back into the river that afternoon,
catching one grilse for a total of seven for the trip, one shy of
my effort.
</P>
<P>
   Rattling the ice in his drink that night, he said to me,
``You're top rod.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have added ``this time,'' but he didn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
