<HEADER>
A6968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COX-GOP-STRATEGY-0730     07-29 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GOP-STRATEGY-0730 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP SEES POSITIVE SPIN AS KEY TO VICTORY
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA Persuaded that the way to win in November is to
make nice in August, the Republicans have made a top-level decision
to curb their Democrat-bashing during their upcoming four-day
national
</P>
<P>
   convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of 10 _ where a 10 would mean we'd ignore the other
party altogether and showcase only our own virtues _ we'll probably
come out here somewhere near an eight,'' GOP National chairman Jim
Nicholson said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have a positive image with the voters,''
Nicholson told reporters at a breakfast meeting. ``So it's vitally
important that this convention reflect that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson noted that, according to past polling, nearly 25
percent of U.S. voters said they decide which presidential
candidate they will support on Election Day based on the
impressions that they come away with _ both direct and indirect _
from the two major national political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The limited-bashing convention tactic also reflects the overall
campaign strategy that has been adopted by the Republicans'
presumptive presidential nominee, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. On
Thursday evening, Bush is scheduled to deliver an acceptance speech
that promises to be the most widely watched event at the Republican
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   In a interview on Friday with ABC's Nightline, Bush again
stressed his intention to run a positive campaign. He said he would
limit his attacks against his Democratic opponent, Vice President
Al
</P>
<P>
   Gore, to ``only those times and places where we're obliged to
counter-punch because (the Democrats) have distorted our positions
or our record.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision to tap former Defense Secretary Richard Cheney
as his running mate offers another signal that the Bush camp
believes it would be better off by adopting a positive message
during the fall
</P>
<P>
   campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In an approach that goes back to the 1952 Republican ticket of
Dwight Eisenhower and Richard Nixon, the former general took the
high road while Nixon took on the ``attack dog'' role against the
then
</P>
<P>
   incumbent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The convention tactics outlined by Nicholson stand in bold
contrast to what the Republicans did at their 1996 convention in
San Diego. On that occasion, for example, Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Tex., launched a
</P>
<P>
   vicious partisan attack against President Clinton, who was
seeking a second term.
</P>
<P>
   While her remarks played exceedingly well with the GOP partisans
in the convention hall, subsequent surveys showed that they tended
to alienate key swing voters who at the time were weighing whether
to
</P>
<P>
   support Clinton or the GOP nominee, former Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush needs a positive convention,'' says Dick Morris, a former
Clinton political strategist who has also worked for Republicans.
``The GOP blew its 1992 convention by concentrating on attacking
Hillary
</P>
<P>
   Clinton. They screwed up their 1996 confab by lacing into her
husband. They need to avoid partisanship in Philadelphia at all
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to ``go positive'' in 2000, Nicholson said, is
that ``we have our political base locked down and the Democrat
Party does not.''
</P>
<P>
   If the party chairman's analysis is correct, it means that Gore
would have to make a major effort wooing such members of his core
constituency as blue-collar workers, who remain suspicious of the
</P>
<P>
   administration's trade policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on the other hand, would feel more free to stress issues
that appeal to swing voters, such as improving the nation's schools
and reforming Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass' e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.co
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB:
</P>
<P>
   www.gopconvention.com
</P>
<P>
   www.rnc.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
