<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will Cheney's Western roots influence regional issues?
 &HT;    By Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ George W. Bush's selection of a
Westerner to be his running mate suggests greater national
involvement in parochial, Western issues, say political observers.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Dick Cheney, who spent 12 years in Washington,
D.C., as Wyoming's lone congressman, on the national Republican
ticket might mean ``some Western issues will get a little more air
time,'' said Pete Kolbenschlag, Western Slope director for the
Colorado Environmental Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   What happens after that, though, depends on the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbenschlag, for instance, would welcome greater federal
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, public-lands issues are really important and
unfortunately, they don't get a lot of attention in presidential
debates, which are dominated by more urban environmental issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Gore, a Glade Park rancher, is banking on Cheney's
reputation to shore up traditional arm's-length Republican policy
toward Western issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt that Bush is far better for
agriculture and ranchers of the West,'' Gore said. ``The best that
(Al) Gore could do is change his name, dammit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney crystallizes many of the strongest feelings in both
political parties, which is odd to Mike Strang, a Carbondale
rancher who served with him in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney had ``the best intellect of anybody in Congress with the
possible exception of Bill Archer,'' a Texas Republican. ``He's a
very thoughtful man and not an extreme person. He's not the
arch-Druid the press likes to make him out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Coler Wyoming congressman, Cheney can
provide that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the access,'' McInnis said. ``Even if I can get the most
strident Easterners, if I can just get an audience with them, we
always gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, though, isn't a proven vote-getter anywhere but Wyoming,
and ``in some ways, the Democrats have to be completely relieved''
by Bush's choice, said Michael Gizzi of the political science
faculty at Mesa State College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a bad thing for the West to have a Western
candidate,'' but in Cheney, it has something else, Gizzi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cheney has become so enmeshed in politics that that
image just doesn't come into play. It would be a lot different if
he picked a Western governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney gives the Republican ticket something no one expects from
Wyoming, which reflects his most recent assignment in Washington,
D.C., as defense secretary, Gizzi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the foreign policy experience that a George W. Bush
would need,'' Gizzi said. ``The real question is how tied in is he
to the West after 25 years of national politics?''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
