<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-29 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TWO STATUES BUT MYRIAD LESSONS TO ABSORB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)   By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is about statues, the one of Harold Connolly planned for
his old neighborhood in Boston and the one of Jackie Robinson and
Pee Wee Reese that doesn't seem to be growing in Brooklyn. I'm sure
there are universal historical, social and political issues in all
this, and if you find them, send them along. Why has
thelipsite(at)aol.com been overloaded lately with more paeans to
Mark Messier than to Linda Bensel-Meyers, the Tennessee
whistle-blower? Beats me.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to erect a statue of Jackie and Pee Wee was officially
announced last year by the administration of New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani after a campaign begun years ago by Stan Isaacs, then a
Newsday sports columnist. The financier and philanthropist Ted
Forstmann pledged the funding. A sculptor and a Brooklyn site have
yet to be named, in part because the city seems to have thought
that a press release was enough, in part because of a philosophic
disagreement over how the relationship of Jackie and Pee Wee should
be cast in stone.
</P>
<P>
   With two appealing young athletes usually described as ``black''
now standing astride America's signature white sports of golf and
tennis, it requires some effort to return to 1947, when Robinson
became the first recognized African-American to play major league
baseball. Robinson's debut was orchestrated by white men, most
importantly Branch Rickey, the Dodger general manager. While mostly
white business people will decide just how much Tiger Woods and
Venus Williams will earn from their talent, ambition and charisma,
the decision to place them in fame's way was not a white decision;
strong nuclear families, in particular visionary, risk-taking
fathers, set them on their paths and ran interference right to the
top.
</P>
<P>
   To properly appreciate this real progress, how much history do
we need to hang onto? One turning point in the Robinson epic,
nicely retold in Peter Golenbock's illustrated children's book,
``Teammates'' (Harcourt Brace, 1990), occurred early that first
season, in Cincinnati, not far from Pee Wee's Louisville home. As
Reds fans spewed hate onto the field, Pee Wee strolled over from
shortstop and put his arm on Jackie's shoulders. The white Dodger
captain was wordlessly saying, ``This black man is my teammate.''
The mostly white campaigners for the statue would like to
memorialize that gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Robinson, Jackie's widow and the force behind the
educational foundation named for him, said last week that although
she appreciated the gesture, she would prefer a statue in which the
two players were depicted as ``equals.'' She remembered a
photograph in which they are leaving the field, shoulder to
shoulder, their hands almost touching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be more of a tribute to both of them,'' she said.
``There have been too many instances of a white person elevated at
the expense of a black person.''
</P>
<P>
   The statue of Harold Connolly, who won the 1956 Olympic gold
medal in the hammer throw, is to be erected on the grounds of
Brighton High School, where he played football despite a twisted,
foreshortened left arm crippled by a birth accident. So much of
Connolly's early life seemed to have been spent hiding the arm and
compensating for it.
</P>
<P>
   A former high school teacher who recently retired from a second
career as a Special Olympics executive, Connolly, who turns 69 on
Tuesday, has been writing his memoirs, mostly for his children. The
pages I've read about his left arm have been particularly candid
and moving. He writes: ``Concentrating on the Herculean effort of
raising my left arm up and sideways, I slowly placed my right hand
above her left hip and groped for her finger-tips with my
half-closed left hand. She, however, had to be the one who finally
took my limp hand into hers; and I became very much aware that she
knew and either felt repulsed or sorry for me.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was just dancing class. Connolly identifies himself as
``a handicapped person'' who ``knows the agony of all-out trying
and not accomplishing.'' After years of physical therapy as a
child, he writes: ``I began to consider myself a reject, chained to
a small army of twisted bodies in the hospital waiting room and
responded by trying to ignore my crippled associates. I wanted to
push myself into the `normal' society.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly paid his own way through college and to Europe to
compete, perfecting an explosive, spinning style that compensated
for his weak arm with speed and leg power. Defensive and shy, he
made himself into a fierce, sometimes ruthless competitor and
Boston's second gold-medal Connolly. A statue of James B. Connolly,
America's first Olympic champion, stands in South Boston, a rival
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Of his own statue, Harold Connolly says, ``I certainly hope my
left arm will be rendered realistically by the sculptor, as it
appears to others, not as it appears in my mind's eye, filtered to
look as much as possible to be the arm I wish it were.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
