<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FEAR-FACTS-ART-NYT &LR;      07-29 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEAR-FACTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCARED? TRY TO BE RATIONAL FOR ONCE IN YOUR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT7 and 8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By KIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people don't sit down with statistical charts and decide on
the basis of the evidence what specter of death or calamity should
most fill them with dread. If they did, they would be pacing the
floor at night over cardiovascular disease. Clogged arteries and
bad hearts carry off nearly a million Americans a year, about as
many as all other diseases and disasters combined.
</P>
<P>
   But no. On some deep level, social researchers and psychologists
say, we choose as a society and as individuals from among an
endless menu of things that go bump in the night, what to fret over
and what to shrug off.
</P>
<P>
   Only neurotics tackle every item on the list, and only Alfred E.
Neuman of Mad magazine blithely ignores them all. But the things
that push the human panic button also have distinct patterns, the
experts say. The specters that haunted last week's news _ the crash
of the Concorde in France, the discovery of West Nile-infected
mosquitoes in New York's Central Park, the failed hijacking at
Kennedy International Airport _ were similar in one respect: They
were loaded with the mysterious freight of fright that can seize
us, whether it makes scientific sense or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``People climb mountains and expose themselves voluntarily to
all kinds of risks, but they don't like risk inflicted upon them
that they don't understand or have control over, like West Nile,''
said Dr. Roger E. Kasperson, director of a risk-study center at
Clark University in Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden catastrophes like the Concorde crash tend to set human
nerves jangling even more. ``If you kill people one by one, people
tend to be very tolerant, but if you kill people in large numbers
in a single event, we don't like it,'' Kasperson said. ``Those
events are very scary and they get our attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Our formulations of fear are also framed and focused, risk
analysts say, by the peculiarities of culture. The great
mythological symbol of America _ the lone-wolf individual, out
there challenging the world and all comers _ makes us devalue some
kinds of risks and elevate others. In surveys, most Americans say
they feel fairly safe in their cars, for example, because they feel
in control behind the wheel. They feel much less safe in planes,
because someone else is at the controls and passengers can't do
much about altering their odds. The fear persists even though
planes crash far less often than cars.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a contradictory mix of impulses that may be at
play, particularly in how people react to the West Nile virus and
the efforts to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because Americans have not had to suffer the worst
effects of the world's most devastating wars, plagues and famines
of the last 100 years, they have a deep sense of optimism, and a
belief in the perfectibility of the world that risk experts say
plays heavily into the theater of fear. They tend to despise
fatalistic acceptance and believe that all problems probably have
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   If there are bad mosquitoes, that line of risk-management goes,
then let's wipe them out. But at the same time there's also a deep
strain of distrust toward experts and politicians who might purport
to know all the facts about fighting mosquitoes or the relative
safety of the pesticides used in the battle. The various
``right-to-know'' laws that have been passed in recent years,
covering everything from food ingredients to the known addresses of
sex offenders, all center on the idea that individuals are best
equipped to assess their own risk tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a paradox of our society,'' said Dr. Donald G. MacGregor,
a senior research associate at Decision Research, a private,
nonprofit research institute in Eugene, Ore., that studies public
perception of environmental health and safety. ``Our historical
perspective is that of the frontiersperson, but at the same time we
want structures to protect us so that while we're out there
practicing our frontier individualism we don't get hurt. We want
all the upside and we want to factor out the downside; we want 15
percent annualized return on our portfolios in the stock market,
but not take on any risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, the result is a three-corner misunderstanding that can
leave scientists, policy makers and ordinary people taking
completely different views of the same thing. Many Americans, for
example, routinely disregard the medical community's constant
refrain about the dangers of unprotected sex. On the other hand,
many people remain deeply anxious about nuclear energy, even though
from a strictly technical analysis, scientists say, it is probably
one of the safest, cleanest ways to generate electricity ever
devised.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers say that while they must occasionally fight the
impulse to write off ordinary people as fools, they also sometimes
find that the lay individual's assessment of risk, while perhaps
not strictly rational, has something that mere numbers cannot
catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often the public is onto something,'' said Dr. Elizabeth L.
Anderson, the former director of risk assessment for the federal
Environmental Protection Agency, now an environmental science
consultant in Washington. ``But you can't get lost in the public
perception and lose what the science informs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What seems risky is also often no accident or happenstance of
evolutionary psychology. Risk has its hangers-on, a kind of
infrastructure of anxiety, that includes various special-interest
groups trying to shape the public sense of risk to suit their own
agendas, as well as media organizations and politicians that
sustain themselves with anxiety's bracing energies.
</P>
<P>
   The public debate over smoking is considered, in risk-management
circles, a premier case in point. For years, the American Cancer
Society's preachy message that people should stop smoking for the
sake of their health mostly didn't work. It was rejected because it
ran up against the American credo of personal control: that an
individual's decision to smoke was an act of free will and no one
else's business. Only when the risks were reframed, centering
instead on the dangers of passive, second-hand smoke that resulted
from someone else's actions, did clean-air and indoor smoking laws
become common.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe these changes happen by themselves,'' said Dr.
M.V. Rajeev Gowda, a professor of public policy at the University
of Oklahoma who studies how people and societies make decisions
about risk. ``Everything involved here has a political
interest-group dimension to it, and part of their effort is to
capture the framing.''
</P>
<P>
   And some players just want a piece of the action. Howard
Rubenstein Associates, for example, the big New York public
relations firm better known for representing high-gloss
celebrities, began calling reporters last week with a whispered tip
about a new turn in the virus story: a mosquito, infected with West
Nile, that apparently feeds during the day, had just been
discovered by researchers at Fordham University. The researchers
themselves were a bit more circumspect; they are not sure yet how
common their new mosquito, Aedes japonicus, is, how well it
transmits the virus, or whether it even bites people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
