<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO BASKETBALL NOTEBOOK: HORNETS' JONES EXPECTED TO JOIN THE HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He almost had Juwan Howard four years ago, but the league voided
the deal and sent Howard back to Washington. At different
junctures, Pat Riley was also on the verge of bringing Mitch
Richmond and Latrell Sprewell to Miami, only to see his grand
pursuit of talent end in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time in the last four years, Riley, the Heat
president and coach, finally seems to be homing in on adding an
All-Star caliber player to his athletically challenged roster.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jones will very likely be headed to South Florida in the
next few days, an Eastern Conference team official said Friday
afternoon on the condition of anonymity. Jones is hoping to leave
Charlotte in a sign-and-trade deal that would bring Jamal Mashburn
and Clarence Weatherspoon to the Hornets in exchange for the
All-Star shooting guard and Charlotte's Ricky Davis, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors could hold up the deal, including a deadline of
Friday night imposed by Jones on the club last week to work out an
arrangement with the Heat. But Jones only appeared to be killing
his own leverage with the ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than reap the maximum allowable contract the Heat can
offer him _ roughly $86 million over seven years _ Jones would have
two options: Take another team's $2.25 million exception with the
unwritten promise that he would be compensated after next season,
or sign for the maximum with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The other potential holdup may be David Falk, Jones' agent.
According to the official, Falk is scheming up a pitch for the
Bulls, who have $19 million in salary-cap space but little talent
after most of the league's top-tier free agents spurned them the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   If Falk's plan comes to fruition, the official said, the Bulls
would acquire Jones and Glen Rice to fill their vacancies at small
forward and shooting guard and keep United Center ticket revenues
from spiraling into the abyss.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets need to clear more cap room to complete the
transaction with the Heat. They need a third team with a salary-cap
exception to take a player such as Brad Miller in order to make
sure Jones gets the maximum deal.
</P>
<P>
   Riley was vehement about not losing two starters in a deal for
Jones, which helps explain why he refused to part with both
Mashburn and P.J. Brown. But he is getting antsy for a player who
can help elevate his team past the Knicks and the Indiana Pacers in
the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Before the second-round series against the Knicks last May, he
was asked if the well-traveled rookie Anthony Carter fit into the
Riley mold of role players he has coached in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love these kind of guys with big hearts,'' Riley said. ``But
I'd also like to get some big talent one of these days, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic a Big Winner
</P>
<P>
   With free agents able to sign Tuesday, Orlando appears to be the
big winner in the summer sweepstakes. Procuring Grant Hill and
Tracy McGrady _ and possibly Maurice Taylor _ should make the Magic
a bona fide playoff threat again.
</P>
<P>
   But its chances of competing immediately for a championship were
severely dimmed when Tim Duncan chose to stay in San Antonio, where
the All-Star center is expected to sign a three-year deal with a
fourth-year option totaling more than $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the Magic acquired one of the top-five players
in the game along with one of the most breathtaking young players.
If Taylor agrees to a deal in the next few days _ he is still
hedging and may wind up in Indiana, which has a $4.3 million
exception to offer him _ coach Doc Rivers has another great
offensive player to put on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   NBC even went so far as to include 10 regular-season Magic games
on their 2000-01 network schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Peel back the facade, though: John Amaechi, still learning the
game, is Orlando's center. Hill is coming off major foot surgery.
Neither he nor McGrady has yet to win a playoff series. For all his
ability, Taylor is coming over from the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic has some nice pieces and will be tremendously
entertaining. But after the oodles of cash were doled out, the
Magic still has some gaping holes, the kind only Duncan could have
fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, general manager John Gabriel did his best to secure the
pick of the litter over the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   If Eddie Jones ends up in Miami, the Chicago Bulls have to go
down as the major disappointment of the summer. Ron Mercer, Derek
Anderson or _ who knows? _Isaiah Rider may be their big
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a particularly rough off-season for general manager
Jerry Krause, whose promise to rebuild the franchise may have to
wait yet another season. After enduring two years of the draft
lottery, you wonder if Bulls fans can deal with another dismal
season after six championships in the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   One of the top free agents next season is Chris Webber, a power
forward. In Elton Brand and the recently drafted Marcus Fizer, the
Bulls have a surplus at the position.
</P>
<P>
   After Hill and McGrady committed themselves to Orlando, the
Bulls seemed to have their heart set on Milwaukee forward Tim
Thomas. But he deftly used Chicago for leverage, securing a maximum
contract from the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   There is a still chance that Jermaine O'Neal will be dealt to
Chicago for a combination of players that may include the rookie
point guard Jamal Crawford. But that remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   If Krause does not shock everyone with a blockbuster deal over
the next two months _ given his cunning and savvy in the past, it's
not an impossibility _ the post-Michael-and-Scottie Bulls are
headed in the same direction as the powerhouse Celtics of the
1980s. Boston is still searching for a playoff berth years after
Larry Bird, Kevin McHale and Robert Parish retired.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Knicks Seem Dormant  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks spent time and money courting Grant Hill and Brian
Grant the past month, time and money that apparently went to waste
and made some of their current players question the franchise's
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Patrick Ewing, the player whom Dave Checketts has
often said ``will retire a Knick,'' wants more years and more
money.
</P>
<P>
   The window on the Knicks' championship hopes is always said to
be perpetually closing, one bad bounce away from the draft lottery.
And just as they slip below the tier of elite teams, the Knicks
find a way to end up deep in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Knicks cannot pull off a deal for a legitimate
rebounder in the next few months, they have no shot at returning to
the finals. At a time when Miami and Orlando are upgrading and
Indiana is mostly holding onto the team that came within three
victories of a title, the Knicks are running out of capable big
men.
</P>
<P>
   Reiterating comments he made in March about playing three more
seasons, Ewing said last week that he planned to play one more
season in New York and then somewhere else if the Knicks did not
extend his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks remember how well Ewing played the last time he
wanted an exorbitant contract. In the 1996-97 season _ his last
injury-free, productive season _ he was in All-Star form. But now
he almost seems out of touch with his own talent. Unlike many aging
former All-Stars, he has no comprehension of his declining skill
and agility.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Knicks pay Ewing for two more seasons given that he
has spent much of the past three years on the injured list? It is
unlikely. Meanwhile, their backup center, Chris Dudley, will very
likely have his contract bought out at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Knicks with a glut of power forwards and
shooting guards. Without capable big men, Allan Houston and Latrell
Sprewell are basically Grant Hill and Jerry Stackhouse and the
Knicks are a lower-echelon playoff team that goes home in early
May.
</P>
<P>
   Unless general manager Scott Layden can creatively find a way to
land an impact post player, the good times at Madison Square Garden
will soon come to an end. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
