<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6975 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-OLY-TV-HYPE-NYT &LR;      07-29 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-OLY-TV-HYPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK AND FIELD'S TRIALS AND TRIBULATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Marc Bloom covered the Olympic Trials for Runner's World
Online.) 
 By MARC BLOOM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene pulled up lame in last
Sunday's Olympic trials 200-meter fiasco in Sacramento, Calif.,
Johnson blamed the news media for overblowing the showdown and
creating a weird chemistry that polluted the event. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when the United States had great milers like Steve
Scott and Sydney Maree going up against foreign stars like Eamonn
Coghlan and John Walker, the mile was usually set up as the final,
climactic event of a televised track meet. Meet promoters, track
officials and TV executives felt the mile was the event to sell.
The mile had glamour, charismatic personalities and the historical
weight of the four-minute barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, television always promised records. Instead of
focusing on the subtleties of competition and the significance of
victory _ the essence of track _ telecasters blabbered for an hour
about some record attempt. Invariably, there was a great letdown as
the records rarely came. No matter who won, the public was left
with the impression that the athletes failed. When track ultimately
fell off the national radar screen, track fans suggested that the
sport had lost its way and needed to refocus on competition, not
records.
</P>
<P>
   For this Olympic year, the competition has been keener than
ever: Marion Jones vs. Inger Miller in the 200; Regina Jacobs vs.
Suzy Favor Hamilton in the 1,500; Adam Goucher and Bob Kennedy in
the 5,000. Track and field had buzz again. The women's pole vault,
led by the world record-holder, Stacy Dragila and, of course, the
incomparable showing of Jones, seeking five gold medals in Sydney,
Australia, sparked weekly excitement.
</P>
<P>
   The event with the greatest legs appeared to be the men's 200.
Unfortunately, the news media drummed up the Johnson-Greene rivalry
to the point where it harmed the sport _ and in a sour finish to a
breathtaking Olympic trials, viewers were the losers. As The
Sacramento Bee mocked it, the simultaneous injury was the ``hammy
double whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, there was no rivalry. Johnson has dominated the 200,
as well as the 400, for a decade, and you could make a case for him
as the greatest athlete in the history of track and field. Greene
is primarily a 100 man and is the world record-holder. When Johnson
withdrew from last year's national 200 against Greene, Johnson
rightly took some heat for claiming injury at the 11th hour.
</P>
<P>
   After that, NBC viewed a Johnson-Greene rematch as the event to
sell for the Olympic trials. NBC set the schedule, slotting the 200
final as the closing event of the meet _ 5:48 p.m., Pacific time _
for its live, prime-time broadcast. Meet officials, seeking marquee
value, went along. In Sydney, the last individual track event is
the men's 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Television not only set the schedule but also the agenda. In
Sacramento, Johnson versus Greene would be big _ huge _ and
reporters pounced on the story in a frenzy worthy of scandal. At a
pretrials news conference, Johnson and Greene were trotted out
together and questions focused on the athletes' supposed enmity,
instigating the trash-talk that followed. Inger Miller sat between
the two men like a referee at ``Wrestlemania.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Johnson and Greene were not innocent victims. They
could have merely said nothing. But the news media drove hard, and
the athletes' pride prevented discretion. Reporters would tell
Michael that Maurice said this; in turn, they would tell Maurice
that Michael said that. It made great theater.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists spent the week looking for anyone to interview on
the 200. They found the pliant Ato Bolden from Trinidad and Tobago,
Greene's training partner, always one with a provocative line. They
searched out the 1968 Olympic sprinter John Carlos, no stranger to
controversy, for his thoughts. Trash-talk escalated from window
dressing to a story unto itself. Johnson said everyone had
something to gain but him. Right again.
</P>
<P>
   The men's 200 was reminiscent of the 1984 women's Olympic 3,000
in Los Angeles, another made-for-television creation that trumpeted
a duel between the American star Mary Slaney and the barefoot
teen-ager Zola Budd, a South African with dual citizenship who ran
for Britain. Slaney was the far superior runner and a gold-medal
threat. Budd was a promising youngster with little international
experience. You know what happened: Slaney and Budd collided as
victory went to Slaney's true opponent, Maricica Puica of Romania.
</P>
<P>
   After the men's 200 preliminary round on July 22, reporters
swarmed around Johnson, and I couldn't get close. I noticed another
sprinter, Floyd Heard, standing by himself and went over to him.
Heard, at 34 the oldest man in the event, had just run his fastest
time in 11 years. In 1986, he had been ranked No. 1 in the world.
After almost quitting track last year with an injury, Heard was
giving it one last shot at the trials. He had a close friend
advising him, a guy named Carl Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Heard looked as if he could make the Olympic team, but no one
seemed to care. When, in the 200 final, the overwhelming tension
and 118-degree temperature played havoc with the two marquee
protagonists' overworked leg muscles, Heard ran a close second to
earn a ticket to Sydney. His performance was a lifetime best 19.88
seconds, a time faster than Greene had run to win the 1999 world
title in Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's good that the ballyhooed 200 blew up in everyone's
face. Now there won't be another circus in Sydney. Johnson can run
the 400, Greene the 100, and fans can root for a rejuvenated
34-year-old unknown in the 200.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
