<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOME-WARRANTY-REAL-NY     07-29 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-WARRANTY-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KEY FOR NEW-HOME PROTECTION? LOCATION, LOCATION, LOCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Conn.)   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtually every new car comes with a warranty that protects the
buyer against major mechanical problems for a specific period of
time or for the maximum amount of mileage.
</P>
<P>
   So, then, what kind of warranty do you get when you buy a new
house?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, it seems, depends on where the house is.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, state law requires that all new single-family
houses and condominiums come with a 10-year warranty.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the law creates an ``implied warranty'' that
protects buyers of new homes for up to six years. But unlike New
Jersey, New York allows builders to modify the warranty with the
buyer's consent.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, where state law provides buyers with a basic
one-year warranty, experts say that its scope depends almost
entirely on what the buyer's lawyer manages to get into the sales
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Desch, the chief of the Bureau of Homeowner Protection in
New Jersey's Department of Community Affairs in Trenton, said that
under state law, before builders can obtain certificates of
occupancy, they must present receipts for fully paid 10-year
new-home warranties, the terms of which are set by statute. They
can buy the warranties directly from the state's New Home Warranty
Program or from a state-approved private warranty company that
offers the same coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the first year, it covers a host of things that could
be wrong with new construction,'' Desch said. They range from floor
squeaks and roof leaks to cracks in the foundation and structural
defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coverage decreases over time,'' he said. In the second
year, the warranty covers only structural defects and flaws in the
electrical, plumbing, heating, ventilation and air-conditioning
systems. From the third through 10th years, the warranty covers
only major structural defects _ in other words, serious structural
problems caused by actual physical damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as this program is, one of the things that people miss
is that this is only a limited warranty,'' Desch said, explaining
that there are some things that are not covered. Among them are
sidewalks, driveways, pools and outbuildings like sheds and
detached garages.
</P>
<P>
   When a homeowner files a claim during the first two years of the
warranty, Desch said, the Bureau of Homeowner Protection sends out
an arbitrator to meet with the homeowner and the builder to
determine whether the claim is valid. If it is _ and the decision
of the arbitrator is binding either way _ the state will order the
builder to make the necessary repairs. If the builder refuses to do
so, Desch said, the department can bar the builder from
constructing new homes in the state.
</P>
<P>
   For claims filed in the third through 10th years of the
warranty, he said, the builder is no longer obligated to perform
the repairs. Instead, the state sends out a claims adjuster to
determine if the claim is valid. If it is, the adjuster will
authorize the owner to hire someone to make the necessary repairs.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, Desch said, and in cases where the builder is out
of business, bankrupt or refuses to cooperate, the money for the
work comes out of the state's New Home Warranty Trust Fund, which
is replenished by the fees builders pay the state for the
warranties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 20 years we've paid out about $35 million in
claims,'' Desch said.
</P>
<P>
   New York's statutory warranty on new homes works somewhat
differently.
</P>
<P>
   New York has a six-year implied warranty on any new home under
Section 777 of the state's General Business Law, said Douglas F.
Wasser, a Manhattan real estate lawyer. , It requires that the
house be free of all defects for a year after the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is defined by the law as meaning that workmanship and
materials meet or exceed the standards of the applicable building
code,'' Wasser said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second year, he said, the warranty covers only mechanical
systems _ including plumbing, electrical, heating, cooling and
ventilating _ and ``material defects,'' defined as actual physical
damage to load-bearing parts of the house that make it unsafe,
unsanitary or otherwise unlivable.
</P>
<P>
   In the third through sixth years of the warranty, Wasser said,
only material defects are covered.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the time periods covered, there are other significant
differences between New Jersey's New Home Warranty Program and New
York's implied warranty.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while New Jersey's program provides both a system
for handling claims and money to pay them, New York's implied
warranty provides neither. And while every new home in New Jersey
comes with the same basic warranty, builders in New York are free
to negotiate with buyers to modify or even eliminate the protection
of the implied warranty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weakest link in the New York law is the builder's ability
to disclaim the warranty,'' said Michael Liss, a White Plains real
estate lawyer, referring to the fact that if the buyer agreed in
the sales contract, builders could substitute their own warranties
in place of the statutory one. In fact, he said, some builders
insist upon a cap on the amount they will be liable for.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where lawyers really start to worry,'' Liss said. ``If
the builder puts a $100,000 cap on the warranty, and you've got a
house with real problems, then you're out of luck for any repairs
above the $100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what the warranty or its terms, the only way for
an owner to force a recalcitrant builder to make repairs is to take
the builder to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most buyers' lawyers wince at handling new construction,''
Liss said. ``The contracts get too complicated, and there are
usually too many postconstruction claims to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in Connecticut face similar challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Connecticut, the only warranty you get by law is that
everything is going to work for one year from the date of
closing,'' said William Selsberg, a Stamford real estate lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The state's implied-warranty law, Selsberg said, provides that
new homes will be free of faulty materials, designed according to
sound engineering standards and constructed in a workmanlike manner
that results in a house that is fit for habitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warranty does not apply to any conditions that an
inspection by a reasonably diligent purchaser would reveal,''
Selsberg said. Such vague provisions leave real estate lawyers no
choice but to try to craft their own warranties by inserting them
into the sales contract and getting the builder to agree to them,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of guesswork on the part of the buyer's lawyer
to try to cover every possible contingency,'' Selsberg said. ``And
when all is said and done, agreements and warranties are only as
good as the people who make them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
