<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) BUSH
VEEP CHOICE COULD CREATE SOUTHERN CHANCE FOR GORE  
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush's
choice of Richard Cheney as his running mate demonstrates his
confidence that the South is safe GOP presidential territory. But
it leaves an opening for Vice President Al Gore to broaden his
appeal in the region.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By passing up such rising sons of the South as GOP Sens. Bill
Frist and Fred Thompson of Tennessee, the Texas governor signaled
his belief that he doesn't need any extra help in rounding up the
lion's share of the South's electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   He has plenty of assistance already. Younger brother Jeb, the
governor of Florida, is firmly in control of the state's GOP
apparatus and is a popular chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi Sen. Trent Lott, a former cheerleader, is a chief
Bush rooter and carries plenty of weight in his home state and
elsewhere across Dixie. Plus, Cheney's rock-ribbed GOP ideology
will play well in Southeastern states that like their politicians
more conservative than the nation in general.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Western tilt of an all-Stetson ticket from Texas and
Wyoming presents an opportunity for Gore should he choose to take
advantage of it. Naming a Southern Democrat such as North Carolina
Gov. Jim Hunt, Florida Sen. Bob Graham or Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C.
_ all names that have figured in speculation _ could bring Gore
support that might have been lost had Bush tapped a native son.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a new dynamic at work as well. Former Georgia Gov.
Zell Miller, chosen to succeed the late Paul Coverdell in the
Senate, will now be on the November ballot in that state, which was
not scheduled to have a high-profile contest.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is an extraordinarily popular Democrat who figures to
boost voter turnout and improve overall Democratic prospects in a
state President Clinton carried in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That could be good news for backers of Graham as a veep
prospect. Consider this: Analysts say neighboring Georgia is the
one state outside Florida where Graham could have an appreciable
impact on his own. Added together, Florida's 25 electoral votes and
Georgia's 13 trump the 32 held by Texas and could prove decisive in
an election.
</P>
<P>
   MANDELA MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   Cheney isn't the only one who might be asked to explain his now
controversial vote against a 1986 House resolution calling for the
release of Nelson Mandela from a South African jail and urging
recognition of the African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every Southern Republican serving at the time and
several Democrats took the same position on the resolution, which
received majority support but failed because it required a
two-thirds margin for passage. Thirty-two Democrats, many from the
South, sided with them, including the entire Georgia delegation and
a handful of Floridians.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Republicans _ led by rising star Newt Gingrich of
Georgia _ raised concerns that the ANC had communist leanings.
Since then, Mandela has been recognized as a worldwide hero and
many lawmakers no doubt wish they had that vote to cast again.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE MANIPULATION
</P>
<P>
   As Southern hospital executives howl about shrinking Medicare
payments, lawmakers are moving to correct a health care financing
formula that has bedeviled rural America.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? Reimbursement rates to hospitals and managed care
programs under Medicare were set according to historical spending
in a county. Hence, rates started out higher in urban areas where
big-dollar, high-tech medical centers were concentrated and skewed
lower in small communities where medicine is practiced more
conservatively.
</P>
<P>
   `'If you were efficient and getting the service at a low cost,
you got stuck with a low reimbursement rate,'' complained Sen. Pete
Domenici, R-N.M., chairman of the Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   To correct the situation, he and other lawmakers are proposing a
measure that would better equalize payments and they hope to get it
passed yet this year.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHECK ISN'T IN THE MAIL
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Spencer Bachus is using his congressional Web site to help
the Internal Revenue Service track down his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   But it is good news. The Alabama Republican has posted a list of
322 district residents due IRS refunds the agency has been unable
to deliver because of illegible addresses and other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no Regis Philbin, but i want to help unite my constituents
with the money the IRS owes them,'' said Bacchus, whose homepage at
www.house.gov/bachus also provides a link to the IRS refund request
form.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
