<HEADLINE>
ETHICS QUESTION ON PICKENS; SCOUTS CAN SEE THE REDSKINS; AROUND THE
LEAGUE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also FBN-FALCONS-REEVES) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bizarre trip of wide receiver Carl Pickens ended last week
when he signed a multiyear, incentive-laden contract with the
Tennessee Titans. Both Pickens and his old team, the Cincinnati
Bengals, were happy he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Late during the negotiations, Pickens dumped his second agent
and was being advised by a third, Marvin Demoff, who is also the
agent for Titans coach Jeff Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that were interested in Pickens last week questioned the
ethics of that situation. But there have been a number of instances
when an agent represented both a player and the head coach on the
same team.
</P>
<P>
   The team officials complaining about the arrangement are simply
upset that they lost out on acquiring the wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts Can See the Redskins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Redskins' decision to charge $10 for admission to
training-camp practices has scouts from competing teams taking
advantage of a little-known league rule. It states that if a team
charges admission to practices, then scouts from competing teams,
normally prohibited from attending, can go.
</P>
<P>
   So scouts from about a dozen teams have paid their 10 bucks and
watched the Redskins go through their summer drills, several said
last week. Teams do not gain a huge tactical advantage by doing
this because teams rarely work on secrets in such a public setting.
But it does give scouts the chance to get an early start on looking
at the Redskins' personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Around the League &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers' potential defensive line: Eric Swann and Sean
Gilbert at tackle and Reggie White and Chuck Smith at defensive
end. That could be, if their conditioning holds out, a formidable
foursome. ... Eric Moulds, the excellent Buffalo wide receiver, is
having his best camp ever, a scary thought for the rest of the
division. ... The Redskins will use cornerback Deion Sanders and
Champ Bailey together in a few of there special-teams situations.
... Look for Oakland cornerback Charles Woodson to be involved in
the offense this season. ... New England coach Bill Belichick on
wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, who was traded from the Jets to
Tampa Bay: ``I have a lot of regard for him. I'm glad he is out of
our division. When we first met, he straightened out some
misconceptions I had about him, and I straightened out some
misconceptions he had about me. We had a good working
relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
