<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-REEVES-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEVES' POOR TALENT PICKS FOR FALCONS RAISE CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-NOTEBOOK) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 1995 and New York Giants coach Dan Reeves informed the
front office he wanted to bring the free-agent quarterback Tommy
Maddox to New York. When several team scouts heard the news, they
rolled their eyes. They had viewed Maddox on film and thought he
possessed a weak arm, played nervous and had bad aim. Other than
that, he was fine.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves insisted. As coach and general manager of the Denver
Broncos, he had drafted Maddox with a No. 1 pick, and even though
Maddox was a disaster there, Reeves still wanted to give the player
another chance. Maddox got it. On Oct. 15 of that year, against
Philadelphia, Maddox went six of 23 for 49 yards and three
interceptions. His passer rating for the game was zero.
</P>
<P>
   Experiment over. Maddox was gone soon after that horrid
afternoon and is now out of the league, but Reeves' stubbornness
about Maddox started a rift between the coaching staff and the
front office.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was fired as the Giants' coach, with the main issue being
control over personnel decisions like picking the players in the
draft. Now, as head coach and general manager of the Falcons,
Reeves has taken the once joke of a franchise to new heights, a
Super Bowl berth. His coaching ability was the main reason the
Falcons upset the Minnesota Vikings in the NFC title game two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves has also continued to demonstrate that he is one of
the worst talent evaluators in football. Except now there are no
checks and balances as there were with the Giants. He makes the
picks and there is no one in the Falcons organization willing to
challenge him. Thus, considering the questionable nature of Reeves'
recent selections, it is not an overstatement to say that the
franchise could soon take several large steps back.
</P>
<P>
   That is already beginning to happen. Atlanta is only two years
removed from the Super Bowl, and St. Louis has passed the Falcons
in the division, as most likely has Carolina. Both teams added
depth and speed with smart drafts.
</P>
<P>
   What some coaches do not seem to understand is that coaching and
evaluating talent are two different animals. Personnel men and
scouts log tens of thousands of miles going to college games and
watch more film than a movie critic. There is no such thing as a
part-time scout, just as there is no such thing as a part-time
coach.
</P>
<P>
   The examples of good coach/bad talent scout are everywhere: Mike
Ditka, the former New Orleans Saints coach, traded his entire draft
for running back Ricky Williams, which may end up being one of the
biggest draft blunders of the last 15 years. That move helped get
Ditka fired, yet he had been a good enough coach to have led the
Chicago Bears to the Super Bowl XX championship in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1997, 1998 and 1999 drafts under Bill Parcells as general
manager of the Jets, he selected 22 players total, but only eight
have started with the team, according to the Elias Sports Bureau.
None of his draft picks has made the Pro Bowl. Parcells was
recently named coach of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   So, great coach plus mediocre talent evaluator does not always
add up to a great draft.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is one of only three coaches in league history to take
three different teams to the playoffs (Parcells and Chuck Knox are
the others). His coaching job with Atlanta the season of Super Bowl
XXXIII was among the best of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves has done a poor job of replenishing talent, to the
point where it is conceivable that a few years from now, when aging
stars like running back Jamal Anderson and quarterback Chris
Chandler move on, there will be mediocre talent, or less, waiting
to replace them.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 draft, Reeves' first for the Falcons, stands as a
symbol for his troubles in picking players. He traded down eight
spots in the first round to take Nebraska cornerback Michael
Booker, passing a better player at the position in Shawn Springs,
and also passing tight end Tony Gonzalez, now one of the league's
best.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Booker, after several years of struggling, bolted
training camp without an excuse (he hung out at a local waffle
house) and questioned whether he wanted to play football. Booker
has returned to camp, but his future is cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine players from that draft, three at one point or
another left the team. Quarterback Tony Graziani was also in that
class, and he has been a total bust.
</P>
<P>
   The recent picks of Reeves have not been much better. His
first-round pick in 1998 was Keith Brooking out of Georgia Tech, in
1999 it was Patrick Kerney out of Virginia. Also in that draft,
Reeves traded his 2000 No. 1 pick to Baltimore so he could draft
Mississippi State tight end Reggie Kelly, despite the fact few
teams had Kelly rated as a first-rounder and the Falcons had a
surplus of tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe those players will turn out to be Pro Bowlers, but so far,
none has shown much potential. In other words, the cupboard is
running bare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
