<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-GOALIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOALIE ON THE SPOT SEEKING SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. _ As he skated around the ice one day last week,
it was difficult to tell Rick DiPietro, the New York Islanders' No.
1 draft choice, from the youngsters he was teaching at a
goaltending clinic. Wearing a sweater with No. 1 and his name on
the back was all that seemed to distinguish DiPietro from the
campers, some of whom were only three years younger than the
18-year-old goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro, the first goalie to be selected as the top overall
pick in NHL history, signed a three-year contract on Tuesday. He
recalled how Tom Barrasso, at age 18, went directly from
Acton-Boxboro High School in Massachusetts to the Buffalo Sabres
and was named the rookie of the year in the 1983-84 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there is going to be a lot of pressure put on me,''
DiPietro said. ``We let go of two great goaltenders. You've got to
remember, I'm a young guy. I'm only 18 years old, so it's a long
shot for any 18-year-old to make an NHL squad right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders traded goaltenders Roberto Luongo and Kevin Weekes
on draft day to make room for DiPietro, who played only one season
at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working out pretty hard and trying to get myself
focused,'' DiPietro said. ``Hopefully, I can have a successful
camp, and wherever the New York Islanders feel best to put me,
that's where I'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarded as possessing puck-handling skills superior to most NHL
goaltenders, DiPietro finds it hard to believe that he could be a
starter in the NHL when this season begins. The Islanders, however,
did take out an insurance policy by acquiring John Vanbiesbrouck,
36, a day after the draft, providing DiPietro with a mentor and a
capable backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mention John Vanbiesbrouck in the same breath as you do
all the other great American goalies,'' DiPietro said. ``Sitting
next to him in the locker room, seeing what he has to say about his
experiences is a wonderful tool for me and something that hopefully
I'll be able to use to my benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They mentioned they were going to try to get an older,
experienced goaltender and I don't think they could have picked a
better guy. I don't think it's hit me yet. I think maybe in late
August when I step in that locker room for the first time and put
on the gear next to a guy like John Vanbiesbrouck, it's going to
actually hit me what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro said that he would not mind serving as the No. 2
goaltender behind Vanbiesbrouck, and he would also accept starting
the season in the minors if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   He believes, however, that he is ready to learn on the NHL
level. The Islanders, who had made Luongo the highest-drafted
goaltender only three years ago, are uncertain just what the plan
will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like him to play all the time,'' general manager Mike
Milbury said. ``That'd be my first preference, but we've got a guy
like Vanbiesbrouck here who's going to want minutes, too. I don't
want to ascribe some game plan that I don't have. Eventually, this
guy is going to be our goaltender if we're right, and I think we
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be our long-term No. 1 netminder. When is the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``With John, we don't have the urgency, the pressure, to get
this kid time here right away. Ask him and he wants to be the
starting goaltender on opening night. That's part of the appeal of
this kid, that he wants to be under the spotlight, wants to feel
the pressure. He likes it, which is a good way to be for a
goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders have put themselves under the microscope with a
drastic upheaval this summer, and Milbury is well aware that the
team's fate may lie in the unlikely hands of DiPietro, along with
other young players like 19-year-old Tim Connolly and 20-year-old
Mathieu Biron.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pressure I've felt over the last few years has all
gone away as of the draft,'' Milbury said. ``If it works and we
fine-tune things, good, then I've done a good job. If it doesn't
work, it's time to move on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
