<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-GARLAND-NYT &LR;      07-29 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GARLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILTON GARLAND, 104, ONE OF OLDEST WORKERS IN U.S.
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Mo., Nev., Ohio, Tenn., Va., Calif., Mass.)  By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milton W. Garland, who showed up for a 47-cents-an-hour job at a
refrigeration company in 1920 and stayed on until this May, died
Thursday at a nursing home in Waynesboro, Pa. He was 104.
</P>
<P>
   Garland, who earned 41 patents over eight decades in the field
of refrigeration, was honored in 1998 as the nation's oldest worker
by Green Thumb, a nonprofit group that helps older and
disadvantaged people get jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, a Green Thumb spokeswoman, Alice Ann Toole, said, he
was the oldest worker who could and would come to Washington for
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Stubbart, a copy editor and columnist for The Examiner, a
newspaper in Independence, Mo., was the first choice in 1998,
because she was two months older than Garland. Her health did not
permit her to travel then or the next year. Toole said that a
Florida real estate agent and perhaps others who were older than
Garland were thought to be still on the job, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by any measure, Garland, a tall, courtly mechanical
engineer, displayed great longevity. Until late May, when he had a
heart attack and moved to a nursing home from the house where he
had lived since 1926, he still worked 20 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   He had stayed on after his formal retirement in 1967 from the
Frick Co., a refrigeration equipment company that is now a unit of
York International. ``They hired him back the next day,'' his wife,
Alice, said.
</P>
<P>
   Using a magnifying glass, he evaluated 2,000 patents a week in
search of ways they might be applied to refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
   Also in his retirement years, he organized a training school for
Frick's refrigeration engineers and wrote an engineering design
manual. He called it ``Industrial Refrigeration 102,'' in honor of
his age when he published it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just report to work like anybody else,'' he said in an
appearance before the Senate Special Committee on Aging in 1998,
when he was honored by Green Thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Wooten, president of Green Thumb, suggested that he was
being modest. ``At 102, I cannot imagine being as sharp as he
was,'' Wooten said. ``He was so balanced and so together. We were
at the press conference and he was asked a question about how he
helped solve a rubber shortage during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he went into detail about the process. It was way over
my head, but he spoke in logical and methodical terms, almost like
he had written it out.''
</P>
<P>
   When Japan controlled Asian rubber plantations, Garland's
inventions helped make artificial rubber-making possible by
reducing temperatures during production.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Garland was officially named Mr. Refrigeration by the
American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning
Engineers, in honor of his work from the gold mines of South Africa
to the ice cream factories of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The group said his most recognizable invention was the first
``shell'' ice maker, which manufactured ice on the outside of tubes
that are 4 inches across and 10 feet long. The method was cleaner
and more efficient than the previous system of making ice in
galvanized cans. Its uses ranged from chicken-processing plants to
dairies to a two-mile-deep gold mine, where temperatures were
reduced from 110 degrees to a more comfortable 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Ward Garland was born Aug. 23, 1895, in Harrisburg, Pa.
His father worked for the Pennsylvania Railroad, and as a boy
Garland went to work delivering newspapers. He later worked in a
shop repairing Indian brand motorcycles. His specialty was the
wooden wheel rims.
</P>
<P>
   In 1915, he built a motorcycle from parts and drove it to
college at Worcester Polytechnic Institute in Worcester, Mass. He
paid for his schooling by managing two apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shoveled the snow, took out the garbage, fired the
furnaces,'' Garland told The Worcester Sunday Telegram in 1995,
when he received an honorary doctorate. ``Had to get up awful early
every morning, but I had good board and lodging and everything I
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   His schooling was interrupted by his service in the Navy during
World War I. After graduating from college, he went to work for
Frick in 1920, rising to superintendent of field installation work
after three years. He held that position until 1948. At his
retirement, he was vice president for technical services.
</P>
<P>
   His passion for refrigeration never abated. ``You see, it's a
heat exchange process, and different materials have different
conductivity,'' he said two years ago. ``There's always a chance of
improving the heat transfer rate.''
</P>
<P>
   His work took him to the Hoover Dam, for which he designed
systems to cool the water, sand and rock used to make the concrete
to build it. Pouring concrete in the fiercely hot temperatures of
southern Nevada would have otherwise been impossible.
</P>
<P>
   He made machinery that allowed the large-scale manufacture of
dry ice, making it possible to ship fresher food to troops overseas
during World War II. He also helped the war effort as a consultant
for Pratt &AMP; Whitney, builders of aircraft engines; the Army's
all-weather laboratory at Fort Belvoir, Va.; Goodyear Aircraft in
Akron, Ohio, and the Atomic Energy Commission in Oak Ridge, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Alice; a son, M. Ward, of Quartz
Hill, Calif.; a daughter, Jean L. Woloshyn of Big Bear City,
Calif.; six grandchildren; 13 great-grandchildren; and a
great-great-grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Garland took work seriously, always showing up at 8 a.m. in a
hat, starched white shirt and three-piece suit. His advice was
simple, old-fashioned and not particularly sugar-coated. ``Go into
something and then stay with it, and then like it,'' he told the
Senate panel. ``You won't like it unless you have expertise in that
line of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he did not have a playful side. He took up piloting his
own airplane at 60 and kept it up until he was 75. He drove his own
car and played golf until he was 99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live like you're going to live forever, not like you're going
to die tomorrow,'' he advised.
</P>
<P>
   When asked his secret for his own longevity, he sometimes noted
that he avoided sauerkraut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1524EDT &QL; 
