<HEADER>
A6986 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PARENTS0730-COX     07-29 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parenthood vs. productivity?
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having children saps your energy, your focus, your
life in general, or so traditional wisdom would have you believe.
</P>
<P>
   Many people think once the babies come, workers _ especially
working mothers _ begin to slip in their productivity, their
allegiance to their jobs and their commitment to career ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common stereotype that having children is a signal the
working parent will use any excuse to get out of work in order to
spend more time at home.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some managers believe that. Maybe some colleagues of
employed parents also share the prejudice. But parents disagree.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1999 national survey of 680 employed parents by
Lutheran Brotherhood, a nonprofit financial services organization
based in Minneapolis, 52 percent of those questioned said
parenthood has made them more productive at work and having
children does not detract from their job performance. Only 10
percent said parenthood made them less productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though some people think parents won't be as focused on
their jobs, I have found that they are more productive because they
want to make things work,'' said Gwen Kuhrt, human resources
manager at Lutheran Brotherhood. ``They're motivated to be good
team players.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed 56 percent of the fathers believe they now
get more done at work, compared with 48 percent of the women. The
reason: ``Women still have more household and child-rearing
responsibilities, though that is changing,'' said Kuhrt, who has a
master's degree in human resource management.
</P>
<P>
   Another finding: Parents of teenagers felt more productive than
those of preschoolers. ``That surprised me, too, but despite the
after-school activities teens have to get to and other demands,
they are more self-sufficient and can even help out with household
chores,'' Kuhrt said.
</P>
<P>
   Arlie Russell Hochschild, professor of sociology and co-director
of the Center for Working Families at the University of California
at Berkeley, says working parents, of necessity, ``become more
productive because they're more organized and distill their tasks
more efficiently. They're clear about their priorities, and that
shows in their decisions. They strive for balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hochschild, the author of ``The Time Bind: When Work Becomes
Home and Home Becomes Work'' (Metropolitan, $9.99) and mother of
two adult sons, says that she ``got better at prioritizing and less
distracted at work'' after she became a parent.
</P>
<P>
   As more mothers choose to stay home, when they choose to
continue working, they must also be choosing to maintain a level of
work ethic and responsibility, reasons Mary Jensen, who is a member
of Mothers &AMP; More, a national organization for women who have
altered their careers to care for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a working mother for two years,'' Jensen says. ``It
didn't affect my productivity. If anything, it probably made it
better. I had to budget my time more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think the people who are continuing to work must be
committed and must be productive because that's a choice that they
are making'' to continue on the job rather than opt out, she says.
``In my organization, those who are working are productive and
committed to that. Those who are not, they have admitted that'' and
no longer work outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely more efficient a worker now because there's
just so much more to do,'' says Pam Hainlin, who is president of
Mothers &AMP; More. ``In order to accomplish all that you'd like to do,
you have to do what you do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a big procrastinator. I used to be a deadline
worker, would thrive at working at 11 o'clock at night,'' she
recalls. ``If I had a presentation that next morning, I was not
stressed out staying up. I'd work the night before and stay up til
3 in the morning if need be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that she's a mom, Hainlin says she's changed her ways. She
had to. ``Children can't wait. You can't say, `Hang on honey, I'll
feed you in a couple hours.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Productivity, Hainlin says, is enhanced by these four factors:
</P>
<P>
   Prioritization. ``You absolutely have to prioritize how and when
you're going to use your time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Planning. ``To get done what you want to get done, you have to
plan ahead of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology. ``I use e-mail instead of the phone, I have a Palm
Pilot I carry around with me, and I never put it down. I have a
headset for my phone so when I am on the phone on a call, I can be
doing other things, hands free,'' Hainlin says.
</P>
<P>
   Flexibility. ``I recognize now, and I didn't before, the need
for flexibility. Not only flexibility on my part because I
understand I truly don't control things, but also for my need for
flexibility at home and on the job,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected happens. Flexibility is the key to keeping up. In
fact, as a volunteer, Hainlin's work is the result of her ability
to work in an accommodating environment. ``I work 20 hours a week
and couldn't do that without flexibility,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
