<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAVORX0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taste great and good for you
 &HT;    By Sofia Villalobos
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EATON, Ohio _ Sour apple, cinnamon, root beer or mint chocolate
_ choose a flavor. Parents can take a vacation from tantrums and
screeching cries since pharmacist-technician Kenneth Kramm invented
Flavorx _ 42 flavors to cover the bitter taste of some prescribed
and over-the-counter liquid medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most popular flavors are bubblegum, cherry and grape,''
said Edee Gosnell, a registered pharmacist and owner of Medicap
Pharmacy in Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   Used to cover even the most brutal antibiotic, the concoction
isn't quite as popular as it could be, but the solution is
beginning to grow. ``We have posters and advertisements telling
customers they can bring their medication and have it flavored for
$3,'' Gosnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Just like an ice cream shop, a large menu hangs from the ceiling
for customers to choose and even try their preferred gusto. The
concoction is easy to swallow, but doesn't taste like candy. ``It
makes the medicine more palatable, but not so good that a child
would want to drink the entire bottle,'' said Gosnell.
</P>
<P>
   According to his Web site, www.flavorx.com, Kramm and his father
began experimenting with the flavors because Kramm's daughter,
Hadley, who was diagnosed with cerebral palsy as an infant, would
gag and even vomit her medication. If she did not absorb the proper
amounts of medicine, Hadley would suffer seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington, D.C., resident says his daughter's condition has
stabilized since she has been able to consuming the proper
medication and keep it down.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Kroger pharmacies in the Miami Valley began
offering Flavorx, charging $3 a shot. ``But not all 42 flavors can
be mixed with just any medication,'' said Mike Davidson, a
registered pharmacist at Kroger. ``My 5-year-old daughter Shelby is
kind of picky and we've had to change the flavor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If a child doesn't care for the first taste chosen, parents can
have the medicine reflavored two or three times free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Flavorx does not alter the effectiveness of the drug taken. An
over-the-counter bottle of cough medicine works just as well after
the few flavorful drops are figured in. And there is no age
restriction _ adults can be choosy, too.
</P>
<P>
   If the children are fine, but you need help getting the cat to
swallow his hairball medicine, Flavorx Veterinary System is working
on a version for pets. Flavors like beef, tuna or liver have been
launched to help owners avoid kitty scratches and barks of disgust.
</P>
<P>
   And, Kramm notes on the Web site: ``Dogs like peanut butter and
birds like grape.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
