<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-ROLLINS0730-COX     07-29 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ROLLINS0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Harry' stirs publishing cauldron
 &HT;    By Ron Rollins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When is a bestseller not a best seller? Well, if
it's a children's book, it might be a different kind of best seller
than you thought.
</P>
<P>
   Next question: When is a children's book not quite a children's
book? Well, maybe when lots of adults are reading it, too.
</P>
<P>
   We're beating around the bush here to get to the same place
everybody seems to be getting these days _ which of course is to
Harry Potter Land, a magical place that's changing more than just
the reading habits of millions of children.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good thing, of course. With the possible exception of a
few oddballs who think J.K. Rowling's little literary wizard is the
work of (gasp!) Satan, nearly every parent, librarian, teacher and
book dealer you can find thinks it's terrific that the four Potter
books are attracting kids who would normally be locked onto video
screens till their eyes bleed.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you've been living under a rock, you know by now that
``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' has sold a gazillion copies
in its first few weeks, and kids by the score are downing the
752-pager in a single weekend, kerplunk.
</P>
<P>
   But publishing being a business, there are ripples caused by
that much money being spent on something. Publishers and
booksellers have been unhappy, for one thing, to see Harry Potter
taking up so darn much space on that most venerated of book-market
indicators, the New York Times best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the list changed. The Times Book Review created a
separate list for children's books (see today's ReadingRoom, page
8C). This moved Harry over and let folks like Danielle Steel, James
Patterson and John Grisham back on top, where Rowling and her
creation had been roosting.
</P>
<P>
   Charles McGrath, editor of the Book Review, admits that the
change was made to keep the best-seller list from being
overHarrywhelmed, but says that's not meant as a negative
reflection on Potter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some complaints that Harry Potter has been relegated
to the minor leagues,'' McGrath said. ``But I'm hoping at least
someone will like it. We've been talking about making a children's
list forever, and the intention was to children's books some
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Some folks might worry that it could also raise the financial
stakes on a genre that so far has escaped the blockbuster mentality
that drives adult publishing and other media, but Jean Gaffney
isn't worried. ``I'm an optimist,'' she says. ``I think a good
author and a good book will always find their place.'' And she
thinks the Harry Potter books are very, very good _ classic, even.
</P>
<P>
   She should know. She's the children's librarian at the
Miamisburg branch of the Dayton-Montgomery County Public Library,
and a former Caldecott Award juror. She's watched kids devour the
books and then, when they're done, look around for other good stuff
to read.
</P>
<P>
   Upsides to Potterism, she says, are that it's made it cooler for
boys to read, has stimulated book talk among kids who previously
couldn't imagine such a thing, and also raises the profile of
children's fiction _ which sometimes has taken a back seat,
marketwise, to picture books for younger kids.
</P>
<P>
   Roth says, ``The good news for us is we now have 15 children's
books on the best-seller list. Before, it was just three,'' the
Potter books on the main list. ``This is more a celebration of all
children's books and authors. So we like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
