<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PLATFORM-1STLD     07-29 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PLATFORM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S STANCE ON EDUCATION PREVAILS IN BATTLE ON PLANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to update with vote to abolish Education
Dept. being defeated; Pickup 5th graf pvs, The platform reiterates
...; subs overline.) 
By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ After a fierce debate, the Republican platform
committee Saturday voted against a call to abolish the Department
of Education, with some conservatives warning that the party was
breaking with the small-government principles of the Reagan
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   It was a victory for Gov. George W. Bush, who has campaigned
hard on education, and it was emblematic of his allies' efforts to
reorient the party, on a small set of issues high on the voters'
agenda, to a more centrist appeal. On other matters, though, from
opposition to gays in the military to contraceptives in
school-based clinics, conservatives held sway Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Saturday's education debate revolved around the way the
party's less-government-is-best philosophy is viewed by the voters
at large. ``When you say the abolishment of the Department of
Education,'' argued Sen &UR; . &LR;  Bill Frist, R-Tenn., a Bush ally, many
people hear ``that we don't care about education _ and if there's
one thing Republicans care about, it's kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Williams of Oklahoma, a conservative committee member who
pushed for the abolition, argued, ``We need to remain true to what
President Reagan began with our revolution in the '80s; that the
government is too large, too costly, and control needs to be
returned to the states.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sue Myrick, R-N.C., countered, ``We deal every day with
people who are scared to death that Republicans want to do away
with education.''
</P>
<P>
   After the votes, which also reinserted elements of the Bush
education program that had been stripped by conservatives in
subcommittee, Bush spokesmen declared a major victory. Ari
Fleischer declared it a ``marked departure from the '96 platform,''
and added that, ``We did make it clear to delegates that this was a
crucial issue to Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   As it pushed toward completion of its work, the 107-member
platform committee reasserted that ``homosexuality is incompatible
with military service,'' overwhelmingly rejecting efforts to remove
that plank. Fleischer noted that ``the governor believes `don't
ask, don't tell' is the appropriate policy and he supports that.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also rejected an attempt to defend contraceptive
services in school-based clinics. Philip Hellreich, a committee
member from Hawaii who offered the amendment, argued that as a
doctor, he saw too many teen-agers with unwanted pregnancies.
``Without the appropriate use of contraceptives,'' he argued, ``we
will have many, many more unwanted pregnancies.'' Opponents, who
asserted that abstinence was the appropriate course, easily
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   While the party's platform does not call for the abolition of
any federal agencies _ four years ago, it called for several _ it
still reflects a party deeply suspicious of the federal government
and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The platform reiterates one of the guiding principles of modern
conservatism _ that more and more power should be shifted to the
states: ``The dramatic success of welfare reform _ once states were
allowed to manage their programs _ is a stellar example of what
happens when we give power back to the people,'' the platform
declares. ``We must acknowledge as a general matter of course that
the federal government's role should be to set high standards and
expectations in policies, then get out of the way and let the
states implement and operate those policies as they best know
how.''
</P>
<P>
   The power of conservatives was perhaps most clear on the issue
of abortion and gay rights. Abortion rights supporters tried on
several occasions to remove the abortion plank or add a provision
recognizing and expressing respect for Republicans who hold
different views on the issue, but they were decisively beaten each
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is are we a pro-life party or are we a
pro-abortion rights party,'' declared Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., a
staunch opponent of abortion. ``It's left to the Republicans, the
heartless Republicans, to care about the unborn.''
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic description of what opponents call partial birth
abortion, Hyde declared, ``If this party stands for nothing else,
it ought to stand for violent objection to that butchery.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of that struggle were pre-ordained; Bush and top
Republican leaders had announced early on that they wanted the
abortion plank left alone. Democrats and abortion rights supporters
see it as an important vulnerability in the fall election, because
it calls for a blanket ban on abortion and the appointment of
judges who reflect the party's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   On gay rights, conservatives declared repeatedly that the party
needed to put itself wholeheartedly on record against recognizing
civil unions between homosexuals, and added a provision to the
platform defining marriage as ``the legal union of one man and one
woman.'' They also added language declaring, ``We do not believe
sexual preference should be given special legal protection or
standing in law.'' And the platform reiterates its contention that
homosexuality is incompatible with military service.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a leading conservative, said in an interview that he
was pleased with the platform. ``On the sanctity of life, it's
solid and consistent with the past,'' he said. ``I think it's a
strong conservative platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Schlafly, another veteran conservative activist, said:
``I think it's wordier and not as good as '96. Of course, we kept
the pro-life plank, but I thought the '96 platform was better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
