<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-PORTWOOD-NYT &LR;      07-29 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PORTWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYMOND PORTWOOD JR., 66, COMPUTER GAME PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill.)   By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raymond Eugene Portwood Jr., who began working as an animator
with the Walt Disney Co. at 17 and went on to become one of the two
principal creators of the pioneering and popular Carmen Sandiego
series of children's computer games, died July 17 in Windsor,
Calif. He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   Portwood died of a heart attack at a convalescent center, where
he had lived since a stroke 18 months ago, according to his wife,
Myra Bates Portwood.
</P>
<P>
   The Carmen Sandiego games, a painless way to learn academic
subjects by following an animated vamp in a trench coat around on
the computer, have sold 6.5 million copies and led to three
television series. Introduced in 1985, the game was one of the
first approaches to computerized education for children, and it
remains one of the most popular.
</P>
<P>
   With his colleague, Lauren Elliott, Portwood is credited with
dreaming up Carmen Sandiego, who, as a former secret agent gone
bad, is the ringleader of a gang of eccentric provocateurs who roam
the world causing trouble, usually by stealing a treasure of local
significance. The player assumes the role of Interpol detective,
tracking Carmen Sandiego or her henchmen from city to city and
nation to nation on the basis of clues provided by witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She changed all her money for zlotys,'' a witness might say,
prompting an informed player to head for Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Portwood and Elliott worked principally on the first two Carmen
games, ``Where in the World Is Carmen Sandiego?'' and ``Where in
the U.S.A. Is Carmen Sandiego?'' Many more games followed, covering
subjects like math and history.
</P>
<P>
   It began in a spare building in San Rafael, Calif., that was the
home of Broderbund Software. The company's creative team would meet
in what was called the rubber room to bounce around ideas.
Portwood's artistic sensibility was critical to the process, his
colleagues say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people could talk it,'' said Douglas Carlston, a founder
of Broderbund. ``He could see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlston gives Portwood much of the credit for Carmen. ``If he
wasn't the most key guy, he was one of the most key guys,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bull, a software engineer who was part of the original
design team, said that Portwood was responsible for ``a large part
of the original concept.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carmen games were some of the first to move computer games
out of the arcade and into the classroom. In 1987, Ariella Lehrer,
president of Lehrer Associates, a Los Angeles-based educational
software consulting firm, said, ``This software gets high praise
from teachers because it combines so many subjects and reference
skills, and kids never get tired of it because the computer
generates clues and geographic settings at random.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Broderbund's best-selling products, Carmen Sandiego
helped the company become so successful as a software maker that it
was bought by the Learning Co. in June 1998 in a stock swap valued
at $420 million. In May 1999, Mattel bought the Learning Co. for
$3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Myra Portwood said her husband and Elliott had no chance to cash
in on the financial bonanza personally. Although they received
substantial royalties for the first two Carmen games, she said,
Broderbund changed its compensation arrangements for later
versions. As a result, she said, the two developers left in 1992
and formed their own game company, Elliott Portwood Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Portwood was born in Chicago on Sept. 16, 1933, the son of a
house painter. When he was 11, the family moved to Burbank, Calif.
He showed talent for drawing cartoon characters, and a family
friend introduced him to a Disney animator, who invited him to
submit a portfolio of his work.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, he joined the Disney animation army of more than 200. He
did not attend college, but read voraciously and became known for
his vast vocabulary. He loved old movies, music and practical
jokes. He positively delighted in turning language upside down.
</P>
<P>
   For example, his and Elliott's last company was in Petaluma,
Calif. His resultant joke: ``You can pet a cat, but you can't pet a
luma.''
</P>
<P>
   At Disney, he worked on films including ``Lady and the Tramp''
and ``Sleeping Beauty.'' For ``Peter Pan,'' he contributed to the
famous scene in which a crocodile chases Captain Hook. In those
precomputer days, each frame had to be laboriously prepared by an
assembly line of artisans. Portwood was a link in that chain.
</P>
<P>
   In his five years at Disney, he also frequently worked on the
Jiminy Cricket animations that introduced segments of Disney's
evening television program. ``He said he'd probably drawn more
crickets than anybody on the planet,'' Carlston said.
</P>
<P>
   To earn more money for his growing family, Portwood took jobs
with Security National Bank in Orange County, Honeywell
International and the University of California.
</P>
<P>
   After a divorce, he married his second wife, who operated a
bakery in Sebastopol, Calif., where he lived until his stroke.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; his daughters, Kim Portwood of Santa
Rosa, Calif., and Kathi Gamberutti, Kari Hermanson, Kelley Portwood
and Kristi Portwood, all of Monterey, Calif.; and two sisters,
Lynette Foster of Redondo Beach, Calif., and Darlene Insley of
Santa Cruz, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Portwood's job at Broderbund was the culmination of all his
passions, his wife said. For one thing, he was paid to play with
words, one of his favorite things. Many of the names of Carmen
Sandiego's henchmen and henchwomen, said to have been his
creations, were either very inspired or very bad puns. Some
examples: Rob Burr, Clement See, Belle Igerent and Mandy Lifeboats.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, he could play endlessly with computers; at
home, his wife finally had to put a sheet over the family PC to
have any hope of catching his attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
