<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT &LR;      07-29 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGENDS OF NFL WELCOME THE CLASS OF 2000 TO THE HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
  By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ One hundred eleven of pro football's 136 living
Hall of Fame members strode onto the stage here, a place revered by
the owners, coaches, and athletes who play the game, and by the
fans who follow them.
</P>
<P>
   Sid Gillman entered in a wheelchair. Roger Staubach and Joe
Namath glided across the stage to thunderous applause. Franco
Harris and John Mackey and Chuck Noll and Bill Walsh and so many
more champions were introduced, a throng of football heroes
immersed in a pool of adoring onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Super Bowl of enshrinement ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   There will never be another ceremony that features this many
20th century members.
</P>
<P>
   That drama and appreciation of history served as the backdrop
for the induction of the class of 2000. And matching the moment was
a noble and glitzy class, one of the most complete and interesting
since the first enshrinement in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Montana, Ronnie Lott, Dave Wilcox, Howie Long and Dan Rooney
shared a common theme of thanks to family, friends and teammates
who helped them reach the Hall. And their reception overflowed with
interest and emotion from the thousands of fans packed around the
Hall, easily the largest crowd for an induction here.
</P>
<P>
   There were many moments that will be chronicled in pictures and
in sound. Moments that will last inside the Hall of Fame _ along
with a bronze bust of each _ forever. This group pushed the total
number in the Hall to 204.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox was the first to be inducted Saturday, and he spoke
unselfishly about the friends he has gained in the NFL and about
his magical memories. Wilcox played linebacker for the San
Francisco 49ers from 1964 through 1974, and he was presented by one
of his coaches, Mike Giddings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football gave me a chance to meet people and to travel all
over the world,'' Wilcox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me if I played with Joe Montana with the 49ers, and
I tell them I played before Joe and before money. I earned $12,500
a season. But the memories are wonderful. And now there are 204
people in this Hall and in the next 100 years, at that rate, there
will be 904. That is still so few. This is so very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Long, a defensive end who played with the Raiders from 1981 to
1993, said that baseball is America's pastime but that football is
``America's passion.'' He was introduced by Earl Leggett, his
former line coach.
</P>
<P>
   Leggett said that Long was the right pick for the right team and
the right time for the Raiders. He said Long was the best leader he
had ever been around. Long is one of only seven defensive ends to
reach the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud that I played my entire career with the Raiders
because that is something that rarely happens in today's game,''
Long said, referring to current players who frequently move to
other teams via free agency. ``I have always appreciated the
history of this league. Now my sons have watched film of my career
this week and they say: `Wow, Dad, you were pretty good. You were
pretty tough, too.' Their love means more to me than anything in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, said Long, does his 22-year marriage to his wife,
Dianne, who, he said, has been his confidante, friend and
counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Lott chose his father, Roy, to present him. Lott was a 49ers
safety from 1981 to 1990, and then spent two seasons with the
Raiders and two more with the Jets before retiring in 1994. He was
a ferocious and feared hitter, but his father talked about his
compassion and his love.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, the former quarterback, was presented by the former
49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo Jr., who said that Montana's legacy is
``much larger than life'' and who described how Montana ``turned
losses into wins.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo praised Montana's ``unmatched loyalty, excellence,
courage and heroics,'' and said, ``They will live in our hearts and
dreams forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana offered humor, pulling out a long sheet that he said
contained his speech.
</P>
<P>
   But Montana went on the speak emotionally about how he felt over
the last six months, as if ``I'm in my grave and people are
throwing dirt on my coffin and I'm trying to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   The glowing praise and retrospect on his career made him
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I didn't understand what this was all about until
I got here this weekend and saw all of these guys and realized I
was on a new team,'' Montana said. ``This is not the ending point
but the beginning of my career and life with a new team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney, the Pittsburgh Steelers owner, was presented by the Hall
of Famer Joe Greene, a former Steeler. Rooney has spent the last 45
years with the Steelers. Now he and the rest of the class of 2000
will be recognized forever in the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many to thank,'' Rooney said. ``I thank them
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
