u p BC-NJ-CAMDEN-CONVENTION-     07-29 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CAMDEN-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GOP GUESTS, CAMDEN TRIES TO PAINT OVER ITS ROT 
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. _ For just one evening, this city is trying not to
ooze misery. It deployed the Public Works Department's only
grass-cutter to mow vacant lots downtown, forsaking 2,000 others
that needed tending. The streets need cleaning, but the city's
seven sweepers are old and broken. Camden has 3,500 vacant
buildings, but only a three-man crew to keep them boarded up.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are coming to Camden on Sunday night, and the
task of making the East St. Louis of the East presentable would
have challenged Potemkin himself.
</P>
<P>
   Welcoming ceremonies for the Republican National Convention will
be held on Camden's waterfront, the only redeveloped slice of the
city. It offers great views of Philadelphia's skyline, and of the
lighted boat show and fireworks planned on the Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   But coming to New Jersey through Camden is like entering a
split-level through the mud room, and cleaning for the guests has
been a chore.
</P>
<P>
   Just over the Ben Franklin Bridge from Philadelphia, state and
regional officials recently spent $45 million to clear out
unsightly businesses on Admiral Wilson Boulevard, including topless
joints and by-the-hour hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Camden has 209 miles of road, but attention has focused on four
routes through downtown to the waterfront. Crumbling buildings have
been knocked down, rotting trees uprooted, flowers and shrubs
planted, broken windows covered with fresh gray boards and light
posts decked with banners. The road to the newly docked USS New
Jersey is lined with shipping containers that hide industrial
detritus. On the waterfront, mulch has been blown among fresh beds
of flowers, and at the Children's Garden near the state aquarium,
the newest creature is an elephant topiary named George, as in W.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first impression is important,'' said Gov. Christie
Whitman, Sunday night's host. But it can also mislead.
</P>
<P>
   As the VIP's gaze at Philadelphia, here's what will be festering
in the city of 82,000 behind their backs: school dropout rates as
high as 60 percent. Almost 40 percent of households earning less
than $20,000. A tax base that yields only about $29 million for
combined city and school expenses of $350 million. A mayor indicted
on corruption charges, like two of his last four predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a casualty,'' said the Rev. Michael Doyle, a priest in
South Camden for 32 years, ``and America is to blame for a Camden.
They don't see it that way. It's like a drunk on a grate and people
say, `It's not my problem.' If you can't save a Camden in a
powerful economy, then when will we be able to make it livable?
When?''
</P>
<P>
   There are glimmers of hope _ a few remaining corporations, the
waterfront, some renovated housing _ but they are hard to spot amid
weed-choked lots, abandoned homes and the addicted roaming like
stray dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, who is waging a legislative battle to seize control of
Camden, said she was shaken by the depth of its problems during a
nighttime tour with state troopers in 1996. That trip recently
produced a photograph of the smiling governor frisking an innocent
black man. Back here the other day to award some grants, she said
that after that tour, ``All I could think of was what would I have
been like if this was my environment growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shinnelle Queensbury perhaps could suggest an answer. At 14, she
lives in the South Camden neighborhood the governor visited the
other day. Despite a family history laced with drugs and prison,
Shinnelle is a serious student at the Creative Arts High School,
taking summer enrichment courses and singing and dancing in a local
production of ``Secrets Every Smart Traveler Should Know.'' Despite
the pressures of the street, she could do a one-girl show of the
same name for Sunday night's visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait until you get to my block,'' she said, leaving the
commotion around the governor. She lives with her grandparents, and
there is only one other house on her side of the street that is not
boarded up. ``A brick fell out of that house and almost hit me,''
she said of a crumbling building on the corner.
</P>
<P>
   On her block, she said, ``the police patrol, but the drug boys
run.'' Her teachers are encouraging, but neighbors razz her
because, she said, ``I like to talk with proper English.'' Imagine
coming home from school happy, she said, only to learn ``one of
your relatives has done something wrong or someone was shot in
front of your aunt's house.''
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, Camden adopted Walt Whitman's poetic line: ``In a
dream I saw a city invincible.'' That dream is long gone, but
flashes of resilience remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really trying,'' Shinnelle Queensbury said, crossing the
deserted street on her way to sing and dance, ``but there's so many
things pulling me down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
