<HEADER>
A7016 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SOCCER0730-COX     07-29 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOCCER0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wolff's at door of major role
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It didn't take a full-page color spread in Rolling
Stone for Josh Wolff to realize that he isn't in Lilburn, Ga.
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   On the opening page of the magazine's special July Olympic
fashion section was Wolff, wearing nearly $200 of designer
sportswear and flying through the air with five superimposed rings
around him. The shots of him and his U.S. men's soccer teammates
were placed ahead of a relaxed pose of Maurice Greene, the
100-meter dash favorite in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we'll take whatever we can get,'' Wolff said. ``It was a
lot of fun to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer always has been a lot of fun for Wolff, the former
standout striker at Parkview High School and for the Brookwood
Steamers elite youth program.
</P>
<P>
   He is certain to make the final Olympic roster that will be
announced next month
</P>
<P>
   Wolff is having his best professional season for the Chicago
Fire of Major League Soccer. In 14 starts, he has scored five
times, and on Tuesday he put his club in the quarterfinals of the
U.S. Open Cup with the only goal of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a knack for scoring in the clutch. His game-winner
in early June against Kansas City knocked off the last unbeaten MLS
team.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff's decision to turn pro after three seasons at the
University of South Carolina symbolizes the U.S. Soccer
Federation's attempt to accelerate the development of its men's
program. Only one current Olympic team member is an amateur, with
most of the rest based in MLS with Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran college and USSF staff coach Clive Charles will take a
more experienced group to Australia than the band of collegians,
indoor players and handful of European pros who represented the
U.S. in the 1990 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic men's soccer is limited to players 23 and under, except
for three older players allowed per team. Most countries use the
Olympics as a springboard for the World Cup and high-level club
competition. Nigeria won the gold in Atlanta, and several of its
players are now starring for some of the top clubs in Europe. So
are those from Brazil, Argentina, Spain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans just want to advance out of group play for the
first time and get a taste of the kind of international game they
will encounter at the senior level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is more pressure on this team, since we're the
first group to come out of a professional environment,'' Wolff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff, who turned 23 in February, spent his first year playing
with an MLS developmental team. Then he went to Chicago, which won
the MLS title in 1998, its first season.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that has slowed him down was a torn knee ligament
suffered on a freak play during a training session last fall. He
lined up to practice a penalty kick, but his left knee crumbled
after just a few steps. He missed the rest of the playoffs but was
ready to go when spring training began in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee is fine, but it's harder coming back mentally than it
is physically,'' he said. ``It's a matter of staying in shape and
knowing it's going to get better every day. You're so eager to get
back to where you were. In April and May, I wasn't back to where I
felt really good about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But a groin injury to Bulgarian World Cup hero Hristo Stoichkov
and the call-up of high-scoring forward Ante Razov to the U.S.
national team for World Cup qualifying has given Wolff more playing
time.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 8 and with great mobility, he is ideally suited to
play beside target players. He has done so most of his career,
including pairing with Conyers native Clint Mathis at South
Carolina. During Olympic qualifying, he played a similar role with
Chris Albright of D.C. United and 18-year-old phenom Landon
Donovan, who out of high school turned pro with German club Bayer
Leverkusen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be good for me or the team to talk about who's
going to start at this point,'' coach Charles said. ``But I do see
Josh playing a major role for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the Olympic squad takes on the Bolton Wanderers, an
English Division One club, in an exhibition in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become better and smarter players because most of us
have been in a professional environment,'' Wolff said. ``The
toughest part is that we're not going to be together very much.
These games are going to be big because they're going to see where
we are as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
