<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SOC-AZIZI-NYT &LR;      07-29 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-AZIZI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IRANIAN STAR AT HOME IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the hundreds of thousands of Iranian expatriates in the Bay
Area of Northern California, the soccer star Khodadad Azizi was
hailed as a national hero when he arrived last March (along with
his wife and 3-year-old daughter) and signed a four-year contract
to play for the San Jose Earthquakes of Major League Soccer. Unlike
many of the aging players who have left leagues in Europe and South
America, Azizi, 29, came to the five-year-old U.S. league in his
prime, having played three seasons in Germany for F.C. Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Azizi led Iran to its first berth in the World Cup
finals since 1978 and played in the emotionally charged 2-1 victory
over the United States in Lyon, France. In 1997, he was the first
Iranian named the Asian Footballer of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   As the Earthquakes (5-10-8) have struggled in MLS this season,
so has Azizi. A lingering hamstring injury has limited him to 13
games, in which he has scored only one goal with four assists.
Still, Azizi, on the strength of balloting by his countrymen, was
voted to the starting lineup of Saturday's MLS All-Star Game in
Columbus, Ohio, finishing fourth among midfielders on the West team
with more than 27,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   While he was in New York the last week in June for a match
against the MetroStars, Azizi toured U.N. headquarters accompanied
by the Iranian ambassador, Hadi Nejad Hosseinian, and recorded a
public-service announcement in support of the international
anti-drug campaign, ``Sports, Not Drugs,'' which will be broadcast
in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Azizi spoke about his career, his country and his move to the
United States with Jack Bell, a staff editor for the sports section
of The New York Times, with the assistance of an interpreter,
Mehran Molkara. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have been called the Persian Michael Jordan. Was there a
negative reaction at home when you decided to come to the United
States to play? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Look, I am a soccer player. I'm not involved with politics.
There was no negative reaction. The people in Iran have no problem
with the American people. They like Americans. There are a million
Iranians living in the U.S. There has got to be something good
about the United States. I always get phone calls from reporters in
Iran and they want to know how I have been treated. I talk about
the hospitality and the friendliness of people here. I think that
many people around the world dream of seeing the U.S. I love Iran
and can't truly live anywhere else. But after Iran, this is the
best place to live in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why, in the prime of your career, did you decide to come to
the United States? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Because it is exciting and interesting. I still had the
opportunity to play in Europe, but after coming to the United
States for a friendly game (Iran-United States in January in
Pasadena, Calif.), after I saw all the Iranian fans, I made up my
mind to join MLS. I chose San Jose because of all the Iranian fans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You played several years in the Bundesliga, one of the
toughest leagues in the world. How would you compare the quality of
play in MLS? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: What surprised me the most is that the German league is very
physical, but I believe that MLS is more physical and hard.
Naturally, in Europe they don't consider MLS a top league, but I
believe people think it is going in the right direction and that it
is able to attract big stars.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have heard that women in Iran are not permitted to attend
soccer games. So what is your impression of the popularity of
women's soccer in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have seen a few games of the American team and, obviously,
they deserve to be No. 1 in the world. You can tell you have better
youth programs here for girls than anywhere else in the world. In
Iran, the reason that women are not allowed in the stadiums is
because of the intense environment. It is not a pleasant
environment for women to be in. Of course, that could be worked on.
This is not a difference in culture; it is a religious thing in
Iran. There is now a women's league in Iran, but you don't see men
going to watch the women play like in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before the World Cup finals in 1998, many Americans looked at
the group that included the United States, Iran, Germany and
Yugoslavia and believed that a victory and three points against
Iran were a virtual certainty for them.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's exactly how we looked at it when we thought about
playing the U.S. We knew it would be harder to get points from
Germany and Yugoslavia. I know that the game was a big deal in
America, but it was even more important for the people of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You were in Iran recently for a tournament. Did you notice
any changes?
</P>
<P>
   A: The atmosphere in Iran is getting better every day, contrary
to what many people have heard in the West. The young people follow
what is happening in foreign countries. They want to and can visit
foreign lands. Travel is not restricted. In my personal opinion, I
think that people are more in tune with what is happening in the
world than they were 10 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SAIL-TEENS-LESSONS-NY     07-29 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-TEENS-LESSONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRETEENS AND OTHERS LEARN SAILING SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass.)  (Eds: Herb McCormick is the editor of Cruising World magazine.) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ To the discordant sounds of halyards slapping against
masts and sirens screeching down Storrow Drive last Wednesday,
11-year-old Brad Louw hauled in on the mainsheet, swung the tiller
over and instructed me to shove off. With a cold, unseasonable
northeast breeze filling the well-used sail of our ancient but
shipshape Cape Cod Mercury, Brad set a course down the gray Charles
River.
</P>
<P>
   As he eased the sheet expertly to spill a 15-knot gust, it was
hard to believe Brad had been sailing for less than two months. But
something in my movements did not inspire a corresponding sense of
confidence. ``So,'' Brad wondered, ``have you ever sailed before?''
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a free moment, I would have regaled the boy with
my sea tales. In that instant, however, Brad was smartly bearing
away to cut astern of a close-hauled Mercury with another urchin in
command. As for sea stories, he was too busy amassing his own.
</P>
<P>
   For over six decades at the full-service boathouse on the
Charles that serves as the headquarters of Community Boating Inc.,
countless sailors of all ages have been logging similar personal
adventures. Today, those between the ages of 10 and 18 can follow
Brad's example and take advantage of the best deal in boating.
Early last month, having just moved to the states with his family
from South Africa, he walked in and plunked down a dollar, which
paid for a summer's worth of lessons, boat rentals and experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations like Milwaukee Community Sailing, St. Petersburg
Sailing Center in Florida, the Dana Point Youth and Group Facility
in California, and the Long Shore Sailing School in Westport,
Conn., all offer similar programs for youths and adults.
</P>
<P>
   A national directory of community sailing offerings called
``Where to Sail'' is available on the U.S. Sailing Web site
(www.ussailing.org), or by calling (401) 683-0800.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last decade, the growth in publicly accessible sailing
opportunities has been huge,'' said Kim Hapgood, the program
director at Rhode Island's Sail Newport center and a member of the
U.S. Sailing council on community sailing. ``An increasing number
of people are attracted by the challenges sailing offers, and it
also appeals to people who already like to sail but don't want to
own boats.''
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1937 by a bullheaded, well-connected social
worker named Joe Lee, Boston's Community Boating Inc. is the
granddaddy of public sailing centers. Lee, who started with seven
ragtag boats with sails fashioned from bedsheets, would be startled
if he could see today's fleet of 75 Mercurys, five Sonars, six
Rhodes 19s, and about a dozen 420s, sailboards, Lasers and kayaks,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, with a miserable forecast better suited
to an afternoon in a library or a theater, about 50 diehard kids of
varied ethnic backgrounds _ down from the hundreds who would gather
on a typical July day _ lingered about the docks in various degrees
of soakage. Charlie Zechel, the director of instruction, didn't
seem to mind the low turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the busiest summer here in years, and it's nice to
have a little break,'' he said. ``Generally, we maintain a nice,
steady state of being on the verge of chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the April-to-October season, about 1,500
junior sailors and nearly 8,000 adults will participate in
Community Boating programs. A full year's membership costs $190,
though short-term plans are also available. Experienced sailors can
take a test that will allow them to use boats on a level
commensurate with their skills.
</P>
<P>
   Beginners must take a five-day shore school that provides them
with a Solo rating. Sailors can then earn higher ratings _ and
privileges on more boats and in greater wind strengths _ with
further instruction and testing, which they can schedule at their
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once someone gets to where Brad Louw is, with a couple of
ratings, it's all pretty self-directed,'' Zechel said.
</P>
<P>
   As we sailed back to the docks, Brad's teeth were clattering.
Bare-chested except for a life vest, with a rivulet of rain
cascading off his nose, he had been sailing for hours before taking
me out. He had turned back now only because I made him. Then he
handed me the tiller and called the puffs funneling through the
Longfellow Bridge. He was a natural, and he was ready for more.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
