u s BC-BKO-WOLTERS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WOLTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLTERS ADJUSTS TO EXPANSION TEAM LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When does playing become more important than winning?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, that may sound like a question that a
self-absorbed athlete mulls over while sitting on the bench,
watching teammates gaining notice and, depending on the situation,
having all the fun.
</P>
<P>
   Almost one year ago, Kara Wolters pondered these thoughts to
herself. She is not selfish, but she knows how to take advantage of
a good opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   So, after spending last season on the sideline as the Houston
Comets proceeded toward a second consecutive WNBA championship,
Wolters was happy to be selected in the fifth round of the
expansion draft by the Indiana Fever. She had appeared in only 10
games for the Comets, averaging 4.1 minutes; she was impatient for
a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely wanted to leave because I knew it was time to
go,'' Wolters said in a recent telephone interview. ``Houston
probably didn't want to mess with a good thing, so I couldn't crack
their rotation. I felt I was ready to play steady minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston (21-4), led by Sheryl Swoopes, Tina Thompson and Cynthia
Cooper, has continued its winning ways this season, while the Fever
(7-18, after a victory over Portland Friday night in which Wolters
went 7 for 7 from the field), as expected, has struggled. As with
most expansion teams, Indiana has had trouble trying to blend a mix
of raw, young players; 10 of the 12 players on the Fever roster are
either rookies or in their second year in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   For Wolters, especially, losing has been an unpleasant change.
She not only played with Houston last year, but she was also a
starter for the University of Connecticut during its 35-0 record
and NCAA title in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough coming into the season because we have that
expansion-team mind-set,'' said Wolters, Indiana's starting center.
``The expectations have to be that, going into a game, we feel we
are supposed to win. We can't say to ourselves, `Hey, it's all
right that we lost because we hung in tonight with a good team.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the on-court transition for Wolters has been a slam dunk.
Nicknamed Big Girl because of her 6-foot-7-inch, 227-pound frame,
Wolters has received the opportunity she yearned for. She is
averaging 25 minutes a game, and her statistics are both
competitive and impressive: 11.8 points a game, .560 field-goal
shooting (second in the league), 4.7 rebounds a game, 1.1 assists a
game, 1.25 blocks a game (seventh) and .795 free throw shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected her to play big minutes this season,'' said Fever
coach Anne Donovan, who at 6-8, a three-time former Olympic center
and a member of the women's basketball Hall of Fame, is someone
Wolters can look up to in more ways than one. ``It was difficult
for Kara in Houston because they had their system already set up,
so there wasn't an opportunity for her. She is a tremendous post
player, mainly because she has great hands. We try to work the
inside-outside game, so when she draws a double team, she does a
good job of kicking it back outside to the perimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, Wolters is playing the inside-outside game
with point guard Rita Williams, a former UConn teammate. ``Rita and
I are close on the court because we know each other's strengths and
weaknesses,'' Wolters said. ``We know when to get the ball to each
other, so we both get good looks at the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Another one of Wolters' former teammates at UConn is Paige
Sauer, a 6-5 center who warms the bench for the Los Angeles Sparks
behind the All-Star and Olympian Lisa Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paige is in almost exactly the same position I was in with
Houston,'' Wolters said. ``She has to pay her dues, but I always
offer her encouragement. She and I realize that we are lucky to be
playing in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   One trend, however, that discourages Wolters about the WNBA is
the increasing emphasis on guard play and the neglect of the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am a dying breed because the game has become so much
quicker,'' she said. ``I think the post is overlooked when it comes
to offense. I have no choice but to evolve with the changes. It's a
shame.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Fever ends its debut season, Wolters' year will
continue in Sydney, Australia, where she and 10 other players on
the U.S. team, including Chamique Holdslcaw, Yolanda Griffith,
Teresa Edwards, Lisa Leslie, Dawn Staley and Sheryl Swoopes, will
play for the Olympic gold medal in women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to do everything I can do for this team, whether it's
playing two or 20 minutes in a game, or just giving encouragement
to other players,'' Wolters said. ``It's really amazing to me to be
a part of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
