<HEADLINE>
ROBERT G. CROWDER, 60; EXPERT ON MEMORY 
 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Robert George Crowder, an experimental psychologist and an
authority on memory, died Thursday at his home in Hamden, Conn. He
was 60.
</P>
<P>
   Crowder gained wide recognition in 1976 with the graduate
textbook ``Principles of Learning and Memory,'' which summarized
the research done on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The book remains in print and until recently he was working on
an updated edition.
</P>
<P>
   He also was author, along with Richard K. Wagner, of ``The
Psychology of Reading: An Introduction.'' A contributor of numerous
articles and book chapters, he was an editor, along with Frank R.
Schab, of ``Memory for Odors.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowder joined the faculty at Yale as a lecturer in 1965, was
promoted to full professor of psychology in 1976 and retired from
active teaching two years ago because of his failing health.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 28 years, Julie Butterfield
Crowder; two sons, Edward and Bruce, both of New Haven, Conn.; a
daughter, Lorial Crowder of Boston; and a half-bother, David L.
Crowder of Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
