<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOTELS-REAL-670(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MANHATTAN HOTELS FIND A READY MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The seemingly unending boom in the hotel business in
New York continued unabated during the first half of this year,
despite an influx of new rooms and the prospect of more to come.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by PKF Consulting, which specializes in
the hospitality industry, the occupancy rate in Manhattan reached
84.4 percent, a record for any six-month period since the firm
began collecting statistics in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of spending a night reached $224.83 during the
period, also a record, and an 8 percent increase compared with the
same period last year. And the trend is upward. PKF reported that
the average room rate for the month of June was $236.54, an 11.7
percent increase over June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers, the accounting and consulting firm,
which conducts a similar survey, reported the occupancy rate at 84
percent and the average room rate at $249 a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occupancy and room rates were at record levels, and this is
supposed to be the slow half of the year,'' said John A. Fox, a
senior vice president of PKF, who explained that demand for hotel
rooms was typically lower in the January-to-June months than in
July to December, a period of vacations and holidays when people
are more apt to travel to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hotels in the city are selling out 200 to 250 nights a year,
which means they are turning away business, so I am not concerned
that we are going to be adding some rooms,'' Fox added.
</P>
<P>
   He said the strong market of the last few years has encouraged
the development of hotel projects, including the conversion of
office buildings and the upgrading of single-room-occupancy hotels
to those catering to transients.
</P>
<P>
   Some 4,000 to 4,500 hotel rooms are expected to be added to the
New York market this year, one of the largest expansions in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist interest in New York accounts for much of the demand for
lodging in the city, as the crowds surging through Times Square and
along Fifth Avenue every day attest.
</P>
<P>
   But the buoyant economy, which is gobbling up office space in
the city, is increasing demand from business travelers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn Hanson, the global leader of the PricewaterhouseCoopers
hospitality practice, has calculated that every additional 100
square feet of office space that is occupied in the city generates
0.7 room nights of hotel demand.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to this demand, developers are rushing to complete
new hotels, most of them conversions of existing buildings. An
exception to this trend is the Sofitel that opened earlier month on
44th Street between Fifth Avenue and the Avenue of the Americas; it
was new construction from the ground up. Rooms cost $350 a night,
and suites, $450.
</P>
<P>
   Another new entrant in the market is the Red Roof Inn Manhattan,
the franchise chain's first in New York City, on 32nd Street just
west of Fifth Avenue in a converted office building not far from
Herald Square. The hotel was developed by Apple Core Hotels, a
company owned by the Horn and Kohane families that has four other
moderately priced hotels in Midtown Manhattan and a hotel and
conference center in Hempstead, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The $23 million conversion of the 17-story loft building on 32nd
Street has produced a hotel with 171 guest rooms plus a business
center, exercise room, meeting space and a breakfast room.
</P>
<P>
   Room rates will range from $89 to $329 a night, which is in
marked contrast to some of the other new boutique hotels scheduled
to open soon, where room rates will start at nearly $300 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Dandapani, Apple Core's chief operating officer, said
converting the old loft building to a hotel was difficult,
particularly so because a retail store on the first floor refused
to leave, limiting the size of the lobby. He said that passenger
elevators are now where the freight elevators were in the old
building, and the shafts for the old passenger elevators are
occupied by a stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everything is new, but the four walls on the
outside,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the building is hemmed in on three sides on the lower
floors, most of those floors were unsuitable for guest rooms, which
have to have a window. So that is where the exercise, conference,
business and breakfast rooms were situated. On the upper floors,
windows have been punched through the walls, even though the view
is often only of the roofs of lower buildings nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be some sweeping views from a glass-enclosed
rooftop bar, which Dandapani hopes to complete within a year.
</P>
<P>
   A similar rooftop bar already exists at the Best Western
Manhattan, which Apple Core also owns. It is on the north side of
32nd Street, just to the west of the Red Roof, and hotel guests
there can take in the sight of the Empire State Building looming in
the background only a block away.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Core's other hotels, all developed in the last five years,
are the Quality Hotel &AMP; Suites on West 46th Street, the Comfort
Inn, also on West 46th, and the Quality Hotel on Lexington Avenue
at 30th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Although all the hotels are operated in collaboration with
national chains, Dandapani said Apple Core had its own reservation
system, which brought in about 50 percent of the reservations
independent of the franchise affiliations. It is staffed 24 hours a
day, he said, to avoid forcing front-desk clerks to make
reservations in addition to their other duties.
</P>
<P>
   Dandapani said the Apple Core's occupancy rate ran well over 90
percent and said that the group was looking for other properties to
develop as hotels in New York. But, he added, they must be well
located and suitable for conversion.
</P>
<P>
   One building that Apple Core bought but later decided was not
suitable for its market is the old Leavitt Building on West.
Acquired from Apple Core for the Mass Mutual Financial Group by
Cornerstone Real Estate Advisers, the new hotel is scheduled to
open next month as the Muse, with 200 rooms. It is being described
as a boutique hotel that will emphasize personal service at rates
that will range from $295 to $395 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's proximity to the theater district will be emphasized
in a ground-floor restaurant _ so far unnamed _ that was designed
by David Rockwell, who did such restaurants as Nobu and Heartbeat.
The exterior will have a simulated curtain of woven stainless steel
drawn up to one side as if opening onto a stage. Inside, the
decorations will include simulated theater scenery with banks of
spotlights.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant will have 85 seats and will provide room service
for the hotel and a complimentary buffet called the ``midnight
pantry,'' where guests can find cookies and desserts, fruit and
cheese plates and ice cream after a night at the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Another boutique hotel scheduled to open late this summer is the
Dylan, in the former Chemists Club, on East 41st, between Madison
and Park avenues. The renovation of the 1903 building cost Morris
Moinian, the developer, $30 million and produced a 108-room hotel,
with rates of $295 to $450 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's restaurant will be called Rx, with a nod to the
building's past. The hotel will have two conference rooms that can
be combined to seat up to 75 people. Guest rooms will have
high-speed access to the Internet and television sets with Web
access.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Central Partnership, the local business improvement
district, is planting trees along the sidewalks in the area and
installing antique-style street lamps with hanging flower baskets.
Plans are to designate that section of 41st Street as Library Walk
in recognition of its proximity to the New York Public Library and
to install plaques in the sidewalk with quotes from famous books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
