<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON FAULTS ARAFAT FOR FAILURE OF MIDEAST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton criticized the Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat Saturday for the failure of the recent Middle
East peace talks at Camp David and, taking a leaf from President
Clinton's political handbook, called for moving the U.S. Embassy
from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who has taken a number of pro-Israel positions in
her Senate campaign, noted that the president had said in an
Israeli television interview on Friday that he favored moving the
embassy and would decide before year's end whether to do so. Israel
and many Jews around the world have long sought international
recognition for Jerusalem as the capital of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has avidly courted New York's Jewish vote _ about 12
percent of the state's electorate and has declared that Jerusalem
should be ``the eternal and indivisible capital of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   She said as long ago as last year that the embassy should be in
Jerusalem, but Saturday, she went a step further than her husband,
setting a year-end deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the president has announced he'll review the
decision about moving our embassy to Jerusalem,'' Clinton said in
an interview on New WCBS Radio in New York. ``That's absolutely the
right thing to do. But I'd like to see that move be made before the
end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's opponent in the Senate race, Rep. Rick Lazio, told
worshippers at an Orthodox synagogue on Long Island on Saturday
morning that he also supported moving the embassy, but said the
move should be done immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the breakdown of two weeks of talks that President
Clinton had brokered at Camp David _ talks that stumbled over the
status of Jerusalem _ Clinton suggested that Arafat was largely to
blame, and she praised Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak for his
efforts to resolve issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that Prime Minister Barak came committed to
reaching a deal that would guarantee peace and security for Israel
and the entire region, and I'm sorry that Chairman Arafat didn't
show the same commitment,'' Clinton said .
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also echoed her husband's appeal to Arafat not to carry
out his stated intention of unilaterally declaring a Palestinian
state by Sept. 13, with or without a peace agreement. She had said
last week that if Arafat did so, the United States should cut off
aid to the Palestinians, and she reiterated that warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian authority must abide by its commitment to
avoid violence or unilateral action,'' she said. ``It must be clear
that any unilateral declaration of Palestinian statehood would be
entirely unacceptable and should be met with a cutoff of United
States assistance. This is an issue that must be resolved between
the two parties at the negotiating table.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was greeted warmly Saturday at an Orthodox synagogue in
Westhampton Beach, on Long Island, after he vowed to continue
working for a unified Jerusalem. He spoke at the synagogue a week
after Clinton addressed the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With regard to Jerusalem, my position has been clear and
consistent, over the past eight years,'' he said, referring to his
terms in Congress. ``I have supported a united, undivided
Jerusalem,'' he told the crowd of several hundred worshippers, who
spilled out onto the outer patios of the synagogue. They greeted
his words with applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have repeatedly called for and voted for the respect and
recognition that comes with having our embassy in the eternal
capital of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   At a later meeting with reporters, Lazio reacted to Clinton's
call for the embassy to be moved to Jerusalem before the end of the
year. He said that the embassy should be moved immediately, and
criticized his opponent for her position.
</P>
</TEXT>
