<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHUMER-ENERGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER OFFERS DETAILED PLAN FOR TACKLING ENERGY PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even with unusually cool weather over the last month,
demand for electricity is rising throughout the region, continuing
a six-year trend that is straining the capacity of power plants,
according to a report to be released Sunday by Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The booming economy and prevalence of computers and high-tech
equipment in the home and workplace have caused electricity
consumption in New York City and Long Island to grow faster than
anyone anticipated,'' said Schumer in the report, which was
obtained Saturday from his staff. Using data from Consolidated
Edison and Keyspan, the report says consumption on a typical summer
day has increased 20 percent in New York City and 23 percent on
Long Island since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to face the music,'' Schumer said. ``If we ignore the
looming, chronic energy shortage, we risk the economic well-being
of the entire region.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who has been a leading advocate of deregulation of the
electric power industry and won favor from national environmental
groups by calling for cleaner power plants, recommended an
unusually detailed shopping list of investments for New York City
and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the proposals are new power plants in the region, although
the report does not specify where.
</P>
<P>
   Other investments, the report says, should come in new
transmission lines connecting the region to other parts of the
country where electricity is more plentiful, fuel cells and other
alternative energy sources, and financial incentives for business
and homeowners to reduce consumption on days of particularly high
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that we can solve this problem in an
environmentally sound way,'' Schumer said. The report calls for a
broad spectrum of local officials, utility executives and
environmentalists to develop an energy-saving program.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis by Schumer's staff, which incorporates data from
the National Weather Service, concludes that residents and
businesses have increased the consumption of electricity to run a
range of appliances besides furnaces and air conditioners, meaning
that spikes on demand are less closely associated with the weather
than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   It found, for example, that New York City residents used 11,231
megawatts of power on the day in June when the temperature reached
88 degrees and service was disrupted temporarily on the Upper East
Side of Manhattan, prompting angry complaints from Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and many residents. In contrast, it found that city
residents had used less power _ 10,551 megawatts _ on a summer day
in 1995 when the temperature soared to 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   On both days, as on many others in between, it said consumption
in the city came perilously close to the maximum that Consolidated
Edison can provide _11,650 megawatts.
</P>
</TEXT>
