<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-SOCIALWORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL WORKERS SAVOR A CITY OF RISKS AND REWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wis., N.J., Kan., Mass., Mo.)  By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was 3 p.m. one recent day at Columbia University,
and seven graduate students, who ranged in age from 25 to 58, sat
in a circle in Room 308 of McVicor Hall, home to the university's
School of Social Work.
</P>
<P>
   The instructor, Judith Marks, read from the students' reports
about their work with clients. But weeks of newspaper headlines,
and the presence of a reporter, later provoked a discussion of
social work and its rewards and perils.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Goldberg, a 25-year-old from Madison, Wis., had been
struck on the back of the head with a chunk of concrete by a man on
a Manhattan street in a seemingly random attack. Goldberg, who
plans to attend Columbia's social work school this fall, had
expressed concern for her assailant. She speculated that he had had
a troubled childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The students, who said they were upset by the randomness of the
attack, said they admired Goldberg's generosity of spirit. They
said it was consistent with a social worker's outlook on violence _
to always try to understand its roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society is into blaming individuals,'' said Kristen Miller,
27, one of the students. ``Violence is intergenerationally
transmitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who grew up in Morristown, N.J., and works with mentally
ill children in Newark, N.J., said she felt sad for Goldberg when
when she heard about the attack. But she thought the incident might
have been avoided if ``society provided the resources people
need.'' Specifically, she advocated more funding for the treatment
of the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   However awash New York City is in Wall Street bonuses and budget
surpluses, venture capital and disposable income, it remains for
some people one of the world's great social work laboratories _
full of poor, troubled people, children at risk and marriages
coming apart. And its magnetic pull brings people here from all
corners of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Kucera, who recently completed the social work
graduate program at Hunter College and is from Columbia, Mo., said,
``Moving to New York, I think I've compromised my safety, but I'm
much more concerned for the safety of the people I've worked with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose to move to New York because it has one of the largest
social service networks in the country,'' she said. ``I also chose
New York to practice because of the diversity of the people and the
complexity of the socio-political climate. Under Giuliani, social
services have been cut back. Nevertheless, I think even in these
difficult times, New York City is an exciting place to study and
practice social work.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Condon, a 26-year-old student at Columbia's School of
Social Work, said the attack on Goldberg had frightened her because
it was random. But Condon, who grew up in Pearl River in Rockland
County, said that she, like Goldberg, would probably look at the
environment the assailant came from and the problems he faced had
she been the victim. Social workers, she said, seek to find out why
things happen.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes the causes of violence, especially after
incidents like the attack on Goldberg or the stabbing death in 1999
of Amy Watkins, a student at Hunter College Graduate School of
Social Work, who had come to New York from Kansas. Watkins was
slain two blocks from her apartment in Prospect Heights, Brooklyn.
Her killer was never caught.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Parker, 32, who graduated from Hunter's school of social
work in May, came to New York from Methuen, Mass., 10 years ago. He
decided to study social work so he could help change society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck by the continuing disparity of income _ how
people were excluded from jobs, education, housing and
opportunities in general,'' he said. ``The system is working
against the poor as far as pulling them out of their economic
hardship.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who knew Watkins, helped to set up a scholarship in her
name at Hunter. Like Goldberg, she had the kind of idealism that
motivates most people in the social work field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy was a beautiful person with a vision of justice and social
equity,'' he said. ``A lot of people would think she was overly
compassionate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
