<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CITY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PAGEANTRY AND PROTEST GREET CONVENTIONEERS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Mummers in sequined costumes strummed banjos.
Demonstrators in dreadlocks pounded jun-juns and other African
drums. Party planners readied a potent vodka concoction called a
``Richard Nixon'' _ guaranteed to give you an 18 1/2-minute gap in
memory.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Brotherly Love _ hometown of the Liberty Bell and
Legionnaires Disease, birthplace of the Constitution and ``American
Bandstand'' _ welcomed thousands of Republican National
Conventioneers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With 45,000 people expected for the convention _ and another
20,000 or so coming for protests _ the world will be watching the
nation's fifth largest city for the coming week.
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders are hoping to showcase a vibrant, revitalized
community and reap financial benefits that will last long after the
GOP delegates leave. But under the watchful gaze of a ubiquitous
police presence, scores of dissident groups also plan to piggyback
on this media focus.
</P>
<P>
   The competing image machines were revved up as visitors streamed
in Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Center City _ the downtown district of shops and hotels and
offices _ was bedecked in red, white and blue. Music greeted
arrivals at the airport and train station. With corporate help, the
city hosted a party for reporters on Saturday night and readied
another gala for delegates the following evening.
</P>
<P>
   The citizenry is expected to turn out for that event, a giant
fireworks show and parade of lighted boats on the Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference, Mayor James F. Sweet predicted a payoff.
Despite the expense and exertion, Sweet said, he expects ``this
city is going to be highlighted in a very positive way to people
around the world in a way we couldn't possibly afford to pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   But TV crews also showed up Saturday for the first of dozens of
scheduled demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Five animal rights activists were arrested for planning to dump
more than a ton of manure at the First Union Center, the site of
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's largest rally attracted about 1,500 people in support
of universal health care.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few blocks from City Hall, African drums set the beat for
a protest against police brutality. The issue has smoldered here
since the 1980s, when then-Mayor Wilson Goode ordered the bombing
of a house in which members of the radical MOVE group had
barricaded themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Then this summer, Philadelphia TV news crews videotaped
Philadelphia police kicking and beating a carjacking suspect named
Thomas Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unfortunate for poor Thomas Jones, but fortunate for
our movement in that the world saw what goes on here,'' said Ella
Forbes, founder of Mothers Organized Against Police Terror.
``That's what we have lived with for many years, but it was just
captured on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Liberty Bell, 200 antigun protesters laid out
nearly 30,000 shoes to represent victims of gun violence, while
nearby a group supporting gun owners set up 1,000 American flags.
And at Independence Mall, 30 people in wheelchairs in a ``Rolling
for Justice'' demonstration for rights for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The largest scheduled protest is a Sunday parade combining many
of the causes _ which range from animal rights to anti-globalism.
Organizers said the parade will feature 30-foot inflatable cruise
missiles, giant puppets and Corpzilla _ a paper-mache,
international corporate monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing like it has ever hit Philadelphia before,'' said
Michael Morrill, an organizer of Unity2000, the umbrella
organization of the protest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the parties have begun.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Richard Nixon'' drink will be featured at a ``Shock the
Vote'' shindig at the Trocadero night club sponsored by Shift, a
non-profit group devoted to increasing voter participation.
</P>
<P>
   Each state delegation will get an individual welcoming reception
on Sunday, and Hank Williams Jr. will play at a concert honoring
elected Republican officials.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first national political convention in Philadelphia
since 1948, when both the Democrats and Republicans convened in the
city. However, the city has a long history of hosting political
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   The First Continental Congress convened here in 1774 and the
founding fathers gathered in 1787 to write the U.S. Constitution.
The first Republican convention was held here in 1856.
</P>
<P>
   For online information: www.unity2000.com and www.gophila.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
