<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA HOPES GOP HOOPLA WILL BOOST CIVIC EGO 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This city has struggled for years with a massive
civic inferiority complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come to Philadelphia and they have worse than low
expectations,'' moans city leader David Cohen. ``They have no
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Republican Party faithful pouring into town for
their political family reunion that starts Monday, Philadelphia
residents believe they have more at stake in hosting a successful
convention than any other city in recent memory. It's not just
reputation on the line, it's self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between politically vibrant Washington, D.C., and
commercial giant New York City, the locals always thought they
suffered by comparison. And when the city began sliding into the
same economic funk plaguing other rust belt cities in the last
decades of the 20th century, they just suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia had lost its manufacturing base and 10 percent of
its population by 1990. People and jobs fled to the suburbs, and
crime filled the gaps. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Former Mayor Ed Rendell gets the credit for stopping the
decline with large infusions of federal dollars and his
determination to lure hotels and entertainment downtown. People use
the word ``renaissance'' when they talk about Philadelphia now.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell decided after attending his own party's Democratic
convention in Chicago in 1996 that snaring one of the major
political conventions was the answer to his recovering city's
public relations woes. But local corporate and political leaders
thought the pursuit was a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked at me like I was stone-cold crazy,'' recalled
Rendell, shaking his head. When the GOP announced in November 1998
that Democrat-dominated Philadelphia was its choice for the 2000
convention, his city was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're different than Chicago, we're different than
New York, we're different than San Diego and Houston. All these
cities have established hospitality presences,'' said Cohen,
Rendell's former chief of staff and co-chairman of the local host
committee for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact for us is going to be completely different,'' Cohen
said. ``If you spend enough time here, you'll see the enthusiasm
for this convention. The Republicans are going to own this city.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In the 18 months since the GOP made its choice, Philadelphia
has scrubbed, primped, rebuilt and renovated everything from
building facades to subway stations. Workers in recent weeks have
hung red, white and blue bunting from every available ledge and
light standard and flowers sprout from hanging baskets, window
boxes and boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   The host committee has raised nearly $50 million from local
donors to help throw the party. Nearly 4,500 new hotel rooms have
been added in time for the convention, and more than 100 taxis have
been added to the traffic winding its way through Philadelphia's
narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
   The city has taken extra care to spruce up the attractions that
underscore Philadelphia's rich, patriotic history _ the Liberty
Bell, the house where Betsy Ross designed the first American flag
and Independence Hall, site of the signing of the Declaration of
Independence and the drafting of the U.S. Constitution. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Small armies of volunteers massed in the last week to clean up
the routes between the airport, downtown and the sports arena
housing the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Philadelphians, taxi driver Sidney Miller was worried
about whether a looming strike by municipal workers would leave
piles of garbage on the city curbs as an estimated 45,000
conventioneers and journalists filled those new hotel rooms. ``What
a mess that would be. They've got the city by a stranglehold,''
Miller fretted.
</P>
<P>
   The city reached a tentative agreement with the union last week,
averting the danger of an embarrassing strike. That moved the
threat of disruption by protesters to the top of the worry list for
many locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we've been dealt an excellent opportunity to create a new
image, a better image and a deserving image, because there is a lot
of great stuff going on here,'' said Republican talk show host Mike
Smerconish. ``And yet it seems like there are people who are
determined to screw it up.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 20,000 activists are expected in town over the week
to protest everything from the death penalty to police brutality _
the latter a particularly hot topic after television cameras
recently caught on videotape a phalanx of Philly cops beating a
suspected carjacker. That incident only served to remind people of
Philadelphia's reputation in the years under former police
commissioner and Mayor Frank Rizzo (now deceased) as a city where
the police frequently administered punishment at the time of
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thinks we're still at that stage,'' said Larry Frankel,
executive director of the American Civil Liberties Union in
Pennsylvania. ``The allegations of police misconduct are certainly
much lower now, and there's a better system of tracking the use of
force.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no real drama left in political conventions, Smerconish
said, since the presidential candidates are anointed in advance and
they've usually announced their running mates by convention time.
Expected GOP nominee George W. Bush announced Dick Cheney as his
running mate last week. So Smerconish worries that protests have
the possibility of becoming a dominant story from the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge spelled out the strategical
importance of his region in pitching Philadelphia to the Republican
convention site selection committee, former Mayor Rendell recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Draw a quadrant across the United States, from Wisconsin to
Minnesota, south to Maryland, north to New England _ we carried one
state there in '96,'' Ridge told the GOP officials. ``You've been
going to the South and the Southwest and California for all your
conventions _ time to get back into that quadrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge was right, said Rendell, who, &UR;  &LR; ironically, &UR;  &LR; has since been
tapped as chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ``And
throwing in the Liberty Bell and Independence Hall as props? Not so
bad either.''
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic consultant questions how much diversity spin the
GOP can pull from Philadelphia, since there's been little movement
from the city's significant African-American population away from
the Democratic Party. Bush has appeal among Democrat-leaning
Hispanics, the consultant said, but Hispanic voters are not a
significant presence in the region.
</P>
<P>
   And the president of Philadelphia's African-American Chamber of
Commerce questions why so few local black businesses have been
awarded convention business if the GOP is interested in broadening
its appeal to minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the GOP has been the party of commerce and
business,'' said Clay Hammond. ``It would have been a great
opportunity to position the candidate, saying this is the
tremendous outreach we did, these are the numbers of
African-American businesses we used.''
</P>
<P>
   But host committee co-chair Cohen said the RNC and host
committee reached out to minority business owners ``in an
unprecedented fashion,'' offering to aid minority businesses in
marketing themselves, and creating an online directory for
potential vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he is proud of the efforts the host committee made to
involve local minority-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I satisfied with the results? Absolutely not,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
