u p BC-KENTUCKY-HNS &LR;      07-29 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENTUCKY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CHALLENGES GORE TO SUPPORT MARRIAGE PENALTY RELIEF  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Republican George W. Bush challenged Vice
President Al Gore on Saturday to ``pick up the phone'' and urge
President Clinton to sign legislation passed by the Republican
Congress that would eliminate the so-called tax penalty paid by
married couples under the federal tax code.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Striking a populist tone on the second day of a five-day, five
state trip to the GOP convention in Philadelphia, Bush urged
Clinton to sign into law the GOP-sponsored legislation that cleared
the House and Senate in time to reach the president's desk before
the opening of the Republican nominating convention on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be penalizing marriage in the tax code,'' Bush
told more than 1,000 supporters spilling out of an aircraft hanger
into pouring rain at an airport rally in Owensboro, Ky. ``Mr.
President, you ought to sign that bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a jab at Gore, Bush noted his opponent's claims to have
been the ``most influential vice president in history'' and
declared: ``If that's the case, he ought to pick up the phone and
he ought to tell President Clinton, `You ought to sign the marriage
penalty relief bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the federal tax code ought to be revised to
``encourage marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-sponsored legislation would end a so-called ``penalty''
paid by married couples that file joint federal tax returns.
Currently, married couples filing jointly pay more taxes than they
would if they were not married and filed individual tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vows to veto the measure, contending it consumes too
much of the federal budget surplus and benefits the wealthy more
than the middle class. Last week, Clinton asserted that Republican
lawmakers have passed a series of ``reckless'' tax cuts that
threaten to ``drain away our hard-earned surplus and put us back in
the red.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush derided the Clinton-Gore administration's resistance to the
deep tax cuts that he proposes as a way to return a portion of the
blossoming federal budget surplus to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``believes a surplus is the government's money,'' Bush
said, eliciting boos from his partisan audience in Owensboro. ``We
believe the surplus is the people's money and after we set our
priorities, I want to share some of that surplus with the people
who pay the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky last voted for a Republican presidential candidate in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is not only going to hear the voices of the
people who are creating jobs, we're going to hear the people who
are struggling go get ahead in their jobs and knock down the toll
booth on the road to the middle class,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed to revise a federal tax code that he said imposes a
higher proportionate tax on a single mother raising two children on
$22,000 a year than on someone earning more than $200,000. ``That's
not right,'' Bush insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush later touted the GOP platform approved by state party
leaders in Philadelphia for final convention action on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he wanted to win the presidency ``not to hold the
job'' but to lead the nation in ``new directions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win this campaign because we have the best
ideas (and) we have the right platform,'' Bush declared. ``We've
got a philosophy that's conservative and a philosophy that's
compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters aboard his campaign plane that he was ``not
overconfident,'' adding that he had ``seen defeat first-hand'' and
had seen ``poll numbers crumble.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments followed Gallup poll commissioned by Time
magazine that showed Bush leading by 16 percentage points among
likely voters _ the widest lead Bush has enjoyed since he and Gore
captured their parties' presidential nominations in March.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is hitting Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky, West Virginia and
Ohio, arriving in Philadelphia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewarthearstdc.com )
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
