<SLUG> BC-CINCINNATI-REAL-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: MORE PEOPLE CALLING CINCINNATI'S DOWNTOWN HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Texas, Colo., Pa., Ga., N.C., Ore., Ky.)   By JOHN ECKBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Hofmeyer family bought the decrepit Biltmore apartment
building on West Fourth Street in downtown Cincinnati in 1990 and
two years later the Lombardi, a historic but condemned apartment
building on an adjacent lot, banks balked at loans to update the
units. Housing in the city's central business district was in a
downward spiral. Parking was scarce. There was no grocery, and few
young professionals were ready to live in a Midwestern downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Max and Angela Hofmeyer and their five sons, who
own a plumbing company, concluded that their out-of-pocket
investment in upgrading the two distressed buildings would pay off.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Hofmeyers, both 68, sold their house on two acres in
a suburban neighborhood on the west side of town, and at an age
when many Americans would be looking to retire to a beach community
became part of a Cincinnati back-to-the-city movement, living in
one of the buildings that they were refurbishing.
</P>
<P>
   They knew there would be challenges. After all, the Biltmore was
half-occupied and four of the 28 apartments had never been
completed after a previous attempt at renovation. The family was
confident, however, that the building could be returned to its
former glory. There were tall ceilings, white marble hallways,
exposed brick walls and distinctive windows in a building that at
one time had been a coveted address.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was risk, but we knew felt comfortable knowing that
after a lot of work we would have quality apartments, and quality
apartments will have renters,'' said their son Paul, who helped
update kitchens and bathrooms in both buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Because of investors like the Hofmeyers _ and heavy public
subsidies for other projects _ the population of the square-mile
Cincinnati Central Business District has reached levels not seen
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The population increase is similar to the trend back to downtown
that has been noted in other cities across the nation. Eugenie
Birch, who heads the department of city and regional planning at
the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia, has compared
housing trends in 40 American cities from 1990 to 1999 and found
that one in four have returned to 1970 population levels.
</P>
<P>
   In her 1999 study, ``Downtown Living: A Deeper Look,'' she
reported that Cincinnati had one of the more robust markets for
downtown housing in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   She estimated that 4,810 people lived downtown in 1999, up from
3,838 in 1990. Kathy Schwab, residential development adviser to
Downtown Cincinnati Inc., a nonprofit group, said that there were
about 2,100 housing units downtown, with 10 or so buildings
restored or converted, five more under construction and two
projects in development.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people were reflecting anecdotally _ that more people
were moving back downtown _ was really happening in some cities
like Cincinnati,'' Birch said. ``This is a fragile trend that has
happened for a lot of reasons. People want to walk to work. They
like an urban life with all its attachments: good restaurants,
theater and art museums.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are living in lofts, converted factories,'' she added.
``It's a lifestyle choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Birch initiated her study when she reviewed a 1998 report by the
Brookings Institution and Fannie Mae, the federally chartered
mortgage financing corporation, that showed many American cities
expected to see healthy increases in downtown housing. In that
report, however, Cincinnati was not in the top tier. Planners had
projected that only 3,500 people would be living in the central
business district by 2010, about the same number they thought were
living downtown in Columbus and Pittsburgh today. But that study of
26 cities did not have fixed central business district boundaries,
and planners had estimated downtown boundaries and populations.
</P>
<P>
   While Birch thought that the methodology of the report could be
sharpened, she agreed with the finding that there was a broad trend
of people moving back to downtown. In preparing her study, she
focused on the growth in the number of downtown households, and
restricted the geographical scope of the report to core blocks.
Instead of relying on rough estimates by local planners, she bought
data from Claritas, a company that specializes in demographic and
economic data. Cities with downtowns that posted significant gains,
according to her study, included Dallas, Denver, Colorado Springs,
Atlanta and Charlotte, N.C., and Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The Hofmeyers never regretted their move from suburbia to
downtown, though they have now returned to a suburb to be closer to
grandchildren. ``We had a rooftop deck with views of downtown and
the river,'' Hofmeyer said. ``But at the beginning friends told us
we were nuts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Hofmeyers' two buildings had waiting lists until earlier
this year, when some tenants fled because of inconveniences from
the construction of a new football stadium for the Cincinnati
Bengals about three blocks south. Seven vacancies resulted, all of
which have since been filled, although the waiting list is a thing
of the past, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Other buildings where young and single tenants live include a
former cigar warehouse called East Eighth Lofts, where all 45 units
were rented in 60 days last fall. Other apartments have gone into
the former Shillito Department Store.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Bonner, a professor of art at Northern Kentucky
University, moved into East Eighth Lofts last fall after spurning
``cookie-cutter'' complexes in nearby suburbs. The central location
means he spends less for gasoline and has a manageable commute to
the university, six miles south. Also, he said, he is not
contributing to urban sprawl, though the lack of a grocery downtown
remains an inconvenience. He pays $670 a month in rent, which does
not include utilities, and $120 a month for two parking spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet half the people in the building are lawyers, doctors or
professionals,'' Bonner said. ``I love it downtown: to walk out the
door and see an opening at the Contemporary Arts Center or go grab
something to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the challenges for developers has been competition from
other neighborhoods and the city's historically low housing costs,
said Ralph D. Bolton, the former head of Cincinnati downtown
development and now a principal at the architecture firm of
Brashear Bolton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were and are very good neighborhoods close to downtown
that were accessible and had relatively inexpensive housing stock
and apartments,'' he said. ``What has to happen for downtown
housing to be attractive is it must attract people from those
neighborhoods: offer some kind of vitality and value.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising rents and property values in recent years in nearby
neighborhoods like Clifton and Hyde Park that have long attracted
young professionals have also added to the attraction of downtown
housing. In the 1970s and 1980s, most housing downtown was aimed at
low-income residents. Today the mix includes more upper- and
middle-income residents, and as a result restaurants and clubs are
opening in long-vacant buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Apartments in the Biltmore and Lombardi bring $350 to $725 in
rent, but that does not include $75 a month for a parking slot.
</P>
<P>
   A few units go for more: the rent for a two-bedroom town house
with deck is $800 a month and approaches $900 when parking is
included. Although that may seem a bargain when compared with rents
in major cities like New York and Chicago, it is pricey by
Cincinnati standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Hofmeyers are in the market to buy another apartment
building downtown, but times have changed. A nearby shell carries a
$325,000 price tag _ far from the $10 that the Hofmeyers paid the
city for the Lombardi nearly a decade ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
