u a BC-NY-ARTISTS-RELOCATE-6     07-29 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTISTS-RELOCATE-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTS SEEKING NEW SPACES JOIN A NEIGHBORHOOD'S MIX 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just 100 yards from the corner of Bushwick Avenue and
McKibbin Street, inside a brightly lighted basement garment
factory, the buzzing of sewing machines rises and ebbs like
dentists' drills as a dozen women hunch over tables stitching
elastic waistbands into blue polyester pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   Three floors above, Rachel Bick works among half-clothed
seamstress dummies and drawings of conceptual outfits, creating
dresses that sell for hundreds of dollars more than the pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   The building at 255-265 McKibbin St., home to Bick and Quality
Knits, is in the midst of a transformation. For decades artists
have been moving eastward, out of the East Village and into
Williamsburg, in search of bigger spaces, lower rents and hipper
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Now the artists have reached farther still, renting former
manufacturing spaces around the fifth, sixth and seventh stops from
Manhattan on the L train. Most of the new arrivals call the area
East Williamsburg, but to longtime residents it is Bushwick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it because it's not as trendy as Bedford Avenue, which
is so hot you have people from Manhattan going out there for the
night,'' said Bick, who wore rose-colored sunglasses, a straw
cowboy hat, beige pants and a short purple top that revealed her
pierced navel. ``I like it better off the beaten path.''
</P>
<P>
   The artists colonizing the old industrial buildings on the
western end of Bushwick say they feel they are playing the role of
pioneers. Crime is down in the area, as it is citywide, but many
new residents have stories of break-ins and car thefts and have
held meetings recently to discuss a series of muggings.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Castagna lives a floor above the garment factory and
creates jewelry and wearable art from discarded dish mats, broken
computer parts, pieces of silver and anything else she can find _
including the scraps from the factory below. Since she moved in six
months ago she has been able to drag friends to her place for a
birthday party, but many acquaintances and relatives have been
resistant to visiting without a special occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My relatives who live in Staten Island are like: `Bushwick?
Why would you want to live out there?''' Castagna said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Williamsburg or the East Village, the fifth subway stop
has no cafes in which residents can gather, but the new arrivals
have organized a summer film festival and studio tours. And the
Hispanic grocery store at the corner of McKibbin Street and
Bushwick Avenue has become the place to pick up food, meet friends
and practice Spanish with the clerks.
</P>
<P>
   But as the neighborhood has changed, so has the store. Two weeks
ago Joshua Nathanson, a painter and recent graduate of the School
of Visual Arts, asked the shop to stock veggie burgers. Their
arrival delighted Nathanson, yet part of him worries about what he
has wrought. What if the veggie burgers force out the mango juice
or plantains? And what if the arrival of the artists forces out the
longtime residents?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to live in New York to do artwork, and live around
other artists, but I do wonder how it affects the people around
me,'' Nathanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the artists appear somewhat torn between their desire to
find fabulous space and the worry that they will gentrify the
neighborhood. And they are concerned that rather than helping
diversify the community, they may merely be establishing a separate
existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange block,'' Bick said as she stood at the window
of her loft, while a neighborhood cookout given by Hispanic
homeowners was barely visible below her. ``They have a block party
with merengue and we will have our party on the roof with techno.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, the artists around the fifth stop seem to be the only
ones worrying. Inside the Latino Supermarket, Octavio Olivo, a
manager, proudly shows off the Honey Bunches of Oats, Woodchuck
Draft Cider and American Spirit cigarettes. All of those items were
suggested by the loft dwellers but have become popular with Latino
customers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they came here we didn't know about this stuff,'' Olivo
said, his hand resting on the oat cereal. ``Now everyone is buying
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the block party below Bick's apartment, the residents said
they were enthusiastic about their new neighbors and the changes
they have brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten very multicultural,'' Nilsa Sievens said as she
stood by the grill. ``I have no complaints. The cops tend to drive
by more now.''
</P>
<P>
   Deeper into Bushwick, however, the prospects for peace between
the new arrivals and longtime residents may not be so good.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the block party, two stops away on the L train,
Andrea Champlin stared down at the black flakes of burned newsprint
fluttering from the edge of what had been her Sunday paper.
</P>
<P>
   Champlin has had plenty of newspapers stolen from apartment
porches. But this felt different. Staring at the burned paper
brought into focus the hard stares and catcalls she had endured on
walks between her loft and the subway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new frontier,'' she said. ``I don't know if I will
stay. I will have to see if the neighborhood changes, but I am
going to give it another year.''
</P>
<P>
   At the seventh stop, artists are hoping to attract a few more
pioneers. Last month someone broke into Eduardo Larrea's studio and
stole his VCR, fax machine and tools. An increase in loft dwellers
would make the streets feel more welcoming and add a few more
watchful eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But at the fifth stop, some people worry that there may already
be too many backpack-toting artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighborhood has changed a lot,'' said Franco Gotte, a
sculptor and one of Bick's neighbors. ``A few years ago we were the
only people getting off the train with backpacks. Now it's like
everyone has backpacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, some loft dwellers said, is that professionals who
have a tendency to follow artists are arriving. ``I saw a suit
getting off the train the other day,'' Ms Bick said to Gotte.
</P>
<P>
   Rents are starting to rise along McKibbin Street and some of the
artists who moved in during the last two years fear they may have
to move. Nathanson said that unlike artists who favored other
neighborhoods in past decades, the people at the fifth stop have
barely had a chance to settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people moved into SoHo they had 15 or 20 years when the
rents were stable, before they started going up and pushing out the
artists,'' Nathanson said. ``But nowadays as soon as the artists
move in, they are priced out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MEDICATION-LAWSUITS-9     07-29 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICATION-LAWSUITS-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS GEAR UP FOR SUITS OVER TWO MEDICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Within two days in March, one widely prescribed
medication was removed from the market and another's use was
severely restricted, after each was linked to scores of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of Rezulin, a diabetes drug, and the restrictions on
Propulsid, a medication for severe heartburn, were coincidental in
timing, but served as a double-barreled call to action for lawyers
who specialize in large-scale litigation involving products to
which illness or injury has been attributed.
</P>
<P>
   In newspapers and on the radio and the Internet, such lawyers
have been advertising their services to people claiming or fearing
harm from the drugs, and the first of what are expected to be many
lawsuits against the drugs' manufacturers have been filed in
federal and state courts across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this legal warfare is centered in New York City. Because
Rezulin's manufacturer has its headquarters in the New York area,
and New York law firms are among those recruiting clients for the
litigation, federal court officials have directed that all Rezulin
suits filed in federal courts anywhere in the country be
transferred to U.S. District Court in Manhattan for consolidated
and efficient handling _ a common practice with complex cases that
are related. Judge Kevin Thomas Duffy has been assigned to preside
over the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising for clients who may have been hurt by Rezulin or
Propulsid vividly illustrates how an aggressive segment of the
legal profession sets the stage for mass-tort actions, those in
which suits are brought on behalf of large groups of people who
suffer similar illnesses after using the same product. This segment
of the bar has long been the subject of bitter debate.
</P>
<P>
   Its critics, including business groups and members of Congress
and law school faculties, say such lawyers are legal buccaneers,
even vultures, who are driven by the prospect of millions of
dollars in fees to seek excessive punitive damages that inhibit
manufacturers and add to the cost of many products.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Burger, the former chief justice of the United States,
was especially riled by such lawyers' advertising for clients,
terming it an unseemly spectacle, and he dissented from rulings
that upheld the right of lawyers to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of mass-tort specialists, including many consumer
groups and others in Congress and academia, say those practitioners
level the playing field, making it possible for people hurt by
wealthy companies' harmful products to be justly compensated. They
also credit this combative arm of the bar with giving businesses a
necessary incentive to exercise care in putting products on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' ads, unless false or misleading, are ``very much in
the public interest'' because they permit people to ``learn their
rights as soon as possible,'' Monroe H. Freedman, a legal ethics
specialist at the Hofstra University Law School, said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the arguments, the mass-tort lawyers' machinery is
clattering away in relation to Rezulin and Propulsid, much as it
did in the past in spawning widespread litigation on behalf of
those who contended they were harmed by drugs and medical devices
like the anti-miscarriage drug DES; the diet-pill combination known
as fen-phen; and the Dalkon Shield, a women's contraceptive device.
</P>
<P>
   On March 21, the federal Food and Drug Administration announced
that Rezulin _ introduced in 1997 to treat type 2, or adult-onset,
diabetes _ would immediately be removed from the market at the
agency's request by its manufacturer, the Parke-Davis division of
Warner-Lambert Co. of Morris Plains, N.J. Warner-Lambert has since
merged with Pfizer Inc., the New York-based pharmaceutical giant.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA said in March that Rezulin, which was taken by nearly 2
million people, had been linked to 90 cases of liver failure,
resulting in 63 deaths and necessitating 10 liver transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the manufacturer of Propulsid, which the FDA
said had been associated with nearly 350 reports of heart rhythm
disturbances, including 80 fatal cases, announced that it would
withdraw the heartburn drug from pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Janssen Pharmaceutica of Titusville, N.J., said it would instead
distribute the drug free to a limited number of patients for whom
all other drugs had failed and who did not have heart problems or
take certain other drugs that made Propulsid potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 million prescriptions had been written for Propulsid
since it was put on the market in 1993 by Janssen, a subsidiary of
Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   A Pfizer spokesman, Bob Fauteux, said last week that the company
was ``aware of approximately 200 suits'' claiming injury from
Rezulin, some involving more than one plaintiff, that had been
filed in federal and state courts across the country. A Janssen
spokesman, Greg Panico, said he did not know the number of
Propulsid suits that had been filed but was sure that ``we do not
have hundreds.''
</P>
<P>
   The two companies say that the number of reported adverse
reactions to their drugs is small compared with the large number of
people who benefited from them.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers who have filed the suits, and those planning to
file, insist that the full picture is yet to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering that only one serious drug reaction out of 10'' is
reported to the FDA, said Robert Gordon, a partner in the Manhattan
firm of Weitz &AMP; Luxemberg, ``we see that as the tip of an
iceberg.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The firm specializes in mass-tort cases involving product
liability law. It has run advertisements asking ``Propulsid
victims'' to ``fully explore'' their legal rights by calling the
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public likes to see it as vultures,'' Gordon said of
lawyers' seeking clients who might have been affected by drugs that
were pulled from the market. ``But the lawyers come in to say, `How
about compensating the people who have been injured?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, the legal results are at odds with later
scientific findings. The manufacturers of silicone breast implants,
for instance, paid $7 billion in judgments or settlements to women
who said they were harmed by the devices. But a scientific study
last year found no persuasive evidence that the implants were
responsible for some of the most devastating ailments that the
plaintiffs attributed to them, such as lupus and rheumatoid
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Jay Bern, of the Manhattan firm of Napoli, Kaiser, Bern &AMP;
Associates, said that Warner-Lambert had ``failed to advise the
medical community as well as the individual potential users of the
dangers it knew were inherent in the use of Rezulin, such as
potentially fatal liver problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Fauteux said that Warner-Lambert ``appropriately warned of
Rezulin's risks,'' while Panico said the adverse reactions to
Propulsid occurred when the drug was not used in an ``appropriate
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   In its newspaper ad, headlined ``Rezulin Alert,'' Bern's firm,
which also has a history of mass-tort litigation, tells former
Rezulin users that they ``may be entitled to financial
compensation'' if they have liver troubles or symptoms like swollen
legs from a buildup of fluids, and it urges them to ``call us
immediately to learn about your legal rights.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Bern's clients, Bruce Dallow, began to experience leg
swelling about a month after he began taking Rezulin in May 1998.
Within several months ``his legs were like tree limbs,'' his wife,
Helen, recalled last week. Dallow, 59, of Ridgefield, Conn., is
awaiting a transplant because of severe damage to his liver that he
attributes to Rezulin. Bern filed a suit for Dallow in state
Supreme Court in Manhattan on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dallow said that while he had been contending with arthritis and
diabetes before using Rezulin, the drug caused weakness and fatigue
that left him unable to continue in his job as a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I was superman,'' he said of his pre-Rezulin
days, ``but I was hanging in there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
