<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES ON FORCE SAY POLICE WATCH THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an unusual alliance, the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association is joining the New York Civil Liberties Union and
groups representing black and Hispanic police officers to discuss
their concerns about the Police Department's possible monitoring of
the groups, which are often critical of the department.
</P>
<P>
   The groups are planning to hold a news conference Sunday to
release a letter they have written to Police Commissioner Howard
Safir about some of the department's activities in connection with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil Liberties Union has always been and continues to be
concerned about the possible surveillance of political activities,
and we will raise serious and substantial questions about it at the
press conference,'' said Norman Siegel, executive director of the
civil liberties group.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations that Siegel and the police union think have
come under scrutiny are 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who Care and
the Latino Officer's Association. The heads of the two
organizations, Lt. Eric Adams and Lt. Anthony Miranda,
respectively, will also attend the news conference, Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   This month, a senior commander in the department's Internal
Affairs Bureau, testifying in an unrelated civil lawsuit, revealed
that two inquiries had been conducted into 100 Blacks in Law
Enforcement and Adams, its president. While the official, Deputy
Chief Raymond King, said the investigations had been closed without
any finding of wrongdoing, the disclosure raised questions about
why they had been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the investigations, Adams was followed and his
telephone records obtained, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter to Safir praises him for his willingness to meet
Adams to discuss the investigations, but suggests that perhaps
other police officials, presumably without his knowledge, have been
monitoring the groups' activities. The letter, signed by Siegel,
Adams, Miranda and Greg Longworth, a PBA lawyer, cites the
department's consistent monitoring of press conferences held by the
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel would not comment Saturday on the contents of the letter,
saying he did not wish to discuss it before it was delivered to
Safir. A police spokesman said the department would have no comment
until Safir saw the letter.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance of the normally conservative police union and
Siegel, one of the city's most persistent and vocal critics of
department practices, comes as the union is locked in bitter
contract negotiations with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased that the PBA has agreed to appear at the
press conference,'' Siegel said, adding, ``We believe that their
involvement with the black and Latino groups sends a strong message
of unanimity on a fundamental question about possibly problematic
NYPD practices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
