<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NASHVILLE ON AUG. 8, GORE PLANS TO ANNOUNCE HIS NO. 2
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Tenn., Pa., Calif.)  By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRIGHTSVILLE BEACH, N.C. _ Vice President Al Gore plans to
announce his choice of a running mate on Tuesday, Aug. 8, campaign
aides said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The date, five days after the Republican convention in
Philadelphia and a week before the Democratic convention in Los
Angeles on Aug. 14, will kick off a three-week road show during
which Gore hopes to dominate the news and establish momentum for
the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat unusual for a presidential candidate to announce
in advance when he is going to announce his choice of a running
mate. But the Gore campaign hopes to set up a stark contrast with
what it perceives as the haphazard atmosphere that characterized
Gov. George W. Bush's selection of Dick Cheney. Gore's campaign
spokesman, Chris Lehane, described that atmosphere as
``carnival-like.''
</P>
<P>
   By setting a date for the announcement, Gore aides said they
hoped that they could eliminate some of the chaos leading to it,
and that voters would perceive Gore as making this important
decision in a mature, methodical manner _ and, by extension, that
they would perceive Bush as not ready to occupy the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is scheduled for Nashville, where Gore's
headquarters are. The new ticket will then almost certainly head to
the running mate's home state. From there the two will travel
through the battleground states, separating at some point. Gore is
not scheduled to arrive in Los Angeles until Aug. 16, two days
after the convention opens. Just before then, he will conduct a
kind of ``passing of the torch'' ceremony with President Clinton so
that Gore can enter Los Angeles as his own man.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gore said Saturday during a walk on the beach with
his family that he had still not settled on a running mate,
although he has given strong indications that he is close to a
decision. He told reporters earlier that there were fewer than 10
people on his list; the list is believed to be much smaller than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had made his choice, Gore said Saturday, ``Not yet,
we're just having a good time.'' Aides said he had been swimming
and working on a jigsaw puzzle as he and his family began a
weeklong vacation at the five-bedroom seaside home of Parker and
Becky Overton, the Greenville couple who own a sporting goods
business and have been longtime friends of the Gores.
</P>
<P>
   The home is on Figure Eight Island, a guarded, gated community
with no commercial development just north of Wrightsville Beach,
where outsiders are stopped at a small bridge. Other homeowners
include the actors Kim Basinger, Alec Baldwin and Andy Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters as he flew here that he was actively
``mulling'' his choice but would probably not reach a final
decision until after he returned to Washington on Thursday. The
``mulling'' process itself is meant to contrast with what Gore
aides characterize as a frantic scramble for Bush and an incomplete
vetting of Cheney that left him unprepared for an immediate assault
from Democrats on his voting record.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore team says that for the first time in the long
preconvention positioning, the Cheney selection has given it an
important assist in illustrating Bush's weaknesses and Gore's
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers, while conceding they are generally in the dark
as to whom he might pick, have given a couple of clues as to what
may be guiding his thinking over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   As they critique the Cheney choice, they focus on two things.
They say that Cheney is a ``retro'' candidate from the past and
that ``the visuals'' _ of an older white man with a history of
heart trouble _ hurt Bush. The suggestion is that Gore will pick
someone young and fresh and that the pictures of the two together
will immediately convey a positive sense of vigor and energy. Gore
is almost certainly guided by the instant lift his own selection
gave Bill Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the first thing people say to be positive and be
something you can build on,'' said one Gore strategist. ``That's
the problem Bush has been having _ they've been on the defensive
the whole week. You want the kickoff to be something powerful that
carries you for the first 48 to 72 hours. This issue stuff is
hurting Cheney. What's left is the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than go for a niche candidate who would help with a
specific state or a specific group of voters, Gore is believed to
be seeking someone who would reinforce his own strengths in much
the same way that he reinforced Clinton's. Both came from the
South, the same age group and the ideological center of the party,
and they proved that reinforcement rather than balance could be a
winning formula.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
