<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANGELICAL-CONVENTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AMSTERDAM, BILLY GRAHAM TORCH WILL PASS TO MANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (Eds: Inserts 2 new grafs, beginning ``Graham also abandoned
...'')  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ The Rev. Jack Ruimb, senior pastor of a
congregation in the western highlands of Papua New Guinea, has by
his own count founded 321 churches in that South Pacific nation
since 1978. When he visits villages to speak about Jesus, Ruimb
said, he sometimes shows movies of another evangelist preaching.
``I use most of Billy's films,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Billy, he meant the Rev. Billy Graham, whose organization,
the Billy Graham Evangelistic Association, has gathered Ruimb and
10,000 other evangelists from 190 countries in Amsterdam this
weekend for a nine-day conference billed as the largest such event
ever held.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam 2000, as the gathering is called, has turned a
rambling convention center on the city's southern edge into an
extraordinary crossroads of global evangelical Christianity. In the
space of a few minutes, a visitor can encounter the head of a
Protestant seminary in Pakistan, a Presbyterian pastor from Sudan
and a married couple of Salvation Army majors from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The makeup of the largely male group of participants reflects
the trend now marking global Christianity: the faith's shift toward
the Southern Hemisphere as the number of Christians expands rapidly
in Asia and Africa while remaining little changed or even declining
in northern countries. Lutherans in southern Africa, for example,
now outnumber those in North America.
</P>
<P>
   This trend accelerated sharply with the demise of colonialism
four decades ago. Churches, like governments, passed into local
hands, and the Scriptures were translated into native languages,
noted the Rev. Ian T. Douglas, associate professor of world mission
and global Christianity at Episcopal Divinity School in Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shift from being a church of the Western, industrialized
nations to being a church of Asia, Africa and the Pacific has
happened within the lifetime of most Christians,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   He called it as significant a development within Christianity as
the faith's earlier and much more gradual shift in its center of
gravity from the Mediterranean to northern Europe and North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans have come here partly to learn about what is
happening in the rest of the world. Samuel Bartholomew, 26, a
student at Dallas Theological Seminary in Texas, said he wanted to
gain ``a greater global awareness of how God's moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference is symbolic in a personal way, for Graham. In
material distributed beforehand, the event is being described as a
``passing of the torch'' from the 81-year-old evangelist to a new
generation of preachers. (However, Graham has given no indication
that he will retire, and indeed plans to preach in Jacksonville,
Fla., in November.)
</P>
<P>
   In an unexpected and poignant turn of events, Graham was forced
to cancel plans to speak at the opening session Saturday night. He
is staying in the United States on doctors' orders, after
undergoing recent surgery to relieve a buildup of fluid on the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Graham also abandoned plans to address the conference Saturday
night by satellite. Instead, his son conveyed the evangelist's
greetings and read a brief statement from him.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham association released a short statement explaining
that Graham had ``felt he lacked the energy and strength, following
a sleepless night, to deliver his opening remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   A close observer of the Graham organization, William Martin, a
professor of sociology at Rice University in Houston, said the
conference seemed a fitting place to speak of passing the torch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the true successor to Billy Graham is not going to
be any single person,'' said Martin, the author of a biography of
Billy Graham, ``A Prophet With Honor'' (Morrow, 1991). ``The
circumstances are not likely to permit it or encourage it. He sees
his own legacy not as one person, but as these tens of thousands of
evangelists preaching all over the world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Graham's absence has heightened the role here of his eldest son,
Franklin, who is first vice chairman of the Graham association and
his father's designated successor as that organization's head.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the younger Graham, 48, president of a
Christian relief organization called Samaritan's Purse, said his
father ``took a nose dive, healthwise,'' after he finished a public
preaching event in Nashville, Tenn., last month. ``It was a
dangerous situation,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Admitted to the Mayo Clinic, Billy Graham had two shunts
implanted to drain off the fluid and relieve the pressure on his
brain. His condition has improved markedly, and he is being treated
on an outpatient basis. He will watch the conference by satellite,
his son said.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Graham will be among the speakers here _ but not until
after he has flown for one day to Philadelphia to offer a prayer at
the Republican convention when it opens on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication of the global reach of the conference, its
proceedings will be simultaneously translated into 28 languages,
from Arabic to Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   In its 50 years, the Billy Graham Evangelistic Association has
built ties to churches and other Christian organizations throughout
the world. It relied on them, a spokesman said, to screen the
28,000 applicants who wanted to come to Amsterdam, selecting the
10,000 due to arrive here.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Southwell, an official of the association, said the
conference was intended particularly to bring in people under 45,
who were ``significantly involved'' in evangelism but rarely, if
ever, had attended a big religious conference.
</P>
<P>
   Two west African preachers who were among Friday's arrivals said
they hoped to learn more about carrying the Christian message into
their countries' communities.
</P>
<P>
   Appollos Nuhu Jabho, a Nigerian, serves as a missionary with
evangelical and Pentecostal churches in his own country, and said
he was seeking ``spiritual refreshment, spiritual revitalization.''
The Rev. Edem J. Anthony, said he came from Togo to learn new
evangelistic strategies. ``I am working with young people in the
schools,'' he said. ``We are getting to the rural villages.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Solomon Kendagor, a Kenyan, and his wife, Ruby, a
Canadian citizen born in Trinidad, illustrate the crosscultural
trends of modern Christianity. They work as missionaries in St.
Louis, training Americans to reach out to international students
studying in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students we work with, not all of them will become
Christians,'' Ruby Kendagor said, ``but they will go back to their
native countries and say: `Yes, Christianity is true. People showed
kindness to me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
