   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-GRID _ What's being offered on the Web by dot-com
companies covering the Republican National Convention. (Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-MONEY _ WASHINGTON _ As Republicans gather in Philadelphia,
there's a lot of wooing going on. The nation's biggest companies,
often with crucial issues before Congress, are pouring millions of
dollars into the Republican National Convention, and they'll do it
again in a couple of weeks when the Democrats meet in Los Angeles.
(Sherman, Cox News Service) MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-STRATEGY _ PHILADELPHIA _ Persuaded that the way to win in
November is to make nice in August, the Republicans have made a
top-level decision to curb their Democrat-bashing during their
upcoming four-day national convention. (Glass, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CHENEY _ CASPER, Wyo. _ The peak touches the sky more than a
half-mile above the Natrona County seat. The range is millions of
years old, squeezed like an accordion when the dinosaurs died, and
now it looms hard over the city and the river and the basins that
seep petroleum oil. (Robbins, Cox News Service) MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERNER-CHENEY _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ George W. Bush's
selection of a Westerner to be his running mate suggests greater
national involvement in parochial, Western issues, say political
observers. The presence of Dick Cheney, who spent 12 years in
Washington, D.C., as Wyoming's lone congressman, on the national
Republican ticket might mean ``some Western issues will get a
little more air time,'' said Pete Kolbenschlag, Western Slope
director for the Colorado Environmental Coalition. What happens
after that, though, depends on the speaker. (Harmon, Grand Junction
Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN-ISSUES _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Never underestimate the
importance of the West to presidential candidates on the stump,
especially when reaching out to voters outside the West. Protecting
wilderness, for instance, ``plays well in California,'' said
Michael Gizzi, a professor of political science at Mesa State
College, even if it might not win Colorado. That kind of
directional drilling for electoral votes _ sink a drill in the
red-rock side of flyover country and hope to strike gold in
California or New York _ is a staple of national campaigning. In
some cases this year, though, the direction gets reversed. (Harmon,
Grand Junction Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-YEARS _ PHILADELPHIA _ The George W. Bush presidential
campaign, which tried to navigate below the political radar screens
for months, maybe years, hit the TV screens with a wooden speech by
a governor not acclaimed as a great orator. ``Tomorrow,'' Bush said
in March 1999 at the Austin Convention Center, ``I will file papers
forming an exploratory committee so I can take the next step in
considering a campaign for president of the United States. This
will allow my friends to begin assessing the level of support for
my candidacy and to begin raising funds.'' Support turned out to be
good. Fund raising turned out even better. (Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ DAYTON _ George W. Bush and the rest of the Republicans
may hate Bill Clinton's presidency but they don't mind stealing
Clinton's good ideas. That's one reason why Bush begins traveling
through Ohio today as part of the ``Renewing America's Purpose
Tour,'' said political scientist Robert Adams. The tour, by plane
and bus, will get Bush to Philadelphia and the Republican National
Convention on Wednesday. (Dayton Daily News) MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
