<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
GOP CHAIRMAN SAYS PARTY DOES NOT DISCRIMINATE AGAINST GAYS &HT;    By SUSANNA McBEE
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Despite strong anti-gay language in the party's
platform, Republican National Chairman Jim Nicholson said here
Saturday that the GOP ``is steadfastly against discrimination of
any kind,'' including that directed at homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson was asked at a breakfast meeting with reporters how he
thought the party's 2,066 delegates would react to the appearance
of the openly gay daughter of presumptive vice presidential nominee
Dick Cheney at the convention Wednesday night when Cheney is
expected to deliver his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Cheney, 31, until recently was the Coors Brewing Company's
corporate relations manager for the gay community. She is now a
college business major in Colorado. Ray Sullivan, a spokesman for
the George W. Bush campaign, said, ``We expect her to attend.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said that if she attends the event with her female
partner, ``I think it would be just fine. I don't think it would be
a problem. This party is steadfastly against discrimination of any
kind against anybody regardless of their race, sex, creed or any
preferences that they choose to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The party chairman's words contrasted with the document approved
by the 107-member Republican Platform Committee, meeting across
town about the same time Saturday that he was speaking. It restored
language on gay rights that had been dropped in an initial draft.
The section ended up saying, ``We do not believe sexual preference
should be given special legal protection or standing in law.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee members also voiced support for the ``traditional
definition of marriage'' and denounced efforts by gay rights
advocates to ``force states to recognize other living arrangements
as marriages.''
</P>
<P>
   After heated debate the committee the committee approved a line
saying, ``We affirm that homosexuality is incompatible with
military service.''
</P>
<P>
   The language would require the armed forces to revert to their
former outright ban on gays in the military, the policy that
preceeded President Clinton's ``don't ask, don't tell, don't
pursue'' system, which permits gays to serve as long as they are
not openly homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's version puts the platform at variance with
Bush's views. The Texas governor ``believes the current military
policy is correct,'' Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said after the
committee's vote. ``There's always going to be some language that's
not 100 percent in sync with the governor. But the governor
believes `don't ask, don't tell' is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   During the debate Cheryl Williams, a platform committee member
from Oklahoma, said that troops ``are in very close proximity when
they are training'' and that gays in the military create
``mistrust.'' She added that the current policy has been ``very
destructive to the morale of our military.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Eleveld, a committee member from Michigan, replied, ``I
don't know what (a soldier's sexual orientation) has to do with
whether you can trust him when he's in the foxhole next to you. I
don't think we should rule out a large group of men and women who
prefer a different sexual lifestyle from service in our military.''
</P>
<P>
   Convention delegates will vote on the platform Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
