<HEADER>
A7094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-465&AMP;ADD     07-29 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ROARS INTO KENTUCKY TO WIN THE STATE'S VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Gov. George W. Bush swung through another
battleground state Saturday, proclaiming that the days of
Republican losses were over. ``We haven't won Kentucky lately,'' he
thundered, ``but that's going to change come November.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised to bring a new tone to Washington as he
criss-crossed Kentucky on the second day of his march to the
Republican National Convention. He drew large crowds despite
downpours and drizzle, with people lined up under umbrellas to
shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're sick of the politics of personal destruction,
there's a place for you in this campaign,'' Bush shouted to an
audience that crammed into an airport hangar in Owensboro and
spilled out onto the rain-drenched tarmac. ``If you want somebody
to unite the nation, there's a place for you in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   His words Saturday were not aimed as pointedly at President
Clinton as they were on Friday when he began his tour in Arkansas,
but he still ended every speech promising to uphold ``the honor and
the dignity'' of the presidency. He tried for soaring tones,
promising ``to lead Americans in new directions.''
</P>
<P>
   But off the campaign trail his vice presidential running mate
was not shy about taking on Clinton. In an interview taped for the
program Fox News Sunday, Dick Cheney said: ``I am generally one of
those people who thinks Bill Clinton has been an embarrassment to
the country. He is a tragic figure in a way, obviously very
bright.'' He said Clinton has ``an impressive set'' of political
skills but has ``fundamental flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign struck back promptly. ``They have been saying
for weeks that they would not engage in the politics of personal
destruction,'' said Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the vice
president, ``But right out of the box they've resorted to old-style
Republican politics.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bush made his way to the convention, gone were his usual
small panel discussions. All across Kentucky, he revved up the
kinds of rally crowds not seen since the height of the Republican
primaries. Balloons fell. American flags unfurled. Confetti
dropped. Rock music blared. And streamers were shot to the rafters.
The only thing that went wrong was the breakdown of a backup press
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere the crowds were large. As many as 5,000 people
chanted his name in a sports arena in Joplin, Mo., on Friday night.
In Owensboro, people stood under umbrellas in heavy rain to shake
his hand. And outside the Louisville Slugger Museum, where an
oversized baseball bat towers over the building, hundreds more
waited in the drizzle for an outdoor rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased by the energy level,'' Bush told reporters on his
campaign plane. He said the audiences were ``like the crowd you'd
expect on the last days of the campaign.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the Republican convention opens on Monday, congressional
leaders will be relegated to less desirable time spots and some of
the focus will be on nonpoliticians whom Bush described as ``people
who are reinforcing our message.''
</P>
<P>
   The perils of that approach were on display Saturday when Chris
Payne, an employee of a grain company, dressed in his work clothes,
kept losing his lines as he was introducing Bush. Several times he
stopped in midsentence and had to pull a written speech from his
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry. I'm not a public speaker,'' he said. He then read
of Bush, `He trusts you and me to make the best decisions,'' which
was supposed to be a plug for Bush's plan to divert some of the
Social Security payroll tax to individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   And he took pains to assure older people that Bush's Social
Security plan would not affect them but only younger workers. ``I
want the elderly here in this audience to hear me loud and clear,''
he said. ``Don't be fooled by that kind of politics where they're
going to get on your TV screen and try to scare you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush,'' he said, ``will keep the promise to the
elderly in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also fired up audiences with talk of tax cuts, though he
did not explicitly mention his plan to cut taxes by $1.3 trillion
across a decade. ``You see I happen to think the surplus means
government has more money than it needs,'' he said, to cheers. ``I
happen to know that one of the reasons we have a surplus is that
the taxes on the people that are working hard are the highest
they've been since World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference in this campaign,'' he roared. ``My
opponent thinks the surplus is the government's money. We know the
surplus is the people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   A small crowd of protesters opposed to the death penalty read
out the names of people executed in Texas and chanted, ``Killed by
Bush.'' But they were far outnumbered by Bush supporters. Bush
shouted louder into the microphones, and the sound system mostly
drowned the demonstrators out.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he arrives at the convention Wednesday morning, Bush
will have passed through three other states that voted for Clinton
in the last two elections _ Ohio, West Virginia and Pennsylvania.
And he pledged Saturday that not only he but Cheney would appear in
swing states as the fall campaign begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times the vice presidential candidate, we'll say OK,
head out to solidify the base,'' he said. ``But our intention is
that both of us will be focusing on swing states. I may be there
one week and he'll be there the next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
