<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMERS CONTRIBUTE IN A HURRY FOR THE METS
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would be hard for even the most pessimistic New
York Mets fan to find anything wrong with Saturday's game. The Mets
played brilliant defense, got hits when they needed them and had
solid pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza hit a mammoth homer. Mike Bordick homered on the
first pitch he saw as a Met. Rick White, the newest addition to the
bullpen, was the winning pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-3 victory over the St. Louis Cardinals will not be a late
addition to the ``10 Greatest Moments in Mets History'' promotion
Sunday, but it was satisfying. The Mets won their fifth game in a
row, and Bordick and White, acquired Friday from Baltimore and
Tampa Bay, respectively, played a part.
</P>
<P>
   White pitched the eighth inning with the score tied, 3-3. He
issued two walks, and with two outs faced Cardinals pinch-hitter
Shawon Dunston, a trading-deadline acquisition by the Mets last
season. White struck him out, then watched as his new teammates
mounted a winning rally in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura, who came off the disabled list after missing two
weeks with a bruised rotator cuff, drew his third walk of the game
to lead off. Bordick singled with one out, and another walk by Mike
James _ the Cardinals' 10th of the day _ loaded the bases for
pinch-hitter Lenny Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who has returned on the bench with Ventura back, dropped
a single into right field, scoring Ventura and giving the Mets a
4-3 lead. Armando Benitez worked a 1-2-3 ninth for his 25th save,
striking out Jim Edmonds on a 97 mph fastball to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest cheer of the game was for Bordick, the Mets' new
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've heard people say is you've got to watch this
guy for a while,'' Bordick said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   It took Mets fans one pitch to recognize Bordick in a big way.
He pounded a chest-high fastball from Andy Benes over the
left-field fence to lead off the third. It was Bordick's 17th homer
of the year, extending his career high and tying the score, 1-1.
One pitch into his Mets career, and Bordick had received a standing
ovation at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets kept at Benes, whom they battered for 11 hits and six
runs in five innings in May. He walked three of the next five
hitters, bringing up Piazza with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza pulled a single to left, scoring Jay Payton and giving
the Mets a 2-1 lead. The hit improved Piazza's career average with
the bases loaded to .400. In 90 at-bats in that situation, he has
12 homers and 101 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, whose 14 career grand slams put him in a first-place
tie with Cincinnati's Ken Griffey Jr. among active players, came up
next. But Ventura, who walked in his first at-bat off the disabled
list, grounded to first to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did not have the lead for long. After Edgar Renteria
singled to open the fourth, Edmonds smacked an opposite-field home
run, his 30th homer of the year, to put the Cardinals ahead, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   That lead stood until the sixth inning, when Piazza came up
again. Piazza had gone eight games without a home run, matching his
longest drought of the season. His drive in the sixth traveled so
far, one run seemed insufficient to account for it. Piazza turned
on a Benes pitch and launched it toward a children's playground
behind the left-field bullpen. It bounced over the bullpen's back
fence and onto the top of a party tent, 455 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning offensive display, and two batters later, the
50,726 fans at Shea Stadium witnessed stunning defense. Todd Zeile
crushed a ball to deep center field, sending Edmonds sprinting
back. Tracking the ball all the way over his left shoulder, Edmonds
extended his glove just far enough to snare the ball, toppling to
the ground as he caught it.
</P>
<P>
   The catch was similar to one Edmonds made for Anaheim three
years ago, which became a staple of highlight shows and helped earn
him the recognition he needed to win a Gold Glove. Edmonds plays
for the Cardinals, but the Mets fans had to stand and cheer this
catch, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   They were happier cheering a great defensive play by their own
center fielder one inning later. Dennis Cook put himself in a
bases-loaded, one-out jam in the seventh by walking two and
allowing a double. Ray Lankford flied to Jay Payton in center, and
pitcher Rick Ankiel _ who was pinch-running _ broke for home.
</P>
<P>
   Payton fired the ball in and caught Ankiel easily. Cook, backing
up the plate, pumped his arm excitedly and did not leave the field
until he greeted Payton.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
