<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-SCRIMMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE SHINES IN GIANTS SCRIMMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was the best of both worlds for coach Jim
Fassel during the New York Giants' annual intrasquad scrimmage
Saturday. In the opening moments of the 41-play scrimmage, the
first-string defense dominated the second-string offense.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Giants' first offensive unit got on the field
several plays later, quarterback Kerry Collins looked sharp,
completing 4 of 5 passes for 87 yards, including a 60-yard
touchdown to Amani Toomer. Meanwhile, the rookies Ron Dayne and Ron
Dixon displayed no stage fright as each scored a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best news was that the Giants' reconfigured
offensive line provided good protection for Collins and opened
holes for Dayne and Tiki Barber, who led all rushers with 24 yards
on three explosive carries up the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive starters were going against the second-string
defense, which is especially inexperienced on the line, but the new
and improved offense the Giants have promised did indeed look new
and improved. It was just a scrimmage, but three years ago in this
scrimmage, the defense outscored the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne, who gained 17 yards on four carries, showed some of the
skills that made him attractive to the Giants. Although he was
stopped for a 1-yard loss on his first carry, Dayne, the team's top
draft pick out of Wisconsin, ran for 5 yards on his next carry and
then ran for 12 yards _ breaking through three arm tackles as he
dashed around the left end.
</P>
<P>
   Later, on third down at the 1-yard line, Dayne took a handoff
from Collins, paused behind the pile at the line of scrimmage, then
bulled easily into the end zone over right guard. The wherewithal
to wait and see a developing hole impressed Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play was actually called to the left,'' Fassel said. ``But
Ron knows how to press a hole and make the cut. That showed a lot
of instinctive patience, and his patience is one of his best
attributes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon caught a 25-yard touchdown pass from Mike Cherry, the
third-string quarterback, bursting alone into the end zone on an
out-and-up route. Dixon, a third-round draft pick from Lambuth
University, dropped the first pass Cherry threw to him, but later
caught a 17-yard pass over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Ike Hilliard also had two receptions for 24 yards and Joe
Jurevicius caught two passes for 11 yards. Joe Montgomery carried
the ball five times for 16 yards. Defensively, linebackers Pete
Monty and Ryan Phillips were credited with sacks, as was defensive
tackle Frank Ferrara.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said the Giants sustained no serious injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
