u p BC-CVN-GOP-EDUCATION-HNS     07-29 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BUSH HAS HIS WAY ON EDUCATION IN GOP PLATFORM
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DAN FREEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - Texas Gov. George W. Bush's convention aides on
Saturday put down a brief conservative Republican rebellion aimed
at scuttling his more moderate education policy.
</P>
<P>
   In several voice votes, the 107-member Republican platform
committee restored Bush's ideas on raising academic standards,
realigning the Head Start program, and providing vouchers for
children in failing public schools. The committee, which wrapped up
business Saturday just 48 hours
</P>
<P>
   before the Republican national convention's opening day, also
turned back a conservative bid to restore an old GOP plank to
abolish the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   That directive was a major element of the party's conservative
agenda under President Reagan in the 1980s. Since then it has been
the most visible dimension of the conservatives' bid to remove the
federal govnment from oversight of public education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has pledged to make education a cornerstone of his campaign
as a ``compassionate conservative.'' On the campaign trail, he has
cited among his achievements as governor boosts in teachers'
salaries and in standardized test scores of minority students.
</P>
<P>
   So when the platform education subcommittee voted Friday to
delete a seven-point outline of Bush's policy, the presumptive GOP
candidate's Philadelphia ground forces swung into action. The
campaign's ``whip operation,'' modeled on the Capitol Hill system
for rounding up party-line votes, succeeded in coralling loyal
platform committee members, and they drafted substitute language.
From the campaign trail, Bush had given his nod to move in,
according to Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   The new five-point outline put more emphasis on local control of
schools in order to meet conservative objections to Bush's view
that Washington does have a role to play in education.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., a Bush ally and co-chair of the
platform committee, argued that the governor's proposals ``are not
new federal programs, federal bureaucracy, but principles of
leadership in education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We send delegations to Texas to see how they do it in Texas,''
said another ally, platform committee member JoAnn Davidson from
Ohio. ``Why would we not want to speak to the principles of
Governor Bush in this platform?''
</P>
<P>
   Platform members who succeeded in stripping out the Bush policy
Friday were muted in their effort keep it out Saturday. Bush ``is
very aware the Department of Education is a stumbling block,'' said
Cheryl Williams, a delegate from Oklahoma. However, the Bush policy
''`renews the feel that it's the federal government that's
controlling (education),`` she charged.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who describes herself as a conservative ``mom'' from
Edmond, a suburb of Oklahoma City, spearheaded the effort to
reinstate the language on abolishing the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The abolition call was in the 1996 platform but was deleted from
the draft of the this year's platform in accordance with Bush's
view that Washington should have a role in maintaining education
standards and offering education alternatives to parents in
academically troubled schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has made tremendous strides despite the
Department of Education,'' Williams said. ``Can you imagine what he
could have done had the federal government not been involved?''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued that Republicans have suffered from the public
perception that in calling for abolition of the Department of
Education, the party is anti-child and anti-education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the perception is fact or whatever, that's the
case,''' said Rep. Sue Myrick, R-N.C., also a committee co-chair
along with Frist.
</P>
<P>
   After her amendment was defeated, Williams said she was
```bothered'' by the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ```I'm having trouble reconciling his work as a sitting governor
with his stand on expanding the Department of Education,''' she
said. ``I don't know how to reconcile it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she said she would continue to support Bush
enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   The full convention will vote on the platform Monday night. $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
