</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-ELECTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELANS VOTE TODAY ON THEIR FUTURE, NATIONAL AND LOCAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS _ In the lingo of Venezuela's residents and its media,
Sunday's vote isn't just big, it's a ``mega-election.''
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 candidates are vying for 6,000 public offices. The
posts include the presidency, seats in the National Assembly,
governorships, mayoralties, and memberships in several lesser-known
local and national councils.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not the last election either. There will be another one
next month for other municipal offices.
</P>
<P>
   While there seems to be little mystery over who will win the
nation's top post (the fiery incumbent, Hugo Chavez, is expected to
win easily over his closest rival, former military comrade
Francisco Arias) and little interest in the smaller offices, much
of the drama of Sunday's vote will focus on the makeup of the
Assembly, or congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the world knows who's going to be president, but
what we don't know yet is whether he'll have a real Legislature to
keep him in check,'' Herman Escara, a 48-year-old congressional
candidate in Carabobo state, said Saturday. ``Hopefully the people
will see the need to have another power to balance a strong
executive.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Venezuela's public offices are up for election because of
a constitution adopted late last year. It is part of an overhaul of
the political establishment pushed by Chavez, the former coup
leader and paratrooper, who himself was elected less than two years
ago on a pledge to destroy the old, corrupt two-party system.
</P>
<P>
   Those parties barely exist today. Most of the congressional
candidates represent one of the many smaller factions that have
sprouted since Chavez's victory in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new parties and their candidates, riding on the
president's still-strong popularity, support Chavez. Others don't,
because they fear he sounds and acts too authoritarian. And some
candidates, like Escara, prefer to remain independent in a country
still in the midst of political transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main message is that we need to keep democracy and we need
a pluralistic assembly to keep political equilibrium in this
country,'' said Escara, a former senator.
</P>
<P>
   To gain a veto-proof majority, Chavez's supporters will have to
win 112 of the Assembly's 166 seats, an achievement that might have
seemed a lock just a few months ago, but now appears less likely,
according to political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venezuelan voters are not as quick to buy into Chavez's
revolution today as they were a year ago,'' said Enrique Urretzia,
a political consultant. ``But even with a simple majority of, say,
51 percent, Chavez will have a lot of power for a president.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's elections are the sixth in less than two years for one
of Latin America's longest-running democracies, making Venezuela's
12 million voters some of the wisest when it comes to recognizing
political tricks, and among the most weary of casting ballots,
especially in a country which is now sandwiched between a stagnant
economy and rising levels of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in democracy, but I'd much rather see someone,
anyone, turn this country around,'' said Gladys Carrillo, 32, who
was selling plastic sunglasses at a weekend street fair Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers are concerned that the magnitude and complicated
nature of the elections may prove difficult to manage. The vote,
originally scheduled for May 28, was postponed at the last minute
because of several irregularities, including computer software
problems and a delay in delivering voting materials to local
precincts.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Organization of American States and the Carter
Center, which sent the two largest teams of foreign election
monitors, said the problems appear to have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Although a national simulation of the electronic vote-counting
system was not conducted in Venezuela, as it was before disputed
elections in Peru two months ago, officials will conduct an audit
of the system Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is concern because this is such a large and complex
system,'' Ruben Perina, chief of the OAS mission here, said
Saturday. ``We will start questioning when we see irregularities or
deficiencies in the process. But so far, none of the political
parties appears to be complaining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1935EDT &QL; 
