u i BC-HONGKONG-DISCONTENT-B     07-29 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-DISCONTENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG POLLS SHOW GROWING DISCONTENT WITH GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Discontent with the Hong Kong government has risen
to an all-time high since the former British colony's return to
Chinese rule, according to the latest bimonthly official survey.
</P>
<P>
   Only one in five people is happy with the government, while six
in 10 are dissatisfied or very dissatisfied, a dramatic slump since
the last official survey in May. Forty-three percent said they were
not confident China's capitalist enclave would continue to be
prosperous and stable, a 10-point jump since May.
</P>
<P>
   The results reflect growing resentment of a local government
widely viewed as ineffective, unrepresentative, and unresponsive.
Residents, who will go to the polls in six weeks, recently have
protested over property prices, wage cuts, and civil service
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In the balloting, voters will be able to elect nearly half of
their Legislative Council directly, but will not be given the
chance to unseat their increasingly unpopular chief executive, Tung
Chee-hwa, picked by a Beijing-selected committee.
</P>
<P>
   Tung, a former shipping tycoon, was chosen to lead Hong Kong for
five years after its return to Chinese sovereignty in July 1997. He
came to office on a wave of patriotic optimism over Hong Kong's
return to Chinese rule and enthusiasm over a breakneck economy, but
his governing style has alienated a majority of the public and a
wide array of legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Tung's administration has been dogged by scandals over faulty
construction in public housing, a fiasco that forced out his
Harvard-educated housing chief, and by perceived attempts to quash
independent surveys that showed rising discontent.
</P>
<P>
   An array of surveys have shown that while Hong Kong people are
disillusioned with their local government, they are generally
satisfied with China and its apparent hands-off policy. Beijing's
Communist leadership promised Hong Kong virtual autonomy for 50
years following its return to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``People appreciate that Beijing has left its hands off Hong
Kong, but people blame Tung for looking to Beijing for advice or
consulting them. He doesn't show his own leadership, and that makes
people feel they can't trust the government,'' said Albert Cheng,
who hosts a popular radio talk show, ``Teacup in a Tempest.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng said his callers complain about joblessness, cuts in
take-home pay, and the perception that a few tycoons are ``looting
Hong Kong'' _ and that Tung is helping them do so by favoring
captains of industry and keeping property prices high for real
estate developers.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's representatives in Hong Kong rallied to defend Tung,
with Saturday's official China Daily saying that Tung ``deserves
full credit for the achievements . . . during the past three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Friday seminar on economic development in China, Henry Fok
Ying-tung, Beijing's top adviser on Hong Kong, said those who
dislike Tung ``are a minority, but Mr. Tung represents the
government, and he was appointed by the central government, so this
cannot be ruined by a few people who chant `Dump Tung' slogans.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael DeGolyer, director of the Hong Kong Transition Project,
a long-term study of Hong Kong, said Chinese officials ``seem
convinced there's a conspiracy of pollsters to dump Tung, as though
the messengers who carry the death notice are the ones who
committed the murder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the intuitive thinking of an authoritarian regime,''
DeGolyer complained. ``A democratic regime . . . would figure out
how to improve performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The new government survey showed people were most upset about
labor issues, with unemployment at 5 percent and wages dropping.
The next most cited concerns were a perceived stagnant economy and
housing problems. Among people dissatisfied with the government, 40
percent accused the administration of inefficiency. Forty percent
of all respondents said the government was indifferent to public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong people are increasingly dissatisfied because they
feel Hong Kong could do better,'' DeGolyer said. ``People no longer
want a patriarchal system with a captain of a ship who says, `You
go where I tell you.' But we have a ship captain for a chief
executive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
