<DOCNO> NYT20000729.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN0730-COX     07-29 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain navigates Bush's route
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Right off, things were different. No coffee or
doughnuts, and precious few memorable one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain gassed up his campaign bus for one more ride
Saturday from Washington to the Republican National Convention. But
in place of the wise-cracking maverick was a politician who was
trying awfully hard to be the loyal soldier.
</P>
<P>
   He mostly succeeded, telling reporters that George W. Bush is
running a centrist campaign that he supports, praising his onetime
rival for choosing Dick Cheney and tamping down talk of his future
in presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 2004, I fully expect to campaign for the re-election of
President Bush,'' McCain said to some of the 72 reporters who
joined a four-bus caravan to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he preferred to think of the ride as a ``trip down
memory lane,'' recalling countless hours aboard the bus in New
Hampshire and later in South Carolina, California, New York and
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped in Blue Bell, Pa., to campaign for Stewart Greenleaf,
a Republican congressional candidate, at a town hall meeting
attended by 200 people in a hot gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain acknowledged, and said he regretted, that the large
entourage and his busy schedule during the convention might have
created the impression that he remains interested in pursuing the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will have a prime-time speaking role Tuesday night, and
he said he would devote his speech to convincing independents and
his supporters to vote for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Today, McCain will address the Shadow Convention, an alternative
gathering that will highlight the need for campaign finance reform,
the growing gap between rich and poor and problems in the war on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of the presidency, while he said several times that
he was reluctant to speculate, McCain, 63, said it was most
unlikely that he would run again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be older. That's a factor,'' he said. ``The second
thing you have to figure is could we catch the lightning in a
bottle again? Could the circumstances that prevailed this last time
happen again?''
</P>
<P>
   About the only time McCain flashed a bit of the pique that was a
staple of his surprising, but ultimately failed campaign was when a
reporter asked if he had received permission from the Bush campaign
to stage the bus trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I checked, I'm a U.S. senator elected by the
people of Arizona,'' he said. Still, he was eager to show himself a
good sport after a sometimes ugly campaign with Bush. McCain's 250
delegates will be urged to support Bush and to accept defeat
graciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be a sore loser. Americans do not admire or
appreciate a sore loser,'' McCain said. ``So we just move forward.
Try to make the very best of it. I think I'm step eight of a
12-step presidential recovery program.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is scheduled to campaign with Bush in the West for three
days during the week following the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush and his wife, Laura, will spend the night at the
McCains' vacation home near Sedona, Ariz. McCain said he has been
asked to set aside another 10 days to campaign with Bush between
now and the election. Most of his energy will go to helping elect
congressional candidates who have been clamoring to have McCain
appear with them.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his campaign's tradition, the buses departed
late from an Arlington, Va., hotel and arrived an hour late in Blue
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's wife, Cindy, was aboard, exchanging hugs and kisses
with several reporters who were regulars on the bus. She also toted
a video camera on behalf of ABC's Good Morning America.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta McCain, the senator's 88-year-old, globe-trotting mother
also rode along, admonishing her son at one point to step aside so
people could move past him. ``I raised my children with no
manners,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several media heavyweights, including George Stephanopoulos of
ABC News, showed up. Unlike most of his media colleagues,
Stephanopoulos climbed into a chauffeur-driven black Cadillac when
he finished his leg of the trip in McCain's bus.
</P>
<P>
   The senator plans to leave Philadelphia on Wednesday, but to
return Thursday to listen to Bush's acceptance speech that evening.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned that he has yet to be asked to join Bush on stage
at the convention's end. The joint appearance of the victor and the
vanquished in a show of unity is a tradition at political
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he'd be pleased to raise his hand with Bush's, then
recalled the end of the 1980 Democratic convention, when President
Carter essentially chased Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.) around the
stage in search of a picture of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be fun if I did like Kennedy did to Carter?''
McCain said mischievously. ``Kennedy was a lot quicker in those
days.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
