<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0730-COX     07-29 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Reform Party members target Buchanan
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaders of the Reform Party aimed to take a step toward removing
Pat Buchanan's name from the party's presidential ballot Saturday.
Seven of the party's 10 executive committee members met at a Dallas
hotel to vote on whether Buchanan could continue as a candidate
after accusations of fraud in his campaign, said Michael Farris,
the party's nominating committee chair. Buchanan spokesman, Brian
Doherty, dismissed the efforts as ``outrageous.'' The 164-member
national committee will review the executive committee's decision
when it meets Aug. 8 in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH WIDENS LEAD OVER GORE, POLL SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George W. Bush has widened his lead over
Democrat Al Gore to 16 percentage points, a CNN-Time poll released
Friday shows. Bush and running mate Dick Cheney led Vice President
Gore, 52 percent to 36 percent. The Green Party's Ralph Nader got 5
percent, and 4 percent for the Reform Party's Buchanan. The poll of
684 likely voters shows Bush's lead increasing by 10 percentage
points since mid-June, when he led 48 percent to 42 percent. The
survey has a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS TO RELEASE NEGATIVE ADS
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee plans to air its first
negative Bush ad this week during the GOP convention, spending
about $3.5 million in 17 states, Democratic Party sources said
Saturday. The ads are designed to slow Bush's steady climb in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   NADER CALLS GOP SCENE A `CARNIVAL'
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader dismissed the Republican convention as a ``political
carnival'' Saturday and denounced the two major parties for
accepting millions in corporate funds for the conventions. Speaking
five miles from the where the GOP convention opens in Philadelphia
on Monday, Nader criticized the parties for accepting $13.5 million
in federal funds, plus cash and in-kind contributions from private
entities. ``They pocket the taxpayers' money and sell the
conventions to special interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BIG DOLLAR CONVENTION DONORS
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million donor list for both conventions includes
Microsoft Corp., which is giving $100,000 in cash and $900,000 in
software and services to each convention. The company is one of
major contributors facing high-stakes issues involving the federal
government. Others include:
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel Service is giving about $1 million in cash and
services to each convention.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace and defense giant Lockheed Martin Corp., is giving
$100,000 to each convention.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, which is on both million-dollar lists, has
loaned a fleet of 400 cars to each convention as part of a
tradition that goes back to the 1950s. The vehicles include: 100
Buick LeSabres, 20 minivans, six Chevy Suburbans, 48 Cadillac
Sevilles and 10 Cadillac DeVilles.
</P>
<P>
   GORE COURTS HISPANIC VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Courting Hispanic voters, Gore challenged Bush to join him in
backing a Democratic proposal to expand immigration rights for
hundreds of thousands of Central Americans. Gore is pushing
legislation that would broaden the rights of about 500,000 Central
Americans and longtime illegal aliens seeking to obtain
citizenship, a hot issue among Hispanics. Currently, people fleeing
Cuba and Nicaragua can obtain citizenship; the new measure in
Congress would expand the list to include Salvadorans, Guatemalans,
Hondurans and Haitians. ``I call upon George W. Bush to make clear
his stance on this issue and join me in challenging Congress to
pass this essential legislation,'' Gore said Friday. Bush ``does
not support a complete amnesty at this time,'' spokesman Scott
McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE AMPUTEE TO GIVE GOP SPEECH
</P>
<P>
   Triple amputee and Vietnam veteran David Wenzel will share his
vision _ of a country where people with disabilities can have
access to homes and jobs _ when he addresses the Republican
National Convention on Thursday. A former mayor of Scranton, Pa.,
Wezel, 55, has been chosen to second the presidential nomination of
Bush. ``We are not looking for a handout. We want to give people
the opportunity to improve themselves,'' said Wenzel. If elected,
Bush has promised to ask Congress for $1 billion over five years to
help aid people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON DISSES `FRAT' BOY BUSH
</P>
<P>
   At a Democratic fund-raiser Friday for Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy
in Barrington, R.I., President Clinton mocked Gov. George W. Bush
for his gee-whiz attitude toward the presidency. ``I've been
governor of Texas. My daddy was president. I own a baseball team.
They like me down there,'' Clinton said, imitating Bush.
``Everything is rocking along hunky-dory. Their fraternity had it
for eight years. Give it to ours for eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. PROTEST SITE MAPPED OUT
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for civil liberties groups and the city of Los Angeles
agreed Friday on a protest site for demonstrators at the Democratic
National Convention, a parking lot across from the entrance to the
Staples Center, where the convention will be held in mid-August,
officials said. A federal judge had ruled last week that the
proposed site, in a parking lot farther away and out of sight and
earshot of entering delegates, was unconstitutionally restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
