<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7109 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-TEXAS-CONVENTION-HNS &LR;      07-29 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    TEXAS REPUBLICANS RALLY BEHIND BUSH DESPITE DISCORD 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If George W. Bush can take anything for granted
in his campaign for the White House, it will be his continued
strong support from voters in his home state, including the 248
Texas delegates and alternates to the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and most of the Texas GOP activists who will help
nominate him for president don't see eye-to-eye on some key issues
_ including education, trade and the role of homosexuals in the
Republican Party. These are differences that the candidate and the
delegates will try to downplay during their party's showcase event.
</P>
<P>
   His choice of a running mate and his stands against such things
as abortion, gun control and taxes emphasize the conservative part
of Bush's ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the Texas delegates are more conservative than Bush
_ and for that matter more conservative than many others at the
national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Before most delegates even arrived in Philadelphia, a potential
tempest was brewing over Bush's decision to allow an openly gay
congressman to address the convention.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., is to speak Tuesday night on trade
issues, not gay rights, but his scheduled appearance was vigorously
attacked by delegate Cathie Adams of Dallas, president of the
ultraconservative Texas Eagle Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an affront to our families. This is just absolutely
wrong,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams estimated that as many as 70 percent to 75 percent of
Texas' delegates and alternates are social and religious
conservatives. They were selected at a state party convention in
Houston last month that also produced a Texas GOP platform
differing sharply with Bush in a number of policy areas and more
conservative on several issues than the national platform expected
to be adopted in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took the unusual step of skipping the state meeting
because, his campaign explained, he needed to spend the time in
states where he has to compete for votes. But there also was
speculation that he wanted to distance himself from debate and
publicity over a state party platform that would raise red flags
with the moderate voters whom he also needs to capture the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republican Chairwoman Susan Weddington said delegates'
differences with Bush are relatively minor. She predicted a ``very,
very strong'' show of support for Bush from his fellow Texans in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of our members are excited about his
candidacy,'' added Chuck Anderson, executive director of the Texas
Christian Coalition and a Texas delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has defused abortion as a convention issue and reinforced
his conservative support by picking Dick Cheney as his running mate
and agreeing to support a strong anti-abortion plank in the
national party platform.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's personal anti-abortion position is not as strong as
that espoused in the state Republican Party platform, which calls
for a total ban on abortions, without exception. Bush supports
exceptions in cases of rape or incest and to protect the life of
the mother, although he avoids calling attention to those
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists, meanwhile, represent a major disagreement between
Bush and many of his fellow Republicans. Bush hasn't exactly been a
hero for homosexuals. He opposes gay marriages and last year
opposed a bill before the Texas Legislature that would have given
homosexuals special protections against hate-motivated crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush had a highly publicized meeting with gay Republican
supporters in Austin a few months ago and declared himself a
``better person'' for the experience. Kolbe's scheduled convention
speech is believed to be an outgrowth of that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republicans, however, have a strong anti-gay plank in
their state platform that condemns homosexuality as ``contrary to
the fundamental, unchanging truths that have been ordained by
God.``
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Ivers, spokesman for the Log Cabin Republicans, a gay GOP
group, said there will be a record 18 openly gay delegates and
alternates to the Republican National Convention. None is from
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush and the leadership of the (national Republican)
party are all very committed to an inclusive, uplifting, positive
convention,'' Ivers said. ``If there are people who are concerned
about that, they are out of step.``
</P>
<P>
   Weddington said Bush has made it clear he isn't yielding on
issues promoted by gay rights activists and said she wasn't
concerned about Kolbe's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the concession is on the part of the leadership of the
gay movement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Weddington said that education, particularly government's role
in it _ and not gay rights _ may be the most significant sticking
point between Bush and many Texas Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Party platform urges abolition of the U.S. Department
of Education, but Bush doesn't go that far.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has made education reform a top issue of his campaign,
says he wants to de-emphasize the role of the federal government in
the public schools. In proposing new accountability requirements
for public schools, he has taken pains to insist that individual
states, not the federal government, would set their own standards.
But some Texas Republicans fear the accountability requirements
would have the federal government hovering over the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who want to do a much quicker dismantling of
the educational bureaucracy, both state and federal, and that's a
conflict,'' Weddington said.
</P>
<P>
   Other differences between Bush and the Texas GOP platform
include:
</P>
<P>
   --The platform urges the repeal of the North American Free Trade
Agreement, which Bush supports. The platform also opposes permanent
trade relations with China, which Bush also supports.
</P>
<P>
   --Texas Republicans called for repeal of the minimum wage. Bush
hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   -- The platform supports the adoption of ``American English'' as
the official language of Texas and the United States. Bush, who is
reaching out to Hispanic voters, doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   -- Texas Republicans have called for abolition of the Internal
Revenue Service. Bush, instead, has called for changes in the tax
code.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
