<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NYT &LR;      07-29 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-PLATFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE REBUFFS EFFORTS TO PULL MORE TO THE LEFT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Repeatedly brushing aside amendments from its
embattled liberal wing, the Democratic Party's platform committee
Saturday adopted a party blueprint that hews closely to Vice
President Al Gore's centrist views on trade, fiscal policy,
national defense, crime and welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-page document approved Saturday was a fitting successor
to the platform created for Bill Clinton's first presidential
campaign in 1992, which broke sharply from the party's liberal
roots. Saturday, the 186-member committee, dominated by Gore
supporters, again and again knocked down efforts to tug the party
back toward the left.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals supporting universal health care, a moratorium on the
death penalty, punishments against corporations that pay low wages,
tougher rules for international trade, and better health care for
prisoners were withdrawn or overwhelmingly defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of a small band of liberals, the committee
approved planks putting the party firmly behind a limited missile
defense system, aggressive debt reduction, modest tax cuts and
expanding global trade through the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The liberals did not go down quietly. Talking to reporters
outside the committee room, members of a group calling itself the
Progressive Caucus to the Democratic National Convention complained
that their views had been ignored and that the Gore campaign had
pressured committee members to vote against their planks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about a big tent,'' said Rep. Dennis J. Kucinich of
Cleveland. ``But this tent just got a bit smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hayden, a state senator from Los Angeles who is also a Gore
delegate, said the platform had failed to address the challenge of
Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate who strongly opposes the
World Trade Organization and who, polls show, has been drawing
voters away from Gore in California.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said the center-straddling platform would turn off the
party's liberal base, making it more difficult to find committed
campaign foot-soldiers. As a result, he warned, Gore would have to
rely on negative attacks against the Republican ticket of Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas and Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to lift the enthusiasm of tens of thousands of
people to make phone calls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Progressive Caucus did not have much support in the room
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   No major environmental groups were present to raise objections
to the platform.
</P>
<P>
   An observer for the United Auto Workers, which objects to Gore's
trade policies and has not endorsed him, said the platform
committee had addressed the union's concerns in private
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And an official with the AFL-CIO, which has endorsed Gore, said
that despite its flaws, the platform was generally acceptable to
organized labor, the single most important constituency in the
Democratic coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've succeeded in moving the party from free trade toward
fair trade,'' said Gerald Shea, an adviser to John Sweeney, the
president of the labor federation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the complaints from the liberals, party leaders
portrayed the platform debate as more open than the Republicans'
process. And they said that the fault lines within their party over
trade and national defense are not as deep as those dividing the
Republicans on abortion and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are sections of this platform that I am not wild
about,'' said Sen. Richard Durbin of Illinois, a co-chairman of the
platform committee. ``But the bottom line is, we know how much
different and how much better this is than the Republican
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Al From, chairman of the Democratic Leadership Council, a
centrist group, said, ``Don't forget, we followed a lot of the
policies the Progressive Caucus would like us to follow now in the
1970s and '80s, and we had the kind of stagnation that turned core
Democrats away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform goes to a full vote by the delegates on the second
night of the Democratic convention next month. No amendments will
be allowed from the floor, and it seems unlikely that liberals will
be able to muster enough support to force a floor vote on a
minority report.
</P>
<P>
   One of the liveliest debates Saturday was over a proposal to
strike language endorsing development of a limited national missile
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals contended that the idea was unproven, costly and likely
to ignite a new arms race. But Gore's supporters argued that
remaining silent on missile defense would give the Republicans
ammunition to attack Democrats as soft on defense. Bush supports a
global missile defense system. The progressives' amendment was
tabled.
</P>
<P>
   On the contentious issue of trade, the platform says, ``It's
clear we live in a globalized world, and that there is no turning
back.'' The platform obliquely endorses a concept known as fast
track _ without using that phrase _ calling for broad presidential
powers to negotiate trade compacts without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   To appease labor unions and environmental groups, the platform
says workers rights, human rights and environmental protections
should be negotiated in all trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   On crime, the platform endorses ``tougher penalties _ including
the death penalty _ for those that dare to terrorize the
innocent.'' But it also calls for DNA testing and ``effective''
legal counsel for death row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   A few members of the committee had proposed calling for a
moratorium on capital punishment. But they withdrew the amendment
for lack of support. Instead, the committee adopted the language:
``In all death row cases, we encourage thorough post-conviction
reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform adopts debt reduction _ Clinton's guiding economic
principle _ as the heart of Gore's economic policies. And it calls
for using the federal surplus to strengthen Medicare and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   In its longest section, on education, the platform supports
using federal money to increase teachers' pay, reduce class sizes,
rebuild crumbling schools and help families pay for college
tuition. But it also calls for requiring teachers to pass periodic
reviews making it easier to close down failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   The platform, like Gore's campaign agenda, firmly endorses a
woman's right to an abortion, strong gun regulations, a hate crimes
law, sweeping campaign finance reform, and an end to racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   On the environment, supporters of Gore proposed an amendment
endorsing several of the vice president's campaign pledges: to
restore the Everglades, restrict oil and gas drilling off the
coasts of California and Florida, and prohibit drilling or logging
in the wildest areas of the national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members from Alaska and many of the Western states
objected to the language, saying it would hurt local economies. But
the measure passed by the narrowest vote of the day, 47-33.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
