<SLUG> BC-BBN-BASCOLM-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS HAVE TAKEN BIG STEP FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Bordick put on a Mets uniform for the first time Saturday,
then hit the first pitch he saw for a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal, you say? That's thousands of miles and two geographic
divisions away, you say? True, the bigger news, as it pertains to
the Dodgers and their playoff push, was Arizona's acquisition of
Curt Schilling. But the moment that deal went down, whatever the
Mets were trying to do, and subsequently did, was the business of
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate focus is on the National League West, and the
Dodgers entered Saturday 2 games behind the Diamondbacks and in the
running for the division title. Yet, that baseball invention deemed
to stir more interest late in the season _ you know, the wild card
_ is as much a part of the playoff race as the Dodgers' pursuit of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Dodgers in third place in the division, but
they're in third place in the wild-card race, which the Mets lead.
San Francisco trails them by a half game and the Dodgers are 2
games back.
</P>
<P>
   What the Mets did Friday _ and it might be determined two months
from now _ could have an equal affect on them as Arizona's dealing
for Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Dodgers, with their limited prospects and their
unwillingness to part with any of the few high-caliber ones they
have, took the only possible path and brought back the
much-maligned Ismael Valdes, and the Diamondbacks grabbed one of
the top 10 pitchers in baseball, the Mets filled their glaring
voids.
</P>
<P>
   And they might have done it with a Bordick, a player who at this
point might be more valuable than the aging Barry Larkin, who nixed
a deal between Cincinnati and the Mets last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bordick) makes all the routine plays and sometimes the
spectacular play,'' Mets general manager Steve Phillips said after
the deal. ``He can turn the double play. He really gives us the
stability that was lacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick was an enormous piece for the Mets to get, but they also
shored up a few of the other areas that were of great concern. They
added right-hander Rick White and right-handed power off the bench
in Bubba Trammell, both acquired from Tampa Bay hours after Bordick
was brought in from Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Mets made their move to make a charge at National
East leader Atlanta, which led the Mets by five games Saturday
morning. That's the focus, but the consolation prize of the
wild-card spot lands the Mets in the playoffs. And Phillips might
not be done.
</P>
<P>
   He's talking to Colorado about Pedro Astacio, Florida about
closer Antonio Alfonseca and Texas about John Wetteland. More
bullpen depth or another starter, all of which puts the Mets in
better position to pull closer to the Braves and pull further away
from the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Diamondbacks made themselves markedly better with
the Schilling deal, though which team it works out better for is
years from being determined because of the prospects they sent to
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are much better with Bordick's defense through the
middle, his veteran approach and his ability to revitalize the
clubhouse by going from a team 12 games out of a playoff spot to
the wild-card leader.
</P>
<P>
   But how much better are the Dodgers by reacquiring Valdes?
</P>
<P>
   It could be an enormous improvement, but it's an unknown because
Valdes has not pitched much this season, and when he has pitched he
hasn't been very good. Valdes is 2-4 with a 5.37 ERA, and while
that's better than the 1-6, 5.75 ERA rookie Eric Gagne had with the
Dodgers, his announced return didn't make many players jump for
joy.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona took a huge step toward winning the division, but
equally important is what transpired on the other coast.
</P>
<P>
   __ Concession from Schilling: The Arizona Diamondbacks gave up
four players, each of whom have high, yet-to-be-reached ceilings to
get Curt Schilling from the Philadelphia Phillies. But the
deal-maker, as far as the Diamondbacks were concerned, was
Schilling's willingness to make a concession.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, owed $6.5 million next season, had a right to demand
a trade after the season since he has a multiyear contract. But
Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo spoke with
Schilling's agent, Rick Thurman, and was told the right-hander
wouldn't ask for a trade after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got two waivers from him,'' Colangelo said. ``He waived his
demand for a contract extension and waived his right to be traded
after this season.''
</P>
<P>
   This point immediately makes the Diamondbacks the team to beat
in 2001. They'll have lefty Randy Johnson and Schilling as the No.
1 and No. 2 starters for the next 14 months. One of the two has led
the majors in strikeouts each season since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he is signed for next year is very important in
this deal,'' Arizona general manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said. ``This
is not a stretch-drive, rent-a-player.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Brave Jordan: Atlanta's Brian Jordan is trying to fight
through the pain and finish the season, but his shoulders are in
such bad shape that he'll have surgery on both of them after the
season. Jordan has a tear in his right rotator cuff and he's
experiencing discomfort in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He is hoping cortisone shots in each shoulder will relieve some
of the pain and there's no question it is affecting him at the
plate. Jordan is hitting .192 with no homers and six RBI this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely getting both repaired this offseason,'' Jordan
said. ``I can't try to make it through another year like this. Any
sane person would probably go on the DL and try and heal up.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Slammin' Sammy: Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa is back to hitting
homers, smacking eight since the all-star break and pulling within
three of Gary Sheffield's league-leading 34. But the ball isn't the
only thing Sosa's slamming around.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs general manager Ed Lynch knew he was in trouble when team
president Andy MacPhail took over the Sosa contract negotiations.
Lynch was fired a month later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more opportunity now to have a winning team because
Andy MacPhail knows what it takes,'' Sosa said. ``I don't want to
criticize Ed Lynch, because he was a great person and made some
beautiful moves, but I think Andy will make the right decisions for
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Um, like a contract extension?
</P>
<P>
   __ Against the book: San Diego manager Bruce Bochy took his
baseball book of conventional wisdom and threw it out at San
Francisco. With two on and none out, Bochy had Kevin Nicholson
sacrifice to set the table for . . . pitcher Woody Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it had merit. Williams was hitting .348 and had three
hits in his last start. Williams drilled a pitch to the left-field
wall and settled for a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't say this too often, but Woody's in a zone at the
plate. He looks so good up there,'' Bochy said. ``It's obvious by
the way he's taking pitches. He's seeing the ball so well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
