<SLUG> BC-BBA-HAAK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTEBOOK: EX-GM ANALYZES ANAHEIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody likes to play GM this time of year, even former GMs
like Bill Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi calls this time of year ``a blast'' with all the activity
going on. Even if there is no trade made by a team, there is plenty
of talk, as Bavasi knows all too well.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 his Angels were in a race with the Rangers, who obtained
shortstop Royce Clayton, pitcher Todd Stottlemyre and third baseman
Todd Zeile in deals. The Angels got nothing and lost the division.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Indians wanted pitcher Chuck Finley, but Bavasi
wanted one more prospect than the Indians were willing to part
with, and again no trade was made. Finley signed with the Indians
during the offseason and the Angels got nothing.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it would be easy to criticize Bavasi for not
making a deal in those cases. But, as Bavasi says, ``You don't want
to make a deal just to make a deal. You want to make a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And if there isn't one available, you just have to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to do what's best for the organization in both
the short term and the long term,'' he said. ``It's not easy to do.
You can set up the organization now and later, or you can cripple
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because Bavasi is not the Angels GM anymore doesn't mean he
doesn't have ideas on what they should do now.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Angels GM) Bill (Stoneman) is in a position where he has to
make a decision,'' Bavasi said. ``Does he think they can win the
division or win the wild card? I think Seattle will win the
division. Oakland has the wild card right now, but I think Anaheim
is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Anaheim gets healthy and stays healthy, I like their
chances. They have a better lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' primary need at this point seems to be a productive
designated hitter, but Bavasi has other ideas. He said he likes the
group of young pitchers the Angels have, and he should. He drafted
and developed them. But to depend on so many of them during a
pennant race, he says, is another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's tough is to count on a whole group of kids to
contend,'' Bavasi said. ``I think they need another arm. Not that
they're out there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Missed it by that much: Last week, Indians shortstop Omar
Vizquel was four innings away from setting the American League
record for consecutive errorless games by a shortstop. Then the
Twins' Matt Lawton hit a tricky hopper to Vizquel, who bobbled it
for an error, his first of the season and first since last Sept.
25.
</P>
<P>
   His errorless streak ended at 95 games, tying Cal Ripken's AL
mark. The major-league record is 101 games by the Mets' Rey
Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   Said Vizquel: ``Ever since I entered pro ball, it's been my
dream to play a whole season without an error.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Gotta be the shoes: All teams have dress codes on flights,
but the Devil Rays' Jose Canseco recently found it difficult to
find a pair of dress shoes that didn't hurt his inflamed left heel.
But he improvised, wearing a pair of comfortable golf shoes on the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes, I'm willing to do it,'' Canseco said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Uniform change: When Hal Morris was traded from the Reds to
the Tigers a couple of weeks ago, the Reds were playing the Tigers
at Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   The game had already started and Morris was in his Reds uniform
when the trade was made. So he simply switched clubhouses, changed
uniforms and finished the game in the Tigers clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quest for .400: Nomar Garciaparra was hitting .398 through
Friday, but he says he doesn't concern himself with becoming the
first since Ted Williams in 1941 to hit .400.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers, I never look at them,'' he said. ``I don't like them.
I don't care about them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
