<HEADLINE>
BUSH DYNASTY HOPING FOR SPOT ON EXCLUSIVE PRESIDENTIAL ROSTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (editors: dynasts in 6th graph is cq) 
 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1988, when then-Vice President George Bush was running for
president, the news media often mentioned that no sitting vice
president had won the higher office since Martin Van Buren in 1836.
But Bush did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard much about the Van Buren factor in this
election,'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the former president's
eldest son, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, it's the Adamses,'' said Bush, referring to John
and John Quincy Adams, the only father and son to have served as
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is expected to receive the Republican presidential
nomination Thursday in Philadelphia, would like to add his and his
father's name to that limited roster of presidential dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   To get there, Bush must defeat Democratic candidate Al Gore in
what will be the United States' first head-to-head presidential
clash between political dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about to have a presidential election between a Gore and
a Bush, and that's the first time you've had dynasts running
against each other, two candidates for president whose fathers have
held high political office,'' said Stephen Hess of the Brookings
Institute and author of ``America's Political Dynasties.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Bush's father president, his grandfather, Prescott
Bush, was a U.S. senator. And Gore's father, Albert Gore Sr., was a
prominent member of the U.S. Senate. The senior Gore died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brother, Jeb, is governor of Florida. Jeb's son, George
Prescott Bush, 25, who is campaigning nationally for his uncle, has
been named one of the nation's most eligible bachelors and is
frequently mentioned as the next generation's heir to the Bush
political mantle.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, is involved
in her father's campaign and is talked about as the next generation
of political Gores.
</P>
<P>
   And one of Gore's potential running mates is Indiana Democrat
Evan Bayh, who now holds the U.S. Senate seat that his father,
Birch Bayh, held for three terms. Another possible Gore running
mate is Maryland Lt. Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, a rising star
in the Kennedy clan.
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes and the Gores are relatively new political dynasties
in the United States, Hess said, and even the glamorous Kennedys
are really only in the second generation of holding elective
political office. Joseph Kennedy, father of former President John
F. Kennedy, was an appointed ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a glamour there. There's also a lot of Kennedys,''
Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   Political dynasties are numerous in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said that when he wrote his book 30 years ago, 17 percent
of the members of Congress had direct ancestors who also had served
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Encyclopedia of the United States Congress says 16 family
dynasties have produced eight presidents and 86 members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
