<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FAMILY-VALUES CROWD UPSET ABOUT GOP'S GAY SPEAKER 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As they tend to do elsewhere, Republicans and
gays are making deeply conflicted bedfellows here in the City of
Brotherly Love on the eve of the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening would almost be an amusing burlesque, except
that it's the latest chapter in a long-running serial.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the only openly gay Republican in Congress
will briefly address the delegates on the issue of free trade. This
innocuous bit of scheduling is being received in some aggrieved
quarters as an affront to family values.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly lathered up on the matter is the Texas delegation,
the members of which include some of the most socially conservative
Republican activists in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas GOP platform reserves some of its harshest criticism
for what it terms ``homosexual behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jim Kolbe, the Arizona congressman in question, gets
three minutes on the podium during the evening event themed
``Strength and security with a purpose: Safe in our homes and in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, some Republicans don't feel safe in their homes with
Kolbe talking about NAFTA in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The Tucson Republican, elected to the House in 1984, served in
Vietnam with the U.S. Naval Reserve and was awarded the Medal of
Valor.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kolbe is a big supporter of NAFTA _ another issue on
which the state party platform takes a dim view _ it's clear the
only objection to his history-making role in the convention is that
he's gay.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the reaction from within the party is no big surprise.
It was just two years ago that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss, equated homosexuals with kleptomaniacs and sex addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, due in for the coronation on
Wednesday, also has struggled with the gay issue. Politically, Bush
intractably opposes gay marriage and tougher hate crime laws.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, the compassionate conservative tries to have
it both ways: He'll meet with gay Republicans, but won't risk
alienating anti-gay Republicans by actually supporting them.
</P>
<P>
   But with the national convention at hand, a different spirit
prevails. What will the delegates say when they find out that Dick
Cheney has a lesbian daughter?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this isn't news to Bush _ he's known the Cheney
family for years, including 31-year-old daughter, Mary. The Kolbe
appearance also is on the schedule with the approval and blessing
of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that Kolbe, the only openly gay Republican in
Congress, was not actually the first. That distinction goes to
Steve Gunderson, the former congressman from Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson did not seek re-election in 1996 after then-House
Speaker Newt Gingrich told him that conservatives in Congress would
never support him to chair a committee he was in line for.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Gingrich's lesbian half-sister, Candace
Gingrich, as spokeswoman for the National Human Rights Campaign,
was grand marshal of Houston's Gay Pride Parade. She urged
attendees to be ``open and proud.''
</P>
<P>
   At this year's Republican National Convention, 18 of the more
than 4,000 delegates and alternates are themselves open and proud,
representing the largest contingent of openly gay conventioneers
(none from Texas) in the party's history.
</P>
<P>
   That's one statistic you won't see touted in the Republican
Party literature.
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
