 ufvj 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BYLINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Yvonne Abraham
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Globe Staff
</P>
<P>
   ABOARD THE STRAIGHT TALK L EXPRESS _ He may have fired up his L
trademark bus once again yesterday, but John S. McCain wants to
make this very clear: He's not trying to steal anybody's thunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't intend this bus trip to be an extravaganza,'' a
jovial McCain said as he sat in his usual red swivel seat in the
back of his white bus, drinking soda after soda. On board were many
of the staff members who had run the Arizona senator's campaign for
the Republican presidential nomination, L and some of the reporters
who had covered his many town hall meetings in New Hamp- shire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were hoping was it would just be a good time, and that
it would be report- ed as such,'' McCain said. ``We thought L we'd
have a trip where just the old timers came with us, but it just
grew and grew and grew.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   McCain traveled from Arlington, Va., to the Republican National
Convention in L Philadelphia with several busloads of re- porters
in tow. The convoy was bigger and a good deal more festive than it
had been for most of McCain's unsuccessful primary campaign, and
McCain was happy to have the company.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He appeared at a town hall meeting L yesterday afternoon in Blue
Bell, Pa., with state senator Stewart Greenleaf, a candi- date for
the US House. The crowd of sever- al hundred gave McCain a loud
ovation, and laughed heartily at his well-worn one-lin- ers, like
the one about Arizona being so dry the trees chase the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that his trip, and his busy sched-  &UR; -------------------- &LR; 
ule in Philadel- phia, had an-L noyed some L aides of the L
soon-to-be L GOP presiden- tial nominee, L George W. L Bush, McCain
L was careful to L give the Texas governor his L due at every L
possible turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always L said I'd sup-L port the nomi- nee of the par- ty,''
McCain L said, ``Gover-L nor Bush is L running the L kind of cam-L
paign I would L have run if I L were the nomi- nee.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised Bush for appealing to a wider variety of voters now
than during the primaries, and said the governor was running a far
more ``centrist'' campaign, concentrating on is- sues like
education and military reform.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won seven primaries, including New Hampshire, Michigan,
and Massachu- setts. The battle in South Carolina, which the
senator lost, was especially vicious, and McCain was clearly angry
during and after it because of what he called the Bush cam- paign's
negative tactics. But the Bush of South Carolina had not been the
true Bush, McCain said yesterday, calling the tactics there ``the
exception to the rule of the cam-  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  paign he's
L run.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, McCain said, L he would do L himself no L good by
dwell- ing on his in-L juries now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I was unhappy about some of L the things that
happened dur- ing the cam-L paign,'' L McCain said. L ``I don't
know L of a campaign L that the loser L isn't unhappy L with some L
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the L point is, you L can't be a sore loser. Ameri-L cans
do not ad- mire or appreciate a sore loser, so you just move
forward and try to make the very best of it. I think I'm at step
eight of the 12- step presidential recovery program.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He described his relationship with L Bush these days as
``cordial.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The senator will deliver a prime-time address in support of the
Texas governor on Tuesday night, and has a busy schedule of
appearances throughout the convention, including a speech at the
``shadow conven- tion,'' organized by commentator Arianna
Huffington. McCain said that speech, too, would be an attempt not
to compete with  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  Bush, but to bolster him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will host a reception for his del- egates today to thank
them for their work, and to urge them to put aside their anger and
throw themselves behind Bush. L McCain will campaign with the
governor out West for three days after the conven- tion, and have
Bush and his wife, Laura, visit his ranch near Sedona, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   McCain stepped gingerly yesterday L into the subject of his own
future ambitions. He said he fully expected Bush to win in
November, and probably would be elected to a second term. His
strongest supporters are counting on the senator's running in 2004
if Bush loses to Gore. And this week's high-profile appearances may
be a kind of testing of the waters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain tried to avoid the subject yes- terday, but when pushed
to talk about what he might do if Bush lost, McCain said he wasn't
sure whether another run at the L presidency was even possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you have to figure is, could we catch that lightning
in a bottle again?'' he said. ``Could the circumstances that pre-
vailed last time happen again? The kind of unconventional campaign
we ran, could L that work?''
</P>
<P>
   He was nostalgic about his campaign. ``It was the greatest
experience of my life,'' McCain said. ``I can't tell you how
grateful I am for having had this experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The old fire returned, however, when a reporter asked McCain if
he had gotten Bush's permission for his pre-convention odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I checked,'' he bristled, ``I'm a US senator elected
by the people of Ari- zona.''
</P>
