<HEADLINE>
`CITY IS JUMPING' AS LAVISH GOP BASHES KEEP REVELERS ROCKIN' 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHELBY HODGE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Forget the somnolent speeches and studied
applause of First Union Center where the Republican National
Convention is being held this week. The real GOP action _ and fun _
takes place far from the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   Museums, Navy yards, restaurants, hotel ballrooms, historic
homes, a rail terminal and golf courses are being commandeered for
the Grand Old Party. Even the steps of the Philadelphia Museum of
Art, scene of a memorable moment in the movie ``Rocky,'' are booked
for a Republican gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia 2000, the convention host committee, rolls out the
red carpet Sunday night with an al fresco dessert party for the
state delegations, a lighted boat parade on the Delaware River and
a fireworks extravaganza above the city skyline. Monday morning, an
abbreviated Mummer's parade and a street-side hoagie party will
keep visitors entertained and well fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is jumping,'' said Jeff Guaracino, Philadelphia 2000
volunteer. ``While the entire city may not be able to be on the
convention floor, the entire city is a part of this thing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, takes over the Electric
Factory club for a late-night, invitation-only party starring Blues
Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest tickets is a Mardi Gras-themed bash in the
Navy Yard, for which supporters of Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., are
flying in Tauzin's cousin, Cajun chef Jimmy Gravois, from
Louisiana. The event is estimated to cost $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   American Bandstand's Dick Clark returns to Philadelphia to the
old WFIL studios, where the original Bandstand was broadcast, for a
party honoring Rep. Michael Oxley of Ohio. Chubby Checker and
Frankie Avalon will join Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The one event guaranteed to rock Republican ranks is the George
Magazine/Creative Coalition fund-raiser benefiting the Michael J.
Fox Foundation for Parkinson's Research and the Christopher Reeve
Paralysis Foundation. Fox will attend, and Heather Locklear also is
on the affirmative RSVP list.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas and New York delegations party together later in the
week at a club called Zanzibar Blue. Chase Bank picks up the tab.
Fans of Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-San Antonio, gather one evening for
festivities at the Hard Rock Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   The city's museums and historic buildings present a wealth of
unique party venues. The roof deck of the renowned Franklin
Institute Science Museum _ offering tree-level views of the city's
skyline and monuments _ is booked every night of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The stairs and plaza in front of the Philadelphia Museum of Art
(the ``Rocky steps'' locale) are the setting Wednesday morning for
``Es Un Nuevo Dia,'' (It's A New Day), a Hispanic-themed event
welcoming Gov. George W. Bush to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 ticketed guests are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Raul Romero, Bush's national adviser for Hispanic
outreach, has spent the last three weeks organizing the event
starring salsa queen Celia Cruz, Jon Secada, Grammy winner Carols
Ponce and Mariachi Campanas de America from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Major contributors to the Republican Party have their own social
schedules to maintain. The Eagles ($25,000 donors), Team 100
($100,000 donors) and Regents ($250,000) donors have the
opportunity to rub elbows with elected officials, policy makers and
former presidents at a host of off-the-convention-floor activities.
</P>
<P>
   After his acceptance speech, George W. Bush and 5,000 invited
guests will reconvene at the Spectrum Stadium for a celebration
bash and concert by country stars Brooks &AMP; Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
