u p BC-LABOR-CONVENTION-HNS &LR;      07-29 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR UNIONS WELCOME CASH OF CONVENTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia may seem an odd venue for a Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Brotherly Love is a union town. Organized labor's
presence, while smaller than in previous decades, is still evident
here, from the docks on the riverfront to the checkout lines at the
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   And Philadelphia's union members, traditionally stalwarts of the
Democratic Party, are a key reason this city hasn't elected a
Republican mayor since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The city's labor unions, however, are largely embracing the
Republican convention. The GOP faithful may not bring a governing
philosophy the union members can espouse, but conventioneers do
carry cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad they're here,'' said Pat Coughlan, international
vice president for the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees,
Local 274. ``They're coming into our town. They're creating work.
They're spending money and creating jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Two unions, representing more than 14,000 local government
workers _ from librarians to garbage collectors _ had threatened to
strike during the convention. Union leaders had even sought
volunteers willing to be arrested outside the convention site.
</P>
<P>
   But the two locals, both affiliated with the American Federation
of State, County and Municipal Employees, reached tentative
agreements with the city earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some union members plan to participate in a mass rally scheduled
for Sunday in Philadelphia's Center City. But a number of unions,
including the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees, as well as
the Building Trades, have promised not to strike or picket during
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's unions claim 250,000 members, or about 10 percent
of the civilian labor force in the greater metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, nearly one of every three jobs in Philadelphia
was a union position, noted Walter Licht, a professor of history at
the University of Pennsylvania. But as the city's manufacturing
jobs migrated elsewhere, Philadelphia's union membership dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, the city's labor unions caused real headaches
for Philadelphia convention planners, with six different unions
squabbling over jurisdictional issues at the Pennsylvania
Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the local unions joined the citywide effort to land a
convention this summer, and the Republicans signed on.
</P>
<P>
   By holding their convention here, in a city that is not only
pro-union but nearly half African-American, Republicans are hoping
they can portray their party as more inclusive. ``It gives us
chance to show that our party can be competitive in urban areas,''
Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   As they finished converting the city's First Union Arena into a
convention hall, hundreds of laborers wore T-shirts identifying
themselves as ``Republican for a Week.'' Later this week, they are
planning a rally at which the shirts will be tossed into a bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Union leader Coughlan noted that while labor leaders want the
GOP's business, they also want their members ``to see them for what
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our answer is going to be Al Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
