<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALLOFFAME-MONTANA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTANA DISCOVERS MEANING OF HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ It was late Friday night when it finally hit Joe
Montana. He had been resisting _ fighting _ this concept of being a
Hall of Famer. He had always viewed it so differently than he did
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was looking at it in the proper perspective,''
said Montana, unquestionably the crowd favorite of the five
enshrined in the Pro Football Hall of Fame Saturday. ``I thought
the Hall of Fame was an ending. I mentioned to a couple of people
that in some ways _ and I'm 44 years old _ in some ways I feel like
I'm in my grave and in my coffin alive and they're throwing dirt on
me. I can feel it and I'm trying to get out. It wasn't until this
weekend, these past three days _ with these gentlemen behind me and
spending the time with them that I really got the true meaning of
what this is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life we spent going from Pop Warner to a new team to
junior high to high school and to Notre Dame, to San Francisco and
Kansas City. And in the middle of the night last night I woke up _
and I had a whole other speech prepared _ I told my wife, Jennifer,
`I got the meaning and I have to write it down and I don't want to
forget it.' This isn't an ending. It's a beginning. A beginning of
the rest of my life with a new team. Look at these guys _ what a
team it is,'' said Montana.
</P>
<P>
   There were friends from the western Pennsylvania area, including
high school coach Paul Zolak (father of former Patriot quarterback
Scott), as well as former 49ers owner Edward DeBartolo Jr., and
former coach Bill Walsh, a Hall of Famer and one of the 111 living
members. The other inductees are Ronnie Lott and Dave Wilcox of the
49ers, Howie Long of the Oakland Raiders, and Pittsburgh Steelers
owner Dan Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   Montana said he achieved his first dream of playing for Ara
Parseghian at Notre Dame and thanked him for recruiting him along
with six other quarterbacks. He thanked Dan Devine for giving him
his chance with the Irish, to Walsh for drafting him in the third
round and for teaching and demanding ``perfection. If he didn't get
that, he'd settle for greatness. He could handle that,'' Montana
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was most emotional in his feelings for DeBartolo, the
embattled former owner who pleaded guilty to failure to report a
felony in a Louisiana riverboat casino gambling scheme that
ultimately led commissioner Paul Tagliabue to suspend him and fine
him $1 million. DeBartolo's sister, Denise, now owns the 49ers and
DeBartolo has moved to Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took care of our teammates and they know what we're talking
about on and off the field. He was always there,'' Montana said.
</P>
<P>
   He felt similarly about Lott, whom DeBartolo called the ``heart
and soul'' of the great 49er teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Ronnie Lott, who taught me on and off the football field
what a true man is supposed to be. Ronnie spoke and Ronnie
delivered. You've heard walk the walk and talk the talk? That's
Ronnie. He's a great example for me to continue. I had a few
injuries to my career and he was always there to pick me up. When a
friend is in need he was always there. It doesn't matter when,
where, how far. His wife would agree with me, he's rarely home
because he's out fulfulling promises to these people. He always has
his hand out _ not to take but to give. To me, that's more special
than anything,'' Montana said.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, who led the 49ers to four Super Bowl titles and won
three MVP awards, thanked his parents, Joseph and Theresa Montana,
for teaching him ``never to quit'' and for bringing him all over
Pennsylvania to play basketball, football, and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke about each of the inductees, saying about Long, ``He
chased my skinny butt all over the place for years and he often
asked me to slow down.'' Montana, who grew up a Steelers fan, noted
Rooney's great Steeler teams. Though Wilcox played before him (his
career ended after the '74 season), Montana was taken by the film
clips of Wilcox's ferocious play and quipped, ``Even your son
called you a cheap-shot artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana, called the ``greatest quarterback of all time'' by
DeBartolo in his introduction, acknowledged his four children and
his wife, whom he called his ``best friend.'' Montana added, ``It's
not the easiest thing to be married to an athlete. We might seem
calm on the outside but on the inside we're a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   No way. Not Joe Cool.
</P>
</TEXT>
