<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-TRIALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIALS LEAVE ROOM FOR ERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In most countries, the two best men in the world would be
automatic choices for the Olympic team. Not in America. Now that
both Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene will be watching the 200
from the stands in Sydney, the old debate has been rekindled.
Should teams be selected in one-shot trials? By a committee? By a
combination of the two?
</P>
<P>
   The United States uses all three models. Track and field and
swimming have always been one-shot. Basketball and baseball rely on
committees. Gymnastics and cycling use the combination. Most often,
the combination works best because it's fairest to everybody. The
best athlete won't be left home just because he or she wakes up
sick on the wrong day or gets tripped in a preliminary. And
everyone else has a chance to make the team at trials without
worrying about backroom politics.
</P>
<P>
   Purists say that one-shot is best because it mimics the Olympics
_ if Dan Jansen falls down at the Games or Sergei Bubka no-heights,
too bad. But if US sports federations are going to be funded based
on the medals they win, they're going to make sure their best
people make the team. That's why USA Gymnastics already guaranteed
Blaine Wilson a spot and why none of his rivals are griping.
Everyone knows he's The Man, and without him, the Americans don't
have a chance at a team medal.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC leaves the decision up to each federation, as long as
the process is open and fair, and allows athletes to appeal to an
independent arbitrator. That's what sets the United States apart
from Kenya, which dumped its whole Olympic men's marathon team last
week for ``complacency.'' Elijah Lagat and Moses Tanui had earned
their places by finishing 1-3 in the 2000 Boston Marathon and
Japhet Kosgei had won Tokyo. Named instead were Eric Wainaina,
Kenneth Cheruiyot and Ondoro Osoro (who was shot by carjackers last
week). Lagat and Tanui claimed they were sacrificed ``at the altar
of personal vendetta and cheap propaganda.'' Lagat has been named
to replace Osoro and odds are Tanui and Kosgei will also end up
going since Kip Keino, the two-time medalist who heads the national
Olympic Committee, says he won't take the second string to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Male bonding
</P>
<P>
   Who says the International Olympic Committee isn't still an
old-boys club? There wasn't a single woman among the 48 new
candidates proposed last week. Among the 14 chosen to be
rubber-stamped at the September meeting is outgoing USOC president
William Hybl. In order to stay a member, though, Hybl will have to
have some senior USOC position after his term ends. His addition
will bring the number of Americans on what will be a 127-member
body to four (Anita DeFrantz, James Easton, and former volleyball
player Bob Ctvrtlik) . . . No royal lodgings and no limo for IOC
president Juan Antonio Samaranch in Sydney. ``We will be in a
hotel, a normal hotel,'' he says. And for wheels, he'll use a van .
. . Stan Smith, named US Olympic men's tennis captain Thursday, has
until Tuesday to (a) persuade Pete Sampras to play, which is
unlikely, and (b) name a doubles team. If Sampras declines, as
expected, Smith will tap Jan-Michael Gambill to go with Andre
Agassi, Michael Chang, and Todd Martin. The doubles team likely
will be fourth-ranked Alex O'Brien and Jared Palmer. Meanwhile,
women's coach Billie Jean King made it easy on herself by naming
Serena Williams to play doubles with sister Venus. Had Serena not
been chosen, Venus had hinted she might stay home, too. And the
sisters made it easy on King by winning Wimbledon. Odd woman out,
then, is Lisa Raymond, the top-ranked doubles player.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All lined up
</P>
<P>
   With the selection deadline two weeks off, the US Olympic rowing
team is nearly set. Since would-be challengers to the women's eight
and men's lightweight four have withdrawn, there'll be no trials
for those events. And since last year's women's quad of Kelly
Salchow, Laurel Korholz, Jen Dore-Terhaar, and Hilary Gehman won a
medal at the recent Lucerne regatta, they'll likely be named the
Olympic boat. The men's eight, favored to win gold for the first
time since 1964, is all but determined. The X factor is Brown
junior Dave Simon, who is coming off back surgery. If he's ready,
he'll row in the four and Mike Wherley will stay in the eight. If
he's not, Wherley will go in the four and Newburyport's Cy Beasley,
who rowed the single in 1996, probably will be in the eight. The
United States, by the way, is the only country to qualify in all 14
events (eight men's, six women's) for Sydney . . . Back in action
for the US women's soccer team are keeper Briana Scurry and
midfielder Michelle Akers, who've been sidelined virtually all
year. Scurry, who's been plagued with shin splints, played her
100th match against Norway last week. And Akers, who has been
recovering from major shoulder surgery, saw second-half action in
two matches. Still missing, but due back soon, is captain Carla
Overbeck. The Americans have a chance to even their series (at
13-13-2) Sunday in Oslo with the Norwegians, the only team in the
world that has the edge over them . . . Defender Jeff Agoos and
defensive midfielder Chris Armas could be two of the three over-23
players on the US men's soccer team in Sydney. They're suiting up
for Sunday's tuneup in Indianapolis against the Bolton Wanderers,
the English first division club . . . Odds are that at least half
of the US track and field Olympians who haven't met the ``A''
standard (e.g. men's walk and women's triple jump and javelin)
won't do it by the Sept. 11 deadline. Those who should include
Michael Stember (1,500 meters), Nick Rogers (5,000 meters), and Jud
Logan (hammer).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pixies don't make cut
</P>
<P>
   The day of the pixie is over in US gymnastics. Of the 30
entrants at last week's national championships, more than half were
18 or older and four (including 28-year-old Kristie Phillips) were
22 or older. Only one (Tasha Schwikert) is 15, which is the new age
limit . . . Who will be in the FleetCenter back room next month
choosing the final three members of the women's gymnastics team
when the trials end? Team coordinator Bela Karolyi, two-time
Olympian Tracee Talavera, longtime judge Marilyn Cross, and former
competitor Chari Knight-Hunter. The standing nine-member men's
committee will pick the final two males . . . Significant upset in
freestyle wrestling, when Charles Burton knocked off former world
champ Les Gutches last week in a wrestle-off for the final spot on
the US team. Gutches, who had won five straight US titles, had
beaten Burton in April, but missed the June trials with a back
injury. Burton won their best-of-three by a 5-0 count in the final
match . . . There was only one surprise at the recent US
weightlifting trials in New Orleans: Shane Hamman outpointing
Olympic veterans Tom Gough and Wes Barnett to join Oscar Chaplin
III on the men's team. Hamman clean-and-jerked 507 pounds, most
ever by an American; he was the first US lifter to break 500 in a
dozen years. The women's team was a given _ Cheryl Haworth, Tara
Nott, Robin Goad, and Cara Heads-Lane. Haworth didn't even have to
show up _ she'd already qualified on past performance. Gough,
Barnett, and Suzanne Leathers of Saunderstown, R.I., still will go
to Sydney, since the Americans expect to get a few last-minute
entries from the international federation . . . Latest Olympic
documentary by storyteller Bud Greenspan focuses on five athletes _
Romanian gymnast Nadia Comaneci, US decathlete Dan O'Brien,
Ethiopian marathoner Abebe Bikila, Australian swimmer Duncan
Armstrong, and Russian greco-roman wrestler Alexander Karelin. It
will air Aug. 20 on Showtime . . . Carrying the Olympic torch last
week was Jack Lockett, Australia's oldest man. At 109, he's five
years older than the modern Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Material from interviews, wire services, the US Olympic
Committee and sports federations was used in compiling this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
