</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON FINDS NO IFS, ANDS OR BUTT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't a head-butt.
</P>
<P>
   That's the official line, according to Hall of Famer Frank
Robinson, Major League Baseball's vice president for on-field
operations, who suspended Red Sox center fielder Carl Everett 10
games for his contact with umpire Ronald Kulpa after his ejection
July 15 in a game against the New York Mets at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never ourselves said he head-butted him,'' Robinson
said by telephone from his West Coast office Friday. ``That was
reported in the papers, and on TV and stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl's agent (Larry Reynolds) sent us a tape. That was his
contention, that he never head-butted him. I hadn't seen the tapes
yet. Carl didn't head-butt him, but he clearly made contact with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say this: Nothing was taken off the penalty because he
didn't head-butt him. There was no deduction. Whether he
head-butted him or not was not the overriding fact of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been considerable speculation that Robinson, who is in
his first year as the man who metes out justice for on-field
incidents, wanted to give Everett a stiffer penalty than the one he
did, but he was pressured by other big league officials and the
union to stop at 10.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't deny that. ``I don't think that's the important
thing,'' he said. ``I think the important thing is what I decided
to do at the end. That's why I like to take my time with these
things, because initially I may feel one way.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances were these: When Everett stepped into the
batter's box for the first time that Saturday afternoon, Mets
catcher Mike Piazza complained to Kulpa that Everett's left foot
was too close to home plate in the righthanded batter's box. A
player is not supposed to be standing closer than 6 inches to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Mets pitcher Dennis Cook had angrily raised
the same issue after being ejected for hitting Everett with a
pitch. Red Sox manager Jimy Williams later contended the Mets had
gone to the umpires before the next game about the issue, but crew
chief Randy Marsh insisted that wasn't the case. Piazza, Marsh
said, was the first to call attention to it that day.
</P>
<P>
   Kulpa drew a line with his foot. Everett got back in the box and
erased the line with his foot. When Kulpa drew another line later
in the at-bat, words were exchanged, Everett was ejected and then
erupted at Kulpa. Twice, he made contact with the umpire, the first
time with the bill of his helmet, which he subsequently threw down,
the second time with some part of his face _ his nose and lips, but
apparently not with his forehead, which would have constituted a
head butt.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said that he thought Kulpa, a first-year umpire, acted
properly. ``I certainly thought he did,'' Robinson said. ``How else
would Carl know where he has to be unless he drew a line? Then Carl
got back in the box and erased it. Back a ways, when I was playing,
an umpire would take the hitter's bat and draw a line, and say,
`This is the box.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So this wasn't something new, you just don't see it nowadays.
So he certainly acted properly in that respect. And what he said to
Carl was proper, but it still may have set him off because Carl
felt he was being forced to do something he's never been asked to
do before.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson interviewed Everett by telephone, with union lawyer
Robert Lenaghan also on the line. Robinson was asked if Everett
expressed any regret for his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``No he did not,'' Robinson said, ``But I wasn't looking for any
at that time. I never anticipated an apology. He may in time, when
we cross paths later, he may show remorse, but that's not important
to me. What's important is that he go on with his career and
conduct himself in a gentlemanly way.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's suspension was the longest given a player for an
on-field incident since Bill Madlock, then playing with Pittsburgh,
rubbed his glove in the face of umpire Jerry Crawford in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to send any messages,'' Robinson said. ``What
I'm trying to do is get a penalty that fits the incident. And this
case warranted a strong penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Everett remained on the field for close to five
minutes after his ejection also factored into Robinson's decision,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all plays into it,'' he said. ``I try to tell players that
what they do after they get ejected weighs just as heavily and is
just as important as what they did to get ejected. Some guys think
that since they've been ejected, they're going to get their money's
worth. I say, `Well, if you're going to get your money's worth,
you're going to have to pay later.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson rejected the suggestion that one reason he didn't give
Everett a stiffer penalty was because he would not only have been
penalizing the player but the team as well. A longer penalty could
have had an even greater impact on the Sox' bid for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Robinson said, ``because I don't feel like I would have
been deciding the pennant race. That comes down to a player's
actions, or a coach's actions, with that type of penalty. He did
it, not me. I only react to what they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was asked if Everett was out of control during the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on who is judging `out of control,' '' he said.
``My definition may be different from yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, I think he had lost control. But I think he had
control enough of himself that he wasn't going to do anything to
physically harm the umpire or anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was managing, and even a few times when I was playing,
and I had heated arguments with the umpires, some of the players
and coaches would say to me, `Man, we had to get you out of there
before you hurt the umpire.' No way. There's something in the back
of your mind that tells you you can't do that, even while you might
be acting silly and crazy out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Everett was getting away from (the coaches and players
trying to hold him), it was like, `Let me have my say.' He's not
going to take his helmet off or throw the bat down if he had lost
total control. Was he out of control? Any time you go off like
that, you're out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he was not surprised when Everett decided to drop
his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know, that's why you just sit here and wait,''
Robinson said. ``I wasn't surprised he dropped it. I think it was
wise on his part, to get it out of the way so he can get back in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dirty little secret
</P>
<P>
   Last week's report that steroids were discovered in Manny
Alexander's Mercedes after the Red Sox infielder loaned the car to
a 20-year-old batboy prompted plenty of jokes, most along the lines
that if Alexander, who has one home run this season, was using
steroids, he must not have read the instructions on the label.
</P>
<P>
   One law enforcement source said that it's unlikely any charges
will be brought against Alexander, since he was in Chicago at the
time of the discovery, batboy Carlos Cowert was in the car, and it
will be very difficult to establish any link between Alexander and
what was found in the glove compartment. Some people have taken
shots at the Sox for hiring a batboy who has had previous run-ins
with the law, but in this view the Sox deserve credit for reaching
out to a kid and judging him by his behavior when he was on their
clock. By all accounts, Cowert had a flawless record in four years
and never violated the trust the Sox placed in him by allowing him
to work in the team's clubhouse. It is no cause for celebration
when a young man loses his job after what began as a routine
traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the jokes about Alexander and steroids, last week's
news accounts thrust a spotlight on a subject that some have called
baseball's dirty little secret. Padres general manager Kevin Towers
has long spoken out about the growing use of steroids in the game;
San Diego has tested its minor leaguers for the last three years
and MLB spokesman Rich Levin said last week that all minor leaguers
are now tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found people in the minor leagues who have been using
steroids,'' Towers said, ``and we've gotten them help.''
</P>
<P>
   How prevalent is steroid use in the big leagues? Some estimates
have pegged it as high as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the data,'' Towers said, ``but I know it's
prevalent. It really hasn't come up at the general managers'
meetings. Beacuse of the players' union we know we can't test them
for it, but if you talked to 30 general managers, all 30 would have
to say they know an individual or more who use them in their
clubhouse. I walk through a clubhouse _ even most writers could _
and say, `That guy is using. That guy is using.' It doesn't take a
rocket scientist to notice a guy who's put on 70 pounds of bulk on
a skeletal system that wasn't designed to carry that kind of
weight, and that's why you see so many guys breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see drunkenness leaving the clubhouse anymore, but
you have all those supplements and shakes and blenders going in the
clubhouse now. That's more prevalent now than alcohol or smokeless
tobacco or amphetamines.''
</P>
<P>
   Many players, including most of the game's top stars, use some
kind of legal muscle-enhancing supplement. Towers was reviewing
some literature on one such product, creatine, when he received a
phone call from a reporter about his concern about steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Towers said that with such big money at stake, more players are
willing to take the health risks associated with steroid use. What
he fears, he says, is a Lyle Alzado situation in baseball,
referring to the former pro football star who died of a brain tumor
that reportedly was linked to his use of steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get to know not only these young players, but their wives
and their kids,'' Towers said. ``I would hate to have a Lyle Alzado
situation, then tell a player's wife we knew about the steroids and
didn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The collective bargaining agreement does not allow for random
testing of any illegal substances. If a player is found to be using
an illegal substance, he is given therapy. After that, he is
subject to discipline.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The low down on Arrojo
</P>
<P>
   One rival baseball uniformed official predicted Cuban pitcher
Rolando Arrojo, who he said was never happy in Colorado after being
dealt by Tampa Bay last winter for third baseman Vinny Castilla,
will be a big plus for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's proved he can pitch,'' he said. ``And being around Pedro
(Martinez) will help him. He needs to be around guys who do it the
right way. Arrojo really wanted out of Colorado in the worst way.
He pitched there in the All-Star Game (in 1998) and didn't like it
then, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not perfect, then it's like it's not worth it. If he
thinks he's out of it, he'll take himself out of a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good guy. He's just got some bad ideas. That's where I
think Pedro will really help him. I don't think there was anybody
on the Rockies he could relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo won't exactly be missed in the Rockies' clubhouse. His
critics point to a game against the Giants July 6, when the Rockies
were in the midst of a 11-game losing streak that knocked them out
of contention, when he gave up a 4-0 lead in the span of 10
pitches. When third baseman Jeff Cirillo came to the mound, Arrojo
shoved him away. He also was known to walk away from pitching coach
Marcel Lachemann, one of the most respected figures in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitched real well in Boston,'' the official said.
``Remember, he came back from that thing in Miami, where he got to
see his mom and brother, and pitched real well against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``His problem can be lefthanded hitters. That's where pitching
in Boston may be a little bit of an advantage, where he may not
have to face as many. He likes to drop down against lefthanded
hitters and sometimes it works against him. He definitely has the
stuff to get them out, but you need to watch his arm angle, because
he'll get too low and stay there, because he likes it. (Red Sox
pitching coach Joe) Kerrigan will either reach him or Rolando will
spit him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's right, Arrojo throws 93 to 94 miles an hour, and
occasionally touches 95. Age is always a question . . . He's really
a pretty good guy, and as a pitcher, he can be as good as he wants
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, he's pitching for a contract, He does want to make some
money. He has to run off a couple of good months if he wants to
have any hope about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo will be eligible for salary arbitration for the first
time after this season.
</P>
<P>
   An executive with another club said that the Sox paid dearly for
Arrojo by having to pick up Mike Lansing's $6 million contract for
next season, plus the $1.25 guaranteed buyout for 2002 if his
option isn't exercised, but that Arrojo could be a big factor down
the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of guy who will make six starts, and four of
them will be good ones. He's serviceable, and he's cheap,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brothers in arms
</P>
<P>
   One AL executive can't imagine the Sox picking up Ramon
Martinez's $8 million option for next season. ``That would be a
mistake,'' he said. ``How can they afford it? Can't they
renegotiate, maybe give him two years at $5 million a year. He
scoffed at the suggestion that the Sox would risk alienating Pedro
if they didn't pick up the option. ``It's nice that they're
brothers, but why do people really think the players hold the
hammer? What's the inherent threat there, that he's going to quit
pitching good? That's ridiculous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
