<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTS     07-29 3183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT PUTTING THRUST IN BELICHICK'S BRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ The New England Patriots are facing odds of 200-1
and up on winning the Super Bowl, according to some Las Vegas
oddsmakers who appear to be discounting the Bill Belichick factor.
Although the team has but a few stars, a lot of mediocre players,
and several unproven ones, Bob Kraft hired Belichick because he
felt the coach could outsmart the opposition. Kraft opted for
Belichick over Dom Capers and Tom Donahoe because Belichick would
bring superior divisional knowledge, as well as an ability to
devise game plans against the biggest weapons in football.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure truly is on Belichick, who has been billed as a
``defensive genius.'' The fact is, he may not have the players to
execute his schemes. He will have the usual three-year honeymoon
period for coaches, but he'd better be a winner before that's over
or face expulsion from the head-coaching ranks.
</P>
<P>
   As Belichick brings his gang of wounded knees here for Monday
night's Hall of Fame game against the San Francisco 49ers, we look
ahead to the regular-season schedule and try to figure what Kraft
was thinking when he hired Belichick. The coach loves to take it
one team at a time. And so do we:
</P>
<P>
   --Tampa Bay (home): Belichick must devise ways to keep Warren
Sapp from stuffing Drew Bledsoe into his meat grinder. That's
priority one. Offensively, who knows Bucs receiver Keyshawn Johnson
better than Belichick and offensive coordinator Charlie Weis, his
former Jets coaches? Certainly they must know how to exploit his
weaknesses. Everyone has weaknesses. And of course, young
quarterback Shaun King should be a perfect example of someone
Belichick can turn dizzy with his game plans.
</P>
<P>
   --New York Jets (twice): Real interesting. Will Belichick, Weis,
and defensive backs coach Eric Mangini get the best of Al Groh and
his staff, or will it be vice versa? Also, Bill Parcells
desperately wants two wins and he wants his draft picks, especially
the one acquired as compensation for Belichick, to be huge factors.
Belichick and Weis know why Vinny Testaverde was so successful two
years ago. They know why Curtis Martin has such good games against
the Patriots. Belichick knows what makes the Jets' defense tick and
the strength and weaknesses of the players he once coached. But
obviously, Groh knows how Belichick thinks defensively. This is the
ultimate chess game.
</P>
<P>
   --Minnesota Vikings (home): Cris Carter is the Hall of Famer,
but the Patriots must stop Randy Moss. How will Belichick
accomplish this? A little Ty Law in Moss's shirt and a lot of
roughing by Lawyer Milloy? The Vikings will start second-year
quarterback Daunte Culpepper. This should be another easy one where
Belichick can gain the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   --Miami Dolphins (twice): Shut down an already suspect running
game, rattle quarterback Damon Huard or Jay Fiedler, and find a way
to score against a tough Dolphins' defense and this could be a
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   --Denver Broncos (away): Regardless of what year it is, or who
the coach is, playing at Mile High Stadium is something the
Patriots simply don't do well. Belichick's role here is to get them
over this psychological hurdle, contain Terrell Davis, and pressure
and confuse a very poised Brian Griese. A win here would be a large
feather in Belichick's cap.
</P>
<P>
   --Indianapolis (twice): It's all about Peyton Manning. Belichick
actually did a pretty decent job containing him last year with the
Jets. The rest of the league is probably wondering how Belichick
could send Manning plummeting into a season-long funk because once
Belichick devises something to stop Manning, the rest of the league
will follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   --Buffalo Bills (twice): The Bills love to pound the ball down
your throat, which will put the interior part of the Patriots' line
and linebackers front and center. With Rob Johnson the likely
quarterback, Belichick may be able to take advantage of yet another
mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   --Cleveland Browns (away): Belichick is always welcome in
Cleveland _ as long as he's the opposing coach. Not a popular guy
there, this will be another case of going up against a coach _
Chris Palmer _ with whom he once worked and who understands how he
operates. In this case, the Patriots might have the edge in player
talent. Once again, young quarterback Tim Couch will have to crack
whatever mind game Belichick will play with him.
</P>
<P>
   --Cincinnati Bengals (home): The Bengals could have a very good
offense led by sophomore quarterback Akili Smith, who is mobile and
exciting. Belichick may have to approach Smith as he does Doug
Flutie and try to keep him in the pocket. The Bengals start the
year with a decent offensive line, good skilled positions. Let's
see if they can hold down the Patriots' offense, which is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   --Detroit Lions (away): The Lions have some terrific receivers
that must be contained and a decent defense, but who knows if pass
rusher Robert Porcher will have ended his holdout by Thanksgiving
or whether Charlie Batch will be the quarterback. This is a tough
one because the Patriots play the Browns Nov. 19 and the Lions four
days later.
</P>
<P>
   --Kansas City Chiefs (home): The Chiefs like to control the ball
and pound it up the middle, similar to the Bills, and they always
have an aggressive defense. Elvis Grbac can be rattled into making
mistakes which is Belichick's best chance of creating turnovers and
getting his team into good field position. It's a Monday night game
at home, so it's a definite adrenaline lift.
</P>
<P>
   --Chicago Bears (away): This is really a great matchup:
Belichick's defense vs. Gary Crowton's offense. This may be as good
as it gets in terms of converging strategies. Belichick and Crowton
are arguably as good at what they do as anyone in the league. The
Bears should be much improved and the game is at Soldier Field in
December.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubting that Belichick will have a strong defense,
but if the offense can't move the ball and they have a lot of
three-and-outs, as was the case a year ago, that wears out the
defense. Weis will also have an enormous amount of pressure to put
together a decent offensive line to protect Bledsoe, and will need
Terry Glenn to stay healthy. We'll begin seeing the season unfold a
little at a time starting Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Belichick hopes to inherit from his years with
Parcells is that his teams get stronger as the season goes on.
Belichick must, however, pull out all of his tricks, knowledge, and
ability to get through the first half of the schedule. If the
Patriots can hit their week off on Oct. 29 at 4-4 or 5-3, Belichick
may have fooled the oddsmakers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Signs of the times
</P>
<P>
   When the owners meet in September, the subject of
incentive-filled contracts is likely to be a hot topic.
Spearheading this is Kraft, who would like to see the
``earn-your-pay'' approach be uniform around the league. Kraft's
negotiators, Andy Wasynczuk and Jack Mula, have begun implementing
this approach in the offseason. Mula signed all nine draft picks
using this approach, and though he may have irked an agent or two
along the way, the bottom line is the Patriots got their draft
picks for bargains, holding down the amount of signing bonuses
while going heavy on incentives. Wasynczuk signed Bruce Armstrong
to an incentive-laden deal for the minimum salary, and when he
renegotiated Vincent Brisby's deal recently, the team cut his pay
in half, but added several incentives based on receptions that
could give Brisby the opportunity to earn $2.6 million _ $1.1
million more than his base salary. Kraft runs all of his businesses
this way, offering employees incentives to earn bonuses based on
performance. Preliminary indications are that players union
representative Gene Upshaw would give his blessing to this provided
there are other concessions made. If the NFLPA goes along with this
method of payment, it would be another shot in the arm for NFL
owners, who already are incredibly protected by not having to issue
guaranteed contracts and now can lower the cash outlay on signing
bonuses and pay big money only if a player performs at a high
level. Wouldn't that be Utopia?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Modeling a different role
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe acknowledges he felt a little intimidated when he walked
into Orafino (Idaho) State Maximum Security Prison July 11, but he
feels he's making a difference in the lives of the children of
convicted criminals. Bledsoe's ``Parenting With Dignity'' program
is a comprehensive course offered by the Bledsoe Foundation that
teaches parenting skills. Although prisoners may find it difficult
to take an everyday role in raising their children, they can still
encourage their youngsters not to follow in their footsteps.
Bledsoe thinks the course is working. ``The best evidence I can
share on that is that my dad (Mac, a former school teacher who
authored the program with his wife, Barbara) had been there the
year before and spoken to them and left our program with them. When
we arrived, they were stating back to us things that were in the
program. They had better lines of communication with their
families. It's an area where we can make a difference. I forget the
exact statistic about the percentage of the criminals whose parents
were also criminals. If you can break that cycle and eliminate one
generation of it, you're making inroads.'' Bledsoe spoke to small
groups, totaling about 350 inmates in all. ``When those doors slam
shut, you get a glimpse of what it would be like to have your
freedom taken from you. It was eye-opening. What struck me the most
is if you put them in a different setting they look like one of
your uncles, just regular people who made mistakes. My perception
was that they were going to be hardened criminals, but I felt
differently after spending time with them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lean on me
</P>
<P>
   Patriots punter Lee Johnson, 39 and still going strong, was
indirectly involved in Steve Young's decision to retire. Johnson,
one of Young's best friends, said the former 49er quarterback spoke
to him quite often about whether to retire, but ``in the end it was
his decision. He's always been known to seek out what other people
think. But it was all him and he wavered until the last minute. He
knew he had to do it but he didn't want to do it.'' Johnson doesn't
believe Young would ever want a full-time broadcasting gig, but
``he'd probably do some things on a part-time or special basis.
He's just going to stay in the Bay Area until his baby is born and
then he'll probably leave the area.'' . . . By the time Ronnie
Lott, who was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame Saturday,
had hit New York (1993-94), he was near the end of his career. But
his coach, Pete Carroll, certainly could see why Lott wasn't far
from Canton. ``Nobody tried to hit somebody as hard as he did,''
said Carroll. ``It was really important to him to set that
standard. He was a great competitor, a team leader. Nobody played
with more disregard for his body, yet he played so long. He could
have played in any age. The expectations for himself were so
high.'' . . . So much for the strength and conditioning program
being such a huge factor. Andy Katzenmoyer attended only about a
half-dozen workouts and instead spent most of his time at Ohio
State with strength coach Dave Kennedy. Katzenmoyer returned in
excellent condition. Katzenmoyer realized he needed to be in even
better shape to contend with the rigors of an NFL season. ``It's
very, very long compared to the college season. I started to feel
the injuries that never occurred to me before _ aching joints,
muscles, and stuff like that.'' Now Katzenmoyer is in position to
be a starting inside linebacker with Ted Johnson. He must battle
Tedy Bruschi for the job, but the feeling is that the combination
of Johnson and Katzenmoyer gives the Patriots two huge bodies in
the middle of the field that could shut down the run . . . Former
San Diego Chargers head coach June Jones has to be wondering about
the way things are done in Hawaii where he's the university's head
football coach. The athletic department has rid itself of the
80-year-old rainbow logo partly because, according to AD Hugh
Yoshida, it ``ties in with the gay community.'' They also said it
tied in with Jesse Jackson's Rainbow Coalition and NASCAR driver
Jeff Gordon's pit crew. Now, the football team will have a green
and white ``H'' as a logo and be known as the Warriors. Hmmm. That
invites a whole new set of problems, doesn't it? Adrian Klemm, the
Patriots' second-round pick, has said that he isn't crazy about
returning to Paradise except to see friends. Evidently, Hawaii
isn't a comfortable place for everyone . . . The Peoria Pirates
went 14-0 for the 21-team Indoor Football League, tying the 1972
Dolphins for a season-best mark for a professional football
franchise. The Pirates are coached by Bruce Cowdrey, who, I guess,
had a wide-open style, averaging 55.9 points per game and allowing
27.4 points per game. Talk about home ``arena'' advantage: the
Pirates won by an average margin of 37 points per game . . . The
induction ceremonies here often remind us: Why isn't Gino
Cappelletti enshrined? . . . Parcells may be the next coach
inducted here as early as next season unless he makes another
comeback. He was adamant again about his statement earlier this
winter that he had coached his last game, but a report came out
this week indicating he was thinking of returning to coaching next
season. Parcells denied it vehemently on various talk shows last
week . . . There was no outward sign that the strain of working for
someone like Daniel Snyder had taken its toll on Washington
Redskins' director of college scouting, Joe Mendes, who worked for
the Patriots from 1982-1993. But that's the speculation. Mendes
signed all of those All-Pro players and top rookies to big money,
then split. There have been rumors that Mendes could be rejoining
Charley Casserly in Houston as the expansion franchise's new
capologist, but Mendes said he has no job plans for the moment . .
. Chasing a dream of playing in the NFL isn't for everyone. It
requires great mental and physical toughness, and though the
rewards are plentiful, so is the sacrifice. Those are the issues
Patriots' fifth-round pick Dave Stachelski appears to be wrestling
with as he decides whether to keep pursuing an NFL career or move
on with his life . . . Talk about not living up to expectations.
When the Cardinals amassed a front line of Simeon Rice, Eric Swann,
Mark Smith, and Andre Wadsworth, it was the second coming of the
Purple People Eaters. But it never materialized. Swann was cut,
Rice has never been the force he was supposed to be, Smith has held
out two years in a row, and Wadsworth is injury-prone. The
Cardinals now start Brad Otis, Tony McCoy, Jerry Drake, and Tom
Burke and, the funny thing is, they might be better off . . .
There's Bills-mania at their new training site in Rochester, N.Y.
The Bills have averaged about 6,250 fans per day. Not bad for a
team that lost Bruce Smith, Thurman Thomas, and Andre Reed and is
without Flutie, who will miss the rest of training camp with a
groin tear . . . One place the Patriots might look for defensive
line help is Carolina, which has 11 pretty good linemen including
Reggie White. Tim Morabito, who was signed as a free agent and who
visited with the Patriots during the offseason, may be available .
. . Give Chad Eaton credit for not trying to be a media darling and
everybody's talk show guest and concentrating strictly on football.
Eaton may have taken a step back last year, but don't bet against
him making the Pro Bowl this year . . . It looks like Crowton has a
great chance to be the coordinator in demand in the offseason after
the fine job he did with the Bears' offense last season. Crowton
interviewed with the Patriots and the Krafts still rave about him.
If things had fallen through with Belichick or Capers, Crowton
might have been the head coach in New England. Crowton earns
$275,000 and his salary will increase to $300,000 and $325,000 the
next two years. But Crowton will likely be a top choice for the
Houston job, as will Weis if the Patriots have a big year on
offense . . . The Cowboys have been sending scouts to watch the
Redskins' practice. Because Snyder charges fans $10 to watch
training camp, teams can get around a rule that prohibits teams
from scouting one another in camp. And they have. Evidently, a few
other teams, including the Rams under GM Charlie Armey, have also
had representatives there . . . Despite searching elsewhere, the
Patriots realize that the best site for training camp is Bryant
College. No other facility in New England offers the same amenities
of practice fields, locker rooms, dorms, cafeterias, meeting space,
etc. . . . In a rare moment when Mike Shanahan was actually loose
and relaxed, he cracked a joke. When asked about guard Mark
Schlereth's left knee after 13 operations, he quipped, ``It looks
like a jigsaw puzzle.'' . . . When Carolina meets Jacksonville next
week, watch Panthers quarterback Steve Beuerlein and Jaguars coach
Tom Coughlin. Beuerlein didn't take kindly to Coughlin's staff
violating Pro Bowl rules and blitzing. At the time, Beuerlein
shouted at both Coughlin and defensive coordinator Capers from the
sideline. Beuerlein said he won't hold any grudges. ``We've got
more important things to do than worry about what happened in the
Pro Bowl,'' said Beuerlein. ``We'll never know why exactly things
happened the way they did. But nobody got hurt. I came out of it
fine and I still have an awful lot of respect for both (Coughlin
and Capers).'' . . . Despite New Orleans owner Tom Benson pushing
for Houston to be in the NFC, the AFC owners, led by Kraft, will
insist that Houston be an AFC expansion team. The Texans (OK, I'm
jumping the gun on a nickname) will likely join the AFC Central in
2002. Here's another possibility, when the divisions are reshuffled
somewhat to take the Texans in, watch a possible push for the Colts
to move out of the AFC East and into the Central . . . The Patriots
never entered in talks with Carl Pickens at any time, though they
should have. The deal Pickens accepted with the already talent-rich
Titans, will count only $600,000 against the cap. He does receive a
$4.5 million roster bonus next March and a $1 million base salary.
Difficult to handle at times in Cincinnati, Pickens fired agent
Steve Zucker who had worked so hard on his behalf for so many
years, hired Atlanta-based Hadley Engelhard, and then fired him and
agreed to the deal on his own. Asked about his past problems he
said, ``When everything around you is negative you can't help but
be negative. Here, the players know from Day 1 they're going to win
10, 11, 12 games. What's not to be positive about? That comes from
the confidence they have. I just want to play.'' The advent of
Pickens protects the Titans from Yancey Thigpen's injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
