<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-OSBORNE-SENATERUN     07-29 2977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSBORNE-SENATERUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSBORNE'S STILL THE CHOICE FOR NEBRASKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Neb. _ The building sits in the eastern part of town, a
one-room log cabin next to a municipal swimming pool, which is
strangely empty on this hot July afternoon, in the middle of a
complex of athletic fields that are also empty.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone is surprised. Sure, it's July, but it's also the
middle of the week and there are chores to be done on the farms
that dominate the area in the heart of the biggest congressional
district in Nebraska _ an area that covers four-fifths of the state
and almost 65,000 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   And in a town like Geneva, which is a two-hour ride from Omaha,
in the middle of Fillmore County, there are other concerns, such as
the decline in the price of corn and the steady exodus of the next
generation of farmers to bigger and better things.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a sense of stability here as the weekly luncheon
meeting of the Geneva Rotary Club convenes. Sloppy Joes, corn on
the cob, brownies, and iced tea are on the menu for the 30 or so
people who have gathered not so much for a discussion of their
problems, but to hear ideas on how to solve them. Or at least words
that will make the tough times more digestible.
</P>
<P>
   It is still the heartland of America where the dream lingers,
where a room of people gets on its feet and sings ``My Country 'Tis
of Thee'' and ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic'' with such
sincerity and passion that it sends chills up and down your spine.
</P>
<P>
   It is here that the guest speaker has come to offer his
thoughts. It is here that Tom Osborne comes on this Tuesday
afternoon, with words of hope, with a vision, as he calls it, to
make things better, even if it's only in a sense of being and of
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   It is here that the former football coach at the University of
Nebraska has come with a simple message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have the energy,'' he said. ``And I still feel I have
a little opportunity where I can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Osborne is running, running as hard as he did when he was
guiding the Nebraska Cornhuskers to 255 wins and three national
championships over a 25-year head coaching career that has made him
almost a mythical figure in this state. He is running for the US
Congressional seat in Nebraska's 3d District, a predominantly rural
area that covers almost all of the state except the urban centers
of Omaha and Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   But at 63, three years removed from a retirement from coaching
that he now concedes may have been premature, Osborne may also be
running away from something as well, as he tries to find something
to fill the void in his life that the absence of coaching has
created.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reputation on the rise
</P>
<P>
   He has been running since January when the idea that had been
percolating in his head for the last few years evolved into a
formal announcement of his candidacy. The last time the rest of the
country had an up-close look at Osborne was after the 1998 Orange
Bowl, when a Nebraska romp over Tennessee gave the Huskers a share
of their third national championship.
</P>
<P>
   After so many years of coming up just one short, Osborne put the
cap on a career that for his last five seasons had produced a
stunning 60-3 record. When it came to winning college football
games, no one did better than Osborne and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Not without cost, however. Osborne had given up much during a
head coaching career that began in 1973 as a 36-year-old
replacement for Bob Devaney, the man credited with building the
foundation of Huskers football.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's family _ wife Nancy, son Mike, and daughters Annie and
Suzi _ had seen only glimpses of him during the long seasons that
began for him in late July and didn't end until the conclusion of
the recruiting period in February.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne concedes with some guilt that Nancy had raised the
children virtually by herself and he promised her that, after 25
years, it would be time to do something else.
</P>
<P>
   He also made a similar commitment to longtime aid Frank Solich
the time was coming when he would step down and Solich would be the
man to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne also had concerns about his health. He had heart bypass
surgery in 1985. After that, Osborne lost weight. He changed his
diet, which included giving up red meat _ a tough thing to do
publicly in a state where cattle outnumber people, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Although Osborne has since had no major heart problems, an
irregular heartbeat in his final year of coaching seemed to be
another omen it was time to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   There was more. While the Huskers were winning games and titles
and Osborne was building his reputation in his home state, a series
of off-field incidents involving his players was tarnishing his
reputation outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable incidents involved defensive lineman Christian
Peter and running back Lawrence Phillips. Both were involved in a
series of crimes involving verbal and physical abuse of women that
caused an uproar across the country, made even greater by
Nebraska's high profile as a college football power.
</P>
<P>
   It also caused concern inside the state, with the eyes of
Nebraska turning to Osborne for explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's message was simple: ``Trust me,'' he said. ``You don't
know all the facts. I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's words were sincere. He has always had almost a
missionary zeal for saving souls, for seeing the good in everyone.
He was a coach, but he was more than that, serving as a father
figure to many of the players who came from one-parent families.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, who earned a doctorate in educational psychology at
Nebraska, also recognized the changing times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer a `Leave it to Beaver' era,'' he conceded when
talking about the new generation of athletes that came under his
sphere of influence.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillips incident, however, changed things. Phillips, a
troubled young man who came from a group home environment in
California, had pushed the envelope since his arrival. Osborne gave
him one chance and then another, feeling that if he turned on
Phillips, no one would be there for him.
</P>
<P>
   But when Phillips's temper flared into a physical attack on his
girlfriend _ something Osborne maintains was not as severe as
reported _ Osborne suspended him for six games, a punishment
Osborne's critics say didn't fit the seriousness of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the other incidents involving Nebraska players,
Osborne's image in the minds of many outside of Nebraska was
sealed: just another football coach who would condone anything to
win football games.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the state, there was concern and investigations, but the
ultimate decision was based on the quality of the man Huskers fans
felt they knew. If Tom said it was OK, it was OK.
</P>
<P>
   And that, as much as anything, is what has made his political
future in Nebraska a mortal lock to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Trust in Tom and things will be fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Primary choice
</P>
<P>
   John Gale was feeling pretty good about things nine months ago.
The state Republican Party chairman from North Platte was ready and
eager to fill the void when Bill Barrett, Nebraska's Republican
representative from the 3d District announced he would not seek a
sixth term. And since the 3d District had not elected a Democrat
since it was created following the 1960 census, Barrett felt
reasonably confident that, if he could win the primary in May, he
would be heading to Washington following the general election in
November.
</P>
<P>
   That was until Osborne made his announcement Jan. 27. The
following day, the first polls came out and Osborne had the support
of 72 percent of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Three candidates dropped out immediately. Gale stuck it out, but
with a feeling of inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt pretty overwhelming,'' he said. ``I knew I wasn't
going to win, because name recognition is the major quality of any
campaign. And he has it in spades.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 9, Osborne won the primary with 71 percent of the vote,
setting up a fall campaign against Rollie Reynolds, an insurance
and real estate developer from Grand Island.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, like Gale, is an overwhelming underdog. Although
Reynolds has not conceded the race and has lobbied for a series of
debates (Osborne says he will participate in one), he understands
he dynamics of the state and Osborne's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my hero,'' said Reynolds. ``He's everybody's hero. With a
name recognition like that, how can he lose?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting the agenda
</P>
<P>
   It is 10:45 a.m. and Tom Osborne is running pretty much on
schedule as he pulls up to the Conoco gas station in his Ford
Expedition. He is running a grass-roots campaign as he traverses
the state.
</P>
<P>
   On the schedule this morning is an appearance at the Fillmore
County Fair, a Rotary Club luncheon in Geneva, a tour of a soybean
processing plant in his hometown of Hastings, and a dinner
appearance in Kearney. It has been that way since January, with
only a slight letup after he won the primary. Schools, plants,
county fairs. Breakfasts, lunches, dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like recruiting in a lot of ways,'' says Osborne,
as he gets out of his truck at the county fairgrounds just outside
Geneva. ``Only the agenda is different. I'm not still talking to
parents about their kids, but I'm talking to them about their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne is running as moderate conservative. He has conservative
values, yet he is in favor of a moratorium on the death penalty and
is for limited gun control. They are stands not normally associated
with conservatives in the heartland. He also placed a limit on
campaign spending and funding. He said he will accept no PAC money
and limits contributions to $300.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne is in the heart of farm country. The price of a bushel
of corn has dropped to $1.50. Farmers are looking at fields that
are rich with crops, but without markets that can get them fair
market values, in their opinion.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, as he has done most of the time, Osborne travels
without fanfare. There is no entourage, just Tom driving with
friends who serve as county coordinators. This time it is Bob
Bettger, a farmer who has 4,500 acres of land, and grows mostly
corn and soybean.
</P>
<P>
   Bettger, like most farmers in the area, concedes Osborne does
not have in politics. He acknowledges that someone like Rollie
Reynolds might have better qualifications, but he says Osborne
still has the trump card. He's Tom Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got stature,'' says Bettger, a 1971 Nebraska graduate and
a Huskers season ticket-holder. ``He wants to do what's best for
the 3d District.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne stands, watching the judging of hogs for leanness and
quality. His initial presence is subtle. A few look his way. Then a
few more. Within five minutes, he is surrounded. Children come up
for autographs. Adults come by to shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is what he's done for us,'' says Don
Bristol, a farmer, who brought his wife and children to the fair
for the day. ``People believe in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol is worried. He is a farmer and he is worried about his
future, about that of his family. ``The situation in the farm
community is pretty bleak,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is leaning toward voting for Osborne, although he
hadn't heard Osborne's opinion on farm issues. ``I'm hoping there
will be a debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he pauses. Barring some gigantic gaffe, he will vote for
Osborne. He concedes there is a danger Osborne might not be
qualified, that despite the effort Osborne has made to get up to
speed on issues concerning farmers, he might not be able to provide
any help.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a concern,'' he says. ``But what's our alternative?''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne is formally introduced to the crowd. He makes some small
talk, takes note of a hog that is a little too frisky, and jokes
about how he can use all the votes he can get.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd laughs. The message is clear. It is not so much the
message. Rollie Reynolds or anyone else can talk about the problems
of Fillmore County and farmers. They can talk about the quality of
life. But it's not the same.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Osborne can say it and it means something, because Tom
Osborne is saying it.
</P>
<P>
   Later, even Osborne concedes that. He has talked about farm
issues and education. Now he is talking about hope. Not only for
the next generation of Nebraska farmers, but for the folks sitting
in front of him who have raised their children and made sacrifices
for them and now are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a vision,'' he tells them. ``I believe in the potential
of young people and usually they respond to that vision.''
</P>
<P>
   He alludes to his handling of the Lawrence Phillips situation.
``Most people in Nebraska felt I tried to do the right thing,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about his commitment and how he feels he can make a
difference. ``This isn't just a two-year commitment,'' he says. ``I
hope to do it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Run is deep-rooted
</P>
<P>
   Things are quiet at the Tom Osborne campaign headquarters in
Hastings. No phones ringing. A muted television in the background,
giving grim details of the crash of the Air France Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   This is where it all began for Osborne more than 60 years ago.
``Just up the street a few blocks from Hastings College,'' Osborne
says with a smile. ``That's where I grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after all these years, he remains a mystery to all but his
closest friends, not showing too much of anything. He is a
Nebraskan to his toenails, tall, a bit worn, but of good stock.
This has been his home. Always will be, even when he goes to
Washington, he makes it clear he will not live there. ``Tuesday,
Wednesday, and Thursday,'' he says. ``Then it's back here. This is
where my interest lies, not Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne has been a star all his life. In high school and at
college he was voted the Nebraska athlete of the year. Yet even
then, more than 45 years ago, he had formed his personality.
</P>
<P>
   Some would call it aloof. Others call it arrogant or conceited.
Even Nancy, his wife of 38 years, found him ``obnoxious'' on their
first date.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's classmates called him ``Yak,'' a swipe at his
reticence in talking very much. Osborne resented the nickname, but
conceded he had an early defense mechanism that precluded him from
showing anger or joy.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the town where his personality and values were
formed, he is very much a real figure.
</P>
<P>
   He is making this run for Congress because he feels it is his
calling, because he has yet more to give. His net worth, estimated
between $6 million and $16 million, is not an issue. He will give
to charity, and says that when he dies, most of it will go to
charity after he takes care of his family.
</P>
<P>
   But he wants to give back more to the state, to the people who
have supported him for so long. He concedes he thought about making
a run for governor two years ago but the timing wasn't right. He
wasn't ready. He needed time to assess what was inside of him.
</P>
<P>
   He says he knows it will be rough at first. Politics and sport
are alike in some ways and different in many others. Others who
have ventured into the political arena after a career in athletics
have told him so.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Watts is a Republican congressman from Oklahoma who played
quarterback for the Sooners against Osborne's teams. Watts, who is
chairman of the House Republican Conference and regarded as a
rising Republican star, says politics and sports have vast
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would find a place where the egos were as
big as they were in athletics,'' said Watts. ``Then I entered
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Watts said he has faith in Osborne's abilities. ``I told
him, `You are going to be fine, whatever you do,' '' said Watts.
``But this business is much different from football and athletics.
In football, you measure success every week. In politics, sometimes
it takes years. In this business, there aren't a whole lot of
40-yard gains. But rather 4 yards here and 10 yards there and
pretty soon you will score.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Seattle Seahawks wide receiver Steve Largent, also a
Republican congressman from Oklahoma, said Osborne has qualities
that can overcome the obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has a lot of credibility,'' said Largent. ``He's so
much more than X's and O's. He lifts the perceptions of the office
we all hold. He enhances what we're about. The general perception
is somewhere just above used-car salesman. To have a person like
this is the best way to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who don't come from sports see a tougher road. Veteran
congressman Marty Meehan (D-Mass.) said, ``It's a lot different
than being head coach at Nebraska, where you say this is what we're
going to run on offense, and this is what we're going to run on
defense, and anyone that doesn't like it, there's the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different in Congress. You have to form
partnerships and friendships over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Meehan concedes Osborne's persona will help. ``Other
members will want to get to know him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That too will be difficult. Osborne is what he is. He is
unlikely to change or bend or veer off course. He said he toyed
briefly with the idea of getting back into coaching last season as
two schools, Houston and Michigan State, made overtures.
</P>
<P>
   But his Nebraska roots were too deep. Now he is ready for
another challenge, another venue, a modern-day Jefferson Smith, the
ideal young congressman played by Jimmy Stewart in the classic film
``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne says he has never seen the movie, but has heard the
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably get my head handed to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But considering who Tom Osborne is and what he has done, don't
count on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
