<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-NY     07-29 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT, AT WIFE'S CAMPAIGN FUND-RAISER, STRESSES DIFFERENCES IN
PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Heaping lavish praise on his wife as the most
intelligent and passionate person he has ever met, President
Clinton exhorted a small but generous clutch of contributors in
Manhattan Saturday to guard against complacency in a time of
prosperity and to remember the vast differences between Republicans
and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good-times elections are as big a test of our judgment and
our values and our national character as the tough-times
elections,'' he said, speaking at a luncheon fund-raiser sponsored
by Korean-American organizations at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The event collected $250,000 for Hillary Rodham Clinton's U.S.
Senate bid. ``Remind your fellow Americans not to go to sleep in
this election year, that what you do in good times is just as
important, maybe more important, as what you do in bad times, in
elections. Elections are choices with real consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The president repeatedly emphasized what he described as the
``huge differences'' between the two parties, singling out tax
cuts, gun safety laws and hate crimes legislation as examples.
</P>
<P>
   But even though his remarks seemed to be less about the Senate
race than about the larger contest between Republicans and
Democrats, he had nothing but praise for his wife, the candidate at
the center of Saturday's fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the hundreds of people I've known, including many
presidents and candidates for presidents, I have never known anyone
who had the same combination of intelligence and passion and
knowledge and ability to get things done for children, for
families, for education, for health care as my wife does,'' he said
in introducing Mrs. Clinton. ``She can do things and she knows
things that no one else now in our public life can do and know,
just because of the life she's lived.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was an equally lavish display of admiration. Mrs.
Clinton, who has tethered her campaign to the successes of the
Clinton administration over the last eight years, urged her
audience to make election-year choices that would continue those
successes, giving her husband credit for reducing crime,
introducing health care for poor children and trimming the welfare
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country is a better place today than in 1992 because of
his leadership, and I'm very appreciative,'' she said. ``We all
have a choice, to decide whether we go forward together or make a
U-turn back to the past.''
</P>
<P>
   What effect Saturday's audience would have on her race, though,
remained unclear. Organizers of the event estimated that a quarter
of the contributors came from out of state, and a few of the most
prominent donors said they had not yet decided whom to vote for.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser was organized by Albert Kwak, a businessman from
Iowa City who said he was approached by a friend of the president's
_ a Cleveland businessman, Tony George _ to arrange a
Korean-American function for Mrs. Clinton's campaign. Neither Kwak
nor another organizer, Gilliam Kim, the owner of a Chicago cellular
telephone company, would say how much they donated.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides said Saturday that the gathering of about 200
people had generated roughly $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's event was Mrs. Clinton's second fund-raiser among
Korean-Americans. The first, held two weeks ago at a Korean
restaurant in Flushing, N.Y., in Queens County, raised about
$60,000, campaign aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton praised Korean-Americans for their educational
achievements, noted her support for a federal hate crimes law and
applauded the contributions of immigrants to New York, pointing to
a recent report that concluded that 40 percent of all New York City
residents today were born outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a wonderful statistic,'' she said. ``New York
is really the world.''
</P>
<P>
   She repeated her call for affordable health care, money to equip
old schools with new technology, and prescription drug benefits for
the elderly on Medicare. Her remarks were notable only in that she
said nothing about her Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio. Last
week, she urged him to engage in a series of debates and excoriated
his links to a group with unorthodox views on the causes of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, in agreeing to debate, suggested three locations. Two of
them had been scheduled months ago, when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was
considering running for the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Mrs. Clinton's aides said she would debate him
anywhere, at any time.
</P>
</TEXT>
