<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-29 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOOR TO HALL A LITTLE WIDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio did not make it on the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Joe DiMaggio who, 15 years after his
inexplicable rejection from the Baseball Hall of Fame, was named
``The Greatest Living Ballplayer'' by the same sort of people, one
presumes, who couldn't see clear to put him into the Hall on the
first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: Do not expect to find any easy answers when
the question is ``Why is/isn't so-and-so in the Hall of Fame?''
</P>
<P>
   The actual process is not difficult. Eligible members of the
Baseball Writers' Association of America receive a ballot listing
eligible players (last year there were 30). A voter may vote for as
many as 10. If no candidates appear worthy, the voter signs a blank
ballot and returns it to BBWAA secretary-treasurer Jack O'Connell.
It is not like football, for which a 36-member committee meets
Super Bowl week with a mandate to select a minimum of four
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The process may not be difficult, but the decision certainly is.
Whereas once the standards used to decide the worthiness of the
candidates were ludicrously high _ Joe DiMaggio not a first-ballot
Hall of Famer? _ the standards that have evolved have created a
Hall of Fame that includes many players the hard markers among us
feel are unworthy of the honor. Once the damage (if that is the
proper word) has been done, a decision must be made. When presented
with a ``borderline'' Hall of Fame candidate, do I adhere to the
current standards? Or do I arbitrarily raise the bar in a haughty,
perhaps even quixotic, show of defiance?
</P>
<P>
   A truly caring voter agonizes when presented with the ballot.
Anointing someone as a Baseball Hall of Famer means you are
changing his life. Isn't that silly, when you think about it? Is
Tony Perez a better player, or, more important, a better person,
than he was nine months ago? We know better. He was a fine player,
and he has always been an honorable and much-respected man. He's no
different now than he was in 1999, '89, or '79. But now he's a
certified Hall of Famer. He has increased stature, and, as he will
soon learn, access to more income.
</P>
<P>
   Does he really belong? Well, sure, if you compare him with the
likes of Billy Williams, Willie Stargell, Duke Snider, Jim
Bottomley, Earle Combs, Rick Ferrell, Elmer Flick, Chuck Klein,
Billy Herman, Harry Hooper, George Kell, Fred Lindstrom, Dave
Bancroft, Jess Haines, Eppa Rixey, Red Schoendienst, and Ross
Youngs, the last 14 of whom were chosen by the controversial
Veterans' Committee after being continually rejected by the
writers. But was he ``great,'' in the sense that Lou Gehrig and
George Sisler were ``great?'' He was not.
</P>
<P>
   The Baseball Hall of Fame has major gradations, and I mean
major. It's a big drop from Babe Ruth, Ty Cobb, Christy Mathewson,
and Rogers Hornsby to George Kelly, Chick Hafey, Jim Bunning and,
yes, Tony Perez. And speaking of Hornsby, did you know that the
righthanded hitter with the highest career batting average of all
time (.358) did not make it on the first ballot, either? You want
to talk about strict constructionists.
</P>
<P>
   Although some pine for those type of Good Old Voting Days,
they're not coming back. We have a very inclusionary Hall of Fame,
and as a result we have any number of borderline candidates who
fall under the category of ``If him, why not him?'' Usually, there
is no good answer.
</P>
<P>
   There is much confusion concerning the voting process. Do not,
for example, put any credence in the idea that Perez was being
``snubbed'' or ``overlooked'' during his first nine years on the
ballot because he was a Latin American. He said during his
acceptance speech that he hopes the door is now open for such
fellow Latins as Tony Oliva, Luis Tiant, Dave Concepcion, and
Minnie Minoso.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bogus issue. Each man's case is different. Injuries
greatly restricted Oliva's career. As for the other two, it just so
happens that I, for one, vote for Tiant and Concepcion every year,
and will continue to do so as long as each is on the ballot. Looie
needs no intros around here, and I maintain Concepcion was the best
all-around shortstop between World War II and Ozzie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   As for Minoso, he is one of my two main personal crusades (Bill
Mazeroski being the other). Minoso, a dark-skinned Cuban, didn't
get to spend a full season in the bigs until 1951, when he was 28.
(He played nine games with the Indians in 1949.) He then batted
better than .300 seven times while scoring more than 100 runs four
times, driving in more than 100 four times, leading the league in
triples three times, stolen bases three times, doubles once, and
hits once. He was a noted scrapper and hustler whose presence
energized teams.
</P>
<P>
   His is a criminal omission, and shame on my fellow voters for
allowing his name to languish on the ballot for 15 years without
enough people doing the requisite homework.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is half-right. Heritage has everything to do with Minoso
not being in. Had he been allowed to play before age 28, he'd have
put up tremendous career numbers. He should not be forgotten. But
people didn't go past his name because they were racists. It's
because they were intellectually lazy.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to the Veterans' Committee to do the right thing for
a man who was a victim of history and circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   It took Perez nine years to get in because he did not have a
compelling case; that's why. It's why Jim Rice is not in and Bert
Blyleven is not in and our friend Luis Tiant is not in. They have
interesting cases. They do not have open-and-shut cases, like, say,
Ted Williams, Bob Feller, or George Brett.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned that there were 30 names on last year's ballot. In
my judgment, 11 of them have absolutely no business being there.
You may look at the same list and decide to increase or decrease
that number by one or two, but I'd bet we'd be in general
agreement. After that, let the arguments begin!
</P>
<P>
   I could make a devil's advocate case for all of my remaining 19
possibilities. I could make a strong devil's advocate case for 12
(Blyleven, Gary Carter, Concepcion, Carlton Fisk, Tommy John, Jim
Kaat, Jack Morris, Dale Murphy, Perez, Rice, Bruce Sutter, and
Tiant). In the end, I voted for Carter, Concepcion, Fisk, Rice, and
Tiant. Notice I did not vote for Perez. I trust this doesn't make
me a bad person.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult, and it will get even harder next year when Don
Mattingly, Kirby Puckett, Dave Stewart, Lou Whitaker, and Dave
Winfield are newcomers to the ballot. I'd say that Puckett and
Winfield should be considered locks. Then again, no one has ever
been unanimous. DiMaggio was made to wait in the corner for a year.
And someone once voted for Terry Puhl. I have enough trouble
explaining me, let alone someone who would waste a precious vote on
Terry Puhl.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
