<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-TRADES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENCY, CAPS DOOM THREE-WAY DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With free agency, an intriguing trade proposal never entirely
fades from memory. A three-way deal involving the Celtics, Nuggets,
and Clippers collapsed under the weight of salary and draft pick
demands that would not be met. It was unofficially pronounced dead
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But a proposed deal sending free agent guards Tariq Abdul-Wahad
to the Celtics and Derek Anderson to the Nuggets could still be
alive. Depending on where much-talked-about free agent forward
Austin Croshere goes (Toronto) or stays (Indiana), the Raptors
might enter the Celtics-Nuggets dealings. (``I think Toronto may be
involved after they're done with Croshere and people like that,''
said Celtics coach and president Rick Pitino Friday. ``Maybe (the
Raptors) would be brought into the equation.'') If Croshere does
not end up in Toronto, the Raptors would make an appealing
under-the-cap partner in a possible deal. Resuscitation efforts
started Friday and continue.
</P>
<P>
   The odd lifecycle of the proposed three-way trade illustrates
the difficulty of deal-making in the NBA. For a team with no cap
room like the Celtics (and the majority of NBA franchises), a
successful deal must satisfy a number of interests and
basketball/business philosophies. Some teams balk at paying the
luxury tax that comes into play for the 2001-2002 season. Some
teams prefer stocking draft picks. Some teams choose not to take
action until key free agents are settled, diminishing the risk of
overpaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any deal that you do, unless you're talking about two players
straight up _ which means that their salaries are within 15 percent
and $100,000 of each other and their contracts are roughly the same
_ there are stumbling blocks because each team has its own rules
that it operates under,'' said Celtics general manager Chris
Wallace. ``Putting a whole group's interests together, several
parties in one, is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Team presidents, general managers, player personnel directors,
and coaches spend much of the free agency period _ which ends
Tuesday _ recruiting players and talking on the phone, trying to
find out where teams stand and what their options are. Boston-based
agent Mike Martin contends that any multiteam deal is difficult to
complete because the teams, players, and agents all hear different
news that sways their decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really happens is by the time you get to what you're
being told, so many other things are happening,'' said Martin, who
represents Fall River's Chris Herren, a player involved in the
original Celtics-Nuggets-Clippers proposal. ``The bottom line is
everybody says it's easy to match up dollars, but that's tough to
do. How do you speculate what a Derek Anderson's going to make or
get in the free agency market. If people are putting numbers
together, it's all speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Celtics' front office will go after a player it
covets, deal-makers Pitino and Wallace are restricted financially
by future league stipulations, like the luxury tax, and current
rules regarding exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   A tax system goes into effect in the 2001-02 season. At the end
of next season, the NBA will derive a figure (estimated to be in
the low $50 million range) from auditing the league's books. If a
team salary exceeds that figure, it will pay a ``dollar for
dollar'' tax or luxury tax to the league for the amount it exceeds
the figure.
</P>
<P>
   Teams such as the Mavericks and Trail Blazers seem to view the
luxury tax as the cost of winning. But the Celtics and many other
franchises do not want to pay the luxury tax, avoiding long-term
contracts that could push them dangerously close to the anticipated
limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's monumental because we have a budget to live by,''
said Pitino. ``There are so many things out there that we would
like. (The budget) stopped us from signing Danny Fortson. It
stopped us from offering and going out of character for Ron Mercer
back when. We have a budget we live by and we stick by it to stay
away from this tax. The luxury tax is just not something we'll get
into . . . Our owners are adamant against paying a luxury tax and
we realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of their NBA brethren, the Celtics have the
league-allowed exemptions, a salary slot at $2.25 million and
another at $1.2 million. Unless they can come to terms on a
three-way deal involving a team under the cap, the Celtics must
wait for players to filter down to their level. Not an appealing
option for a power broker like Pitino who is bent on action.
(``There are about five or six teams in the league that'll pull the
trigger,'' said Pitino. ``We're one of them.'')
</P>
<P>
   Boston chose to reach for talent considered above the exemption
level, making shooting guards (namely Abdul-Wahad, Anderson, and
Mercer) priorities. Abdul-Wahad was already offered a $32 million
contract from the Nuggets that he turned down. But a player does
not push away $32 million and take $2.25 million so he can enjoy
winters with a view of the frozen Charles River.
</P>
<P>
   Although the admiration between Abdul-Wahad and Pitino appears
mutual, the player's agent had a much more practical outlook.
Unless Wallace ``became a magician,'' Paco Belassen thought it
would be impossible to complete a deal with only the Celtics. Time
and again, Belassen has said his client will not settle for the
exception, believing Abdul-Wahad is worth approximately $5 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   As Tuesday draws closer, agents are more apt to consider all
scenarios open to their clients. Tony Dutt set Tuesday as the date
he will discuss options with his client Anderson. At the start of
the month, the best case Dutt envisioned was a sign and trade,
allowing the Clippers to explore opportunities. Now, Dutt is no
longer content to wait, reasoning that if Anderson must play for
the exemption, it should be on a team such as Miami or San Antonio,
which are said to have cap room in 2001-2002. Dutt does not want
his player left out in the cold, an exemption player on a team that
will not provide a good fit or delayed payday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's world with the new collective bargaining agreement,
free agency is not really what it says,'' said Dutt. ``You have to
be under the cap to even make a run (at a player) and there's very
few teams under the cap because of the fact they go over the cap to
sign their guys. So the teams that are really taking care of their
guys are the teams that don't have any money. You have to be
prepared to make some hard decisions at some point. We knew all
along that a sign and trade could be difficult because it means
everybody's got to be happy and that's not an easy thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Players like Grant Hill, Tim Duncan, and Tracy McGrady are the
few lucky free agents. They agreed to deals early (Hill and McGrady
heading to Orlando and Duncan remaining in San Antonio). When the
negotiating period started July 1, it was a seller's market.
</P>
<P>
   As the final week of July passes, free agents face a buyer's
market. Some teams ask themselves, ``Why overpay now when players
might take less later?'' But it can be a risky strategy when most
free agents have more than one suitor and some franchises will meet
money or year demands.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the decision on deals often rests with the team
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some owners, this is a hobby for them and they'll throw
money around,'' said Martin. ``Other ones run a tighter business
and they worry about the bottom line. If that's the case, that's
why I think trades like this (Celtics-Nuggets-Clipper) seem like
they're getting done and they don't get done. It's usually because
everybody involved up until that point who is a decision-maker has
agreed, and then you get to him (the owner) and it's, `No way.'
It's his money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
