</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-GARBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARBER SEES MLS AMONG ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS _ MLS commissioner Don Garber made an ambitious
statement during his state of the league address last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be among the leading soccer leagues in the
world,'' Garber said. ``That dream is achievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching a typical MLS game often makes that dream seem either
far-fetched. But when D.C. United defeats Vasco da Gama of Brazil
or Newcastle United of England, the dream comes slightly more into
focus.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a feel-good time in the league, Garber is still in
the honeymoon stage of his reign, and the investors have committed
funding through 2003, despite decreasing attendance and sustaining
losses of about $50 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   And Garber, wisely, did not place a timetable on his goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be five or 10 years, or it might take 50 or 100
years,'' said Mark Noonan, the MLS executive vice president of
marketing and fan development. ``You have to think of it as a
process and we are at the beginning. That is how the investors see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The MLS is in its fifth year and is far behind the more
sophisticated leagues in England, France, Germany, Italy, and Spain
_ the top five leagues in the world. But the US is fertile
territory for soccer development, and even bucolic outposts such as
Ohio are becoming home to aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a crowd of 18,212 attended the Columbus
Crew-Newcastle United exhibition at the Lamar Hunt-built Crew
Stadium. Saturday, 23,495 tickets were sold for the MLS All-Star
game. And, judging by the pre-game introductions, those fans are
knowledgeable and opinionated. Lothar Matthaus, the controversial
MetroStars defender, was almost unanimously booed by citizens whose
major tourist attractions include the Germantown culinary district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting with (Newcastle players) Alan Shearer and Duncan
Ferguson when they played Columbus, and they were knocked out about
the quality of play,'' Miami Fusion coach Ray Hudson said. ``They
had no idea it would be as good as it is. They thought it was going
to just be banging into everyone. They were genuinely impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got every right to be optimistic but we shouldn't be too
eager. It's evolving well by itself. I just hope that we can bring
in the players that can't be nurtured by the college system, the
ones with the God-given talent. We don't need any more of the
athletic-type player. We need the ones who can take your breath
away. Marco Etcheverry. Carlos Valderrama. Mamadou Diallo is like
that _ he just has that something.''
</P>
<P>
   In its mission statement, the MLS hoped to be ``competitive on
an international level'' and ``to provide affordable family
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Garber, though, has increased the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the first time I've heard something like that from the
league,'' agent Cory Clemetson said. ``And it's important because
nobody wants to be second-best in this country, much less the No. 5
sports league.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good indication of how serious their intentions are will be
how they handle Cobi Jones's contract. If you are not going to
reward Cobi Jones who are you going to reward?''
</P>
<P>
   Clemetson is hoping to gain a contract worth $1 million annually
for Jones. The league's stated maximum salary, though, is less than
$300,000, and team salary caps are $2 million for the total player
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   No other soccer league in the world has salary caps. In fact,
instead of colluding to suppress salaries, the top leagues are
spending more than ever. The recent transfer of Portguese star Luis
Figo from Barcelona cost Real Madrid $56.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though MLS owners such as Los Angeles's Phil Anschutz
could compete with the riches of Lazio and Manchester United, they
are choosing to play it safe with the MLS. Among the first steps
for the league is to build stadia such as the Crew, a $28 million
project with a capacity of 22,555.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz has unveiled plans for a $100 million, 29,000-capacity
stadium in Carson, Calif., for the Los Angeles Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee it will be a model not only for facilities in this
country but a model for facilities anywhere in the world,'' Garber
said.
</P>
<P>
   But building stadia and pouring money into soccer does not
guarantee success. Bolivia, for instance, has a third-world
economy, poor infrastructure and a small population, yet has
produced two of the most inspiring and successful players in the
MLS, Marco Etcheverry and Jaime Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not producing those players, but eventually we will,''
Hudson said. ``That is the type of thing that can't be rushed. You
can't create magic. That is something that can never be
manufactured. You don't know where the next (Diego) Maradona is
going to come from. George Best came from a shanty town in Ireland.
The next one (phenom) might come from El Salvador or Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming clear, though, that the creative players will not
be produced within the US system. In fact, the system appears to be
stifling creativity, discouraging individual enterprise. The US
will have athletes and goalkeepers, but creativity and skill will
have to be imported. And, until players begin capturing the
imagination, soccer will struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I graduated from college in 1987, John Kerr had gone to
Portsmouth and everyone thought it was great that he made the
team,'' Noonan said. ``A generation later, John Harkes goes to
England and is in the starting lineup for Sheffield Wednesday and
scores the goal of the year against Peter Shilton. Now you have
Kasey Keller and Claudio Reyna as important cogs on their teams.
The next generation, hopefully, will produce the best one or two
players on teams, whether it is Landon Donovan (Bayer Leverkusen)
or whoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last six years, we have had two World Cups in the US,
and a professional league which is getting better. We are sending
players like Eddie Lewis (Fulham) and Joe-Max Moore (Everton) to
Europe, but at some point players are going to want to stay home.
If we can make everything equal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
