<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-HEISMAN-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
TCU USES WEB TO WIN HEISMAN VOTES FOR LaDAINIAN TOMLINSON 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ ``He loves his momma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves his Big Uglies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, and he also loves to run.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, those three sentences pop up on your computer screen
at the launch of LaDainian Tomlinson's cyberspace home in perfect
sequence with the radio call of a 70-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic stuff to be sure. The kind of stuff that scares up the
goose bumps on any fan of the record-setting TCU running back who
led the nation in rushing last season.
</P>
<P>
   But those same three lines are more than just the Web site intro
at www.LTfor2000.com. They are the essence of a campaign aimed at
having Tomlinson join Davey O'Brien on TCU's Heisman Trophy mantel.
\Nsubheds:THE CAMPAIGN Work on Tomlinson's 2000 Heisman bid
seemingly began moments after TCU knocked off East Carolina in
December in the Mobile Alabama Bowl. A TCU committee of four worked
diligently developing, preparing and launching Tomlinson's bid for
college football's most prestigious award.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson has been involved in every stage of the campaign,
offering suggestions and giving his blessing on each aspect. Frogs
coach Dennis Franchione also is kept aware, making sure his star
isn't spread too thin and the whole to-do doesn't become too much
of a distraction for the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson's Web site has received more 5,000 visitors since the
June 30 launch, the site's organizers said, and more than 1,000
people have registered for e-mail updates. And TCU's season doesn't
start until Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione said Tomlinson's renown brings welcome attention to a
program on the upswing the past two seasons. Tomlinson's
willingness to credit his teammates, especially the offensive
linemen, keeps everyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   So the TCU machine charges ahead, not only wanting to educate
the sports world on Tomlinson's numbers _ and there are many _ but
also seeking to go beyond and humanize the 21-year-old senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know LT not just as a football player, but as
a person,'' said Trey Carmichael, TCU's assistant media relations
director. ``A big part of our Web site is to focus him off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pick up the paper on Sunday and see what his stats
are, but you don't know LT the person by reading the stats. We
wanted to get that smile out there; the importance of family to LT.
Granted, that won't win you the Heisman, but you could lose the
Heisman if you don't have the great background.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's Peter Warrick might have lost the Heisman last
season for that reason. Warrick's arrest for grand theft in a
Florida department store raised questions about his character and
negated his on-the-field feats.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson had a legal scare last summer when he and two other
men were arrested on suspicion of marijuana possession, but the
charges were later dropped. Tomlinson, however, admitted great
embarrassment, and from that point the self-confessed mama's boy
has tried to act like an Eagle Scout.
</P>
<P>
   TCU wanted to make sure that image _ and that smile _ are the
lasting impressions on Tomlinson's Web site, the cornerstone of its
Hesiman campaign, privately financed at a cost of $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Go online and peek into ``LT's World'' to catch video
highlights, such as the 70-yard run, and sound bytes from postgame
interviews. Did you know the first time Tomlinson touched the ball
as a peewee football player, he scored a touchdown? It's in ``LT's
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper your PC with pictures of No. 5 diving into the end
zone or throwing out the first pitch at The Ballpark in Arlington.
Register and receive weekly e-mail updates on Tomlinson's latest
stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Web site,'' Tomlinson said. ``I never thought I'd
have one. It is fun to show people you have a Web site. People can
keep up with me even though they don't come to games.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cyberage, Web sites are necessary to any Heisman
campaign. Purdue's Drew Brees and Virginia Tech's Michael Vick, the
preseason Heisman favorites, each have their own. Carmichael and
Victor Neil, director of new media, studied other sites and
borrowed certain facets for Tomlinson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Brees' and Vicks', and they have a lot of stuff
dealing with football, and everybody does that,'' Tomlinson said.
``We did a great job trying to do something different. It's nice to
know I have a different Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael also contacted different media relations departments,
such as Texas, Georgia Tech, Wisconsin and Marshall, to get a
better understanding of Heisman campaigns at those schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find out what they did, to see what they did
right and what they did wrong,'' Carmichael said. ``That's why I
called schools that won the Heisman and schools that didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire campaign _ posters, billboards, bumper stickers and
mailouts, including a letter from respected sportswriter Dan
Jenkins, a TCU alumnus _ is focused to reach two groups, identified
by TCU as the media and, appropriately, the non-media _ or everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see bumper stickers on the back of cars and posters, and
it's fun to see that,'' Tomlinson said. ``You're thankful for the
support, but there's also an embarrassing side. Sometimes I'm with
my friends or a cousin and they see that stuff and make fun of it.
I don't want to seem like I'm better than anyone else, but I enjoy
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The TCU media relations office is out to blanket influential
media types at organizations such as ESPN and ``Sports
Illustrated'', as well as reporters, columnists and commentators
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   When ESPN's Chris Fowler visited Fort Worth recently to film a
promo spot at Amon Carter Stadium, Carmichael arranged a lunch
meeting with Tomlinson. The purpose: the host of ``College
GameDay'' and the Heisman hopeful have a history. It might lead to
an on-air personal anecdote. \Nsubheds:THE RESULT All the bells and
all the whistles won't mean a thing if Tomlinson doesn't get it
done on the field and the Frogs fail to fulfill their promising
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson probably needs to rush for at least 2,000 yards to
have a shot at the Heisman _ as long as TCU finishes 9-2 or better
in their last Western Athletic Conference season.
</P>
<P>
   ``LaDainian has been told this many times,'' Carmichael said,
``you can't win the Heisman if your team isn't any good.''
</P>
<P>
   It's going to take the boffo combo of stats and team ranking for
Tomlinson to nose out the likes of Brees, Vick and others. But that
doesn't mean it can't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson rushed for 1,850 yards last season and set an all-time
single-game Division I-A record with 406 yards against UT-El Paso.
The Frogs are a certain preseason top 25 pick in the major polls _
they are in every preseason magazine _ and their schedule has a
cake walk quality.
</P>
<P>
   If all falls into place, TCU hopes to see Tomlinson at least
invited to the New York Downtown Athletic Club in December. But if
Tomlinson isn't a Heisman finalist, it doesn't mean the campaign
failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to show that LaDainian is very typical of the kind
of student we have here at TCU,'' said Kelli Horst, TCU's director
of communications. ``This is LT the person, behind the helmet. We
are all very proud of him and that pride is fostered throughout
campus.''
</P>
<P>
   And like Tomlinson's smile, that can't be bought or taken away.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
