<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS START ON EVE OF REPUBLICAN EVENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Kelly Carlisle of Houston joined thousands of
demonstrators Saturday in a campaign almost as well organized as
the Republican National Convention they are protesting.
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle was among those rallying near the Liberty Bell for
tougher gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters placed thousands of shoes in Independence Park
before starting a silent march to send a message to Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the expected Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a governor that wants to be president,'' Carlisle
said. ``Texans need to make our voices heard.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention starts Monday, but several demonstrations were
held over the weekend, including an anti-abortion rally at a
Planned Parenthood clinic and a health care march through an area
called Center City that drew about 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have planned events throughout the week on a variety
of issues, such as gun violence, abortion rights, poverty, health
care and corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the demonstrators have united under an umbrella group
called the R2K Network. The leaders of R2K are the same
anti-government organizers who coordinated demonstrations during
the world trade talks in Seattle last year and in Washington this
spring, when hundreds were arrested near the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Coordinators say demonstrators have agreed to a nonviolence
pact. They plan to use marches, rallies and other peaceful
disruptions, like sit-ins and human blockades, to draw attention to
their causes.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers concede, however, that some may stray from
nonviolence. If so, police say they are ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are security experts that think we're not
prepared,'' said Philadelphia police Commissioner John Timoney. ``I
beg to differ. I think we can handle whatever comes our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Two animal rights activists were detained Saturday after police
found them at a gas station with a rental truck filled with manure.
Police said the men planned to dump it at the First Union Center,
where the convention is being held. Officers had to release them
because they had not committed a crime, however.
</P>
<P>
   Another man was arrested for possession of a device that could
launch potatoes. Police described the device as a weapon and said
the man could face unspecified criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said his 7,000 officers have been trained to keep their
tempers in check. Although any violence will be dealt with swiftly,
he said, civil disobedience will be handled with what he called an
``understanding of the philosophical underpinnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Timoney denies that his department is bent on using tear gas on
crowds. That would happen only if there is an ``extreme''
situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With tens of thousands of hits on its member organizations'
Internet sites each month, the R2K Network has had little trouble
organizing what one site says will be the ``shenanigans'' in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   One site gives tips on what protesters should bring _ sleeping
bags, bowls, utensils and water jugs. Helpful hints include using
sunscreen lotion sparingly because it can trap pepper spray in skin
pores.
</P>
<P>
   A contingency of lawyers is on standby to help protesters who
are arrested. And a group of legal observers will be at each
demonstration to watch for improper arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The city issued permits for the weekend events. But political
observers and thousands of journalists will be watching Monday as
the Kensington Welfare Rights Union, the city's largest advocacy
group for the poor and homeless, marches without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said his department has tried to reach a compromise with
members of the group, promising them safe escort if they use
sidewalks, which do not require a permit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
