<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-HEISMAN-SWINK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Long before Web sites, TCU's Swink almost connected with Heisman 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MONSERUD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram Frogs Fab Four Four TCU players have finished in the top five in
Heisman voting. TCU quarterback Sam Baugh had his greatest
collegiate season in 1935, the first year of the Heisman, but
players west of the Mississippi weren't eligible to win the award.
Year Player Finish Heisman winner 1936 Sam Baugh 4th Larry Kelley,
Yale 1938 Davey O'Brien 1st O'Brien 1955 Jim Swink 2nd Howard
Cassady, Ohio State 1984 Kenneth Davis 5th Doug Flutie, Boston
College
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were no Web sites to update, no ESPN highlights to
overnight, no goofy publicity pictures to arrange. When TCU
halfback Jim Swink made his 1955 run for the Heisman Trophy, he did
so on the momentum of his incredible statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really push him,'' recalled Jim ``Hoss'' Brock,
former TCU sports information director. ``He came out of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Swink gave hints of his greatness as a sophomore in 1954,
reeling off touchdown runs of 79, 67 and 68 yards. But, with a
powerful team returning and a plethora of stars, few outside the
TCU coaching staff knew what the Frogs had.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the 80-yard touchdown run early in the 1955 opener vs.
Kansas. Three weeks later came the three touchdowns in a 21-0 upset
of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   And on and on Swink ran.
</P>
<P>
   In a 47-20 whipping of Texas, Swink ran for 235 yards on 15
carries and scored four times.
</P>
<P>
   He led the nation in scoring (125 points) and yards per carry
(8.1). He was second nationally in rushing with 1,283 yards for a
9-1 team that won the Southwest Conference and finished No. 6 in
the final Associated Press poll. It was almost enough to land him
the Heisman, but ``The Rusk Rambler'' was edged out by Ohio State
running back Howard ``Hopalong'' Cassady, who ran for 958 yards and
15 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still say he had the best balance and vision of any running
back I've ever seen,'' Brock said. ``He could see the whole field.
And anybody hitting him high he would shake them like a bowl of
jelly.''
</P>
<P>
   Swink's amazing junior season prompted Brock to mount a
``pull-out-all-the-stops'' publicity campaign for the 1956 season,
much like TCU is doing this year for senior LaDainian Tomlinson.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Brock beefed up the TCU media guide from a 55-page
mimeographed handout to a full-fledged brochure with a cover photo
of Swink and three-page story on him inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up to the chancellor's office and told him I need to
put out a fancy book. He said, `What's it going to cost?' I said I
think it'll cost $1,200. He said, `You've got $1,500 and don't
spend a penny more or you'll be looking for work.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brock, who helped get Swink on the cover of ``Sports
Illustrated'' and almost every preseason football magazine that
year, went to work getting the name of every prominent college
football writer so he could mail them weekly updates each Sunday
night. But the publicity didn't get Swink into Heisman contention.
</P>
<P>
   TCU used a more balanced offensive attack co-starring halfback
Ken Wineburg to counteract defenses targeting Swink. He still led
the conference in rushing but broke few of the long runs that had
become his trademark a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody set up their defense to stop him,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as TCU's opponents undoubtedly will try to do against LT.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
