<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HEISMAN-CAMPAIGNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STATS DON'T LIE AT HEISMAN TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the statistics, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Heisman Trophy campaigns do not win the Heisman Trophy. The
player who winds up clutching college football's most famous trophy
in the Downtown Athletic Club in December typically has the numbers
_ statistics, victories _ to back up his election. Winning the
Heisman these days requires more steak than sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it should be; you should be rewarded for
performance,'' said Wisconsin sports information director Steve
Malchow, who staged a low-key campaign for 1999 Heisman winner Ron
Dayne. ``You don't win with a unique campaign. You win being a
productive player on a productive team.''
</P>
<P>
   For TCU's LaDainian Tomlinson to make a serious run at the
Heisman, he needs to have the numbers, and the Frogs need to have a
nearly perfect season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many good quarterbacks on too many good teams,''
said Don Borst, a senior college writer with CBS Sportsline.com.
``TCU probably has to go 12-0, and he'll have to get more than
2,000 yards and lead the nation in rushing for him to win.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be debate about whether the Heisman consistently
goes to the best college player, but the numbers rarely mislead in
the Heisman balloting. The past 10 years, the Heisman winner has
either been among the statistical leaders at his position or played
for a national championship contender. Those 10 Heisman winners
played for teams that averaged a won-loss record of 10-2.
</P>
<P>
   For running backs such as Tomlinson, numbers are even more
important. Of the past 10 Heisman-winning running backs, Eddie
George finished the lowest on the rushing charts (fifth in 1995).
Six of those Heisman winners won the rushing title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to wow people,'' said Rick Campbell, the
NCAA's football statistician. ``Barry Sanders was like that. His
numbers were so staggering. After just two or three games, he was
the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Heisman campaigns have evolved into
noncampaigns. Sports-information directors have discovered that
with so many information streams flowing there is no need to
publicize a player with good ``highlights'' and no way to hide a
player who isn't performing.
</P>
<P>
   Clever campaigns have had little effect on Heisman voters. Notre
Dame sports-information director Roger Valdiserri advised his
quarterback to change the pronunciation of his name to rhyme with
the trophy. Joe ``Thees''man became Joe ``Theis''man ... and
finished second in the 1970 Heisman voting to Jim Plunkett.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State tried to promote offensive tackle Orlando Pace for
the 1996 Heisman. They sent out refrigerator magnets that resembled
a stack of pancakes. The idea was to link Pace and the ``pancake''
blocks for which he was becoming famous. A good try, but Pace
couldn't keep pace with Danny Wuerffel, Troy Davis and Jake
Plummer, who finished 1-2-3 in the Heisman voting.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State publicists kept it simple in 1997. They mailed
envelopes containing a single leaf to remind voters to consider
Cougars quarterback Ryan Leaf. He finished third behind Charles
Woodson and Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win with performance,'' Malchow said. ``There's a real
bond between team success and the player having a good year.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
