<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANICS, WOMEN, BLACKS HAVE HIGHLY VISIBLE POSTS FOR GOP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LETITIA STEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Hoping to present an image of diversity, Republicans
have named Hispanics, blacks and women to highly visible posts for
this week's GOP National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Henry Bonilla of San Antonio, Jennifer Dunn of Washington
state and J.C. Watts of Oklahoma will serve as deputy permanent
chairs of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two other Texans _ Railroad Commission member Tony
Garza and Dallas businessman Alphonso Jackson _ were named
assistant secretaries for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments are part of a continuing effort by Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush to counter images lingering
from his appearance at a conservative Christian college during the
South Carolina primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a convention that is more the softer side
of the conservative image than you usually see from Republicans,''
Dunn said, referring to the Republican effort to appeal to women
and minorities during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, like Bonilla and Watts, is more than window-dressing. She
prides herself on being one of the more visible members of
Congress. Dunn made history as the first woman to run for a top
leadership post with her 1998 challenge against Rep. Dick Armey,
R-Irving, for House Majority Leader.
</P>
<P>
   Although she lost that bid, Dunn led many GOP initiatives,
including her recent work to repeal a tax penalty on married
couples.
</P>
<P>
   She got involved in the Bush campaign in its early stages and
considers the Texas governor a ``soul mate'' in how he addresses
national problems. She also supports his efforts to reach out to
voters who have not been aligned with the Republican Party in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla's relationship with Bush goes back to the days before he
ran for governor in 1994. Bush campaigned in San Antonio to help
win his first election to Congress in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bonilla was among those who urged Bush to seek
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that our party really needed someone like him, who
understood the importance of reaching out and communicating to
every ethnic group,'' said Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   When Bonilla came to Washington in early 1993, he was the first
Hispanic Republican elected to Congress from Texas. He has served
on the House Appropriations Committee since his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   Watts has always been known as a team player, from his days as
star quarterback for the University of Oklahoma Sooners to his
current role as co-chairman of the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my real lessons in life have come from, I think,
understanding the team concept,'' he said. ``In the team concept,
you're never concerned about who gets the glory and who gets the
credit. You're just concerned that the team wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his election to Congress in 1994, Watts has championed the
Community Renewal Project, a measure that aims to revitalize poor
communities by helping citizens invest in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Watts became the fourth-highest ranking Republican in
the House with his election to chairman of the House Republican
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Watts also spoke at the 1996 Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Garza was elected to the Railroad Commission in 1998, the first
Hispanic Republican to hold statewide office. Garza served as
Bush's secretary of state from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, an African-American and native of Dallas, has been a
Republican for the past 25 years. A member of the Texas Southern
University Board of Regents, Jackson is president of the American
Electric Power Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention secretary is Linda Shaw, a North Carolina
Republican. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
