<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CUNNINGHA     07-29 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CUNNINGHAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUNNINGHAM ACCEPTS BACKUP ROLE WITH COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Settling in more and more as Troy
Aikman's backup with the Cowboys, Randall Cunningham maintains an
inner peace that almost defies what he is capable of doing with a
football held majestically in his right hand, even at age 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the timing down with the receivers yet,'' said
Cunningham, who will make his Cowboys debut tonight against the
Pittsburgh Steelers in a preseason opener at Texas Stadium. ``I'm
still about one or two feet off on the timing routes right now. It
all takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Timing routes? There was a time when a much younger Randall
Cunningham, then with the Philadelphia Eagles, couldn't _ or
wouldn't _ stay in the pocket. He didn't become the NFL's all-time
leading rusher at quarterback (4,799 yards) by being a dropback
passer all his life.
</P>
<P>
   That's the point about Cunningham, who passed over Tampa Bay and
Detroit to sign with the Cowboys a week after his June 1 release
from Minnesota. He is willing to learn on the run, even in his 15th
NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't just grow old. He evolves.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys want him to be the quarterback who makes opposing
defensive coordinators devise two distinctly different games plans:
one for Aikman and another for Cunningham, just in case he comes
into a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a `set plan' for Randall in a lot of
ways,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said. ``But, at the same time, we
want him to learn the offense and be effective \Rwith what Aikman
runs\S as well.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense that Cunningham is cramming off the field (he
has the Cowboys' new numbering system down pat) but that he is
taking it one throw at a time on the practice field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Randall is just about where I thought he would be,''
Campo said, ``but not where I think he will be when the season
rolls around'' Sept. 3 vs. Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham could play several series tonight. Much depends on
how many series it takes Aikman and the first-team offense to get
in their 10 snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get totally comfortable with the Vikings, it took me about
a year and a half,'' said Cunningham, who joined Minnesota in 1997
and was the NFL's MVP a year later, when he replaced an injured
Brad Johnson in Week 2. He ended up passing for 3,704 and 34
touchdowns against only 10 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always harder on myself than anyone else is,'' Cunningham
said.
</P>
<P>
   His signature easygoing smile and total acceptance of his role
as Aikman's backup make him a pleasant addition in the eyes of
coaches and teammates alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past the stage where I get really frustrated or where it
becomes overwhelming,'' he said. ``I'm at the point now that I
learn from my mistakes and I'm thankful for what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   The only hole in Cunningham's rsum is a Super Bowl, something
that he hopes can come with the Cowboys. It's much easier for
Cunningham, 3 1/2 years Aikman's senior, to sit behind someone who
owns three more Super Bowl rings than he does.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was supposed to be in the second year of a five-year,
$28 million contract with the Vikings right now. He signed that
deal in December 1998. But six games into the '99 season (2-4),
Vikings coach Denny Green benched Cunningham and turned to his
backup, Jeff George.
</P>
<P>
   When Green committed to second-year quarterback Daunte Culpepper
during the off-season, Cunningham declined to have his contract
reworked without a chance to be a starter again. He did stay around
long enough to collect a $1 million roster bonus on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's working with the Cowboys' second group of receivers _
Chris Brazzell, Wane McGarity and Jason Tucker _ trying to get his
timing down in this Jack Reilly offense.
</P>
<P>
   The whole concept is new to Cunningham. Neither at Philadelphia
(1985-95) nor at Minnesota (1997-99) did he get work in a
timing-route offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're late with the ball here, you definitely can throw an
interception,'' Cunningham warned. ``Troy has the system down. I'm
still adjusting to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham is 79-50-1 in his career as an NFL starter, including
8-4 against the Cowboys. In his last appearance at Texas Stadium _
Thanksgiving Day 1998 _ he threw for 359 yards and four touchdowns
in a 46-36 Vikings victory.
</P>
<P>
   After all of Cunningham's seasons as a Cowboys nemesis, it will
be understandable if it takes awhile for fans to get used to
rooting for No. 7 _ even if he is wearing a star on his helmet.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
