<HEADLINE>
TEAM SUCCESS GIVES PITCHER FINE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Jim Parque was sitting in the clubhouse
working on a crossword puzzle before a recent game when a teammate
sat down beside him and tried to help.
</P>
<P>
   Parque's Chicago White Sox teammates are giving him plenty of
help on the field, too, making him confident there won't be a
repeat of his 1999 second-half slide and giving the left-hander a
chance to establish a career high for wins when he starts today's
series finale against the Angels at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Six years removed from his days as a standout at Crescenta
Valley High near Los Angeles and three years after the White Sox
drafted him out of UCLA, Parque is 9-4 with a 3.95 ERA for the team
with the best record in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, the key is we're all playing as a team and pulling for
each other,'' Parque said. ``We've pretty much eliminated every
stat except the one that goes on the scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Parque went 9-6 in the first half of 1999 but was 0-9 with four
no-decisions in his final 13 starts. He calls the numbers
deceiving, because many of the runs he gave up were unearned. His
teammates scored more than two runs for him just twice.
</P>
<P>
   He points to the team's record as proof that he wasn't the only
one suffering in the second half. Although the White Sox remained
in second place, they dropped from 12 games back at the end of June
to 21 games back and 11 games under .500 by the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing anything different this year,'' Parque said.
``Last year, the second half, the media really blows it out of
proportion. . . . In most of those games, I didn't give up a lot of
runs. If you look at my ERA, it was below the American League
average. But the team didn't play as well. There were a lot of
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Chicago is the team with the large lead in the AL
Central and flirting with the best record in the majors, so Parque
isn't feeling the need to do everything himself even though the
White Sox defense again ranks among the league's worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me personally, the key is just keeping an even keel,''
Parque said. ``Last year was up and down. The key is just not to
really worry if something goes wrong behind me and not get too high
or too low.''
</P>
<P>
   Parque, 24, has had plenty of highs in his career. After an All-
American junior season in which he helped UCLA reach the College
World Series, Parque was the only White Sox player selected in the
1997 draft to play above the Single-A level that year. He was in
Triple-A by the end of 1997 and in the majors the following May.
</P>
<P>
   He is on track for his first season with an ERA less than 5.00
as well as improving other stats, but with this year's team-first
attitude Parque almost didn't notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking over my stats the other day,'' he said. ``It was
the first time it dawned on me that I was doing better than last
year. I know things have been going well, but I wasn't really
paying attention to my own stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you play for a better team, you can't help but do
better. This team has surprised a lot of people and the success
comes from being a total team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
