<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS CONFIDENT AS CONVENTION NEARS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The city will break ground soon on a new downtown
pavilion to house the Liberty Bell.
</P>
<P>
   A few neighborhoods away, the Republican Party will embark on a
grand restoration project of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP wants its 37th annual national convention, which starts
Monday, to help restore a Republican to the presidency after eight
years of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the last half-century, two Republican presidents have served
two complete four-year terms: Dwight Eisenhower and Ronald Reagan.
But in the same period, Clinton is the only Democrat to keep the
presidency out of the opposition's hands for that long.
</P>
<P>
   And, to the compounded frustration of his foes, Clinton did it
with less than 50 percent of the national vote in both elections
when independent candidate Ross Perot siphoned votes away from the
leading contenders.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican victory in the November election would also restore
the Bush name to eminence.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP will use its convention to nominate Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, son of the president beaten by Clinton in 1992. President
Bush, who has never matched Reagan as an inspirational giant of his
party, will be officially honored at the convention. He will also
have the chance to watch in person as his son officially accepts a
slot on the national ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican ticket offers to restore Bush's running mate,
Dick Cheney, to familiar turf, too. Cheney was chief of staff for
President Ford. Later he was a Republican congressional leader and,
under President Bush, secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   With Perot out of the picture and this year's alternative
candidates posing less of a threat in the early polls, Republicans
are gleefully eyeing voter-survey numbers. They show Bush leading
the Democratic pick, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before in my memory have we been so united on the eve of
a great election,'' Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson told
national party leaders here. ``We are almost at the mountain top.''
</P>
<P>
   To a great extent, the vantage point Nicholson has in mind is a
mirror image of the 1988 election. The vice president, Republican
George Bush, vied to succeed a two-term president, Reagan, against
a challenger-governor, Democrat Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts.
Now Gore is in the elder Bush role and the younger Bush is in the
Dukakis role.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say that now it's the challenger's turn to win. Gore
says the Bush ticket will take the country back to failed policies
of the Republican past.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it's part of a familiar plot, the four-day
performance here is designed to be unfamiliar.
</P>
<P>
   In line with Bush's ``compassionate conservative'' pitch, party
leaders have drafted a platform that softens the built-in
Republican opposition to government.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the platform that will be submitted to the
delegates for approval Monday drops the long-running call for the
U.S. Department of Education to be dismantled. It also says,
``There should be a strong federal role in environmental
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the platform does not dilute the party's opposition
to abortion. Delegates are expected to preserve the platform plank
that calls for a constitutional amendment to ban abortion.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the platform committee rejected efforts by the Bush
campaign to remove a provision calling for elimination of school
counseling programs that tell students about birth control and
other forms of family planning. Instead, the committee said,
schools should teach only sexual abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention stage at the Comcast-Spectator First Union
Center, a basketball/hockey arena in south Philadelphia,
Republicans will present their version of a catchy variety show
geared toward a national television and Internet audience. House
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois is expected to gavel the
gathering to attention from a remote location in Philadelphia _
perhaps a historical one related to the American Revolution _ while
his image is shown on the stage's video screens.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, vanquished by the Texas governor in
the Republican primaries, is a featured speaker. So are two retired
generals from the Persian Gulf War, Colin Powell and Norman H.
Schwarzkopf.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainers will include movie stars Bruce Willis and Bo Derek
and country singer Hank Williams Jr. And presentations that relate
to Bush's core issues, such as education reform, will come from
regular folks _ including minority students from KIPP Academy in
Houston and a significant number of women.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, convention planners said, is for voters to see a
punchier, friendlier, unprecedented convention that relies less on
insults against the Democrats and policy pronouncements by veteran
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the party will give at best a low-key role to
its more combative leaders, such as House Majority Whip Tom DeLay
of Texas, and more divisive approaches to issues, such as the GOP
opposition to gun control and resistance to campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cheney will give his first major speech of the
campaign as he accepts the vice-presidential nomination. It will be
a major test for a politician who, after serving as a guiding force
in government for decades, nevertheless has yet to establish an
identity on the national stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will deliver his acceptance speech Thursday night under the
same intense spotlight _ not only in the presence of his parents,
but at the conclusion of a convention in which his family is
elevated to near-dynasty status.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Laura, is scheduled to give a featured speech on
Monday night. His brother, Jeb, reigns as governor of Florida, a
key state in the presidential election. Jeb's 24-year-old son,
George P. Bush, will help introduce the Texas governor to the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the arena will be 2,066 delegates, 2,066 alternates and
many more guests, observers and news media personnel. The cost for
the extravaganza starts at $70 million, most from corporations and
other financial backers tapped by the city of Philadelphia; some
from the Presidential Election Fund stocked by $1 check box on
federal income tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
