<HEADLINE>
STAKES SOAR IN SUIT OVER WRESTLER'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   A legal battle royal has erupted in the
case of Owen Hart, the professional wrestler who fell to his death
from the rafters of Kemper Arena last year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defendants in the negligence lawsuit filed by Hart's parents,
wife and children have accused the family's lawyers of trying to
buy off witnesses by agreeing to share with them the proceeds of
any recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The family is represented by the husband-and-wife legal team of
Gary and Anita Robb, two of the best-known personal injury lawyers
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants include the World Wrestling Federation and the
city of Kansas City, owner of Kemper Arena. They and other
defendants contend that an agreement the Robbs entered into with
some of Hart's 10 siblings amounts to witness tampering. That's
because the siblings could be key witnesses in the case but have no
right to share in any recovery under Missouri's wrongful-death
statute.
</P>
<P>
   The statute allows only the dead person's surviving parents,
wife or children to be plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs have vehemently denied any wrongdoing and have said
the agreement was nothing more than an effort to secure unity among
members of Hart's extended family. The Robbs rescinded the
agreement after the defendants uncovered it.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents, the Robbs said ``nothing in the (agreement)
even hints that the signatory siblings are under any obligation to
testify falsely or evasively. It merely provides that they shall
help the plaintiffs and not help the defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs noted that the spouses of two of Hart's siblings were
under contract or associated with the WWF and might have an
interest in undermining a large settlement with the family.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs also said the WWF has been trying to reach a separate
settlement with Hart's parents, Stu and Helen Hart. That, they
said, would expunge any further claims by Hart's widow and
children, because Missouri's wrongful-death law treats all of them
_ parents, children and widow alike _ as a single class. A
settlement with one member of the class would bind the others to
the settlement amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that the WWF wants to settle this case,
preferably without involving plaintiffs' counsel, who have some
idea what it's worth, and it's perfectly willing to pull on
whatever family ties it can,'' the Robbs stated in court filings.
</P>
<P>
   The incendiary allegation of witness tampering has raised
serious ethical questions that cut to the heart of the integrity of
the judicial process. Legal experts say the charge, if proved,
could lead to disciplinary sanctions, including disbarment. It
could result, they say, in the Robbs being removed from the case.
</P>
<P>
   Legal authorities not involved in the litigation expressed
surprise at the existence of a side agreement with potential
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a remarkable document,'' said Charles Wolfram, a law
professor at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y. ``I've never heard
of anything like it _ and perhaps with good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal battle has been waged in documents that were sealed by
court order at the request of the Robbs, who said the agreement is
protected by attorney-client privilege and was improperly obtained
by the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star obtained a copy of the agreement from an
open file at the Missouri Court of Appeals, where the Robbs filed a
petition urging the court to bar the trial judge from unsealing the
document and to prohibit the defendants from asking the siblings
about it in depositions. The trial judge, Douglas Long Jr., had
ordered the document unsealed and authorized the defendants to
inquire about it after a hearing May 31.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court temporarily granted the Robbs' petition July
5, pending further review.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs declined to comment on the agreement, saying the
court's order barred them from talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``About all I can tell you is that this case is about the tragic
death of Owen Hart,'' said Anita Robb. ``And from the beginning,
the WWF has tried to divert attention from their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``...The entire Hart family deeply resents the hardball tactics
that the WWF has used against their family in this case. They've
even sued the widow and minor children for breach of contract for
filing this suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the defendants also cited the court's order and
declined to comment on the agreement with the siblings.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs rescinded the agreement after the defendants uncovered
it, saying they didn't want it to become a ``red herring'' that
would distract from the underlying issues of the case. But the
agreement remains a bone of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, Your Honor, to have given these siblings a financial
interest in the outcome of this case and then to have tried to keep
it from the court, from my client and from myself is something that
seriously undermines the potential for a fair trial in this case,''
said Kent Sullivan, a lawyer for the riggers who helped set up
Hart's harness system, in the May 31 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Key provisions of the agreement:
</P>
<P>
   - Called for the Robbs to represent the interests of the
siblings who signed it.
</P>
<P>
   - Stated the siblings would be entitled to their ``allocable
share'' of the recovery due Hart's parents, who also signed the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   - Required the siblings to cooperate with one another _ and to
refrain from cooperating or even communicating with the defendants
_ in pursuing the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   - Provided that any siblings who cooperate with the defendants
would not share in any recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hart brothers and sisters shall cooperate with and
participate with the above-referenced counsel in all respects to
ensure and enhance the prospects of success in this legal action,''
one of the agreement's provisions stated.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Hart siblings was present when a stunt went awry and
Hart fell more than 70 feet to his death on May 23, 1999. But their
testimony could prove crucial on the key issue of how many more
years Hart planned to work as a professional wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how much longer Hart planned to wrestle bears on
the issue of lost earnings, which could figure prominently in any
compensatory damages awarded in the case. And because the U.S.
Supreme Court has ruled that punitive damages must bear a
reasonable relationship to compensatory damages, the question also
has a bearing on overall damages.
</P>
<P>
   After Hart's death, several Hart family members were quoted in
the media as saying Hart had planned to retire in the next year or
two, after his contract with the WWF expired.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs have indicated in court proceedings that they will say
Hart, who was 34 years old when he died, planned to wrestle
professionally for eight to 15 more years. At $750,000 per year,
the amount they say Hart earned, that amounts to $6 million to
$11.25 million in lost income.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said the agreement with Hart's siblings smacked of
an illegal inducement of witness testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lubet, a law professor at Northwestern University in
Evanston, Ill., said that in most jurisdictions ``it would be
considered wrong to provide that sort of an agreement to a witness,
because it gives witnesses a financial interest in the outcome of
the litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   David Achtenberg, a law professor at the University of
Missouri-Kansas City School of Law, said an agreement to pay a
witness ``contingent on the witness testifying in a particular way
raises serious ethical questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's Rules of Professional Responsibility specifically
state that a lawyer ``shall not ... offer an inducement to a
witness that is prohibited by law.'' In Missouri, as in most
states, that means only expert witnesses can be paid for their
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfram of Cornell said the provision calling for the siblings
not to cooperate with the defendants _ without making any exception
for subpoenaed testimony _ ``is written in a way that a nonlawyer
who signs it might think he can't even speak truthfully when called
as a witness.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendants only found out about the agreement with the
siblings when a copy was sent to the WWF's attorneys in Pittsburgh
by Ellie Neidhart, one of Owen Hart's sisters. Ellie Neidhart's
husband, Jim ``The Anvil'' Neidhart, used to be a WWF wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs learned that the defendants had a copy _ which was
signed by five of the siblings _ when lawyers for the WWF marked it
as an exhibit at a deposition of Owen Hart's mother, Helen Hart.
</P>
<P>
   After angry protests by the Robbs, who said the document was
protected by attorney-client privilege and should have been
returned by the WWF, Long ordered the agreement sealed. But the
WWF, intent on asking witnesses whether they had been promised any
financial interest in the case, moved for an order compelling
witnesses to answer questions about the agreement. The WWF
simultaneously asked that the agreement be unsealed.
</P>
<P>
   Long granted the WWF's motions after the May 31 hearing,
prompting the Robbs to file their petition with the Missouri Court
of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In their petition, which was filed earlier this month, the Robbs
contended the agreement simply allowed Hart's siblings ``to retain
some interest'' in the proceeds of any recovery if both parents
died before the case was resolved. That way, they said, ``they
would be less likely to be tricked into pursuing a quick and cheap
settlement by the WWF.''
</P>
<P>
   But as noted by lawyer Leonard Frischer, who represents the city
of Kansas City, the agreement did not condition the siblings'
recovery on their parents' death. Rather, the agreement stated that
the siblings would be entitled to recover ``irrespective as to
whether Stu Hart or Helen Hart, or both, may predecease the
ultimate resolution of this action.'' The agreement amounted to
witness tampering in any case, the defendants allege.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the defendants note, the agreement invoked a
nonexistent Missouri statute to justify the sharing of any damages
with the siblings. The statute in question, which had to do with
juries, was repealed in 1989. The Robbs said they mistakenly
invoked the wrong statute number, but they failed to specify what
statute they meant to invoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no statute that supports this particular kind of
agreement,'' Frischer told Long at the May 31 hearing. ``That is
bothersome (that) they would put that in this agreement _ say to
the people, `Here, sign it. Here's how we are going to do it. It is
OK under Missouri law.' But the statute doesn't exist. That is very
troublesome to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court is expected to decide soon _ possibly within
days _ whether to unseal the agreement and allow the defendants'
attorneys to pursue information about it with Hart family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to know what is going on,'' WWF attorney Craig
O'Dear told Long at the May 31 hearing. ``Otherwise it subverts the
process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
