<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7313 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-INTERNET-CONVENTION-H     07-29 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET PICKS UP CONVENTION COVERAGE WHERE TV LEAVES OFF &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When Republican Party activists gathered in
Philadelphia in 1948, fledgling television viewers in nine East
Coast cities fought with their rabbit ears and tuned in a fuzzy
black-and-white picture of Thomas Dewey accepting the party's
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   This week, 52 years after that first live broadcast of a
political convention changed the nature of politics and TV forever,
the GOP returns to this city. But the major TV networks have
abandoned gavel-to-gavel coverage, citing lack of viewer interest.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Justin Friedland, an Emmy-award-winning former
senior producer at ABC News' ``World News Tonight'' and ``Good
Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the future,'' said Friedland, a consulting producer for
Pseudo.com, one of the first two Internet TV sites to be granted a
skybox at a political convention. ``The TV networks are getting out
of the business, and we are here. With the Internet, you can have
input into the process. It allows you to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four days, as speaker after speaker takes the
podium at the First Union Center and as GOP members argue about
whether to soften their position on abortion or gay rights, most TV
viewers will be watching sports or their favorite sit-coms,
squeezing in a political speech or two during prime time or
catching the convention highlights on late night news.
</P>
<P>
   But for those willing to dial up and log on, Internet TV sites
such as Pseudo.com and aol.com, as well as a host of other sites
run by newspapers and TV stations, independent nonprofit
organizations and the political parties themselves, will provide a
torrent of information.
</P>
<P>
   With about 150 Internet sites providing coverage of the
convention, Internet users from around the world will be able to
take a virtual tour of the convention floor, watch a Webcast and
read text on the proceedings, participate in political polls, rate
speakers' performances and voice their opinions through chat rooms
set up with convention delegates and Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can imagine CNN and MTV, combined with these
interactive features, on crack, you basically have what we're
doing. It's irreverent and fun,'' said Jeanne Meyer, senior vice
president of Pseudo.com. ``If you want something that's
couch-potato fare, turn on your TV. If you want to dive in, and if
you have any voyeuristic tendencies, this is going to be your
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet Web site, www.speakout.com, expects about 5,000
people to participate in opinion surveys as speeches are being
televised on MSNBC. The idea is to target Internet users who have a
computer in the same room as their TV.
</P>
<P>
   Political pundits interviewed on MSNBC after the speeches will
have the benefit of a sort of ``opinion EKG'' on how the speech
went over in cyberland.
</P>
<P>
   Speakout.com's Rekha Chalasani hopes the Internet coverage will
encourage more young people to get involved in politics and to vote
in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have pretty low voter turnout, and part of the
reason is that people don't have a voice in the process,'' she
said. ``The Internet gives them that voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bailey, who founded The Hotline, an Internet site packed
with news geared mostly toward political junkies and the media,
agreed. Bailey, who is now president and CEO of the nonprofit
FreedomChannel.com, said he hopes to reach a wider audience by
October, when most people really begin to focus on the race.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, FreedomChannel will join a network of 17
organizations to create a rolling cyberdebate among the candidates
themselves (if they choose to participate), their campaigns and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone will be able to log on to any of the 17 sites to ask a
question or offer an opinion. And in the weeks preceding the Nov. 7
election, about 10 million elementary and high school students are
expected to vote online in a ``youth e-vote,'' the first, although
obviously unofficial, national test of online voting.
</P>
<P>
   Tami Buhr, research coordinator for Harvard University's Joan
Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy, which
manages the Vanishing Voter Project, isn't so certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess, so far, I'm kind of a pessimist,'' Buhr said. ``The
research so far shows that only about 20 percent of the electorate
has taken an interest in the campaigns, and the number of people
following politics on the Internet is still much smaller than those
getting their information from traditional news sources. So people
are not flocking to the Internet to gain information.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
