<HEADLINE>
HART FAMILY LAWYERS' REPUTATION GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Gary and Anita Robb have built one of
the most successful personal injury practices in Kansas City, often
taking on corporate giants and besting them in court.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The husband-and-wife legal team, both graduates of the
University of Michigan School of Law, established Robb &AMP; Robb in
1984. Three years later, they won their first million-dollar jury
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Robbs have won at least a half-dozen
multimillion dollar verdicts or settlements for their clients.
Among them:
</P>
<P>
   - A $20 million jury verdict in March 1991 on behalf of an
11-year-old Kansas City girl who came out of minor surgery blinded
and permanently brain-damaged. A Missouri law capping medical
malpractice awards limited the recovery to about $3 million. The
award eventually was reduced to $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   - A $70 million jury verdict in 1995 on behalf of a patient
killed in the crash of a LifeFlight helicopter in 1993. An appeals
court later reduced the award to $29 million and the defendant,
Turbomeca SA of France, eventually paid the patient's family $39.2
million. Evidence at trial indicated that Turbomeca, the
helicopter's manufacturer, knew a defective engine part could cause
the helicopters to crash.
</P>
<P>
   - A $350 million jury verdict in 1995 _ at the time thought to
be one of the biggest product liability verdicts in U.S. history _
on behalf of the pilot of the LifeFlight helicopter. An appeals
court later reduced the award to $30 million. With interest, the
total paid came to $40.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   - A $14 million pretrial settlement in 1997 on behalf of the
mother of 14-year-old Ryan Sayles, who was dragged and crushed to
death when his clothing snagged in the handrail of a school bus
door.
</P>
<P>
   - A $25 million jury verdict in 1998 on behalf of the family of
Jackson County Circuit Judge Michael Coburn, a neighbor of the
Robbs who died after he fell into a pit while inspecting a
dangerous building.
</P>
<P>
   - A $23.4 million verdict last December on behalf of the
families of Cecil and Tracy Stowers, who were killed along with
their infant daughter by a drunken driver on Christmas Day 1998.
The defendant, who was sentenced to 15 years in prison in a
separate criminal proceeding, isn't thought to have had the
insurance to cover the award.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs prefer to go it alone. They are the only lawyers in
their firm, although they employ several paralegals. Typically, the
defendants they sue are represented by big law firms, often chosen
by defendants' insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs live in one of Kansas City's biggest houses, a mansion
at the southwest corner of 55th Street and Ward Parkway that was
built by lumber baron M.B. Nelson in 1915 and that is valued by
Jackson County at $3 million. The Robbs frequently host parties and
fund-raisers at the house for charitable causes such as the Kansas
City Ballet and for political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs are active in Democratic Party politics and are major
donors to Democratic candidates at the local, state and national
levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs recently underwrote the cost of a technology center at
the downtown headquarters of the Kansas City Metropolitan Bar
Association. The center, known as the Robb &AMP; Robb Technology
Center, provides association members and staff with technology
training and includes a classroom, seminar room, exhibitor area and
other space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
