<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON OF POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE WERSTINE  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ There is no mistaking the power in the Anaheim Angels'
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With 172 home runs, they have already eclipsed last season's
total of 158 and are on pace to smash the club record of 192.
Furthermore, the Halos have a legitimate shot of becoming the first
team in major-league history to have five players hit 30 or more
round-trippers.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus took over the Angels' lead Saturday with his 31st
homer, followed by Garret Anderson's 30, Mo Vaughn's 26, Tim
Salmon's 22 and Darin Erstad's 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice (to be part of the group),'' Vaughn said. ``We are
going to keep swinging and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   To set the mark, the Angels will have to beat the Toronto Blue
Jays to the punch. The Blue Jays are also on pace to have five
players hit more than 30 homers, led by AL home run leader Carlos
Delgado (32) and Tony Batista (31).
</P>
<P>
   __ Leading man: Erstad has shown the mettle of a leadoff hitter
this season, leading the majors with 167 hits, 80 runs scored, 18
stolen bases and a .427 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   While he is chasing George Sislers' all-time single-season
record of 257 hits set in 1920, Erstad could become the first
major-leaguer to drive in 100-plus runs from the leadoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   With 77 RBI _ second on the club behind Vaughn's 81 _ Erstad
needs just 22 more to surpass Boston's Nomar Garciaparra's mark of
98 in his Rookie of the Year season of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad also has the chance to break the all-time single-season
mark for homers by a leadoff hitter. Baltimore's Brady Anderson and
former San Francisco Giants great Bobby Bonds hold the record with
35.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mercker rehab: After missing more than two months
recuperating from a cerebral hemorrhage, left-hander Kent Mercker
will make his first scheduled rehab start Monday for Lake Elsinore
at Modesto.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, who suffered the injury May 12 and has missed 68 days
on the disabled list, threw a simulated game earlier this week and
was originally set to make the rehab start Saturday, but it was
pushed back two days because of extended bullpen work Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is fine,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``His
velocity is great, but he is going to have some command issues that
you'd expect with a guy who has been off so long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
