<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... ADDS QUOTES IN FIRST ITEM 
GIMELSTOB TEMPER DOESN'T LEAD TO WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GERRY GITTELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some professional tennis players play better after
losing their cool.
</P>
<P>
   Not Justin Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the first set against Michael Chang in Saturday's
Mercedes-Benz Cup semifinal, Gimelstob began acting out midway
through the second set, and he was never the same in a 3-6, 6-3,
6-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Up 3-2 in the second set, Gimelstob was bothered by a ringing
cellular phone during his serve. He stopped and loudly screamed,
``Shut off your phone!''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd laughed and cheered, but it was the beginning of the
end for Gimelstob, who never regained his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand it. Turning off your cell phone is not a
very difficult concept,'' Gimelstob said. ``Obviously I'm a prima
donna.
</P>
<P>
   After Chang won the next two games, Gimelstob tossed his racket
_ this time the crowd booed _ and the umpire issued a warning for
racket abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob punctuated losing the set by tearing off his shirt _ a
la Hulk Hogan entering a wrestling ring.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the match, Gimelstob, a UCLA graduate, had a lot
less fan support than when he started.
</P>
<P>
   He punched a locker after the match and bruised his right hand.
He was too busy getting it examined to talk immediately to the
media, because he had to play a doubles match _ losing in straight
sets _ in the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After the doubles loss, Gimelstob briefly appeared with a
heavily bandaged hand in front of reporters. He didn't elaborate on
how it happened, and no one asked. But Gimelstob did admit his
emotions got the best of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got flustered, scattered and distracted,'' he said. ``That's
exactly why the result was what it was. I'm obviously
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang was asked if Gimelstob's behavior was the turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's difficult to say,'' Chang said. ''Part of the way
Justin is is to be intense and show his frustration. It's just a
part of his personality. I know John McEnroe always played better
when he got fired up. I don't know if Justin does or he doesn't.
Everyone handles it differently.''!dlim!!end!
</P>
<P>
   __ Clawing ahead: Jan-Michael Gambill raises baby tigers at the
Cat Tails park near his home in Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   __ Taking stock: Gimelstob, who recently surpassed $1 million in
career prize money, said he enjoys following the stock market _ his
best friend is a stockbroker _ but only as a ``hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bringin' the heat: Late in the second set of the
Chang-Gimelstob match, play was halted when a fan fell ill and was
carried off by attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Identified as Phyllis Adler, she was taken to UCLA's emergency
room for dehydration and heat exhaustion, according tournament
officials.
</P>
<P>
   She was reported in good condition shortly after the match.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fast start: No one was hotter than Arnaud Clement this week.
He hadn't lost a set through the first three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   __ Celebrity sighting: Dustin Hoffman, who participated in a
charity match here Monday, sat in the first row for Chang's
victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
