<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKW-COMETS-SPARKS-1ST     07-29 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-SPARKS-1ST </SLUG>
 LEAD -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
By W.H. STICKNEY JR. 
Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ On a day when the Comets became the first WNBA team to
retire a player's jersey, they found they could have used the
inspirational leadership of the late Kim Perrot against the Los
Angeles Sparks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without the fiery point guard, who died from cancer last August
and had her No. 10 jersey hung from the rafters at Compaq Center on
Saturday, the Comets took a nine-point, second-half lead only to be
outscored by 17 points down the stretch en route to an 84-74 defeat
before a national television audience and a sellout crowd of
16,285.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (24-3), who won for the first time ever in Houston,
increased their Western Conference lead over the Comets (22-5) to
two games with five games remaining in the regular season. In the
process, the Sparks became the first team to sweep a season series
(3-0) from the three-time defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my wildest dreams did I think I'd walk in here today
and LA would beat us three times in a year,'' Comets coach Van
Chancellor said after the Comets' second loss in six days. ``But
they're doing a marvelous job of taking it to us. They're playing
well. They really beat us in the second half. Unbelievably.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Comets lead the league in total defense, they were
torched for 48 points by the Sparks in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets also shot poorly, hitting only 26 of 64 attempts from
the field (40.6 percent) and missing 11 of 12 field-goal tries at
one point in the second half to spark LA's decisive, second-half
rally.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five Sparks starters scored in double figures, led
by Tamecka Dixon with 19 points, including 13 in the second half.
And LA shot 30-for-58 (51.7 percent) from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game had been much anticipated since July 14 when the
Comets blew a 15-point lead with 11:42 to play and lost 63-58 at
the Forum in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Comets guard Cynthia Cooper was missing from action
because of a sprained right ankle suffered three days before. She
was back on the floor Saturday _ although not at full strength _
and led all scorers with 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheryl Swoopes, the league's leading scorer who was playing
with a sprained right index finger, scored only eight points, 13
below her average.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson added 14 points but was 0-for-4 from three-point
range as the Comets were shut out from beyond the arc (0-for-8) for
the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Though emotionally moved during the pre-game jersey-retirement
ceremonies, Cooper shot 6-for-12 and scored 14 points in the first
half as the Comets took a 43-36 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after a pair of Cooper free throws gave the Comets a 56-47
lead at 14:25 of the second half, the Sparks caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's only points during LA's 21-4 ensuing blitz came on a
pair of free throws and a field goal from Swoopes with 9:48
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like LA really wanted it,'' Chancellor said. ``I
really think, if you want my honest opinion, where we've got to get
better, we've got to get somebody to inspire us when things are
going bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone like Perrot, who took an in-your-face approach to
motivate her teammates whenever the occasion warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's loss cannot diminish, in my mind, the thought that Kim
Perrot's jersey was retired and that we honored a wonderful
person,'' Chancellor said. ``That won't detract in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   An obviously inspired Cooper looked like the Cooper of 1997
during the first 12 minutes of the game in which there were five
ties. Cooper drove the lane for layups or passed off to Tiffani
Johnson and Janeth Arcain for easy buckets. One of Cooper's
patented moves broke the final tie and put the Comets up 29-27.
</P>
<P>
   Four consecutive free throws by Thompson and another Cooper
layup closed out the Comets' first-half scoring and gave Houston a
seven-point halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets were still coasting when LA's Mwadi Mabika fouled
Cooper, whose two free throws made it 56-47. But a layup by DeLisha
Milton, who had 17 points on the afternoon, fueled the Sparks'
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, who scored 13 of her 19 points in the second half,
followed with a three-point play, and the Comets' lead was down to
56-52.
</P>
<P>
   After Ukari Figgs nailed a 3-pointer to give the Sparks their
first lead of the half at 57-56, a Milton basket gave LA the lead
for good 59-58. Two free throws by Figgs made it 68-60 and
completed the 21-4 run.
</P>
<P>
   A layup by Dixon later pushed the Sparks' lead to 76-66 before
Arcain gave the Comets and their fans cause for hope. She completed
a three-point play to trim the deficit to 76-69. After being fouled
by Lisa Leslie as she tried to launch a three-point shot, Arcain
made all three of free-throw attempts and to get the Comets within
78-72.
</P>
<P>
   But that was as close as they would get.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper had no answer as to why the Comets went stale after going
ahead by nine points.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is they outscored us, they outplayed us the second
half, they won,'' she said. ``It's all well and good to play well
the first half, but you've got to come out and play hard the second
half. You've got to close out the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Thompson, ``We'll have to go back and figure out what (the)
answer is. If not, we're going to be in a really big hole from now
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, with their loss in Los Angeles two weeks ago, gave
up the homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs to the Sparks.
Saturday, they ceded a huge psychological edge to the team they
beat 2-1 in the Western Conference finals a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only our fifth loss,'' Swoopes said. ``We have five games
to go. And hopefully, we can go into those games and play better.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
