<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS COACH'S MOVIE MESSAGE: ROAD SUCCESS POSSIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Either Cowboys coach Dave Campo is a master
psychologist or an expert jockey.
</P>
<P>
   After two intense weeks of training camp workouts, Campo eased
up on his team heading into tonight's preseason opener against the
Pittsburgh Steelers at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Practices on Thursday and Friday ended at least 30 minutes
early. He canceled team meetings Friday night and instead treated
the team to a ``Mission Impossible'' movie, and ``some popcorn.''
After the movie, Campo moved the players' curfew back to 1 a.m.,
extra time many used to partake in the Wichita Falls night life.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of focusing on the home game against Steelers and the
Cowboys' paltry 1-9 preseason record the past two years, Campo used
the movie to teach the Cowboys about playing on the road. The
Cowboys are 10-24 on the road, including playoffs, since the start
of the 1996 season, including a 1-8 mark last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to them about playing on the road and being a team
like the Mission Impossible team that goes out and takes missions
that people don't think they can handle, but they get the job
done,'' Campo said after the team's easy walk-through practice
yesterday at training camp in Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said he has talked to his team about playing well against
the Steelers and playing to win. However, given that quarterback
Troy Aikman and many of the starters will likely not play much more
than a series or two, Campo said the Steelers' game is most
important for evaluating players, especially the young players who
are trying to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   He said he impressed upon them that it's important to play well
because ``you make the football team in games, not practice.'' And
since the individual intensity will be at a high level, he expects
it to result in a favorable showing.
</P>
<P>
   Two areas that will draw much of Campo's attention are the
offensive line and secondary, because of the injuries and absences
at guard and cornerback. He said he is eager to see how the rookie
cornerbacks, Mario Edwards, Kareem Larrimore and Dwayne Goodrich,
play in a game. \Nsubheds:Staff evaluations, too The coaches will
be evaluating themselves against the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer is trying to discern whether
it's best for him to coach on the sideline or be up in the booth.
Zimmer, who prefers to be on the sideline looking at his players in
their eyes, will be on the field against the Steelers. He will go
in the booth at a later game.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Jack Reilly will be in the booth along
with consultant Ernie Zampese, while Dave Campo, who has been in
the booth the past four years as a defensive coordinator, tries to
get used to being on the field and listening to both the offensive
and defensive play calls. \Nsubheds:Injury updates Running back
Emmitt Smith (sprained toe), safety George Teague (strained
gluteus) and tight end David LaFleur (strained groin) are
considered game-time decisions for tonight's game against the
Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo said if the players aren't 100 percent healthy at
game time, they will not play. If the three can't go, Chris Warren,
Jason Kaiser and Jackie Harris will start in their places.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive guard Tony Hutson, linebacker Brandon Tolbert and
receiver James McKnight, who all underwent off-season knee surgery,
will not play tonight for precautionary reasons.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
