<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS BEAT YANKS, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The question for most of Saturday night's duel
between the Yankees' Roger Clemens and Minnesota's Eric Milton was
whether anybody would get a hit. But in the bottom of the eighth
inning, the question was whether the usually sterling Yankees'
bullpen would get anybody out.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens turned over a two-run advantage to the relievers for the
bottom of the eighth, but it required five pitchers and five trips
to the mound by Manager Joe Torre and the pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre to get three outs. By then, the Twins had pieced
together a 6-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza (7-4), who allowed the tying and go-ahead hits,
was charged with the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Milton did not allow a hit until the sixth inning, while the
Twins mustered their first hit against Clemens with two outs in the
fifth. Clemens had five consecutive victories before Saturday
night's no-decision and has compiled an earned run average of 1.91
in his last six outings. He allowed just four hits over seven
shutout innings Saturday night, and his pitch count was just 109
after seven innings. There had been 12 previous occasions this
season when he threw more pitches than that.
</P>
<P>
   But with the score 2-0, Clemens was relieved for the eighth
inning by Mike Stanton, who had not allowed an earned run in 11
straight appearances. Matt Lawton singled to lead off, and with one
out, David Ortiz smashed a double that bounced over the wall in
right-center field. The switch-hitting Denny Hocking was announced
as the pinch-hitter for Corey Koskie, and Torre called for Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mendoza's first appearance since June 24 _ he was placed
on the disabled list the next day _ and he walked Hocking to load
the bases. Mendoza struck out pinch-hitter Midre Cummings. Two
outs.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacque Jones laced a single to right, scoring the tying
runs. Chad Moeller followed with a sinking liner to left, where
Ryan Thompson charged and dove for the ball, trying to make the
catch that would end the inning and keep the score tied.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson missed the ball, however, and it rolled to the wall.
Moeller sprinted around the bases and crossed home plate before the
relay from the outfield for his first major league home run and a
5-2 Minnesota lead. The Twins went on to add another run in the
inning, and Milton (10-6), who allowed two hits and two walks and
struck out 10 in eight innings, won his duel with Clemens, because
of the Yankees' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won two championships and are contending for a
third with Chuck Knoblauch as their second baseman and leadoff
hitter; they felt Knoblauch would make them a better team and he
has, in spite of his intermittent throwing jitters.
</P>
<P>
   Time has vindicated Minnesota General Manager Terry Ryan as
well. Along with $3 million in cash and a couple of minor leaguers
who have not panned out, the Twins received two very good players
in return for Knoblauch _ Cristian Guzman and Milton. Guzman, a
shortstop, is 22 years old and although he has not yet developed
into a big-time hitter, everything he does seems to give the Twins
a better chance of winning the game, in a manner similar to that of
the Mets' Edgardo Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   Milton is left-handed, throws very hard, and last Sept.11, he
pitched a no-hitter against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch and Scott Brosius were out of the starting lineup with
injuries, and David Justice was given the day off by Torre, whose
bating order had an unusual look. Jose Vizcaino was the leadoff
hitter, Glenallen Hill was the designated hitter, Thompson started
in left field and Clay Bellinger played third.
</P>
<P>
   Milton reigned over the Yankees in the first three innings, like
a Little Leaguer who had reached puberty faster than his opponents,
striking out two in the first, two in the second and three more in
the third. All of the strikeouts were on swings and misses, on
failed attempts to hit his 94-mile-an-hour fastball. Milton reached
a two-ball count just once in the first three innings. He had
no-hit stuff, similar to the left-handed repertory David Wells had
when he pitched against the Twins on May 17, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was almost as good, his fastball sizzlin, his splitter
diving, his slider spinning tightly and veering. He struggled with
his control in the second inning, walking back-to-back hitters with
one out. After he struck out Torii Hunter, he walked Jones to load
the bases. But Clemens whirled a chest-high, 93-mph fastball past a
swinging Moeller to end the inning. He, too, had not allowed any
hits after three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Milton walked Derek Jeter with one out in the fourth, but
whiffed Paul O'Neill and retired Bernie Williams on an easy fly.
Clemens issued a two-out walk in the bottom of the fourth, then
struck out Jones to end the fourth inning. It was still early, it
was a double no-hitter in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Before each pitch, Clemens stood erect on the mound, looming
like a skyscraper. He holds his pitching hand and glove in front of
his face as he prepares to throw each pitch. His cap, drawn low on
his forehead, casts a half-moon shadow over that part of his face
the hitter can see, the area around his eyes; it looks as if
Clemens has donned war paint.
</P>
<P>
   Milton stood slightly to the third-base side of the pitching
rubber, turned at a 45-degree angle to the hitter, his glove held
at his right hip, his Popeye forearms covered in sweat. A gold neck
chain often escaped his jersey, hanging over the collar of his
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Milton retired the Yankees easily in the top of the fifth,
needing only 10 pitches. Moeller and Jay Canizaro made outs for the
Twins to start the bottom of the fifth. Thirty-five batters had
come to the plate in the game and there had not been a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman fouled off a two-strike pitch with two outs in the fifth,
and Clemens responded by pumping a fastball high and inside, 94
mph. Ball 3. Then Guzman laced a single to center, the first hit of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The game was scoreless after five innings. Milton had thrown
only 65 pitches, but he managed to walk the free-swinging Thompson
to open the sixth. Finally, with one out, Vizcaino skittered a
single through the middle, the ball skipping along the artificial
surface. On a grass field, it would perhaps have been a double
play. Thompson stopped at second on the hit.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter then looped a single into right-center field, where right
fielder Lawton approached the ball conservatively, worried that it
might bounce over his head, and he had no chance to throw out
Thompson at the plate. Vizcaino, reading the hit perfectly, took
third and eventually scored the Yankees' second run when O'Neill
flied out to center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
