<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TESTAVERDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: TESTAVERDE MISSES A SEASON, BUT NOT A BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Vinny Testaverde's first completion
happened hours before Saturday night's exhibition against New
Orleans, the first game for Testaverde since his Achilles' tendon
exploded in the season opener last September. He walked into Giants
Stadium with his pal Wayne Chrebet. That's what a smart quarterback
does _ stay close to your best wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde stuck to that philosophy once the game began. On the
first play of the Jets' third possession, Chrebet faked out both
safeties with a cut move inside, then darted the opposite way. Not
bad for a guy who supposedly has no speed. Testaverde lobbed a
perfect bomb, complete with tight spiral. Chrebet caught the pass
near midfield and cruised into the end zone for a 75-yard
touchdown. The only thing missing from that scene was a Hollywood
slow-motion shot and the score from ``Chariots of Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Keyshawn Johnson breaking down the play with one of those
Telestrator gizmos. But we digress.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown was especially important because on the previous
series, Testaverde, while trying to lob a screen pass to fullback
Richie Anderson, underthrew the ball by a few inches. Safety Sammy
Knight made an outstanding athletic play by picking off the pass
and running 65 yards for the touchdown. Testaverde was in pursuit
of Knight the entire time, and you can bet Coach Al Groh was
screaming inside for Testaverde to cease his Michael Johnson
imitation.
</P>
<P>
   Two important things about that play: During it, Testaverde was
not shy about testing his Achilles' tendon by sprinting down the
field chasing after Knight. That no body parts fell off can only be
encouraging. And on the very next series, Testaverde rebounded
strong from that embarrassing interception with the Chrebet
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes were on Testaverde for this game, and he did not
disappoint. In many ways he looked like a quarterback who had
missed no time. In fact, the entire Jets offense clicked. Chrebet
was sharp, running back Curtis Martin ran through obscenely large
holes and the play calling of Dan Henning was smart.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had a solid night. He completed 5 of 9 passes (with
one drop and one pass he threw away under a heavy pass rush) for
130 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   No one should be surprised if Testaverde looks like he has
barely missed a beat when the Jets open against Green Bay on Sept.
3. A quarterback, of course, needs to be in sync with his team, and
that is what Testaverde fears losing the most. When the season
begins, will his passes sail north when his receivers skate south?
</P>
<P>
   But Testaverde is a veteran, with 13 years in the league. Those
synapses inside his head will again begin firing quickly, and he
will recapture that delicate flow. It's already happening.
</P>
<P>
   The retired Miami quarterback Dan Marino had an injury similar
to Testaverde's, and after it, Marino was never quite the same. The
difference is that Marino had more knee surgeries than zeroes on
his fat paychecks. His legs were gone. Testaverde showed Saturday
night that his legs were still strong. His drop backs were crisp,
his mechanics smooth, his arm still a cannon.
</P>
<P>
   His Achilles' tendon should not be a concern. I officially give
him a clean bill of health. Yet his future with the Jets, and the
team's future at the position, well, that is a different story.
</P>
<P>
   This off-season, Testaverde told a former Jets teammate that he
wanted to finish his career near his Florida home, preferably with
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, either after this season or the next.
Sports Illustrated reported last week that Testaverde had a similar
conversation with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Testaverde's contract with the Jets runs through the 2005
season. Chances are that Testaverde, who turns 37 this year, will
not complete his contract anyway. So whether he leaves New York or
retires from football altogether, he will be gone in a few years,
maybe less. That is where things will get quite cloudy for the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets made a smart move in drafting a quarterback to replace
Testaverde, and Chad Pennington, one of their four first-round
picks, was judged by most league scouts to be the best available in
this year's draft. He had better be. Because once Testaverde
leaves, the team will be Pennington's. General Manager Bill
Parcells and Groh apparently think _ mistakenly _ that the backup
Ray Lucas is only that, a backup. Lucas will most likely leave the
Jets after this season.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to tell if Pennington is a franchise player
based on a few throws in a preseason game against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   One concern has to be Parcells' record as a talent evaluator,
which is lukewarm at best. When he was with the New England
Patriots, Parcells at first favored picking Rick Mirer over Drew
Bledsoe. Thank goodness he was talked out of that potential
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   There is the distinct possibility that after this season,
Testaverde and Lucas could be gone. That would leave the most
critical position on the field in a major state of flux.
</P>
<P>
   For now, all Testaverde and his teammates care about is the
present. The Jets still don't have a pass rush, they had four
turnovers against the Saints, and the schedule is brutal. But their
biggest concern coming into this game, Testaverde's health, is a
concern no more.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny's back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
