<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ON-BASEBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: INSTANTLY, BORDICK IS A FINE FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Bordick had not even found the appropriate belt
Saturday, but Robin Ventura had already outfitted the savior
shortstop with an interesting addition to his new Mets uniform.
Ventura dug up a name tag, scribbled Bordick's identity across it
for any Mets who were as oblivious as Rickey Henderson and then
stuck it on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, my name is Mike,'' read the name tag, ``but you can
call me Bordy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was simple, it was silly, but it was the perfect welcoming
for the 35-year-old Bordick, who is the reason the Mets went from
suspect to much more secure in 24 hours. If the Mets want their
aspirations about October to remain serious, they needed a tested,
reliable shortstop. Not Melvin Mora and not a player who would have
been an improvement in experience only, like Mark Loretta.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Mets desperately needed Bordick, who will make every
play and will make players around him better. Mora is energetic,
but he is a utility player and his presence at shortstop would have
eventually helped doom the Mets. Bordick was the best player on the
Orioles and, after the Barry Larkin disaster, General Manager Steve
Phillips responded quickly and cleverly to give the Mets a
necessary boost on the field and in their minds. Bordick will
provide the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Bordick displayed his value in major and minor ways as the Mets
quieted the St. Louis Cardinals, 4-3, a day on which Bordick
hammered a home run on the first pitch he saw as a Met, cued a
single during a decisive rally and played shortstop like he rented
office space at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much emotion,'' a sweaty Bordick said. ``It was
so exciting. For me, it was so exciting to be back in a pennant
race. Every pitch matters. Every play matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Ventura gave Bordick a name tag and Bordick listened
to advice from his teammates, his stomach was gurgling. Bordick
felt like he was in his first day in kindergarten, trying to fit
in. He gets nervous before every game, but Bordick's nerves were
more jangled Saturday. The Mets wanted him and needed him, and
Bordick knows the hefty expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Before he batted in the third inning, there was a faint ``Let's
Go, Bordick'' chant. It lasted around 10 seconds, but it would have
been drowned out anyway because Bordick drilled Andy Benes'
fastball for a towering home run. Hello, Bordy. Welcome to
Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   After Bordick's fly ball caromed off the retired numbers above
the left-field fence, he scooted around the bases to a standing
ovation. When Bordick returned to the dugout, the fans continued
howling, so the Mets nudged him out for the second curtain call of
his career. Bordick sheepishly said that he was the type of player
who had to be watched for a lengthy period to be appreciated, but
that was false Saturday. It took one game for Bordick to have an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible, certainly one of the biggest highlights of
my career,'' Bordick said about his homer and the reaction. ``It
was very exciting. This whole thing was exciting. Obviously, the
victory was most important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bordick helped set up the winning run, too. With Ventura on
first base and the score tied at 3-3 in the eighth, Bordick smacked
a grounder that bounced seven times before hitting the lip of the
infield where the dirt meets the grass and hopping over second
baseman Fernando Vina's glove. It sent Ventura to third, and he
eventually scored the winning run on Lenny Harris' pinch-hit
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``The homer was spectacular,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said.
``The rest is the type of stuff you'll see often. He makes the
plays without the flash.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets played the Montreal Expos last Wednesday, they
started Mora at shortstop and Harris at third base in place of
Ventura, who was still injured. Think about those names. Harris and
Mora are best suited for coming off the bench, as Harris showed
Saturday. Valentine started Bordick and Ventura Saturday, two
players who allow the Mets to think about improving on what they
did last season, when they reached the National League Championship
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said Bordick and Ventura brought ``instant stability to
the left side of the infield'' and, even if the general manager
does not obtain a leadoff hitter or another reliever, the Mets are
in a strong position. Bordick said the Mets were ``right on the
edge of where they want to be'' and, though he would not admit it,
Bordick can put them over that edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be the ingredient we need to get to the next level,''
Jay Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bordick smoothly and seamlessly replaced Cal Ripken at shortstop
in Baltimore, a much more daunting task than diving into a pennant
race.
</P>
<P>
   He has increased his off-season workouts and focuses on hitting
to all parts of the field, which is why he has a career-best 17
homers.
</P>
<P>
   What Bordick learned from replacing Ripken is that the team will
also dictate the success of his transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``What helped me the most that year is the fact that we won,''
Bordick said.
</P>
<P>
   Bordick loved Ventura's playful approach to introducing him to
the other Mets and wore the name tag as proudly as a Boy Scout
wears his first merit badge. Ventura also stuck a name tag on the
new reliever Rick White and was looking for Bubba Trammell, the
outfielder who was also just acquired, to give him a name tag, too.
The Mets have won five straight games and have renewed hopes,
especially because of the new shortstop called Bordy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't believe this, to tell you the truth,'' Bordick
said. ``It's incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
