u a BC-NY-JFK-HIJACKER-NYT &LR;      07-29 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JFK-HIJACKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK AIRPORT HIJACKER PUZZLES NEIGHBORS IN MILWAUKEE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The residents of a red-brick apartment building here
say they have been in disbelief since a neighbor, Aaron Amartei
Commey, was accused of boarding a National Airlines flight at
Kennedy International Airport with a 10mm handgun and a knife and
ordering the pilots to fly to Miami, Argentina and then Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   They have been searching for answers since word first spread in
northeast Milwaukee that Commey had been arrested and charged with
attempted air piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Commey, 22, a native of the Bronx, N.Y., who moved to Milwaukee
several years ago with his mother, was arrested after a five-hour
standoff in which the plane's passengers escaped and one pilot was
freed with a list of demands.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Commey has been described as a violent, calculating
and brazen man who spent weeks planning the attempted hijacking.
</P>
<P>
   But here, although most people who knew him say he had problems,
assessments have been more gentle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't seem like he was too crazy,'' said Damon Eastern,
24, who lives on the same floor as Commey in this working-class
black neighborhood on the northernmost border of Milwaukee, near
its more affluent suburbs of Shorewood, to the east, and Glendale,
to the north.
</P>
<P>
   To observers in New York, Commey's actions seem delusional. In
interviews with FBI agents, he confessed to trying to hijack the
plane, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   As Commey sits in a federal holding cell in New York awaiting
trial, the case has become a topic of discussion in churches and
saloons here.
</P>
<P>
   The events in New York, those who knew Commey said, appeared to
be the culmination of a long series of events that troubled
relatives and friends. Commey dropped out of high school and moved
to Milwaukee in 1996, when his parents divorced. His father,
Samuel, who lives in Brooklyn, N.Y., said he had not seen his son
in about four years. ``He was not responding to the help that I was
trying to give him,'' Samuel Commey said.
</P>
<P>
   Commey said he was trying to get his son to finish high school,
but, judging from recent telephone conversations, feared that his
son was suffering from an undiagnosed mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   A man who answered a knock at Aaron Commey's apartment on Friday
said his mother, Tina, and brother Benjamin would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives said that Aaron Commey had long been
quiet, but had become more reclusive after the move. They said he
began working odd jobs at factories in the Milwaukee area, and in
1997 moved out of his mother's home and lived temporarily with
Benjamin, his older brother, in a house in Kenosha, a southern
suburb of Milwaukee. Less than a year later, neighbors said, Commey
moved into his $325-a-month apartment here on North Sixth Street.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his friends, neighbors said, were from outside the area.
They included many whites _ somewhat unusual in this area,
neighbors said, who worked with him at several factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been around a little while, but did not come in here
much,'' said Houton Wilson, 55, the owner of one of two bars a
block away from the apartment building. ``Things have been up and
down here and we are back up,'' Wilson said of the neighborhood.
``This is all we need.''
</P>
<P>
   His room was sparsely decorated and filled with bags of trash,
neighbors said. Although reclusive, he did not stand out, said Tony
Parker, 22, a neighbor, though noting that Commey often seemed like
a social misfit and a conspiracy theorist.
</P>
<P>
   Those conspiracies began to dominate his life in recent years,
said one relative who did not want his name used.
</P>
<P>
   He began to talk about how the government had been cloning
humans for decades, offering theories seeming to mirror those on
``The X-Files,'' a television show. Indeed, investigators said
Commey told the pilots and negotiators that he believed that humans
were being cloned. Later, he told them he wanted to go to
Antarctica, the site of several secret government bases and landing
strips for human-alien hybrid cloning in ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks ago, officials say, he began planning to hijack a
plane in New York. He quit his job at a factory a week later. ``He
told us about that,'' Eastern said, ``that he was looking for a new
job, he was not making enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials said Commey never found a new job and spent much
of his time planning the hijacking and collecting weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, Milwaukee police detectives appeared at the
apartment building looking for someone who fit Commey's
description. ``The detectives pulled me over outside,'' Eastern
said. ``They asked me if I knew somebody a little shorter than me
with an Afro who lived in the building. I lied and told them I did
not know anything. But he was the only one who fit the
description.''
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee police officials declined to comment on why they were
looking for Commey.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday morning, Commey took a city bus near his home to
the bus terminal in downtown Milwaukee. Parker said he remembered
seeing Commey leave that morning _ in the same white shirt and
black pants he was arrested in _ carrying a brown paper bag and a
large duffel bag. Commey caught a Greyhound bus for a 20-hour ride
to New York, arriving Wednesday about 10:20 a.m., according to the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   About 10:25 p.m., Commey boarded National Airlines Flight 19, a
Boeing 757 bound for Las Vegas, after pointing his handgun at
security workers. After police negotiators persuaded him to get off
the plane they immediately began retracing his steps, and found his
duffel bag _ with a shotgun, about 20 shells and two additional
knives _ in a locker at the Port Authority Bus Terminal.
</P>
</TEXT>
