<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-29 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7347 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     07-29 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MOST OF THE MOST OF S.J. PERELMAN &LR;  (Modern Library, $15.95.)
These essays by the cranky, urbane humorist, first published
between 1930 and 1958, zing targets large and small, from Hollywood
to Raymond Chandler and Groucho Marx. ``Perelman misses no mad word
we write or say, and its image and essence he translates back to us
with an artistry acute, brilliant, devastating and ... funny,''
Eudora Welty wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPINNERS &LR;  By Anthony McCarten. (Harper Perennial, $13.) In this
first novel, a 16-year-old girl discombobulates a small town in
rural New Zealand when she claims to have been abducted and
molested by space aliens. ``McCarten is part barker, part juggler,
part aerialist,'' David Finkle wrote last year. ``He hangs
attributes on his characters as if they were caps and bells, and he
has these unwitting jesters say and do thigh-slapping things.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; APPOINTMENT AT THE ENDS OF THE WORLD: Memoirs of a Wildlife
Veterinarian &LR;  By William B. Karesh. (Warner, $13.95.) The author,
who works for the Wildlife Conservation Society, describes his
harrowing, often hazardous, job making house calls around the world
and helping the society in its far-flung research efforts. In 1999
the reviewer Marcia Bartusiak called this an ``engaging memoir''
that ``puts the need for conservation on a personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELEPHANT MEMORIES: Thirteen Years in the Life of an Elephant
Family &LR; , by Cynthia Moss (University of Chicago, $18), follows the
histories of 25 or so elephants in Amboseli National Park in Kenya,
detailing their daily lives and close family bonds. ``Moss tells
the story in a style so conversational, so free of academic jargon,
that I felt like a privileged visitor riding beside her in her
rickety Land Rover as she showed me around the park,'' Sarah
Blaffer Hrdy wrote in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUSHKIN'S BUTTON &LR;  By Serena Vitale. (University of Chicago,
$16.) An Italian scholar mines family archives, diplomatic records
and letters in this meticulous account of the impulsive Russian
poet's death in a duel in 1837 and of the society that allowed
people to settle grievances in such a way. The result ``is a
delightful combination of retrograde pleasures (court balls, the
demise of a doomed genius) and primary sources,'' Richard Lamb
wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TRUE HISTORY OF PARADISE &LR;  By Margaret Cezair-Thompson.
(Plume, $13.95.) Set in Jamaica in 1981, this ambitious first novel
uses the experiences of a young woman trying to flee her homeland
during a time of political upheaval to explore the island's vibrant
history and culture. Last year the reviewer Madison Smartt Bell
admired the author's ``talent, grace and confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOOK OF BLAM &LR;  By Aleksandar Tisma. (Harvest/Harcourt, $13.)
This novel, originally published in Yugoslavia in 1972, traces a
family history of Hapsburg Jews migrating across Eastern Europe in
the 19th century and describes in chilling detail the massacre of
thousands of Jews and Serbs in the city of Novi Sad by the
Hungarian military in 1942. ```The Book of Blam' offers a literary
memorial to the former Jews of the former Yugoslavia,'' Larry Wolff
wrote in The New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIAR'S MOON: A Long Story &LR;  By Philip Kimball. (Plume, $12.95.)
This neowestern, in which two toddlers fall off a wagon and are
raised by coyotes, ``explores the horizon where the West of myth
and the West of reality merge,'' Alanna Nash wrote in 1999.
``Kimball's bold use of character and language puts a new jingle
into the step of an often hoary genre.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAN YOU WAVE BYE BYE, BABY?: Stories &LR;  By Elyse Gasco. (Picador
USA, $12.) These seven interwoven tales, each dealing with
contentious issues of adoption and parenthood, feature mothers who
are biologically or emotionally uncertain and fathers who, while
absent or unhelpful, have no such doubts. ``Moments of insight are
one of the strengths of Gasco's collection,'' Margot Livesey wrote
in 1999. ``Another is its zany humor.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CODE BOOK: The Science of Secrecy From Ancient Egypt to
Quantum Cryptography &LR;  By Simon Singh. (Anchor, $14.) The author
uses a series of historical incidents, including a plot to
assassinate Queen Elizabeth I and put Mary, Queen of Scots on the
English throne, in this survey of code making through the ages.
``The almost universal fascination with codes undoubtedly derives
from the extraordinary feats of ingenuity that have gone into
devising and breaking them, as well as their enormous impact on
world events,'' Robert Osserman wrote last year. ``Singh's book
offers more than its share of both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
